<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Honduras-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0953 03-16 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0953,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Honduran Armed Forces Reportedly Surround Sandinista Troops</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with Honduran troops reported surrounding
Nicaraguan soldiers; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduran troops on Wednesday
surrounded about 2,000 Nicaraguan soldiers who entered the country
chasing Contra rebels, military intelligence sources told The
Associated Press.
   They said the Sandinista troops had crossed about 3 miles into
the Honduran border province of Olancho, east of the capital of
Tegucigalpa, and had remained in the area for 24 hours.
   One official, who asked not to be identified, said the
Nicaraguan troops ``have been surrounded by our army ... and we are
only waiting superior orders to enter into action.''
   ``There really is tension and there is crisis, however we are
acting with prudence but with strength in these affairs, and we
hope that everything will stabilize in the next two days,'' he said.
   The Honduran military went on alert, the sources said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras said that Honduras'
president, Jose Azcono Hoyo, contacted Nicaraguan President Daniel
Ortega to demand the withdrawal of the troops.
   Ortega has not confirmed the presence of Sandinista soldiers in
Honduras, and the Nicaraguan Foreign Ministry has denied any
incursion.
   In Washington, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
United States was dispatching 3,200 soldiers to southern Honduras
to carry out training exercises and to be ``a signal to the
governments and the people of Central America.'' He said they would
not enter any combat zones.
   Earlier, Fitzwater said Azcona had asked the United States for
help in dealing with an invasion.
   Intelligence officials said the Sandinista troops apparently
entered Honduras to destroy a base camp of the U.S.-backed Contras.
   ``We have done everything possible to avoid a confrontation that
would drastically affect ... both countries,'' one source said.
   The Superior Council of the Armed Forces, the country's highest
military body, was in session most of the day, the officials said.
Earlier Wednesday, Azcona met for about six hours behind closed
doors to discuss the situation with top officials and the armed
forces military chiefs.
   Lopez Contreras told reporters at a news conference that the
military command was reviewing battle plans in case the Sandinista
forces continued occupying Honduran territory.
   In Managua, Ortega refused to confirm or deny that Nicaraguan
troops had encroached on Honduran soil.
   Lopez Contreras did not comment on reports that the Reagan
administration was dispatching U.S. troops to Honduras.
   ``We don't want to create a national panic. We only ask our
compatriots to have confidence in the government and in the armed
forces,'' he said.
   The foreign minister added that Azcona had demanded that Ortega
order the ``withdrawal of the troops because they are raising
tensions and producing insecurity in the border.''
   Azcona also asked presidents of Costa Rica, El Salvador and
Guatemala to appeal to Ortega ``to abstain from bringing about
aggressive military actions against Honduras,'' Lopez Contreras
said.
   ``The government and the army are ready to put into action the
right of legitimate defense,'' the foreign minister declared.
   Military intelligence sources said that at least 2,000
Sandinista troops were inside Honduras and that another 4,500 were
near the border in the Bocay region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
