<1ST_LINE>u i AM-IRAFuneral 3rdLd-Writethru a0975 03-16 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IRA Funeral, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0975,0863</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3 Killed, Dozens Injured in Attack on IRA Funeral</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-7 UPDATE with attacker identified, Paisley
denounces attack. Picks up 7th graf pvs, The litle-known ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON14,16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who fired guns and
grenades from behind a tombstone killed three people and wounded 68
at an IRA graveside service Wednesday before enraged mourners
cornered and beat him.
   Young Catholics rioted in the streets afterward.
   Belfast police arrested the gunman at the end of a wild chase
over graves in the Milltown Roman Catholic cemetery during which he
hurled grenades at the pursuing mourners and fired until his gun
jammed. They identified him as Michael Stone, a Protestant, but
gave no other information about him.
   Thousands of mourners screamed and dived for cover when shots
shattered the silence of the cemetery in early afternoon, as the
coffins of three unarmed IRA members killed by British soldiers in
Gibraltar were being lowered into a single grave.
   A companion of the attacker fled in a van parked nearby, and
police said they captured him in another part of the city. Both men
can be held without charge for seven days. Police provided no
details on the second man.
   Mainstream Protestant organizations disavowed the attack. The
Rev. Ian Paisley, leader of the Protestant Democratic Unionist
Party, said all ``right-thinking Protestants'' would condemn the
attack ``without any ambivalence whatsoever.''
   The British Broadcasting Corp. in Belfast said an anonymous
caller claimed responsibility Wednesday night on behalf of the
Protestant Action Force, but gave no recognized codeword to
establish authenticity of the claim.
   The little-known extremist group has claimed responsibility for
numerous sectarian assassinations.
   Catholic youths ignored government and church appeals after the
attack and rioted through the evening. They burned hijacked buses
and other vehicles and blocked streets with flaming barricades.
   Palls of smoke hung over the Catholic ghettos of West Belfast.
   Police said they fired plastic bullets at rioters who fired a
shot and threw stones at a police patrol in the Ardoyne district of
west Belfast. In Londonderry, the province's second city, one car
was hijacked and set ablaze in the Catholic Bogside district.
   Police identified the three people killed Wednesday as Thomas
Charles McErlean, 20; John Murray, 26; and Kevin Brady, 30. All
came from Catholic areas of Belfast.
   One of those wounded at the cemetery was in critical condition
and four were in seriously wounded, said a spokesman for Royal
Victoria Hospital. Most victims were shot or hit by shrapnel while
scrambling for cover during the melee, which lasted about five
minutes.
   Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army, blamed Protestant paramilitary groups and accused
Britain of collusion.
   In London, aides of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said she
was ``shocked and appalled.''
   Her government denounced the attack as ``insane and depraved.''
It appealed for calm, as did Sinn Fein, church leaders and the
Irish Republic government in Dublin.
   Police, the British government and the Ulster Defense
Association, an umbrella organization of Protestant vigilante
groups, and the outlawed Ulster Freedom Fighters denied involvement.
   The largely Catholic IRA is waging a guerrilla war to drive the
British from Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland, and Protestant
paramilitary groups have grown up to fight it.
   Martin McGuinness, vice president of Sinn Fein, said: ``It's
obvious it was an attack by Loyalist (Protestant) movements.''
   Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams said: ``There was collusion
between elements with the British Crown forces, probably the Royal
Ulster Constabulary (provincial police).''
   Police said they deliberately kept away from the funeral because
of assurances that the IRA would not turn it into a paramilitary
display.
   Commandos in civilian clothes killed the guerrillas, Mairead
Farrell, 31; Sean Savage, 24, and Daniel McCann, 30, on March 6.
British officials said the three were on a mission to bomb a
military ceremony at the colony.
   Mourners were lowering Miss Farrell's flag-draped coffin into
the grave when a bearded man opened fire 15 yards away from behind
a gravestone.
   Young men yelled ``There he is! There he is!'' and the thickset
gunman bolted.
   His cap fell off as he reloaded his pistol, and still dodging
and weaving, he fired at the youths and hurled two grenades while
taunting the pursuers to keep coming, witnesses said.
   ``I saw a young man throwing things from the back of the
mourners,'' said the Rev. Alec Reid, who was saying prayers beside
the open grave. ``I thought they were stones, but it looks as if
they were grenades. He was also firing shots into the crowd. There
was absolute chaos.''
   Adams said the two men involved in the attack entered the
cemetery carrying bags and cameras and were mistaken for
journalists.
   The attack occurred after moderate Andy Tyrie was ousted as
leader of the Ulster Defense Association. Hardliners accused him of
weakening the armed fight against the IRA.
   More than 2,600 people have been killed in Northern Ireland's
sectarian violence since August 1969.
</TEXT>
