<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--OKVacation     03-16 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--OK Vacation,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oklahomans Trying To Lure Snowbirds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>McALLEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oklahoma officials say a vacation in their
state is more than OK, and they hope a road campaign in South Texas
will persuade ``snowbirds'' to stop by on their way back north this
spring.
   State and private tourism supporters opened up a two-day travel
show in this lower Rio Grande Valley city Tuesday, hoping to reach
the thousands of retired Midwesterners and Canadians who spend
winter in the area.
   ``You have to try pretty hard coming to South Texas not to go
through Oklahoma,'' Oklahoma Lt. Gov. Robert S. Kerr III, who
traveled to McAllen.
   A tourism survey, however, showed that ``Oklahoma doesn't have
much of an image,'' Kerr said.
   The state has launched a $1.2 million tourism promotion
campaign, said Eugene Dilbeck, director of the Oklahoma Tourism and
Recreation Department.
   State officials project they will get a five-fold return on
their promotional investment.
</TEXT>
