<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-MissAmerica     03-16 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Miss America,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miss America Addressing Critical Needs Of Nursing Profession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unlike Miss Americas of recent years,
Kaye Lani Rae Rafko is not looking for movie contracts or modeling
jobs after her reign ends.
   Instead, she is anxious to return to her job as a registered
nurse at a hospital in Toledo, Ohio, working with terminally ill
cancer and AIDS patients.
   ``After another six months of this, I'll be ready to hang up the
heels and the tiara and head back to work,'' she told nurses
Tuesday while visiting hospitals here.
   The 24-year-old former Miss Michigan is using her reign to
maximize the image of her career, however, promoting the nursing
profession rather than snipping ribbons to open new shopping malls
or shaking hands at state fairs.
   The first months of Miss Rafko's reign, which began in
September, were booked with appearances for the pageant's six
sponsors, said pageant executive director Leonard Horn.
   ``But once people saw that Kaye Lani was a nurse, we cleared her
schedule to make room for more public service appearances,'' said
Horn, in his first year as head of the pageant.
   ``This is what I want Miss America to do more of anyway _ less
commercial appearances and more living up to the role model that
she really is.''
   Miss Rafko has visited numerous hospitals and hospices and
spoken to many nursing associations and medical groups. She has
done a public service announcement for the nursing profession and
appeared on the cover of a nursing trade journal.
   Horn said that Miss Rafko's career fits in perfectly with public
service appearances, acknowledging that future Miss Americas who
sing or dance for a living might not have as much expertise in
dealing with service-oriented groups.
   ``But we're going to emphasize the fact that any Miss America
has a beneficial interest when she speaks to any number of groups,
whether it's the Future Farmers of America or the American Cancer
Society,'' he said. ``You don't have to be a nurse to speak to
those groups and make an impression. Miss America can make a
difference simply by promoting education.''
   But this year, Miss Rafko is intent on hyping her career.
   ``A main focus of today's American people is health, and
fortunately I know a lot about that,'' she said.
   At least one other Miss America was inundated with special
requests for speaking engagements. Miss America 1984 Vanessa
Williams, the first black Miss America, addressed many black
organizations until she relinquished her crown in a scandal over
nude photographs.
   But most recent Miss Americas have followed a fairly routine
round of promotional appearances.
   ``In the past few years, many Miss Americas have concentrated on
entertainment careers. There's nothing wrong with that,'' Miss
Rafko said. ``Everybody has their own dreams and goals and that's
what the Miss America pageant is all about.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
