<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0204EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ArmedJudge     03-16 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Armed Judge,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduran Judge Says He Fights To Keep Drugs Off U.S. Streets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TELA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As he stripped and cleaned the AK-47
assault rifle on his desk, Federal Judge Miguel Angel Izaguirre
said he has good reason to try to stop Latin American cocaine from
reaching the streets of the United States.
   ``In 20 years, the youth that is taking all this cocaine will be
running America and influencing Latin America _ with the mentality
of cokeheads,'' he said. ``North America's influence in this region
is tremendous. So we Latin Americans have to try to ensure that
American youth does not take cocaine.''
   The 41-year-old Izaguirre is the federal judge in this Caribbean
coastal town. He also is a weapons buff and student of military
history.
   ``Men, like arms, are proven on the field of battle,'' he said
in an interview in his cramped and cluttered office that also
contained an Uzi submachine gun. ``And this is my field of battle.''
   He has survived two attempts on his life, he said _ one with an
incendiary bomb, the other a machine-gun attack on his home during
which he returned fire with his Soviet-made AK-47.
   ``I love the AK,'' he said. His arsenal of weapons, he
explained, is ``to defend myself against the Medellin Cartel.''
   The Medellin Cartel, named for the city in Colombia where it is
based, is believed responsible for more than 80 percent of the
cocaine smuggled into the United States.
   ``They have tried to bribe me with money, women, airplanes and
yachts,'' he said.
   Leaning against the wall were five segments of hollowed out
Honduran redwood ostensibly intended for assembly into rustic
doors. They are evidence from the biggest drug bust in U.S. history
_ the confiscation in November of four tons of cocaine by U.S.
federal agents in Florida. The drug, shipped from the northern
Honduran coast, was hidden in the hollows.
   ``According to our information, the shipment was 8,000 kilos
(almost 9 tons). So more than half of it got through,'' he said.
   U.S. authorities were greatly concerned when, over the past few
years, Honduras became an increasingly important transshipment
point for Colombian cocaine.
   Izaguirre has been cited as a key man in joint U.S.-Honduran
efforts to reduce the flow.
   The judge said Honduras, with its long and relatively unguarded
coast and scores of clandestine air strips, provided the ideal
midpoint for northbound shipments.
   ``When I came here in June 1987, I found a series of cases, all
of which were being dismissed for lack of evidence. ... Other
judges had certain fears, some got sick, some left,'' he said. But
within two months, he had handed down the first conviction and
prison term for cocaine trafficking in Honduran judicial history.
   He has convicted 10 others on drug charges, and has nearly three
dozen suspected traffickers in jail awaiting judgment. Two major
traffickers based here, the Colombian Luis Guerrero and the
Cuban-American Rafael Gonzalez, were extradited to the United
States after being arraigned by Izaguirre. They are both serving
terms in U.S. prisons.
   Izaguirre said he has given the maximum penalty under Honduran
law to all the drug traffickers he has convicted _ five years in
prison and a 5,000 lempira ($2,500) fine. He complains, however,
that the law is too lenient and would like to see penalties
increased. He said the law provides the same penalties for cocaine
trafficking as it does for marijuana trafficking.
   The judge _ divorced four times and the father of five children
_ carries his weapons with him wherever he goes.
   ``If it befalls me to die in this post, then I'll die, without
the slightest fear,'' he said.
   He keeps a .357 Magnun revolver on his desk within easy reach.
   The judge insists he has no political ambitions, but maintains
contact with a number of the country's political leaders.
   ``I tell them it is imperative that we verify the origin of the
parties' funds. Because if we don't, we're running the grave risk
that the traffickers get their people elected to Congress. Then
they reform the Constitution in their favor, they gut the
anti-narcotics law; they destroy us.''
   Though U.S. authorities have expressed concern that drug money
has corrupted some officers in Honduras' armed forces, Izaguirre
said the cooperation given him by the military has been ``total.''
   He said his interest in the military began when he was 12 years
old, with the reading of Karl von Clausewitz, the 19th century
Prussian general and writer of military strategy.
   ``I was two centimeters (about an inch) too short to get into
the military academy,'' he said. ``But if I had, I'm sure I would
have made general.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
