<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0209EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama-Chronology     03-16 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Chronology,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of events in the Panamanian crisis:
   
   THURSDAY, FEB. 25 _ Panama's president, Eric Arturo Delvalle,
announces he is dismissing Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, indicted on
U.S. drug charges, as defense chief and replacing him with Col.
Marcos Justines, chief of staff. Justines refuses job.
   FRIDAY, FEB. 26 _ Noriega-dominated National Assembly votes to
oust Delvalle. Education Minister Manuel Solis Palma named new head
of state. Noriega opponents call for general strike in protest.
Diplomats and economists say customers begin run on domestically
owned banks.
   SATURDAY, FEB. 27 _ Delvalle goes into hiding in Panama, defying
Noriega's order that he leave country.
   SUNDAY, FEB. 28 _ Organization of American States sidesteps
Panama issue by refusing to choose between two men claiming to be
Panama's ambassador.
   MONDAY, FEB. 29 _ General strike begins with mixed
participation. Panama's ambassador to United States, Juan B. Sosa,
refuses to relinquish post to Noriega designee.
   TUESDAY, MARCH 1 _ General strike gains support in second day.
Locally owned banks close. International banks limit withdrawals.
Plainclothesmen wreck only remaining opposition radio station in
Panama City. Security forces crack down on protests amid scattered
violence. U.S. government officially denounces Panama as deficient
in fighting drug trade. Delvalle outlines plans to freeze
Panamanian assets outside country. United States, still recognizing
Delvalle as president, supports action.
   WEDNESDAY, MARCH 2 _ Doctors join businesses in general strike.
U.S. officials confirm they will ask U.S. banks to freeze
Panamanian government assets. More violence reported in Panama City.
   THURSDAY, MARCH 3 _ Organizers end general strike as support
fades, saying money crunch will keep pressure on government.
President Reagan indicates he believes Noriega must go. Congressmen
propose trade, air travel and currency embargo on Noriega regime.
U.S. federal courts temporarily block withdrawal of Panama funds
from U.S. banks.
   FRIDAY, MARCH 4 _ National Bank of Panama says it cannot meet
banks' cash demands because of freeze on bank deposits.
International banks fearing a run on deposits close their doors.
Local banks remain closed.
   SUNDAY, MARCH 7 _ Alliance of business and civic groups opposed
to Noriega calls for ``government of national reconciliation'' and
``authentic democracy.'' Retired people unable to cash pension
checks rally in streets.
   MONDAY, MARCH 8 _ Riot police disperse demonstrators in Panama
with tear gas and birdshot.
   TUESDAY, MARCH 9 _ Government says banks can reopen but no one
can cash checks or withdraw funds. Few banks respond. Two prominent
Panamanian diplomats break with Noriega.
   WEDNESDAY, MARCH 10 _ The U.S. House votes 367-2 for a
non-binding resolution calling on Reagan to ``consider seriously''
additional economic and political sanctions. Libyan television
reports Noriega asked for Libyan backing against ``American
military aggression and economic threats.''
   FRIDAY, MARCH 11 _ Reagan imposes economic sanctions, including
eliminating trade preferences for Panama and withholding Panama
Canal fees from the Noriega government by placing them in escrow.
Noriega government meets army payroll. Miami federal judge grounds
Air Panama, freezing its assets while he decides which Panamanian
officials should control the airline. Spain tells Ukkknited States
it would accept Noriega if he asked for asylum.
   SATURDAY, MARCH 12 _ Panamanian Cabinet meets in emergency
session.
   SUNDAY, MARCH 13 _ Solis Palma calls Cabinet into another
emergency session.
   MONDAY, MARCH 14 _ Public employees stage work stoppages and
riot after government is unable to pay wages. Riot police use tear
gas and truncheons to disperse hundreds blocking traffic. Reagan
administration hints it may reassess demand for Noriega's
extradition in order to allow him to step down. U.S. sends 100
additional military personnel to beef up security around canal.
   TUESDAY, MARCH 15 _ Reagan says U.S. wants Noriega ``out of
there.'' At least a dozen are injured in demonstrations as civil
servants take to streets to demand paychecks. Panama orders U.S.
Embassy official to leave country, but U.S. rejects demand.
Government says it will make partial payments to public employees.
Employee union leaders reject plan and demand full salaries.
</TEXT>
