<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Robertson 1stLd-Writethru a0814 03-16 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0814,550</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with Robertson comments; pick up 4th graf pvs
bgng ``I am bumping...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson met with the Republican national
chairman Tuesday to discuss his faltering presidential bid and said
later he is ``laying the foundation'' for 1992.
   Robertson suffered another disappointing showing in Illinois,
collecting just 7 percent in Tuesday's primary. Though he insisted
he will remain in the 1988 race, Robertson appeared to be looking
ahead.
   ``I am laying the foundation now and definitely talking to
people about 1992. I will play a major role in the GOP,'' he told
reporters at his headquarters in Chesapeake, Va.
   Robertson also talked with reporters after his meeting with
Republican National Committee Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf. He said he
is approaching the $27 million limit that candidates are allowed to
spend in the primary season. He said he is laying off staff and
will be forced to discontinue the big spending that has
characterized his campaign so far.
   ``I am bumping up against the limit. ... I have enough money to
keep in the race through California and the convention. But I don't
have enough to do telemarketing and television,'' he said. ``My own
personal travel will continue but as far as a full-blown media
campaign I can't afford that any more.''
   Election law restricts spending by presidential candidates who
accept federal matching funds for their campaigns.
   The meeting with Fahrenkopf took place at Robertson's request, a
party spokeswoman said.
   Robertson said, ``We were discussing arrangements for the
convention in August and also discussing ways where I could help
Republicans gain control of key state legislatures, for instance
the legislature of California, so that we could achieve
redistricting of a fair basis in the early 1990s and use that as a
basis to gain control of the House of Representatives and the
United States Senate for the Republican Party.''
   RNC spokeswoman Kathryn Murray confirmed the meeting had focused
on those two topics at the suggestion of Robertson.
   She said Robertson expressed a wish to campaign on behalf of
Republican candidates at all levels. Fahrenkopf ``welcomes his
support,'' she said.
   ``As long as he can continue to bring new voters into the
Republican Party, that's a positive,'' Murray said.
   Robertson also met Tuesday with Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir who was in Washington for talks with U.S. officials.
   Robertson said he and Shamir were ``old friends.'' The Christian
Broadcasting Network that Robertson founded broadcasts in the
Middle East.
   Robertson endorsed Shamir's stance against giving up Israeli
occupied lands to the Palestinian people until after ``a period of
Palestinian self rule.''
   ``Any surrender of territory in the near future would seriously
imperil the ability of Israel to defend itself,'' he said, adding
that he supports negotiations among the Israelis, Jordan and
Palestinians.
   On politics, he was pressed to explain how he could continue
campaigning without spending money. Robertson said that in Illinois
he spent only $20,000.
   ``I have tens of thousands of volunteers who are working
ceaselessly night and day because they care for a cause, they care
for principle,'' he said. ``Its a movement to bring about
conservative principles in America.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
