<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Ozone     03-16 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ozone,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Panel Says It Can Show CFC Effects On Ozone</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Aeronautics and Space
Administration says the ozone shield is in fact thinning measurably
due to chlorofluorocarbon compounds.
   A NASA panel said the shield thinned out by about 2.3 percent
over a 17-year period ending in 1986 in the temperate zones of the
Northern Hemisphere. The panel said the shield thinned by 0.5
percent to 1.8 percent over nine years ending in 1987 in the
tropics and part of the temperate zones of both hemispheres.
   This means increased skin cancer around the world, largely
unknown effects on fish and wildlife and increased pressure from
environmentalists to go beyond the treaty approved by the Senate to
cut emissions of ozone-destroying chemicals.
   Chlorofluorocarbons are used as refrigeration fluids, cleaning
solvents and plastic foam blowing agents.
   ``At this point there is no other culprit to blame,'' panel
member Sherwood Rowland of the University of California at Irvine
said Tuesday. ``We have taken out all the natural phenomena that
are believed to affect ozone.''
   A massive 17-month effort by more than 100 scientists convened
by NASA went through practically every ozone observation made in
recent years, trying to correct for instrument errors and drift and
to remove the effects of the 11-year solar cycle and the biennial
oscillation of high-altitude winds.
   Since 1985, there have been several reports of ozone decline
worldwide in addition to the well-established ozone ``hole'' over
Antarctica _ a 50 percent decline in springtime, followed by
recovery.
   Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Lee M. Thomas said
the report ``will certainly be a part of the 1990 assessment''
called for in the treaty. ``The crucial first step, however, is
speedy international ratification,'' he said.
   But Sen. Robert T. Stafford, R-Vt., said, ``The nations of the
world should immediately reconvene to consider amendments'' to the
treaty, and the United States should resume its advocacy of a
complete ban. ``We've got to make deeper cuts in CFC emissions,''
said Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont.
   Kevin Fay, executive director of the Alliance for a Responsible
CFC Policy, a group of producers and users, said the 1990 schedule
``is the framework to be followed'' because unilateral reductions
won't help.
   The Senate voted 83-0 on Monday to approve a 31-nation treaty
calling for 50 percent cuts by 1998 in production of
chlorofluorocarbons.
   Noting that CFC compounds over Antarctica now were released at
ground level about 10 years ago and that the Antarctic hole could
last 100 years even if the treaty is followed, Rowland said,
``There's plenty of reason to re-open the ... protocol.''
   Ozone at high altitudes makes life on earth possible by blocking
the harmful ultraviolet rays. The EPA estimates that each percent
decrease in ozone means a 4.8 percent to 7.5 percent increase in
non-melanoma skin cancer and a 0.8 percent to 1.5 percent increase
in the more deadly melanoma form.
   Considering the incidence and death rates of both forms, this
would mean 280 to 455 deaths per year on top of the 10,000 from
skin cancer in the United States, or 640 to 1,050 deaths if a 2.3
percent decline were uniform across the country.
   The 2.3 percent is not uniform. NASA presented its 1969-1986
Northern Hemisphere estimates from ground obserations as averages
over each of three bands: 30 degrees latitude (about the latitude
of Houston, Cairo and Shanghai) to 40 degrees (Philadelphia and
Madrid), down 1.7 percent; 40 degrees to 53 degrees (Edmonton,
Alberta, and Berlin), down 3.0 percent; and 53 degrees to 64
degrees (Fairbanks, Alaska, and Reykjavik, Iceland), down 2.3
percent.
   No single estimate was presented for all three bands, but
Rowland said the average, a 2.3 percent decline, would be close.
All the estimates have substantial uncertainty about them. Each of
the three band estimates has a 68 percent chance of being plus or
minus 1.0 percentage point, at most, away from the number given.
   Corrected satellite data show an ozone decline of about 2.5
percent in the band running from 53 degrees north to 53 degrees
south from 1978 through 1987. But 0.7 percent to 2.0 percent of
this results from the solar cycle, the report said.
</TEXT>
