<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SupremacistMarch     03-16 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Supremacist March,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Natchez Agrees to Allow White Supremacists To March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in Natchez say they'll
reluctantly permit a white supremacist protest march against a
14-week-old black boycott of white-owned businesses in exchange for
dismissal of a lawsuit against the city.
   U.S. District Judge William H. Barbour announced the settlement
Tuesday in dismissing a lawsuit filed by Jackson attorney Richard
Barrett on behalf of The Nationalist Movement. The judge also
ordered Natchez to pay Barrett's attorneys' fees in the case.
   ``The law of the land will prevail in Natchez, not the law of
the jungle,'' Barrett said after the announcement. ``This is a
victory for the red-white-and-blue people _ meaning red-neck, white
skin and blue collar.''
   Boycott leaders are seeking, among other things, a black school
superintendent and more black teachers in the Adams County-Natchez
school district.
   ``I'm opposed to Richard Barrett and his movement, but as mayor
of the city, you have to abide the by the laws and the courts. We
just hope nobody will show up for it,'' Natchez Mayor Tony Byrne
said of the march.
   Byrne said officials decided to settle after the County Board of
Supervisors said the city couldn't ban the rally scheduled for the
county courthouse grounds Saturday afternoon, the day Barrett was
seeking permission for the parade through city streets.
   Barrett had contended in his lawsuit that the city was
infringing on the group's constitutional rights by retroactively
applying a parade ordinance adopted March 8.
   ``We'll see to it that Mr. Barrett comes to town, has his parade
and rally, and leaves town as expeditiously as possible,'' Byrne
said.
</TEXT>
