<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-OPIC     03-16 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-OPIC,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Government Agency Would Buy Shares In Business Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two years ago the Reagan administration
proposed selling its Overseas Private Investment Corp. to private
interests. Now it's urging that the government agency be allowed to
buy shares in private companies.
   Craig A. Nalen, OPIC's president for more than seven years, told
the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on economic policy on
Tuesday that the agency wants to begin a pilot project that would
put $10 million over the next five years into black Africa and the
Caribbean.
   The money would be spent to take up as much as 30 percent of the
shares in new American companies there. Government bodies in Japan,
West Germany, Britain and the Netherlands already help their
private investors in this way.
   OPIC's main job is to sell insurance to American investors
overseas, against what are called political risks: war, rebellion,
civil strife, confiscation and official freezing of assets. It is
one of the few federal agencies that makes money: $300 million over
the past three years, Nalen said.
   ``OPIC's strong financial position makes the agency a good
candidate for privatization,'' said the president's budget proposal
for the year that ended last September.
   There was considerable opposition to the idea, both inside and
outside the agency, on grounds the insurance was sought precisely
because it had the power of the U.S. government behind it. After
some study, the president's Office of Management and Budget decided
that OPIC had better stay part of the government.
   The privatization plan was quietly dropped.
   OPIC also makes loans to U.S. companies setting up business in
other countries _ $202.8 million worth of loans and guarantees last
year.
   Nalen said Tuesday that buying shares as well as making loans
would help small projects get started.
   It would allow these heavily indebted countries to borrow less
for industrial development, he said. Many are unable to borrow
because banks have cut back their lending he said.
   Nalen also argued that direct investment by his agency would
help U.S. investors.
   ``OPIC's major ... counterparts all have the ability to invest
equity, thus providing their clients with a significant advantage
over their U.S. competitors,'' he said in his prepared testimony.
</TEXT>
