<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SimplifiedTaxes Bjt   03-16 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Simplified Taxes, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Venture Where the IRS Fears to Tread: Into Simplicity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If your idea of a good tax form is one with
short sentences and short words, take heart.
   A group of students, venturing where government has been less
than successful, vows to come up with a series of tax forms that
are understandable even to the high school dropout. And the
students say they will finish the job within less than six months.
   ``I don't say it's a simple task, but we're going to try,''
Professor Nicholas J. Creme, director of the Center for Taxation
Studies in the Akron University School of Law, said in an interview
Tuesday.
   He said he wants the students to work with the Internal Revenue
Service on the project, although the IRS has not yet embraced the
idea.
   The students' interest was piqued by what they learned while
representing low-income taxpayers in audits, collections and other
actions involving the IRS. They learned that on the average, only
11 percent of taxpayers with less than a high school education have
the reading skills to comprehend instructions for filling out Forms
1040 or 1040EZ.
   The students concluded that if taxpayers can't understand how to
comply with the tax laws, they probably won't. Or as Creme, a tax
lawyer for 20 years, put it, ``When people can't figure out the
right answer, they will take the answer that gives them the best
break.''
   High school dropouts aren't the only people having trouble with
this year's tax forms. Even tax professionals shake their heads at
some instructions prompted by the more complex provisions of the
1986 tax overhaul, which was initially billed as tax
``simplification.''
   This sentence is part of the Form 1040 instructions for
determining how much interest is deductible:
   ``If all of your mortgage debt on your principal home was
borrowed before August 17, 1986, (and you have not borrowed any new
amounts on that debt); OR, at all times in 1987, the total of your
mortgage debts was less than or equal to what you paid for the home
plus improvements (such as adding a room), the mortgage interest
you paid is fully deductible on line 9a or 9b, whichever applies.''
   Creme says that about 20 students training in law, business or
education will develop a more-readable W-4 withholding form; W-2
yearend wages-earned statement; 1099 interest-earned form and the
basic 1040, 1040A and 1040EZ forms.
   ``We're not saying we could bring it down to a second-grade
level, but we certainly can make it simpler,'' he said. ``If you
simplify the forms, people will be a lot less hostile toward the
IRS. And you'll raise a lot more revenue.''
   Creme and some of the students volunteered for the project
Monday while testifying before a Senate Finance subcommittee about
IRS penalties. The chairman, Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., welcomed the
idea.
   Creme and Professor James W. Childs, director of the
university's Tax Clinic, said it is not difficult to figure out why
the tax forms and instructions are difficult. ``The average
sentence length of these publications exceeds 25 words,'' they said
in written testimony. ``One-third of the words in these
publications are multisyllabled words.''
   Creme's solution: ``By reducing the number of syllables and the
number of words in a sentence we can make the forms and
instructions significantly more readable. And we want to change how
the forms look _ change the spacing so things don't look so crammed
in.''
   IRS forms are developed in consultation with lawyers,
accountants and educators. In changing its forms last year to
reflect the new tax law, the IRS hired a consultant and even went
to some shopping malls for instant reaction from random taxpayers.
   As for the students' project, IRS spokesman Steve Pyrek says,
``One-syllable words are nice, but what do you do about
`dependents'?''
   The IRS estimates nearly half of taxpayers will pay
professionals to fill out their returns this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
