<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Greenspan-Stumped     03-16 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greenspan-Stumped,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greenspan Had All the Answers _ Except One</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan easily
fielded one complicated economic question after another from a
congressional committee, but then one request stopped him cold.
   Who was on the Fed committee that charts national monetary
policy when it held its most recent meeting last month?
   That question, posed on Tuesday by Sen. John Melcher, D-Mont., a
member of the House-Senate Joint Economic Committee, stumped
Greenspan and the six aides seated behind him, at least temporarily.
   At issue was a Feb. 9-10 meeting of the 12-member Federal Open
Market Committee, or FOMC. It is made up of the seven members of
the Federal Reserve Board and five regional Fed bank presidents.
   Greenspan, shuffling papers and conferring with his aides, made
a halting effort to name the five Fed bank presidents on the panel
in February _ and finally got four of the five right.
   ``You're a little bit fuzzy on just who voted in February,''
Melcher said.
   ``I'm not fuzzy on who voted. I know who was on the committee.
What I don't remember is which ones of them were on at that
particular time,'' said Greenspan, a former New York business
consultant who took command of the Fed last August.
   The committee meets every few months to chart the nation's
monetary policy.
   Melcher contends that the Fed committee is unconstitutional
because it holds vast power over U.S. economic policy even though
five of its members are not appointed by the president nor do they
undergo Senate confirmation. So far, federal courts have not agreed
with Melcher's assertion.
   At that February meeting, the committee voted to widen the
target range for the growth of the nation's money supply in 1988 _
an action that could bear on inflation and interest rates.
   Greenspan told the committee he was confused because committee
membership is rotated among the presidents of the 12 Fed banks _
and ``we're in the process now of changing.''
   Joseph Coyne, a spokesman for the Fed, said the rotation of
members onto the committee took place on March 1 _ after the last
meeting.
   For the record, the five bank president members of the committee
in February were Gerald E. Corrigan, president of the New York Fed,
a non-rotating position; Edward G. Boehne, Philadelphia; Robert H.
Boykin, Dallas; Silas Keehn, Chicago; and Gary H. Stern, Minnesota.
   The one Greenspan missed? Stern. Instead, he named St. Louis Fed
Chairman Thomas C. Melzer, not a voting member of the committee
then or now.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
