<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LegalImmigration     03-16 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Legal Immigration,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Clears Measure To Set Cap On Legal Immigration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate sponsors of a bill to change the
nation's legal immigration system say they'll begin negotiations
with key House members, and push for final passage this year.
   Despite the Senate's 88-4 vote Tuesday for the legislation,
there is no indication that the House is ready to tackle the bil 16
months after Congress enacted a landmark law to curb illegal
immigration.
   The current immigration control bill took six years to pass
Congress, as large numbers of special interest groups prevented a
consensus until the fall of 1986.
   In contrast, the new legislation was guided through the Senate
with a minimum of debate by Democrat Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts and Republican Alan K. Simpson of Wyoming. They had
smoothed the way by holding extensive discussions with their
colleagues.
   The bill deals with those who apply through normal government
channels to come here _ not with illegal immigrants.
   The Senate measure would establish a cap on legal immigration to
the United States. It would maintain the current priority for
applicants with relatives in this country, but vastly expand
immigration visas for those with needed labor and professional
skills.
   The most influential House member on immigration matters,
Judiciary Committee Chairman Peter W. Rodino Jr., has said he wants
to move slowly until Congress has a better idea of how the 1986 law
is working.
   That means no immediate action, but does not rule out approval
of the legislation later this year.
   Kennedy and Simpson said they plan to initiate discussions with
Rodino soon.
   Simpson's spokeswoman, Mary Kay Hill, said the senator thinks
House leaders ``can see the need to reform the (legal immigation)
system.''
   Others expected to be part of the consultations include Rep.
Romano Mazzoli, D-Ky., chairman of the Judiciary panel's
immigration subcommittee; Rep. Patrick L. Swindall of Georgia,
ranking Republican on the subcommittee; and Rep. Charles E.
Schumer, D-N.Y., who has introduced a measure similar to the Senate
bill.
   The Senate measure is expected to allow more Western Europeans
into the country by expanding the number of visas for those without
family members here.
   Sponsors say the family preference system has resulted in 85
percent of the immigrants to the United States coming from Asia and
Latin America.
   Ninety percent of the people immigrating to the United States
arrive under the family system. The remaining 10 percent come in
under other categories including job and professional skills.
   Rodino has expressed worry that any new bill would interfere
with family reunification. Simpson said that would not happen,
because the Senate's cap is 100,000 above the currrent figures.
   The maximum number of visas under the Senate bill would be
590,000 annually.
   Under this umbrella, 470,000 visas in each of the first three
years (440,000 thereafter) would be reserved for family
immigration, and 120,000 (150,000 after three years) would be for
the new ``independent'' category.
   Currently, spouses and minor children of U.S. citizens can enter
the country without limitation.
   Schumer's bill would have a more generous cap of 750,000,
including refugees fleeing from persecution. The Senate cap does
not include refugees, who now are admitted under a separte law that
sets annual limits. The current refugee cap is 68,500.
   Schumer has said there may be attempts in the House to link a
legal immigration bill with proposals to extend an amnesty program
for some of those who came here illegally. The 1986 law grants
legalization to those who have lived in this country since before
Jan. 1, 1982, but the program ends May 4.
   Simpson opposes an extension, and conservative senators would be
expected to filibuster if an extension were added to a legal
immigration bill, according to Simpson and Kennedy staffers.
   Rodino has favored an extension, but has not said whether he
desires linking the issues.
   Voting against the bill in the Senate were Democrat Dennis
DeConcini of Arizona, and three Republicans: Jesse Helms of North
Carolina, Pete Wilson of California and Mark Hatfield of Oregon.
</TEXT>
