<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RadiationRelease     03-16 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Radiation Release,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say NRC Statements May Imperil Prosecution Of Spill Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors fear that statements by
Nuclear Regulatory Commission officials may have jeopardized their
investigation of a 1986 radioactive spill at an Ohio military base,
according to agency documents.
   The Democratic staff of the Senate Governmental Affairs
Committee released documents Tuesday that include a memo from an
NRC official who said other NRC representatives believed
regulations governing the incident were ambiguous and open to
interpretation.
   The memo also said Christopher Barnes, assistant U.S. attorney
for the southern district of Ohio, believed those statements may
have ``significantly impacted'' on the chances for a successful
prosecution of officials involved in the spill.
   The case involves a Sept. 18, 1986, spill of highly radioactive
Americium-241 at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base near Dayton, Ohio.
The spill occurred when workers opened an unlabeled drum at a base
storage facility.
   Air Force officials have said almost no radiation escaped from
the building despite a second spill Oct. 6 while a cleanup was
under way. The building eventually had to be torn down at a cost of
$1 million.
   An inspection by the NRC's Region III office in Chicago
determined that the Air Force's failure to report the incident
promptly violated an NRC regulation requiring disclosure within 24
hours of any incident that threatens to shut down operations of a
facility for one day or more or causes over $2,000 in property
damage.
   The documents released by the Senate committee included a
January memo from Eugene T. Pawlik, director of the NRC's Region
III investigations field office in Chicago. Pawlik's memo refers to
a December 1987 meeting between two NRC officials at the agency's
Region IV office in Arlington, Texas, and Barnes.
   Pawlik said Barnes met with Jerry Everett, nuclear materials
safety section chief for the NRC, and Charles Cain, radiation
specialist.
   According to the NRC memo, Everett said the NRC regulations
governing disclosure were ambiguous and the NRC had not
communicated to the Air Force a full interpretation of how the
regulations were to be implemented.
   And Cain stated that the first spill was open to interpretation
and not reportable and that in his mind the Air Force was not
negligible in waiting to file a report.
   ``I think it is a fair assessment to say that the two recent
interviews of Everett and Cain have at this late date placed most,
if not all, of the ... investigation in jeopardy,'' Pawlik said in
the memo.
   Everett and Cain declined comment on the documents Tuesday
through a spokesman.
   Americium powder is not considered dangerous on the skin, but
small amounts can cause cancer if inhaled or otherwise introduced
into the body.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
