<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BaptistFiring     03-16 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baptist Firing,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baptist Minister Fired For Saying Jews Don't Need Jesus To be
Saved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNION, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Southern Baptist minister says he was fired
from his denomination's regional mission board because he believes
Jews can achieve salvation without converting to Christianity.
   The Rev. George Sheridan of the First Baptist Church here was
regional director of interfaith witness for the Southern Baptist
Convention's Home Mission Board for 12 years. The region runs from
North Carolina to Maine and west to Michigan.
   As director of the interfaith witness, Sheridan was the Southern
Baptist liaison with other religious groups, including Jews.
   A statement from the mission board's Atlanta headquarters said
Sheridan ``was not fired or terminated'' but ``declined transfer''
from New Jersey to a position as an editorial assistant at the
headquarters.
   But Sheridan, 45, said Tuesday he was fired, and has hired an
attorney to counter any claims by the mission board that he
resigned.
   The minister believes he was fired because he opposed Southern
Baptist plans to begin a program aimed at converting Jews. The
program was discussed at a private meeting in New York last year.
   Sheridan said he was asked in June to submit to the board a
written statement about his theological views about Jews.
   ``In the absence of any Biblical contradiction, I believe that
the Jews of today, as ever, receive salvation through their having
been chosen by God in covenant with Abraham, Moses and the
prophets,'' Sheridan wrote in his statement.
   He said board members grilled him about his views when he was
summoned to a special meeting in Atlanta in November. The board
informed him in a letter dated Jan. 9 that he was being assigned,
he said.
   Sheridan said he has not been able to determine if the board
considered his views heretical, and added that the board had not
given him a specific reason for removing him from his post.
   In 1987, the national convention of the United Church of Christ
accepted the view that Jews can achieve salvation without believing
in Jesus. Opposition to attempts to convert Jews often is based on
this view.
</TEXT>
