<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     03-16 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Lawmakers Flirt With Big New Trade Subsidy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers may make a massive new farm subsidy
program part of sweeping trade legislation, while its chief backer
argues that U.S. trade negotiators want it despite the threat of a
presidential veto.
   The subsidy plan known as a ``triggered marketing loan'' was
included in the Senate version of the 1,000-page trade bill. House
and Senate negotiators are working on a compromise.
   Final action on the loan program was postponed when House
Agriculture Chairman E. ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas, said Tuesday
that Senate Agriculture Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., had the
votes but wanted a few revisions.
   Under marketing loan programs, some of which already are in
effect, producers receive the U.S. price for their crops, which are
then sold at world market prices. The taxpayers make up the
difference.
   The plan under consideration would create such provisions for
wheat, corn and soybeans but only if current negotiations failed to
produce an agreement among the nation's trading partners to reduce
agricultural subsidies by the 1990 wheat marketing year.
   Leahy said he was convinced of the need for a triggered
marketing loan on a trip to Geneva last week to get a progress
report on negotiations aimed at reaching a new General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
   He said European negotiators have been ``arrogant'' in their
rejection of U.S. demands for an end to export subsidies. He said
Americans at the table in Geneva favor the triggered marketing loan
as a ``club'' to hold over the Europeans and prod them on the issue.
   ``If you were talking to some of the people we have to negotiate
with, then you might think we need it, too,'' Leahy said.
   In other action, the panel approved expanding the 1985 Export
Enhancement Program by more than $1 billion to $2.5 billion. It
provides bonuses in the form of government-held commodities to
exporters to ship American commodities that they acquired at U.S.
prices.
   Critics of the triggered marketing loan program said that the
sum involved could strain the budget.
   ``This is potentially a huge sum of money we're talking about in
agricultural programs,'' said Rep. Sam Gibbons, D-Fla., whose
home-state growers are often wary of anything that could prompt
restrictions abroad against orange and grapefruit exports.
   Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, said the use of such a measure
as a bargaining chip would not be credible now because it would
require reshuffling budget priorities.
   Stenholm did say he favored the objective. He said the United
States should tell the European Community: ``If they have unlimited
supplies of money, it's going to cost all of it and we're going to
raise you five.''
   Gibbons presented a letter from Agriculture Secretary Richard
Lyng, U.S. Trade Representative Clayton K. Yeutter and other
administration officials suggesting that attaching the program
could prompt a presidential veto for the trade bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
