<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0805,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says His Message Has Created Fervor Across The Country</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Jackson quotes; pick up 5th graf pvs
bgng ``Jackson voted...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson set aside his disappointment in
finishing second in his home state primary Tuesday night and
focused on his overall strength, saying ``I am where every
candidate wishes he could be tonight.''
   Jackson had predicted he would finish first in Illinois and
defeat another favorite son, Paul Simon. But the results showed
just the opposite.
   ``I finished second, it seems, in Illinois,'' Jackson said.
``(But) I'm a winner. I am the leading contender for the Democratic
nomination. I am where every candidate wishes he could be tonight.''
   A noticeably tired Jackson told supporters at a downtown Chicago
hotel that both he and Simon had reason to celebrate. Illinois
voters, he said, ``paid their respects on a sitting senator who
focused on one state.''
   Jesse Jackson voted near his South Side home earlier in the day,
accompanied by sons Jesse Jr., 23, and Jonathan, 22, at the Bryn
Mawr Community Church.
   The Democratic candidate said his message to ``stop drugs from
coming into our country, save our jobs, secure our farmers and
invest in our children'' has touched voters and given them
something to fight for.
   ``I have run all the way, and we've been winning all the way,
and we'll keep winning,'' Jackson said. Jackson had hoped to add
Illinois to a string of successes over the last week, beginning
with Super Tuesday and continuing over the weekend in South
Carolina. He and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis top the
delegate count.
   Jackson voted shortly after 9 a.m. in a small church room jammed
with reporters, photographers and a handful of bewildered-looking
voters.
   Afterward, donning a topcoat on a chilly day, Jackson said he
was touched by ``the joy I see in my children voting. When I was
their age, I did not have the right to vote.''
   ``It says a lot about the greatness of America, the fact that we
have the right to grow to our potential,'' Jackson said. ``Hope is
going to prevail.''
   The South Carolina native said he has been the most effective
and best managed candidate, despite relatively weak financing.
   ``If my opponents had my budget, they could not compete,''
Jackson said. ``If I had their budgets, they could not compete.''
   Jackson, whose delegate total was second only to Massachusetts
Gov. Michael Dukakis' going into Tuesday's primary, said he has
broadened his base of support since waging his first presidential
campaign four years ago.
   ``Expectations are higher; the experience factor is greater and
I've had a chance to serve more people,'' Jackson said. ``People
who feel that the process was not working for them find hope in the
campaign. ... Now they feel there is a way out. There is hope.''
</TEXT>
