<1ST_LINE>u p AM-IllinoisBallot 3rd-Writethru a0924 03-16 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Illinois Ballot, 3rd - Writethru, a0924,0744</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Byrne Loses Bid To Regain Office In Chicago; Michel Shrugs Off</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Challenger
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Michel's 1982 challenger
wins primary, adds updated voting percentages, early returns on
Cubs ballpark vote. CORRECTS courtesy title for Pucinski to Mrs.
sted Ms. Picks up at dash.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Jane Byrne's bid for a political
comeback ended in defeat Tuesday, but House Minority Leader Bob
Michel, President Reagan's point man in Congress, easily overcame
his first GOP primary challenge in 32 years.
   Michel's Democratic arch-foe, attorney G. Douglas Stephens, won
the Democratic primary, setting the stage for a November rematch of
the 1982 contest that almost cost Michel his 18th District seat.
   With nearly three-quarters of the votes counted, Michel defeated
Tazewell County Board Chairman James E. Unsicker by 85 percent to
15 percent, while Stephens beat an unemployed recent college
graduate, Justin Z. West, 89 percent to 11 percent.
   The state Board of Elections said between 45 percent and 48
percent of the state's 5.9 million registered voters went to the
polls.
   In Chicago, Mrs. Byrne lost to Aurelia Pucinski in a race for
the Democratic nomination for clerk of the circuit court. With
nearly three-quarters of the vote reported, Mrs. Puchinski had 53
percent of the Democratic primary vote.
   ``It means that when the people spoke, they apparently shouted.
... I am very good at taking hints,'' Mrs. Byrne said. Asked
whether she would consider running for office again, she said,
``I'm not even thinking of it right now.''
   Ed Vrdolyak, former Democratic powerbroker who left the party,
was unopposed on the Republican side and will face Mrs. Pucinski in
November.
   Also back on Illinois ballots were followers of political
extremist Lyndon LaRouche. At least 20 LaRouche supporters were
candidates in races ranging from president to county register of
deeds.
   In Southern Illinois, the retirement of veteran Rep. Melvin
Price, a Democrat, set off a four-man scramble in the 21st District
primary. Vying for the party's nomination were St. Clair County
Board Chairman Jerry F. Costello, Madison County Auditor Pete
Fields; former Price administrative aide Mike Mansfield and
perennial local candidate Steve Maragides.
   In the 22nd District, state Sen. Glenn Poshard of Carterville
was unopposed in the Democratic primary as he moved to succeed Rep.
Kenneth Gray, who is retiring after 12 terms. Pete Prineas of
Carbondale and Patrick J. Kelley of Carbondale sought the GOP
nomination.
   Chicago voters held a non-binding referendum on the training of
Illinois National Guard troops in Central America. With roughly
three-quarters of the precincts reporting, those wanted to stop
sending Illinois troops to Central America outnumbered those
favoring the foreign-training program about 2-to-1.
   Neighbors of Chicago's Wrigley Field also opposed night games at
the Cubs' vintage ballpark, piling up 3-to-1 margin in early
returns in a non-binding referendum. With four of 21 precincts
counted, 692 voters opposed lighting Wrigley for night baseball and
237 supported night games.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Chicago's City Council in February approved lights at Wrigley
Field, the only major-league ballpark without them, after years of
controversy. The issue pitted neighborhood groups concerned about
noise, litter and parking problems against the Cubs' owners,
Tribune Co., which argued the team was losing prime-time television
revenues.
   The latest bid for office by Mrs. Byrne, who lost the mayor's
office to Harold Washington in 1983 after one term, was made
without the backing of the party, which supported her opponent,
Mrs. Pucinski. Vrdolyak became a Republican after a failed
third-party challenge to Washington.
   Michel defeated Stephens six years ago with 51.6 percent of the
vote after the toughest campaign fight of his career. His office
attributed the tight race to redistricting.
   The LaRouche candidates were back two years after winning the
Democratic primary for lieutenant governor and secretary of state.
Illinois Democrats tried without success this year to remove La
Rouche candidates from the party.
   In the 21st Congressional District, the winner of the Democratic
fight will face Republican Robert H. ``Bob'' Gaffner, who was
unopposed in the primary. In 1986, he came within 943 votes of
upsetting Price, who is leaving Capitol Hill after 44 years.
   Gray held his 22nd District seat from 1955 to 1975, when he
retired for health reasons, and in 1985 returned to Congress for
two additional terms.
</TEXT>
