<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     03-16 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Puts Best Face on Third-Place Finish In Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Michael Dukakis
declared himself undaunted by a third-place finish in the Illinois
primary, saying ``the field is wide open'' in coming contests.
   ``Now we move on to Michigan where there are no favorite sons,''
a somewhat subdued Dukakis said at a news conference Tuesday night
at a Boston television station.
   Two Illinois home-state favorites _ Sen. Paul Simon and civil
rights leader Jesse Jackson, who has made Chicago his home _
finished well ahead of the Massachusetts governor. On the other
hand, Dukakis' showing was far better than that of Sen. Albert Gore
Jr. of Tennessee, who failed to demonstrate any appreciable
strength outside his Southern base.
   Dukakis said his third-place showing in a state where he
invested more than $350,000 was not a setback.
   ``I don't get disappointed. ... I was running against two
citizens of Illinois who had strong bases and a great deal of
support from those who know them,'' Dukakis said. ``We did what I
can characterize was a respectable third.''
   Those around the Massachusetts governor echoed his contention
that his showing was good under the circumstances. Leslie Dach, a
spokesman for the Dukakis campaign, ``We did as well as we
expected.'' Campaign manager Susan Estrich added, ``We did beat all
the non-favorite sons.''
   During the Illinois campaign, Dukakis had said a vote for Simon
would increase the chances of a brokered Democratic National
Convention, something he said would be a ``disaster.''
   Tuesday night, Dukakis said, ``I've been making a number of
calls around the country to key Democrats and there is an
overwhelming sentiment that we should get behind a nominee.
   ``I don't believe we have any front-runners; I don't think we're
going to have a front-runner until the convention,'' Dukakis said.
   The seven days between Super Tuesday and the Illinois primary
left Dukakis too little time to attract strong support in Illinois,
he said.
   But he said effort and money expended in Illinois will pay off
later, if he is the Democratic nominee.
   Dukakis wasn't about to make any bold predictions on Michigan's
caucus March 26.
   ``I don't have to win any primary. I have to do as well as I
possibly can. When you have a multi-candidate field, the vote tends
to get split up,'' he said, adding that he hoped Michigan would
help winnow the field.
   Dach said Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, the big Democratic
loser on Super Tuesday, would be competing fiercely with Dukakis
for labor votes in Michigan.
</TEXT>
