<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson     03-16 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Scales Back Campaign, But Vows To Continue To Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHESAPEAKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Pat Robertson ran a distant
third in the Illinois primary but repeated his vow to continue his
campaign to the national convention.
   ``I am in all the way to New Orleans,'' Robertson said Tuesday
night, insisting that he was ``not a bit in the world
disappointed'' over the Illinois results.
   Robertson has spent nearly $25 million on a campaign that has
gained 17 national convention delegates, according to The
Associated Press tally. The federal spending limit for primary
campaigns is $27 million.
   Thus, Robertson acknowledged, he must run a drastically
scaled-back effort from here on.
   ``My own personal travel will continue but as far as a
full-blown media campaign, I can't afford that any more,'' he said
after meeting Tuesday afternoon with Republican National Committee
Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf
   But, he added: ``I have enough money to keep in the race through
...the convention.''
   Marc Nuttle, Robertson's campaign manager, said the exact amount
that could be spent before hitting the limit would not be known
before the next seven to 10 days.
   ``Whether it's between $2 million and $3 million or less than $2
million it will be enough for the campaign,'' he said.
   Richard Pinsky, national field director for Americans for
Robertson, characterized the new campaign as ``mean and lean. We
have always been labor-intensive and have won on organization and
grass-roots support from volunteers.''
   Robertson said he would campaign in California, which holds its
primary June 7, to help local candidates with their races.
   ``We would like to see Republican majorities enunciating major
conservative causes by 1990 or 1992,'' he said.
   Robertson said his meeting with Fahrenkopf was mainly to plan
the role of Robertson delegates in the convention.
   ``We talked about housekeeping things,'' he said.
   Nuttle said the talks were to ensure that the convention went
smoothly, and that Robertson's backers, many of whom have never
attended a national convention, are included in the preparation for
the event.
   ``Our goal is to unify the party,'' Robertson said. ``I am going
to be the conservative champion.''
</TEXT>
