<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dole     03-16 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dole,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Vows To `Hang In There' Despite Illinois Defeat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Dole says his Republican presidential
campaign is still alive and ``we're just going to hang in there''
despite another crushing loss to George Bush.
   But the Kansas senator has been without a win for three weeks,
and the primary calendar offers him little hope: the next GOP
contest is March 29 in Connecticut, another one of the vice
president's home states.
   Dole returned home for a few days, flying into Washington as the
disappointing Illinois results began unfolding. Bush rolled up more
than half of the popular vote, and more importantly, held a 3-1
ratio in distribution of the 82 GOP delegates.
   Despite the bleak news, Dole told reporters, ``We're doing all
right. We're just going to hang in there. There's a long way to go
yet.''
   Pressed on whether he would continue his candidacy, he said,
``We're staying in, we're staying in.''
   Dole's campaign was stunned by Bush's 16-state sweep on Super
Tuesday, and he ordered massive staff layoffs and a halt to all
advertising in Illinois late last week. At the urging of some
aides, Dole considered giving up his White House hopes but decided
to stay in.
   He campaigned in Wisconsin and Connecticut as Illinois primary
voters went to the polls, saying: ``I don't give up very easily.''
   In Hartford, he said, ``This is called a surprise state from
time to time. We're ready for one. We could use it.''
   Dole hasn't had much to cheer about since Feb. 23, when he won
contests in South Dakota and Minnesota. A week before that, he was
surprised by Bush's come-from-behind win in New Hampshire, the
first signal of chaos in Dole's campaign.
   Little over a month ago, Dole was the early leader with his
impressive victory over Bush in Iowa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ExitPolls     03-16 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Exit Polls,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exit Polls Show `Little Chinks' in Bush's Armor Despite Big
Illinois Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even as George Bush rolled up a victory in the
Republican primary in Illinois, exit polls indicated ``little
chinks in his armor'' that could bedevil him in the general
election, analysts say.
   Bush on Tuesday overwhelmed Sen. Bob Dole in virtually all
ideological and demographic groups of the Republican electorate,
cementing his huge lead in the GOP race.
   ``It's a blowout,'' said ABC News poll analyst Doug Muzzio.
   Results were far less clear on the Democratic side, where Sen.
Paul Simon cashed in on his favorite-son status and Jesse Jackson
rode another huge wave of black support to finish first and second
respectively in their home state.
   While Bush swamped his Republican opponents, his ratings on
leadership and toughness were weaker than may be expected from a
prohibitive front-runner, said NBC News poll analyst Sheldon
Gawiser.
   Additionally, Bush failed to win the independents who voted in
the GOP primary.
   ``If Bush is going to win the general election, he's got to
start attracting independent voters,'' said CBS News poll chief
Warren Mitofsky.
   The results did not foreshadow problems for Bush within the GOP;
he even won among former television evangelist Pat Robertson's
natural supporters, born-again Christians and voters concerned
about so-called ``morality issues.''
   But among the 23 percent of Republicans who said leadership was
a key issue, Dole and Bush split the vote, ABC found.
   ``A prohibitive front-runner should be showing some leadership,
particularly given the fact that he holds the second-highest office
in the land,'' Muzzio said.
   In NBC's poll, 55 percent of GOP voters said Bush was tough
enough to be a good president, but 24 percent said he was not and
21 percent were not sure. The 55 percent was ``a pretty small
number,'' considering that it came among Republican primary voters,
said Gawiser.
   Thirty 30 percent of Republicans told NBC that Bush would be a
very strong leader, 42 percent said he would be somewhat strong, 16
percent said not very strong, 6 percent said not at all strong and
6 percent didn't know. Again, ``That's not a terrific standing
among Republican primary voters,'' Gawiser said.
   In another measure, a plurality of Republican voters, 41
percent, said Bush had not fully disclosed his knowledge of the
Iran-Contra affair, while 32 percent said he had and 21 percent
were not sure, NBC found.
   While the issue has not been a significant one in the minds of
Republican voters, ``it's there,'' Gawiser said. ``That's a
tomorrow story,'' one that could gain significance in the general
election.
   These Bush results amounted to ``little chinks in his armor,''
not major campaign problems, Gawiser noted. Muzzio noted that the
flaws spotted in the ABC poll also were minor, with Dole beating
Bush among the tiny number of Republicans who rated ``honesty'' or
``getting things done'' as key.
   ``It doesn't tell us all that much about Bush's electability,''
Muzzio said. ``But it certainly indicates he's not a prohibitive
favorite to beat a Democrat.''
   In the Democratic race, weaknesses were demonstrated most
strongly by Sen. Albert Gore of Tennessee, who failed to turn his
Super Tuesday victories into a sizable showing, and Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri, who finished last.
   ``The G-boys just didn't show,'' said Muzzio. ``They were
squeezed by the hometown favorites.''
   One favorite, Simon, even drew voters who doubt he can succeed.
ABC said just 40 percent of Simon's supporters gave him the best
chance to win in November, and 35 percent named Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis even though they voted for Simon. NBC said only 35
percent of Simon's voters thought he would win the nomination,
while 39 percent picked Dukakis to win it.
   Jackson enjoyed his now-customary huge black support: He
received 91 percent of the black vote, which was about a quarter of
the Democratic turnout, ABC said. But he won only 8 percent of the
white vote by ABC's count, 7 percent by the CBS News-New York Times
poll.
   ``Jackson still can't attract any white votes,'' said Mitofsky.
``He got 7 percent. And that's not enough.''
   Though Dukakis finished third, ABC said a plurality of
Democrats, 35 percent, thought he had the best chance of winning
the general election. Jackson had 27 percent, Simon, 18 percent.
   The margin of sampling error for the results was about 5 points
for most subgroups.
</TEXT>
