<HEAD>Congress OKs Prime Site for Black Patriots Monument</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has given final congressional
approval to legislation authorizing prime federal parkland in
Washington for a national monument to the 5,000 black patriots who
served in the American Revolution.
   The voice vote by the House on Tuesday followed Senate approval
of the bill on Feb. 26.
   The House is expected to approve similar, Senate-backed
legislation today that would authorize a choice Washington site for
a national memorial to Americans who fought in the Korean War.
   Rep. James J. Florio, D-N.J., said the Korean War memorial, to
be built on the mall that extends from the Lincoln Memorial to the
Capitol, will be ``a fitting and long-overdue monument to the
55,000 Amricans who lost their lives in a forgotten war.''
   Private sponsors say they have raised $2.5 million toward a goal
of $10 million for the Korean War memorial. The black patriots
monument, also expected to be built on the mall, will cost an
estimated $4 million.
   Both the black patriots and the Korean War monuments previously
were authorized by Congress, and will be built with private
donations.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<HEAD>Judicial Panel Says House Should Consider Impeachment of Judge
Nixon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of judges that makes policy for the
federal courts is urging the House to consider impeaching U.S.
District Judge Walter L. Nixon of Mississippi, who is scheduled to
go to prison for perjury on March 23.
   The group, the Judicial Conference of the United States, on
Tuesday unanimously supported a resolution that says
``consideration of impeachment may be warranted.''
   Nixon, 59, was sentenced to five years in prison following his
1986 perjury conviction. He has remained a judge but has not been
hearing cases since he was indicted in 1985 although he continues
to be paid his annual salary of $89,500.
   Nixon would forfeit his salary and his eligibility for a pension
at age 65 if he is impeached by the House and removed from office
by the Senate.
   The recommendation that the House consider impeaching him was
approved by a vote of 24-0 by the judges' group. Three members
abstained, including Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, who
traditionally does not vote on such matters.
   Nixon is the third federal judge ever to be indicted for crimes
allegedly committed while in office.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<HEAD>Panel Blames Flying Instructor in 1987 Utah Commuter Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal panel has determined that the
primary cause of a 1987 collision that killed 10 people in Utah was
an instructor's failure to keep his plane out of restricted
airspace during a student training flight.
   The single-engine training plane collided with a SkyWest
commuter plane near Kearns, Utah, on Jan. 15, 1987, while making an
approach to Salt Lake City International Airport after a flight
from Pocatello, Idaho.
   The National Transportation Safety Board on Tuesday absolved the
air traffic controller handling the SkyWest plane. The other
aircraft was flying under visual flight rules and was not under the
direction of air traffic control.
   Nevertheless, the NTSB said the accident might have been avoided
if the private aircraft had equipment that would have provided the
controller information on the plane's altitude. Investigators said
the single-engine Mooney M-20C was on the radar screen, but without
altitude information the controller would not have known the two
planes were about to collide.
   The safety board put the primary blame for the accident on the
instructor of the private aircraft's ``lack of navigational
vigilance ... which led to the unauthorized intrusion'' into the
restricted airspace that surrounds the Salt Lake City airport.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Official Urges End to Speeding Penalties For States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal official is telling Congress that
states whose drivers ignore the 55 mph speed limit should not be
penalized, but two senior lawmakers said they are writing bills
that would do just the opposite.
   Reps. James Howard, D-N.J., chairman of the House Public Works
and Transportation Committee, and Glenn Anderson, D-Calif., who
heads the Public Works surface transportation subcommittee, said
they are working on measures that would extend the penalties to
states that have adopted the 65 mph limit.
   States with 55 mph limits can lose up to 10 percent of their
federal highway aid if monitors find that more than half their
motorists are driving too fast. But when two laws were passed last
year allowing 65 mph driving on many rural highways, the penalties
were not extended to roads where states allow the faster speeds.
   ``The states are clearly in the best position to determine where
speed enforcement is needed to enhance safety,'' Diane K. Steed,
chief of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, said
in a statement delivered Tuesday to Anderson's panel. ``They should
be able to deploy enforcement personnel accordingly, without the
threat of losing federal funds.''
   Lawmakers from the 11 states that have retained the 55 mph limit
have complained that it is unfair for their states to face the loss
of federal assistance while states that permit faster driving
cannot be penalized for motorists speeding on 65 mph roads.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>---</HEAD>
<HEAD>Studies Say Changes Needed at VA, With or Without Cabinet-Level
Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent study group says significant
changes are needed in the way the Veterans Administration is being
managed whether or not it is elevated to Cabinet status.
   In its report to the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee, a
panel of the National Academy of Public Administration said it
found ``little evidence'' in its study that Cabinet-level status
would materially improve the VA's mission of providing for the
present and future needs of veterans.
   ``The panel does not believe that such an elevation would
significantly improve either access to the president, the adequacy
of necessary resources, or the organization, management and
delivery of high-quality services and benefits,'' the report said.
   The seven-member panel said it ``does recognize the potential
political value of raising the public visibility of the needs of
veterans and the programs designed to meet these needs by making VA
a department in the president's Cabinet. However, given the broad
political support which already exists for the VA and its programs,
the gain would be at the margin.''
   The academy panel and the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, did not make recommendations on
whether the VA should become part of the president's Cabinet.
</TEXT>
