<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Soar In Morning Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with closing figures. PICKS up
3rd graf pvs bgng, Volume in the ... DELETES 6th graf pvs, In
foreign exchange... to conform.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose slightly in Tokyo trading
Wednesday, while stock prices rallied in heavy trading, ending the
day sharply higher.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which climbed 42.16 points Tuesday, closed the day
at 25,704.43 points, up 228.76 points, or 0.90 percent, from
Tuesday's close.
   The U.S. currency closed at 127.49 yen, up 0.24 yen from
Tuesday's close, after opening Wednesday at 127.38.
   Volume in the first section was estimated at a heavy 1.1 billion
shares, compared with 550 million shares traded Tuesday morning.
   Individual investors were active buyers of heavy industrials,
helping to absorb some selling of those issues by institutional
investors such as life insurance companies, traders said.
   The Nikkei average's previous closing high since the Oct. 19
market crash was 25,682.82 points on March 2.
   ``The yen is easing against the dollar...but everyone is waiting
for the latest U.S. trade data,'' said an exchange dealer at a
major commercial bank in Tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The U.S. Commerce Department is scheduled Thursday to release
the nation's foreign trade figures for January.
