<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,1000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Set on GOP Delegate Slate Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hearing is set for today on whether the
delegate slates of Republican presidential candidates Pat Robertson
and Sen. Bob Dole should be on the primary ballot in all of New
York's 34 congressional districts.
   Supporters of the two GOP contenders filed a civil rights action
at federal court in Manhattan Monday, claiming that state election
laws violate the Voting Rights Act by making it unfairly difficult
for their candidates to compete for delegates in the April 19 New
York primary.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard B. Sand scheduled the hearing on a
request by Dole and Robertson supporters that he should order
delegate slates for their candidates placed on the ballot in every
congressional district, pending the outcome of the lawsuit.
   Under state law, candidates had to get 1,250 signatures on
petitions from registered Republicans in each of the state's 34
congressional districts to get their delegate slates on the ballot.
All the signatures had to be gathered between Jan. 5 and Feb. 11,
1988.
   Only Vice President George Bush's campaign was able to
accomplish that and as a result, Bush slates are running unopposed
in about half the districts, according to the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Keeps Strong Lead over Jackson in Washington Democratic
Caucuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis holds a
strong lead over Jesse Jackson according to results released from
last week's Democratic presidential precinct caucuses by Washington
state party officials.
   With about 68 percent of the precincts reporting the results of
last Tuesday's balloting, Dukakis had 45 percent, Jackson 35
percent, and 14 percent were uncommitted.
   All the other candidates were well off the pace, with Illinois
Sen. Paul Simon a weak fourth at 4 percent, Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. at 2 percent and Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri with 1
percent.
   The Democratic Party made no effort to collect results statewide
on caucus night, gathering precinct returns slowly by mail instead.
   Republicans say it will be at least another week before county
chairmen submit the names of GOP delegates elected in last week's
precinct caucuses.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>NY Assembly's No. 2 Democrat Backs Gore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s bid for the
Democratic presidential nomination has been endorsed by New York
state Assembly Majority Leader James Tallon.
   In making his announcement Tuesday, the Binghamton Democrat and
former chairman of the Assembly's Health Committee stressed Gore's
work on the federal Organ Transplant Act and his grasp of new
technologies.
   The Legislature's No. 1 Democrat, Assembly Speaker Mel Miller of
Brooklyn, has yet to endorse any of the Democratic candidates
although his wife is running in the state's April 19 presidential
primary as a prospective Gore delegate.
   ``I've been speaking to the Gore people more frequently than
anybody else, but I've not finally made a decision,'' said Miller.
   Also not taking sides yet is New York's top Democrat, Gov. Mario
Cuomo. Cuomo has said he doesn't know when, or even if, he will
endorse any of the Democratic candidates.
   Cuomo has bridled at suggestions that he's holding off an
endorsement because he's hoping a deadlocked national convention
would turn to him as a candidate. While Cuomo has said he won't
seek the nomination, he's refused to rule out accepting a draft for
the nomination if there's a deadlocked convention.
