<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cuomo Task Force Proposes Election Day Registration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gubernatorial task force has proposed that
New Yorkers be allowed to register and vote on Election Day.
   Issuing a 94-page report Tuesday, the Governor's Task Force on
Encouraging Electoral Participation noted that Maine, Minnesota and
Wisconsin had ``experienced a substantial increase in voter
turnout'' after switching to such a system.
   The 17-member commission included officials from Gov. Marion
Cuomo's administration, the state Legislature, the New York State
and City boards of elections, college student representatives and
private citizens.
   The task force conducted a poll of 3,500 New Yorkers and talked
to focus groups. Cuomo said it had done all of that for ``less than
$20,000.''
   In the end, the task force came up with 30 recommendations to
get more New Yorkers to the polls by, among other things, allowing
college students to register to vote in their college communities
when they register for classes.
   The group also recommended that elementary and secondary schools
be required to offer classes that stress the importance of voting,
that public employees be allowed to assist New Yorkers in filling
out voter registration cards, and that the state create a permanent
state primary day. The state primary day has varied from summer to
fall during recent elections. It is scheduled for Sept. 8 this
year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Professor to Study State Voting Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apathy often is blamed for low voter
turnouts, but the real reason people don't go to the polls may be
found in examining voter registration laws, says a University of
Michigan researcher.
   Many states have voter registration laws that discriminate
against the electorate by making it difficult to register, contends
political science Professor Steven J. Rosenstone, who is
coordinating a nationwide study of registration laws.
   Rosenstone said preliminary research suggests that modified
voter registration laws would increase overall voter turnout by
about 9 percent, bringing about 16 million more people to the polls.
   ``Blacks, Hispanics and the poor would benefit the most from the
changes,'' said Rosenstone, who is coordinating the nationwide
project funded by the Ford Foundation.
   In most states, voters have to register weeks before interest
peaks on election day, leave work early or travel an inconvenient
distance to the registration office, and finally, stand in a long
line, Rosenstone said.
   Almost half the 180 million eligible U.S. voters, including more
than half of the 20 million eligible black voters, aren't expected
to go to the polls in November, Rosenstone said.
   ``Contrast this situation to Canada, where registration
officials go door to door to make sure every eligible voter is on
the rolls. Their election-day turnout averages about 68 percent _
about 15 percent higher than in the United States,'' he said.
</TEXT>
