<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WaspSting-Liability     03-16 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wasp Sting-Liability,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards $1.7 Million for Wasp Sting that Left Man Paralyzed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded $1.45 million to a man left
paralyzed from a 1985 wasp sting at an inn.
   The jury Tuesday awarded the money to Joseph Febesh, 68, after
finding the the Fox Hollow Inn of Woodbury liable for the sting
that within an hour put him into a three-week coma.
   Febesh, former manager of the golf program at the Doral Country
Club in Miami Beach, is unable to talk, feed himself or use his
arms and legs in any way at all, according to his lawyer Joseph
Napoli.
   Febesh's wife, Shirley, was awarded $250,000 for loss of her
husband's companionship and services.
   The Febeshes were at a 50th wedding anniversary party in the
garden of the inn when they noticed yellow jackets around the
garbage and the food. They told the head waiter, who shrugged off
the situation, Napoli said, and about an hour later Febesh was
stung in the hand.
   Napoli said the wasp's venom attacked Febesh's brain stem and
part of his spinal cord, putting him in a coma. He said Febesh,
paralyzed since regaining consciousness, is undergoing physical
therapy at a Miami hospital.
   The jury, after a 10-day trial before State Supreme Court
Justice Harold Baer, awarded $3.4 million to the Febeshes. The
court reduced the verdict by half after the jury found the couple
50 percent negligent.
   Lawyers for the inn argued that the Febeshes should have left
the area if they were worried about the yellow jackets.
</TEXT>
