<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Roemer'sFirstDay     03-16 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Roemer's First Day,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Louisiana Governor Tackles Budget Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer, elected on the
promise of ending waste in government and changing Louisiana's
image of cronyism, dove headfirst into the state's financial
problems by ordering budget cuts and calling the Legislature into
special session.
   During his first full day in office Tuesday, Roemer also huddled
with legislative leaders, visited with foreign dignitaries and took
time out to pose for his official portrait.
   Roemer went to work on measures to solve the fiscal crisis
immediately after his Oct. 24 election victory over Gov. Edwin
Edwards and said Tuesday included ``more of the same.''
   ``I really feel like I've been doing this for 100 days,'' he
said at a news conference. ``I feel the same. I'm still feel
excited about it after 24 hours. I feel good getting into the
substance of it.''
   Just hours after he was inaugurated Monday, Roemer turned down a
stay of execution for Wayne Felde, convicted of killing a
Shreveport police officer in 1978. Felde died in the electric chair
shortly after midnight.
   While Roemer settled into his new job, former officials of the
Edwards administration jammed the three main elevators in
Louisiana's skyscraper Capitol, moving out boxes of personal
belongings.
   Roemer ordered $7.9 million in immediate spending cuts and
summoned the Legislature into a 10-day special session next Monday
to consider government reorganization and giving him emergency
power to cut spending through the rest of the fiscal year without
lawmakers' approval.
   The largest of the new cuts include $2.6 million from the
Department of Health and Human Resources, $2.2 million from the
Department of Public Safety, and about $1.1 million from the
vocational education system.
   Louisiana faces an accumulated four-year budget deficit and cash
shortfall of $1.2 billion.
   The governor can cut up to 20 percent from any budget unit
without legislative approval. Roemer said one idea under
consideration was asking for the power to cut up to 20 percent from
an entire agency and eliminate entire state programs.
   The governor also said he was developing other executive orders
to save the state 10s millions of dollars, primarily through budget
cuts that Edwards refused to impose at Roemer's request.
   ``We are in a position in this fiscal year where the numbers
drive the policy and not the policy driving the numbers,'' Roemer
said. ``When this state is busted, broke, when the deficit is
approaching a number too large to comprehend, the numbers are
driving this now.''
   To alleviate a cash-flow deficit that threatens to shut down
state government, about $156 million in additional cuts from the
state's $5.3 billion budget will have to be found, Roemer said.
   Edwards approved about $36 million in reductions before leaving
office and Roemer's budget team plans to delay state payments to
retirement systems, hold up income tax refund checks and push one
state payday into the next fiscal year to conserve cash.
   Roemer has said new taxes probably will be needed to overcome
the budget deficit. However, he said that topic would not be
considered during the special session.
   Roemer met Tuesday with representatives of the government of
Taiwan about the possibility of building an industrial plant in
Louisiana. After Monday's inauguration, the governor met with
business representatives from Japan and Nigeria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
