<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0559EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     03-16 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>24 Rebels Killed in Fighting With Indian Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian soldiers shot and killed at
least 24 Tamil rebels during search operations in two northeastern
districts, a Sri Lankan military official said today.
   The official, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
said the operations in the Mullaitivu and Kilinochchi districts
began early Tuesday and lasted the entire day. He said eight of
those killed were women and that at least four rebels were injured.
   More than 300 Indian soldiers backed by helicopter gunships and
tanks were involved in the operation, the official said.
   The search operations follow the killing of members of the
majority Sinhalese community, allegedly by the rebels, in
neighbouring Trincomalee district and retaliatory killings of
Tamils by an outlawed Sinhalese group. At least 98 people have died
in Trincomalee in the past two weeks.
   The official said the Indians also had searched unsuccessfully
for members of the People's Liberation Group, an ultra-nationalist
Sinhalese organization.
   At least 50,000 Indian soldiers are in Sri Lanka to disarm Tamil
rebels, who have been waging a separatist guerilla war since 1983.
The Indians were deployed under a peace accord which granted
limited autonomy to the minority Tamils in exchange for an arms
surrender.
   But the Tamils renounced the July 29 accord last fall and since
then they have been battling the Indian soldiers.
   The People's Liberation Front also opposes the peace accord,
saying it grants too many concessions to the Tamils.
   India says more than 400 soldiers and at least 1,100 rebels have
died in the fighting, but the militants claim that most of the
Tamils killed were civilians.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people while
the Sinhalese comprise 75 percent. Tamils say they are
discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who control the army and
the government in Sri Lanka.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
