<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-16 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Dumps Snow on West; Deep South Shivers Under Cold Snap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm from Nevada to Kansas today left up to 6 inches of snow,
while freezing temperatures shattered record lows and threatened
crops in the Deep South.
   Nearly clear skies with light winds helped temperatures drop
throughout the South. By midnight, frost was scattered across
Georgia, Alabama and Mississippi into northern Florida.
   More than 40 cities tied or broke records for low temperatures
on Tuesday. Today, Apalachicola, Fla., had a record low of 39
degrees, one degree colder than the mark set on the same date in
1954. At midnight Tuesday, Tallahassee hit 28 degrees.
   Georgia peach growers were worried about the freezing weather's
effect on the state's crop of an estimated 140 million pounds.
Temperatures of 28 degrees or below can damage peaches in their
early stages.
   ``We don't need cold now,'' said Stephen Myers, a horticulturist
with the University of Georgia Extension Service in Athens.
   In Florida, a forecaster said citrus trees could withstand the
cold, but vegetables that are just weeks away from harvesting are
vulnerable to frost damage.
   ``Definitely, we're in a critical period,'' Larry Pfeiffer, a
specialist with the National Weather Service in Ruskin, said,
referring to central and south Florida vegetables.
   In the West, up to 6 inches of snow fell on Fillmore, Utah, and
heavy snow also was reported over Spanish Fork Canyon and the
Brianhead ski area in southern Utah.
   Snow continued this morning across Wyoming, northern Nevada,
northwestern Montana, northern Minnesota, Michigan, the Ohio
Valley, New York state and northern New England.
   Snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 a.m. EST included 6
inches at Lander, Wyo., 3 inches at Mount Washington, N.H., and 1
inch at Charleston, W.Va.
   High wind warnings were posted over southeast Kern County in
Southern California.
   Today's forecast called for snow extending from eastern Nevada
and northern Arizona across the Rockies into central Kansas. Snow
should be scattered over the Great Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley and
New England. Highs should be in the 20s and 30s from the northern
and central Rockies to New England. Temperatures should warm into
the 50s across much of the south-central and southeastern portion
of the nation. Highs are expected in the 60s in southern and
central Texas, much of Louisiana and the Florida peninsula.
Temperatures also should warm into the 50s and 60s across the West
Coast, the Southern Plateau and the southern half of New Mexico.
Highs in the 70s were expected in the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 4
degrees at Bismarck, N.D., and Rapid City, S.D., to 66 at Phoenix,
Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 30 fair; Boston 31 partly cloudy; Buffalo 29
snow; Charleston, S.C. 30 fair; Cincinnati 22 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 28 snow; Miami 46 fair; New York 32 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 29 fair; Pittsburgh 23 snow; Portland, Maine 29 fair;
Washington 28 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 5 fair; Chicago 28 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
47 fair; Denver 25 windy; Des Moines 28 cloudy; Indianapolis 26
cloudy; Kansas City 21 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 28 cloudy;
Nashville 24 fair; New Orleans 45 fair; St. Louis 24 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 36 fair; Anchorage 27 cloudy; Las Vegas 49
windy; Los Angeles 55 partly cloudy; Phoenix 61 fair; Salt Lake
City 35 cloudy; San Diego 57 cloudy; San Francisco 58 fair; Seattle
44 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 30 cloudy; Toronto 30 cloudy.
</TEXT>
