<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSFraud     03-16 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Fraud,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quack AIDS Treatments May Cost Americans $1 Billion This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Confusion and fear generated by AIDS has
created an unlimited audience for quacks who are expected to take
in $1 billion this year, speakers at the National Health Fraud
Conference said.
   ``Many persons who have AIDS will try anything to defeat it;
many who don't have AIDS will try anything to avoid it,'' said Dr.
John H. Renner, director of the National Health Information Center
in Kansas City. ``That makes it easy for quacks to convert every
trick in their repertoire into an AIDS treatment or preventative.''
   Dr. Robert E. Windom, assistant secretary for health of the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services, called Tuesday for health
professionals to join in an anti-fraud effort.
   Renner said he's seen fraudulent AIDS remedies that include
processed pond scum, hydrogen peroxide injections, the food
preservative BHT, pills derived from AIDS-infected mice and
``herbal'' capsules containing poisonous metals.
   ``We've even discovered a phony doctor who, for a $100 fee, was
injecting his patients with a processed byproduct of their own
urine,'' he said.
   About 400 people attended the two-day conference on health
fraud, including representatives of law enforcement agencies,
consumer groups, medicine, insurance companies and business.
   Michael R. Botwin, a California deputy attorney general, said it
was understandable that people faced with AIDS would try any
treatment, and that it some cases quack treatments provided a
psychological boost.
   ``However, many so-called AIDS treatments are sold with scare
tactics, pose health hazards, or carry the risk of substantial
financial loss,'' he said.
</TEXT>
