<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AquinoTrial     03-16 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aquino Trial,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Sound Expert Says Benigno Aquino Killed With Different
Gun</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tape recordings indicate President
Corazon Aquino's husband was killed with a gun other than that
which officials claim was the murder weapon, a Japanese sound
expert testified today.
   Based on the tapes of voices, footsteps and gunfire, Matsumi
Suzuki also identified four soldiers as the ones who shouted the
Tagalog words ``This is it,'' ``Let me do it'' and ``Shoot''
seconds before former Sen. Benigno Aquino Jr. was shot and killed
on Aug. 21, 1983.
   Suzuki, president of the Japan Acoustics Institute of Tokyo,
made the statements at the trial of 34 soldiers and three civilians
accused of murdering Aquino and Rolando Galman, an alleged
communist agent initially tagged as the assassin.
   Aquino was killed as he walked down the stairway from a China
Airlines plane to the tarmac at Manila airport under military
escort. He was returning to the Philippines from three years' exile
in the United States. Galman was shot and killed by soldiers
immediately after Aquino fell.
   Suzuki, speaking in Japanese through an interpreter, said he
reached his conclusions after analyzing sounds picked up by
journalists' tape recorders during the assassination and the test
firing of various types of guns in studios in Japan and the United
States.
   Chief prosecutor Raul Gonzales told reporters that Suzuki's
testimony supports the prosecution's claim that Aquino was shot on
the stairway, where only soldiers were in a position to shoot him
in the back of the head.
   The military under deposed President Ferdinand Marcos claimed
Aquino was shot by Galman on the tarmac with a .357-caliber Magnum
revolver.
   In his testimony, Suzuki said an analysis of the tape recordings
show that the first shot, which has been established as the one
that killed Aquino, could have come only from a .45-caliber pistol.
   ``The sound of the gunshot was close to the sound of a
.45-caliber automatic pistol,'' Suzuki said. ``The sound was quite
different to a great degree from the sound coming from a .357
Magnum.''
   Suzuki said the sound of the footsteps of Aquino and his four
soldier escorts were clearly picked up by two boom microphones
extended over the top of the stairway, as the party began
descending.
   ``We can clearly analyze the sound of the first step to the
eleventh step,'' Suzuki said referring to the stairway, which had
21 rungs. ``After the eleventh step ... the sound of gunfire was
heard.''
   Suzuki said he could not pinpoint the step where Aquino was shot
but calculated it was between the 11th and 15th rungs.
   The tapes also picked up the words ``Eto na'' (This is it),
followed by ``Ako na. Ako na'' (Let me do it. Let me do it) and
``Pusila. Pusila.'' (Shoot. Shoot.)
   Suzuki said the words ``Eto na'' were uttered by Lt. Jesus de
Castro, chief of the security detail assigned to Aquino, who
remained at the top of the stairs while Aquino was led down.
   The words ``Let me do it'' were said by Sgts. Claro Lat and
Arnulfo de Mesa one after the other, Suzuki said.
   He said the fatal gunshot came after both Castro and Constable
1st Class Mario Lazaga shouted ``Shoot!'' one after the other.
   Suzuki said he identified the voices by comparing voice prints
on the tapes with tape-recorded statements made by soldiers during
a formal investigation shortly after the murder. A five-member
board had required all the soldiers who escorted Aquino to say
those words.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
