<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OrchidLegacy     03-16 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Orchid Legacy,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Leaves $5 Million Estate To Orchid Society</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former auto-parts salesman whose
collection of orchids was among the world's largest has died,
leaving his $5 million estate and its nearly 12,000 orchids to the
American Orchid Society.
   Lewis Vaughn died Monday at age 92.
   ``It's just kind of special to see a man's life turned into such
beauty and love,'' said Pat Pepper Schwab, the city's vice mayor.
   ``He was our best friend, there's no doubt about it,'' said Lee
Cooke, executive director of the society. ``He's going to be very
sadly missed.''
   Vaughn and his late wife, Varina, bought their first orchid
about 50 years ago. He became a leading amateur grower _ one of the
first to develop the yellow phalaenopsis _ and his private
collection is among the world's largest.
   ``Somebody said, `Try an orchid,' and I bought one in a pot, and
the blame thing bloomed. That was a cattleya, C. bowringiana. And I
still have a cutting from it on the mango tree by the office,''
Vaughn said in a 1987 interview.
   On Tuesday, about 9,000 of Vaughn's orchids were blooming.
   ``It's a little bit of heaven here,'' Cooke said.
   Vaughn, who was childless, is survived by six nieces and
nephews. Funeral services were scheduled for Friday afternoon here.
</TEXT>
