<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Carey     03-16 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Carey,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actress Olive Carey Dead At 92</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARPINTERIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Olive Carey, veteran actress of
Hollywood's Golden Age and wife and mother to a pair of famous
Harry Careys, has died. She was 92.
   Born Olive Golden on Jan. 31, 1896, she came from a performing
family headed by her father, famed vaudeville entertainer George
Fuller Golden.
   Mrs. Carey died of natural causes at her home Sunday.
   The actress destined to wed actor Harry Carey appeared on screen
with him in the 1914 silent movie, ``The Sorrowful Shore.'' She
later worked with director D.W. Griffith.
   While the Careys worked under contract for Universal Studios,
she introduced her husband to a 21-year-old prop man, John Ford.
She persuaded Carey to allow the unknown Ford to direct his first
two-reel western, ``The Soul Herder.''
   Ford went on to rank among the top directors in film history.
   They became lifelong friends along with another budding young
western actor, John Wayne.
   Mrs. Carey made several films with Ford, Wayne, her husband and
their son, Harry Carey Jr.
   When Carey died in 1947, Mrs. Carey came out of retirement to
act in such films as ``The Searchers,'' ``The Alamo'' and ``Two
Rode Together.''
   She has appeared with other Hollywood greats such as Jimmy
Stewart, Richard Widmark, Vera Miles and Natalie Wood.
   Mrs. Carey is survived by a sister, Mignonne, her son, Harry
Carey Jr., a daughter, Cappy Carey, six grandchildren and seven
great-grandchildren.
   She was to be memorialized today in a private ceremony at her
home about 75 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
