<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrushFires     03-16 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brush Fires,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hay, Feed Stockpiled for Livestock Roaming Scorched Prairie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ranchers whose rangeland was devastated by
a wildfire that killed about 200 head of cattle are receiving gifts
of about 350,000 pounds of hay daily to keep their operations
going, officials say.
   Many cities around the state are conducting hay drives for
ranchers affected by the fire, said Alan Heirman of the federal
Soil Conservation Service.
   ``We have received a tremendous response to the hay program,''
Heirman said Tuesday. ``Today, we received about 100 different
donations of hay, with promises of close to 15,000 square bales and
500 to 1,000 round bales.''
   The wildfire charred an estimated 350,000 acres of rangeland
before it was declared under control Monday afternoon. Weary
firefighters who had fought the blaze since last Thursday were sent
home Tuesday.
   A frost helped cool the ground and extinguish the blaze, said
Mahlon Hammetter, a spokesman for the Texas Forest Service. But
rain is needed to help rejuvenate the scorched ground, he said.
   ``We are saving a lot of cattle,'' said Heirman. ``If we can get
some rain, we may see them continue to live. Everybody's praying
for rain right now.''
   About 200 cattle died on 53 ranches in Shackelford County, he
said, and about 500 head were injured.
   On Monday, Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby issued a disaster proclamation
for the region, said Don Couch of the governor's Emergency
Management Division in Austin. Gov. Bill Clements was out of the
state, said the governor's press secretary, Reggie Bashur.
   The fire probably started when flames from burning trash went
out of control near Abilene last Thursday, authorities said.
   The fire burned in an area 56 miles long and 24 miles wide in
Shackelford, Jones, Haskell, Throckmorton and Callahan counties.
</TEXT>
