<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Media 1stLd-Writethru   03-16 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Media, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0433,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis On Offensive Against Foreign, Domestic Media</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Koch's comments^, explain
reference to tin can in 7th graf: `In the occupied...' Pick up 8th
graf pvs: `Most of...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>With PM-Israel, Bjt
^By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Israelis are protesting that domestic and
foreign journalists covering riots in the occupied lands are
producing reports that are pro-Palestinian and damaging to Israel's
image.
   Israel Television has received dozens of threatening letters for
its reporting of the more than three months of violent protests in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip _ coverage most foreign journalists
consider mild.
   Even New York Mayor Edward Koch has joined in the criticism.
Koch wrote in the Jersualem Post today that television cameras
should be barred from the occupied territories.
   ``Many other nations throughout the world are experiencing
troubles similar to those now taking place in Israel. Should Israel
be the only nation to allow full television coverage of these
troubles?'' Koch wrote.
   An American television network says threats have forced it to
hire private guards to protect its offices and an Israeli cameraman.
   ``There's an escalation in statements against us,'' Eli Fassman,
head of the Union of Television Crews, told Israel radio this week.
``These criticisms border on incitement to murder.''
   There is also growing physical danger in covering the rioting,
the managing director of Israel's state-run television, Chaim
Yavin, said in an interview.
   He said Israel Television cameramen have been given a special
first aid and self-protection course. They were taught to defend
themselves against a mob, make speedy exits and use the camera as a
weapon, the daily Hadashot reported.
   In the occupied West Bank's Al Amari camp, cameramen were seen
Tuesday wearing large tin containers over their heads to protect
themselves from stones.
   Most of the mail that arrives at Israel Television is critical.
   ``We are accused of being leftists, PLO supporters. There are
threatening letters, too,'' said Yavin.
   An Israel Television spokeswoman, Sari Timmerman, said at least
five or six such letters arrive each day at her office while others
go directly to Yavin.
   The number of letters has not increased since the
anti-occupation rioting began Dec. 8, but most are now devoted to
patriotic criticism of Israel Television's performance in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``Many ask why we permit hostile elements to use state-run media
for expressing their views,'' Ms. Timmerman said.
   There are also telephoned complaints.
   ``If the action gets tough, we get up to 100 calls a night, most
from people who say they don't want to see this or want us to be
more favorable to the government,'' said Yair Stern, the head of
the news department.
   The TV's Arab-language department faces another kind of threat.
   Israeli media reports said its workers have received Palestine
Liberation Organization-inspired calls to stop cooperating with
Israeli authorities and resign. Department head Yosef Barel denied
the reports.
   ``People in the territories want coverage, and they know no Arab
TV is covering them apart from us,'' he said.
   Foreign networks are sometimes accused of inflaming violence and
unwittingly aiding anti-Israeli rioters.
   ``The press _ and I'm speaking primarily about the foreign TV
networks _ has explicitly been a side involved in the events,''
President Chaim Herzog has said. He said foreign television crews
are ``the main weapon'' of the Arabs.
   He was the latest in a series of Israeli officials to criticize
foreign media. Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Rabin and army spokesman Brig. Gen. Ephraim Lapid also have
spoken out.
   ``Certain Israeli officials, by their public statements, have
created a lynch atmosphere against reporters,'' said Bill Seamans,
ABC News bureau chief.
   The CBS News bureau chief, Terry Plantinga, said his network
hired guards to protect its Tel Aviv offices and cameraman Moshe
Alpert after receiving telephoned threats.
   Last month, Alpert filmed four Israeli soldiers brutally beating
two bound Palestinian youths with rocks in the West Bank city of
Nablus. The broadcast sparked international criticism and the army
put the soldiers on trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0076 </DOCNO>
