<HEAD>Man Held in Murder by Torching</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASBURY PARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 34-year-old man has been charged with
murdering a friend by dousing him with gasoline and setting him
afire after an evening of drink and drugs.
   William Wesley Swain was charged Tuesday with murdering Henry L.
Brown, 37, also of Asbury Park, during the evening of March 9.
   Brown's body was found March 10 by firefighters who responded to
a call at 3 a.m. at his apartment, according to Monmouth County
Prosecutor John Kaye.
   The body was found in the kitchen, Kaye said. Firefighters
apparently removed the body, and it was not until the medical
examiner's office detected gasoline on the clothes that an
investigation began, leading to Swain's arrest Tuesday.
   Kaye said the two men had been drinking and taking drugs during
the day and evening before Brown argued with Swain and threw him
out of Brown's car.
   Swain returned to Brown's apartment, found a can of gasoline
Brown kept for a motorcycle, doused Brown and ignited him, Kaye
said.
   Swain was sent to the Monmouth County Correctional Institution
on $150,000 bail.
