<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   03-16 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0545,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Proceed; Soviets Hit U.S., Pakistan Delays</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0584 to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with talks resuming, new comments
from Afghan and Kremlin leaders on delays. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Afghanistan peace talks resumed today with no
new target date for their completion and growing impatience in
Moscow, which renewed charges that the United States and Pakistan
were blocking the pact's progress.
   Afghan Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil, speaking at a news
conference, also said that Pakistan was delaying progress on a
settlement but said Afghanistan sees no reason to suspend the
talks, now in their sixth year.
   In Moscow, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told
U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock that the Kremlin wants the United
States and Pakistan to stop ``artificially procrastinating'' on an
agreement, the Tass news agency said.
   The Soviets offered fresh assurances, however, that it would
still remove its estimated 115,000 troops two months after a
settlement is signed. Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in
1979 and are helping the Marxist government fight U.S.-backed
Moslem guerrillas.
   At issue were Pakistan's demand for a broad-based transitional
government to replace the current, Soviet-backed adminsitration in
Kabul, and for a simultaneous end to military assistance to the
warring sides.
   Pakistan argues that only a government replacing the present
administration of President Najib could guarantee that a peace
settlement would be put in place and ensure the safe return of more
than 5 million refugees.
   Pakistan, where most of the Afghan refugees live, has been
representing the guerrilla movement during the U.N.-sponsored talks.
   The importance of a simultaneous cut-off of superpower military
aid has been particularly stressed by Washington. It would mean
that Soviet aid to its allies in Kabul would have to end at the
same time as aid to the guerrillas who get the bulk of their
supplies from the United States.
   An official Soviet statement issued Tuesday in Moscow condemned
attempts ``to dictate to the U.S.S.R and Afghanistan how they
should build their bilateral relations.''
   The Soviet statement confirmed, however, that the decision to
pull out the troops still stands and that the withdrawal would
begin two months after the signing of a Geneva settlement.
   In Moscow, Tass said the discussion between Shevardnadze and
Matlock dealt mostly with the Afghanistan issue.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Richard Gilbert confirmed that Matlock
had a meeting with Shevardnadze that included a discussion on
Afghanistan, but said it is embassy policy not to disclose details
of diplomatic exchanges.
   ``The ambassador's attention was drawn to the Soviet
government's statement of March 15, which contains a principled
assessment of the unsatisfactory situation at the Afghan-Pakistani
talks in Geneva, and also contains a clear-cut qualification of the
actions of Pakistan and the United States which are artifically
procrastinating the signing of actually agreed-upon accords,'' Tass
said.
   In Geneva, Wakil told reporters that Pakistan's stand amounted
to a ``unilateral suspension'' and would get the talks nowhere.
   Wakil spoke shortly before a new session with U.N.
Undersecretary General Diego Cordovez, the intermediary in the
talks. It was the first meeting since the talks failed to meet the
target of March 15 set by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev for their
conclusion.
   He charged that Pakistan had organized the war which had already
led also to ``tragic events'' on Pakistan's side. He warned that
allowing the conflict to continue would pose a threat to the entire
region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0849EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson'sWeek 1stLd-Writethru a0470 03-16 0914</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson's Week, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home-State Primary Ends Jackson's Winning Streak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new to update with Jackson quotes; picks up 3rd
graf pvs, ``I'm running ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's best week in the 1988 campaign brought seven
victories in seven days, but his streak ended with a disappointing
second-place finish in Illinois that highlighted the obstacles he
faces in the big-state primaries to come.
   Jackson drew less than 10 percent of the white vote in Tuesday's
primary.
   Nevertheless, Jackson said today that he has broader support
than any other candidate. ``When you get second place in Idaho and
in Florida, and Minnesota, Vermont, Maine, you're getting white
vote,'' he said on NBC's ``Today'' show.
   ``When it's all said and done, it's just Democratic votes. I
have the most Democratic votes. I expect to have the most
Democratic delegates.''
   Jackson is locked in a tight race with Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis for the lead in the delegate count.
   ``I'm running No. 1 in popular votes and in delegate votes,''
Jackson said after the Illinois results were known Tuesday,
overstating the delegate situation a bit. ``Illinois has been good
to two favorite sons today. It has also given me the lead for the
party.''
   Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois easily won the primary.
   ``If I have the most Democratic votes and I have the most
delegates, I will be the nominee. That is my preoccupation,''
Jackson declared.
   Taking a third of the popular vote in Illinois, Jackson was
close to amassing 3 million votes in the first 20 primaries of 1988.
   Before the home-state primary, he had trailed Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis slightly in total primary votes, 2.61 million to
2.57 million. Dukakis was winning less than 20 percent of the vote
in Illinois, boosting his total to just over 2.8 million votes.
   In delegates before the Illinois returns, Dukakis held the lead
over Jackson, but his margin was almost wiped out by the Illinois
returns. Dukakis was being shut out in the direct election of
delegates in Illinois.
   Jackson has proven that he can win votes. And on Super Tuesday
he proved he can win state primaries, taking the top spot in
Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi and Virginia. Later in the
week he won the caucuses in South Carolina and, surprisingly Alaska.
   The calendar now forces him to prove again that he can win
primary victories, this time in states not nearly as friendly to
his hopes as those in the past week.
   Jackson's showing in his home state of Illinois on Tuesday
illustrates his problem.
   He swept the black vote in Chicago and added less than 10
percent of the white vote to put together a second-place finish to
fellow favorite son Simon.
   Jackson decried any emphasis on the racial division of the vote,
saying ``there is a preoccupation with the ethnic breakdown'' of
the balloting.
   But to win in the states to come, Jackson must do better among
the white voters while holding the great bulk of a high-turnout
black vote.
   In the major states holding primaries in the next six weeks _
Michigan, Connecticut, Wisconsin, New York and Pennsylvania _ there
are substantial black populations to give Jackson a core of
support. But the relative size of the potential black voting bloc
is smaller in each of the coming states than it was in the South,
where Jackson won his primary victories.
   And, in the industrial states to come, those black voters are
heavily concentrated in a few congressional districts.
   Jackson will do quite well in the delegate contests there _ as
he did in three districts in Illinois _ but without substantial
white backing in other districts, his delegate count will not add
up as fast as his opponents'.
   The Jackson campaign didn't win any victories in the early going
of the presidential season, but he did have some surprisingly
powerful showings in states outside his traditional strongholds.
   He was fourth in Iowa and New Hampshire. But then he came in a
surprising second in the Minnesota caucuses on Feb. 23. He was
second as well in the Maine caucuses on Feb. 28 and in the Vermont
primary on March 1.
   The victory march for Jackson began in the region that was his
birthplace, the South. Jackson won five states across the region on
March 8, Super Tuesday. On Saturday, he returned to the state of
his birth _ South Carolina _ for a big victory in that state's
caucuses. He then took first place in the Alaska caucuses.
   Looking to the upcoming events, Jackson faces the Illinois
problem again.
   In Michigan, with its caucuses March 26, about 12 percent of the
population is black. But only four congressional districts out of
18 had more than 10 percent black population in the 1980 census.
   In Connecticut, only about 7 percent of the population is black,
although three of the six congressional districts have substantial
minority populations in the March 29 primary.
   In the Wisconsin primary on April 5, the black population is
centered in Milwaukee, adding up to only about 4 percent statewide.
   In the big New York contest on April 19, about 14 percent of the
population is black. And some 13 of the 34 congressional districts
have more than 10 percent minority residents.
   In Pennsylvania _ with an April 26 primary _ the black
population is about 9 percent, heavily concentrated in four of the
state's 23 congressional districts.
</TEXT>
