<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ClassReport     03-16 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Class Report,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Visits Mississippi for Class Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old girl, frustrated in efforts
to get information for a class report on Mississippi, flew there
for a five-day visit there as a guest of the Southern state.
   Melissa Montgomery, a fifth grade student at John Swett
Elementary School in Martinez, was greeted by classmates when she
returned Tuesday night to Oakland International Airport.
   She said the strangest part of the trip was when people laughed
at her accent.
   ``I said `you guys,' they said `you all,''' she said.
   Her mother, Kathryn Montgomery, said all expenses except plane
fare were paid by an anonymous person.
   The mother said she called the Mississippi secretary of state's
office and was told the office was out of reference works. She was
half-seriously told to send the girl to Mississippi.
   ``I said, `great, I will,''' she said. The next morning she got
a call from a Mississippi mother who was wiling to take care of
Melissa.
   The girl even met Ray Mabus, the Mississippi governor.
   ``He was nice,'' she said.
   Melissa said she toured museums, battlefields, mansions and rode
a pony.
   ``There are a lot of museums,'' she said, adding that the
favorite part of the trip was a visit to the Impressionist Gallery.
   ``It had neat stuff in it,'' she said.
   The 5-to-10 page class report is due March 23.
</TEXT>
