<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--OlympicClub     03-16 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Olympic Club,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Olympic Club Admits Two Blacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 128-year-old exclusive private club has
admitted its first two black male members but continues to ban
women.
   The two men broke the color barrier at the Olympic Club, where
membership costs $12,500 plus monthly dues and greens fees.
   ``I've played golf for years with Olympic members,'' said Roy
Clay, president of a company that makes electronics testing
equipment. He said he applied and was interviewed last fall and was
accepted last week.
   ``I'm not a golfer,'' said Jessie Knight, vice president of
marketing for the San Francisco Newspaper Agency. ``I joined
strictly because of the athletic facilities. The club is close by,
and it's good place to work out.''
   A city ordinance that went into effect in December bars private
clubs with more than 400 members from discriminating against
minorities and women.
   However, club spokesman Jim Myers said the ban on women members
will remain pending the outcome of a court battle with the city and
an appeal to the federal courts on constitutional grounds of
freedom of association.
</TEXT>
