<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DestroyerSlaying     03-16 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Destroyer Slaying,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Paymaster Murdered, Ship's Safe Robbed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The USS John Hancock's
disbursement office was robbed of $120,000 in cash and the battered
body of the ship's paymaster was found stuffed in a locker aboard
the destroyer, Navy officials said.
   The body of paymaster Lt. Ratish Prasad, 24, of Park Forest,
Ill., was found Tuesday, said Chief Petty Officer Art Riccio.
   ``He'd been bludgeoned,'' said the spokesman. ``He was beaten up
pretty bad.''
   The destroyer's disbursement office safe was found open and
$120,000 in cash plus an undetermined number of blank checks were
missing, Riccio said.
   ``An audit of the ship's funds is pending and alternate
arrangements have been made to pay the crew,'' said Riccio.
   Tuesday was payday for Navy personnel, who are paid the 1st and
15th of each month, said Riccio, adding that Navy and Jacksonville
sheriff's investigators were working on the case.
   Access to the Hancock, which was tied up at its home port here,
is strictly controlled, said Riccio. People trying to board the
ship must pass checkpoints at the base entrance, the pier area and
the ship itself, he said.
   Only family members and friends of the crew who have been
previously cleared are allowed aboard the ship in port, he said.
Even Naval personnel who do not have business on the ships cannot
board them, he said.
</TEXT>
