<DOCNO> AP880316-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0910EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTLSuit     03-16 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL Suit,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Sues Former PTL Lawyer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fallen television evangelist Jim Bakker has
sued a New York attorney who formerly represented the PTL ministry,
charging that the attorney tricked him into resigning and turning
the ministry over to the Rev. Jerry Falwell.
   In the suit, which seeks more than $10,000 in damages and was
filed this week in York County, Bakker and his wife, Tammy Faye,
say they did not know that Roy Grutman also represented Falwell
when he advised the Bakkers to step down.
   ``What the Bakkers are really saying in the lawsuit is that Mr.
Grutman tricked the Bakkers into resigning from office to open the
way for Mr. Falwell to take over the leadership of the ministry,''
said Jim Toms, one of the Bakkers' attorneys.
   Grutman said Tuesday the allegations were ``utterly meritless,''
adding that he was never Bakker's attorney.
   ``I didn't tell him to resign. He made that decision,'' Grutman
said.
   Bakker left the Fort Mill-based ministry last March amid a sex
scandal involving a church secretary, Jessica Hahn. Falwell took
over the ministry for several months. PTL now is undergoing
reorganization in bankruptcy court.
   Grutman told the Bakkers, according to the suit, that television
evangelist Jimmy Swaggart, now beset by a sex scandal himself, was
heading a conspiracy to take over PTL.
   The Bakkers claim that Grutman and Falwell advised them to
``turn the leadership of the ministry over to Mr. Falwell, who, it
was said, would lead the ministry as a caretaker until such time as
the (Bakkers) could return to the ministry,'' the suit said.
   The suit also charged that ``Grutman either knew or should have
known that the alleged conspiracy to seize control of PTL by Mr.
Swaggart, either was not truthfully reported or was impractical of
attainment.''
   Bakker resigned as PTL president on March 19; a month later,
Falwell took the Bakkers off the PTL payroll.
   The suit said the Bakkers left PTL ``severely damaged
financially and diminished as a Christian ministry'' and accused
Grutman of giving the Bakkers incorrect advice to resign, resulting
in damage to the Bakkers' reputations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0912EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hostages-Say     03-16 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostages-Say,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sister Says Government No Longer Cares About Captives' Fate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sister of the longest-held American
hostage in Lebanon said today that the Reagan administration, once
obsessed with securing freedom for the captives, no longer cares
about their fate.
   ``I think it's rather interesting to look back and see the
concern expressed by the administration, by President Reagan, Vice
President Bush, and their rationale for the Iran-Contra scandal
that they were so obsessed with the fate of the hostages that they
made this move,'' Peggy Say, sister of hostage Terry Anderson, said
of the arms-for-hostages deal.
   ``And for the past year, silence. That obsession seems to have
been overcome and the fate of the hostages no longer seems to be of
great concern to anybody in this administration,'' she said on
NBC-TV's ``Today'' show.
   Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, is the longest-held of 22 foreign hostages in Lebanon. He
was kidnapped on March 16, 1985, in Beirut as he was returning from
a tennis game.
   Services to mark the third anniversary of his abduction were
scheduled in Anderson's hometown of Batavia, N.Y., as well as
Buffalo and Rochester, and in California and Florida, Mrs. Say said.
   In Washington, Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson
was taking part at an afternoon service at Holy Trinity Roman
Catholic Church where prayers for Anderson and the other hostages
were to be offered by Christian and Islamic clergy.
   Participants, including three former hostages _ the Rev.
Lawrence Jenco, the Rev. Benjamin Weir and ABC News correspondent
Charles Glass _ were to read passages from the Bible and the Koran.
   Marilyn Langston, daughter of American hostage Frank Herbert
Reed, said today she hopes the service ``puts an awareness in
everyone's mind that this hostage situation is going on continually
and until they're all out we can't forget it.''
   Ms. Langston said, however, that she feared the captives have
been forgotten by the U.S. government.
   ``I feel they've been put on the backburner, that the concern
for the hostages _ I don't know if there is any any more,'' Ms.
Langston said on the NBC program.
   Reed, director of the Lebanon International School in Beirut,
was kidnapped Sept. 9, 1986. He is among the nine Americans held
captive in Lebanon, including Thomas Sutherland, Joseph James
Cicippio, Edward Austin Tracy, Jesse Turner, Robert Polhill, Alaan
Steen, and Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins.
</TEXT>
