<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContinentalProbe     03-16 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Probe,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Looks Into Testing Procedures at Continental</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is
investigating Continental Airlines' pilot testing procedures
following comments made last week at a hearing into a November
crash that killed 28 people, officials said.
   Daniel Beaudette, manager of the FAA's air transportation
division in Washington, said Tuesday that the investigation was set
off by one pilot's report that he made deliberate mistakes in wing
settings to test pilots.
   ``I can't see how they could safely do that in
passenger-carrying operations,'' Beaudette said. Federal
regulations prohibit pilot training on flights that carry
passengers.
   The inquiry follows testimony by Continental Capt. Kenneth
Watson last week before a National Transportation Safety Board
hearing into the Nov. 15 crash of a Continental DC-9 that killed 28
and injured 54 as it was taking off from Denver's airport.
   On a flight last October, Watson said he made incorrect
adjustments to an aircraft before takeoff in order to test pilot
Frank Zvonek, who died in the November crash.
   ``As is my common practice, I advised Frank that I would
intentionally make several mistakes,'' Watson told the hearing.
   ``I intentionally misset flaps, (stabilizer) trim and weight
cards for takeoff. He caught and corrected me on them,'' he said.
   If a violation is found, Continental could be issued an
administrative warning, fined, or Watson's license could be
suspended, Beaudette said.
   Continental spokesman Bruce Hicks said the procedure Watson
reported using is not a company policy.
   But Hicks said he didn't know whether the technique has been
used by other Continental pilots and said the airline has not yet
decided whether to permit that kind of pilot testing in the future.
</TEXT>
