<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0549,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Fire More Missiles At Each Other's Capitals</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs after 4th graf pvs: `On Tuesday...,' to UPDATE
with report Iran cut ties to Security Council. Pick up 6th graf
pvs: ``Iraq on...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said it fired five missiles into
Baghdad today, and Iraq said it shot seven into Tehran. The
Iranians said 52 civilians were killed in Tehran and in Iraqi
warplane raids on other cities.
   Iran also said its warplanes bombed other Iraqi cities today,
and its troops pushed into northeastern Iraq overnight and seized
the border town of Khurmal, Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency
said. IRNA said 1,150 Iraqi troops were killed or wounded, but Iraq
had no comment on the reported offensive.
   Also today, foreign ministers of the Gulf Cooperation Council
met in Saudi Arabia to discuss the 7-year-old Iran-Iraq war and its
implications for the oil-rich region.
   On Tuesday, Iran accused the U.N. Security Council of wasting
time on an arms embargo instead of ending the missile duel, in
which scores of civilians have been killed or wounded.
   In Switzerland, the prestigious newspaper Neue Zuercher Zeitung
today quoted senior Iranian Charge d'Affaires Mohammed Hussein
Malaek as saying his country had cut all ties to the Security
Council.
   Malaek also was quoted as saying only a military solution could
end the Persian Gulf war, and that Iran no longer felt obligated to
respect international conventions, presumably including the Geneva
Convention on the conduct of nations at war.
   Iraq on Tuesday reiterated the claim that Iran broke a two-day
truce in the ``war of the cities'' and said it would continue to
attack Tehran until Iran stopped shelling border cities.
   The Iraqi News Agency said warplanes Tuesday night bombed
Iranian towns and attacked a ship in the Persian Gulf. Maritime
sources had earlier reported an Iraqi attack at around the same
time on the 249,223-ton Trade Fortitude.
   The Iranian agency said Revolutionary Guards fired five missiles
into Baghdad in retaliation for an air raid Tuesday that killed 25
students and teachers at a high school in al-Eshtar in western Iran.
   The Iraqi agency confirmed three of the hits on Baghdad and said
``many'' civilians were killed. Iraq said it fired seven missiles
into Tehran.
   Iran said an unspecified number of missiles hit the capital of
Tehran today and said Iraqi warplanes also bombed Bakhtaran and
other cities in western Iran. The Iranian agency said a total of 52
civilians were killed.
   Iraq says it has fired 22 missiles into Tehran since the tenuous
truce broke down late Sunday. Iran has reported launching seven
into Baghdad.
   Neither side has given an overall casualty count.
   Iran's news agency said Iranian jet fighters bombed the northern
Iraqi oil city of Kirkuk and other cities today, ``inflicting heavy
casualties and losses on the enemy.'' It said the jet fighters also
shot 16 air-to-ground missiles into Kirkuk.
   It said nine short-range missiles were fired into the southern
Basra province, the area surrounding Iraq's second-largest city.
   It said Revolutionary Guards pushed farther into Sulaymaniyah
province in northeastern Iraq, inflicting ``heavy losses.'' Earlier
in the week Iran said its fighters seized villages and hills in the
region, 160 miles north of Baghdad.
   Iranian forces took the town of Khurmal a few miles from the
border after a ``pitched battle,'' the agency reported today.
   It said residents of ``liberated villages'' in the area ``warmly
welcomed the attacking Iranian combatants,'' and Iranian forces
seized 95 square miles of Iraqi soil, including 21 villages.
   Announcing today's Iraqi missile strike on Iran, an Iraqi
military spokesman was quoted by the official Iraqi News Agency as
saying:
   ``We will continue our destructive hits into the nest of vice
and ugliness.''
   It also said Revolutionary Guards pushed farther into
Sulaymaniyah province in northeastern Iraq, inflicting ``heavy
losses'' and that Khurmal had fallen.
   Earlier in the week, Iran said its fighters seized villages and
hills in the region 160 miles north of Baghdad.
   The Iraqi and Iranian reports were monitored in Cyprus.
   The attack Tuesday on the Trade Fortitude raised the possibility
of revived attacks on shipping in the gulf, where the U.S.-flagged
Kuwaiti tanker Gas Prince was heading north in the 17th
U.S.-escorted convoy this year.
   Since Feb. 15, there have been two confirmed Iraqi attacks on
tankers in Iranian shipping lanes.
</TEXT>
