<HEAD>Death Probe Leads To Stolen Chickens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police investigating the death of a man
who was crushed between a truck and his porch ended up arresting
two people after they found out the truck was loaded with stolen
chickens, authorities said.
   Officers said Joshua Horton, 50, was pronounced dead at
Mississippi Baptist Medical Center after he was crushed between the
truck and a porch at his home about 11:35 p.m.
   Investigators said Patricia Tucker, 33, of Jackson, the victim's
step-daughter, was attempting to back the truck into Horton's
driveway to unload the frozen chickens when the brakes failed.
   The truck contained 20 boxes of chickens allegedly taken from a
Jackson firm where Tucker's husband, Edgar Tucker, 36, was
employed, officers said.
   A police spokesman said Tucker, who was at work when the
accident occurred, was arrested on an embezzlement charge while his
wife was charged with accessory to embezzlment.
