<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0940EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Syria-Oil     03-16 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Syria-Oil,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syria Now Exporting Oil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria will become an oil exporter for the
first time because of new discoveries, officials said today.
   James Audu, a spokesman for the Vienna-based Organization of
Petroleum Exporting countries, said that Syria produced 240,000
barrels per day during the fourth quarter of last year.
   With local demand estimated at about 220,000 barrels a day, the
country would become a net exporter on an annual basis for the
first time this year, helping it to cope with a foreign debt of at
least $3 billion.
   The small amount of oil to be sold abroad will not qualify Syria
for membership in the oil cartel, Audu told The Associated Press in
Vienna. But it is expected to make that Arab nation a net exporter
in 1988, he said.
   Syria, with 10 million people, is not expected to become a big
exporter. But the modest 1.8 billion barrels of estimated oil
reserves should help alleviate the economic burden.
   President Hafez Assad announced in a speech to the nation last
week that there have been new oil discoveries but he did not
elaborate.
   The Damascus government currently gets millions of tons of
cut-price oil from Iran each year.
   Syria is Persian Iran's main ally in the 7-year-old Persian Gulf
war against Arab Iraq. But Damascus has come under growing pressure
from other Arab countries to stop supporting Iran against a fellow
Arab nation.
</TEXT>
