<1ST_LINE>r p PM-LotteryElection     03-16 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lottery Election,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democracy In Action or Democracy Inaction?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAND LAKE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whoever said one vote doesn't count
isn't following Sand Lake politics, such as they are.
   In a somewhat less than spirited election for a vacant village
trustee's seat, Bob VandenBerg, Ralph Boerman and Earl Thomas
finished in a three-way tie _ each receiving precisely one write-in
vote.
   A winner will be chosen at 9 a.m. March 21 under Kent County's
official tie-breaking method, a drawing at the County Clerk's
office in Grand Rapids. Two slips of paper marked ``Not Elected''
and one marked ``Elected'' will be put in a box and drawn by the
candidates or their representatives.
   The Village Council in this community of about 400 people will
appoint a trustee if the winner declines the job, something that
appeared to be more than a remote possibility.
   Thomas, 40, served 14 years as village clerk but didn't run this
year, saying his night job prevented him from attending council
meetings. ``I was a clerk for 14 years, so I did my time,'' he said.
   VandenBerg, 51, chose not to run for re-election as village
president this year after six years in local politics. ``I figured
it was time for the young ones to take over,'' he said.
   Boerman, at 22 a political neophyte, could be considered one of
VandenBerg's ``young ones.'' But Boerman said he didn't know he was
in the running until a reporter telephoned him with news of the
three-way tie.
   ``I haven't ever thought about it,'' Boerman said. ``No one has
approached me or asked me or anything.''
   Thomas said he'd like to know who wrote in his name.
   ``I'll kill `em, whoever it was,'' he joked.
</TEXT>
