<2ND_LINE>PM-Rape-Repent,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tearful Rape Defendant Opts For Plea To Spare Victim, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After tearfully telling his lawyer
``there was still some good in him,'' a rape defendant pleaded
guilty so he could spare his 16-year-old victim the trauma of
testifying.
   Terry Lee Buckholtz was charged with raping the teen in November
1986 when he was in a prison work-release program, and then trying
to kill her and her brother with a meat cleaver.
   The brother and sister survived their wounds, and were to take
the witness stand Tuesday in court here.
   ``He called me this morning totally out of the blue,'' defense
attorney John Voigt said Tuesday. ``He was in tears. He said that
even though nobody thought so, there was still some good in him.
   ``The only good thing left for him to do was not make (the
victims) testify,'' Voight said.
   Circuit Judge Stanton S. Kaplan asked Buckholtz to explain.
   ``I didn't want to put them through any more,'' replied
Buckholtz, 20.
   Under a deal with the prosecutor, Buckholtz was sentenced to 40
years in prison followed by 15 years of probation. In return for
the guilty plea, prosecutor Kate Kearney agreed to drop charges of
armed kidnapping and aggravated battery.
   Kearny said Buckholtz had rejected that plea-bargain offer a
week ago.
   ``It's been an exceptionally traumatic experience for the
family,'' she said. ``The state offered this to avoid having the
victims exposed to Mr. Buckholtz.''
