<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Amnesty-Misdemeanors     03-16 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Misdemeanors,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New INS Policy To Accept Misdemeanor Convicts For Amnesty,
Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Undocumented aliens seeking amnesty despite
misdemeanor criminal records may be eligible if the convictions are
more than a year old, a newspaper reported today.
   But amnesty rights activists said the proposed change in
immigration-law standards comes too late.
   ``Immigration has been very lax in coming forward to publicize
this major change,'' said Susan Alva, director of a legalization
appeals project for the Legal Aid Foundation.
   Under the existing U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service
policy, immigrants who have been convicted of three or more
misdemeanors, or any felony, are not eligible for amnesty.
   The proposed change would allow immigrants to expunge
misdemeanors from their records and be eligible for amnesty,
according to a report published today in the Los Angeles Herald
Examner.
   Alva estimated that thousands of people, many of whom have been
told by officials that they weren't eligible for legalization,
would be affected by the reported policy shift.
   But Duke Austin, an INS spokesman, disagreed.
   ``I don't think this would dramatically affect the numbers of
people in the program,'' he said.
   In a letter dated Jan. 18, Joe Thomas, director of the INS
western region processing facility for amnesty applications,
explained to an immigrants' rights attorney that ``an expungement
will not remove ineligibility for criminal convictions.''
   However, attorneys from the immigration committee of the
National Lawyers' Guild and the Los Angeles County Public
Defender's office said the INS is now accepting expungements,
though too late to be of use to many immigrants.
   The amnesty deadline is May 5, and Ray Santana, a deputy Los
Angeles County public defender, said it takes a month or longer to
get an expungement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
