<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Arrest,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Detain Arab-American</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab-American who advocates non-violent
resistance to Israel's occupation was detained today for allegedly
taking part in an illegal gathering, police said.
   Mubarak Awad, 44, was being held at a city police station and
his case was under investigation, police spokesman Rafi Levy told
The Associated Press.
   Levy said the illegal gathering took place on the main road
between Jerusalem and the West Bank city of Nablus, but he had no
further details.
   ``We do understand that Mr. Awad has been taken into custody,
but our understanding was that he was stopped for a traffic
violation,'' said a U.S. Consulate official who spoke on condition
of anonymity. ``We have consular officers seeking access to him at
this time.''
   Last year, Israeli officials confiscated Awad's Israeli identity
card and ordered him out of the country in November, when his
three-month tourist visa expired.
   On Monday, Israel's Supreme Court ordered the Interior Ministry
to show within 60 days why Awad had not been expelled.
   Awad, a Palestinian who also has homes both in Jerusalem and
Wapakoneta, Ohio, came under fire after the publication in Hebrew
of his book entitled ``Non-Violent Resistance: A Strategy For the
Occupied Territories.''
   The book urged the 1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip to refuse to pay taxes, lay down in front of bulldozers
to prevent land confiscation and boycott Isreli products.
</TEXT>
