<HEAD>Lawyers Appeal to High Court to Stop Hanging of Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for the ``Sharpeville
Six'' today filed an appeal with the Supreme Court for a stay of
execution for the six blacks, whose scheduled hangings have
prompted worldwide cries for clemency.
   Attorney Prakash Diar filed the request on the basis of new
evidence relating to allegations that police assaulted and
pressured a state witness into giving false evidence against two of
the defendants.
   The hearing was scheduled for Thursday morning. The executions
are scheduled at dawn Friday at Pretoria Central Prison.
   A finding of new evidence is the only grounds available to stop
the hangings, since President P.W. Botha said Tuesday he had turned
down the last appeal to save the five men and one woman.
   The six were convicted of murder in connection with the Sept. 3,
1984 mob killing of black township councilor Jacob Dlamini in
Sharpeville, about 40 miles south of Johannesburg.
   The attorneys submitted documents stating that Joseph Manete, a
black trial witness, was forced by police to say in a sworn
affidavit that he had seen two of the defendants at the scene, when
he really did not.
   Manete testified in the non-jury trial under protection of
anonymity. The attorneys tried to question him during the trial
about his allegations, which were made to his attorney. The court
refuThe
Sharpeville riots were provoked by the local council's decision to
raise rents.
</TEXT>
