<HEAD>Bush Hails `Great And Convincing' Illinois Victory</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates Robertson percentage in 6th graf, Bush resoundingly</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, with another Republican
primary victory under his belt, celebrated his ``great and
convincing'' win in Illinois, while backers proclaimed he has the
GOP presidential nomination sewed up.
   ``This is the state, it will be remembered, which locked it up
for George Bush,'' said James Thompson, Illinois' four-term
Republican governor. Thompson served as Bush's state chairman and
campaigned with him all over Illinois.
   ``Who says nice guys finish last?'' a buoyant Bush asked
supporters at a victory celebration in this northwest Chicago
suburb.
   ``Thank you, Illinois,'' he said.
   The vice president was returning to Washington today for a
campaign hiatus.
   Bush resoundingly beat his nearest rival, Kansas Sen. Bob Dole.
Former television evangelist Pat Robertson ran a distant third with
7 percent.
   ``Illinois has spoken loud and clear and strong, and so now we
go on, right down to the wire in November, and with your help we'll
win Illinois in November,'' he told supporters who waved red, white
and blue balloons and chanted ``Bush '88.''
   With a victory in the first big industrial-state primary on top
of his Super Tuesday sweep, Bush said his campaign themes had won
nationwide approval.
   ``Wherever there's a primary, I am going to be there taking the
Illinois message,'' he said. ``Ours is a national message for a
national campaign.''
   Backers said Bush was virtually assured of winning the
nomination.
   ``I think the race is going to be wrapped up when Bob Dole
decides to drop out, but the numbers certainly would indicate that
it's all over,'' said Ed Murnane, deputy director of the Bush
campaign in Illinois.
</TEXT>
