<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Church     03-16 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Church,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inquest Finds Theologian Killed Self After Writing Critical Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Church of England theologian committed
suicide after writing a controversial article accusing the
archbishop of Canterbury of weakness and indecision, a coroner
ruled today.
   The Rev. Gareth Bennett, a traditionalist figure in the church,
wrote the traditionally unsigned preface to ``Crockford's Clerical
Directory 1987-88,'' the church's own reference book listing
Anglican clergy.
   The article, published Dec. 2, started a furor in the state
church because it was widely interpreted as the opening shot in a
campaign to pressure Archbishop Robert Runcie, 66, into retiring
early and to block the appointment of a liberal to replace him.
   Runcie is spiritual head of the church and the world's 70
million Anglicans.
   Bennett, 58, wrote in a diary four days before his Dec. 7 death
that ``I should be lucky to weather this business through without
disaster.''
   He was found dead in his fume-filled car at his home in Oxford,
western England. Bennett had purchased a hose pipe on Dec. 5 that
was used to siphon fumes into his car from the exhaust, the inquest
heard.
   Oxfordshire Coroner Nicholas Gardiner said the tenor of
Bennett's diary entries ``changes dramatically in the last few days
of his life'' and there was ample evidence to suggest Bennett was
under extreme pressure.
   ``He decided that he had only one course of action open to him
and took that course of action fully aware of what the results
would be,'' Gardiner said. ``Accordingly, my verdict must be that
he took his own life.''
</TEXT>
