<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Accidents     03-16 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Accidents,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negligence Causes 11,700 Deaths in 3-Year Period</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negligence and dereliction of duty have caused
the deaths of 11,700 people over the past three years, a top
Chinese official was quoted today as saying.
   The official China Daily quoted an official of the Supreme
People's Procuratorate, the nation's top prosecutor's office. He
was not identified by name.
   The official said accidents resulting from ``rampant
bureaucratic bunglings'' and negligence cost the state $378 million
in direct economic losses over the same period.
   He said there had been an unexpected rise in the number of
serious cases of negligence involving criminal liability over the
past two years.
   He gave no reason for the increase. Previous reports have linked
China's serious problem with industrial accidents to both inept
bureaucracy and economic reforms which have decentralized industry
and encouraged the establishment of hundreds of thousands of small,
often poorly regulated factories.
   The official said most criminal cases are in the fields of
construction, mining and transport, forcing the resignation of
several senior government leaders.
   The head of the Forestry Ministry was forced from office last
year because of his poor handling of a disastrous forest fire and
the railways minister stepped down earlier this month to take the
blame for three fatal train accidents in January.
   The official said the procuratorate will impose stricter
punishment for people who have committed crimes of derelection or
have caused major accidents due to negligence of duty.
   Organizations caught trying to cover up such crimes or which
delay reporting them will also face severe criminal punishment, he
said.
</TEXT>
