<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Carlucci-Yazov 2ndLd-Writethru   03-16 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci-Yazov, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0596,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Meets With Yazov For Military Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Pentagon spokesman's
comments. Picks up 11th graf pvs, `Inside, the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci and Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri Yazov today held the
first such high-level military talks in an atmosphere characterized
as friendly and non-pressured.
   ``The tone has been very positive and cooperative throughout,''
said Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard. ``We are pleased with the way
things are going.''
   The two discussed the Strategic Arms Limitation Talks,
implementation of the treaty to eliminate medium-range superpower
nuclear missiles, and the size of the respective armed forces, said
Howard.
   They also discussed U.S. allegations that the Soviets violated
the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty by building a phased-array
radar far from the Soviet border in Siberia, said Howard. The pact
requires such radars to be along the border.
   Howard declined to give full details of the talks, saying that
Carlucci and Yazov reserved that right for news conferences both
plan at the end of the talks Thursday.
   Opening the morning session at the U.S. Embassy, said Howard,
Yazov ``commented that the room ... was a very small room, and said
there is a saying in Russian that although we have close quarters,
we shouldn't quarrel.''
   ``Everyone got a laugh out of that,'' said Howard.
   ``The main point that Mr. Yazov made in the beginning was that
he wanted to have useful discussions without having the pressure of
negotiations ... to arrive at some sort of agreement,'' Howard said.
   Carlucci welcomed Yazov to the opening round.
   Inside, the two men, flanked by about 10 aides apiece, faced
each other across a long table at the end of which stood a relief
map of Europe, the area defended by the opposing forces of the
North Atlantic Treaty Alliance and Warsaw Pact.
   The two men exchanged greetings, but made no public remarks. It
was the first ever business meeting between U.S. and Soviet defense
secretaries.
   Reporters and photographers were ushered out of the room as the
first, three-hour session began.
   Carlucci and Yazov ate lunch at the residence of U.S. Ambassador
Faith Ryan Whittlesey before the afternoon session at the Soviet
embassy.
   On Thursday, Carlucci and Yazov were to eat breakfast at the
residence of Soviet Ambassador Zoya Novozhilova before their third
and concluding session. Carlucci told reporters earlier that he
hoped Yazov could give him concrete evidence of a highly publicized
new Soviet military doctrine.
   Despite extensive Soviet press commentary on the Kremlin
doctrine of reasonable or defensive sufficiency, he said he had
seen seen ``absolutely no practical change.''
   ``If anything, their military continues to grow. They continue
to modernize,'' Carlucci said Tuesday.
   Yazov said before he left Moscow that he hoped for ``frank,
constructive discussion'' on arms control issues including
strategic arms, nuclear testing, chemical and conventional weapons.
   Carlucci emphasized that he did not want the meeting to open a
``parallel channel'' to on-going superpower arms negotiations in
Geneva.
   Soviet journalists covering the session said they had been told
it was likely to produce no dramatic announcements, but to serve as
an ``impulse'' to other negotiations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1057EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Gorbachev-Excerpts     03-16 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gorbachev-Excerpts,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excerpts From Gorbachev's Speech to Yugoslav Parliament</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's speech Wednesday to the Yugoslav Parliament:
   ``We will have to thoroughly examine the question of improving
inter-nationality relations, one of the most important and delicate
issues in a multinational country such as ours. Basic positions
here are firm.
   ``Recently, when the 70th anniversary of the Great October
Revolution was formally celebrated in Moscow, we spoke with a
justified sense of gratification of the results of the Leninist
nationalities policy of how much had been done in the country to
upgrade the economy and culture of the many peoples inhabiting our
land, so that they might live in friendship and accord.
   ``Whatever constituent or autonomous republic or region we take,
it is now bound by thousands of threads to all other parts of the
sountry, and it has indisoluble links within the integrated
economic and political complex ... It would be a mistake, however,
to regard the life of nations and relations of nations as something
settled once and for all.
   ``There are certain difficulties inherited from the past. There
are problems that emerged in the course of time prompted by changes
in economic life and social relationships and in the consciousness
of people.
   ``We are determined to secure democratic solutions to these
problems which would correspond to the interests of each and every
nation and in the family of Soviet nations and our entire socialist
society.
   ``I should like to stress that the changes in our society are
closely linked with the activity of the Communist Party. The
Communist Party of the Soviet Union is the initiator of perestroika
(change). In the current crucial stage, its role as the Soviet
people's political vanguard is particularly great. And we are
convinced that the party can carry out the current responsible
tasks it is confronted with, not by methods of command and
administration, but by putting itself at the head of the mass
movement for a revolutionary renewal of society, and by
consolidating two-way connections with the working class, the
farmers, the intelligentsia and all social strata.''
   ``We are implementing our perestroika in keeping with the
conditions and needs of our own country, and we have no intention
whatsoever to palm it off as a universal model or recipe that would
be good for all.
   ``Today, the Mediterranean is one of the most explosive regions
of the world, an intricate knot of conflicting interests abounding
in huge military arsenals which are continuing to grow. There is no
other enclosed sea with the same concentration of naval forces.
   ``For us, the Mediterranean base is no remote, out-of-the-way
area. It is close to our southern borders, and it is crossed by the
only sea route linking our southern ports with the world's oceans.
   ``Naturally, we are interested in routes of peace, rather than
those of war, passing here. In this connection, I would like to
declare that we fully support the program of security measures
advanced by the Mediterranean nonaligned states at their (Brunei)
meeting. It is a sound basis for broad and fruitful dialogue on the
problems of the region.
   ``Along with the earlier Soviet proposals to reduce military
potential in the Mediterranean area, we would like to advance
additional proposals for consideration to the international
community.
   ``Reaffirming our readiness to withdraw the Soviet naval forces
along with those of the United States, from the Mediterranean. We
suggest that this should not be put off indefinitely ... and that
as a first step, the number of ships in the two countries' naval
potential here should be frozen as from July 1 this year.
Thereafter, ceilings would be set for them.
   ``Second, even before general confidence-building measures are
agreed upon in the spirit of the Stockholm accords, the Soviet
Union and the United States could give each other and all the other
Mediterranean countries advance notice of any redistribution of
warships and of naval exercises. They could also invite observers
to them.
   ``Third, our country will fully support the elaboration by
Mediterranean and other interested countries of principles and
methods assuring the security of intensive shipping, especially in
international straits.''
</TEXT>
