<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CoptersCrash     03-16 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Copters Crash,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memorials Held For Helicopter Crash Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives and close friends attended
memorial services today for 17 soldiers killed last week in the
collision of two helicopters during a night training exercise.
   Soldiers and dignitaries, including Gov. Wallace Wilkinson,
filled the 450-seat main post chapel. An opened Bible rested on a
simple altar.
   ``I have flown personally with each of these men. I can tell you
without reservation that they truly loved what they were doing,''
said Lt. Col. Joseph A. Fucci, commander of the 101st Aviation
Regiment's 5th Brigade.
   ``We all share in the loss of these men. And though all the
grief that we feel does not begin to compare with the sorrow being
felt by their wives and their families, our hearts and our prayers
go out to you.''
   Seven aviation flight helmets mounted atop sabers and M-16
assault rifles standing next to seven pair of boots to represent
those victims from the fort's aviation brigade.
   ``Over the last week we have expressed our sympathies to
families, friends and fellow soldiers with our heads down, unable
to find the right words, if any at all, and an emptiness felt
within,'' said Maj. Paul J. Pozorski, Sr, acting commander of the
aviation regiment's 1st Battalion.
   One service was held for members of the 101st Aviation Brigade,
a second for members of the 502nd Infantry Regiment. Both units
lost members in the crash.
   Thirteen infantrymen and helicopter crew members died when their
craft, returning to Campbell Army Airfield from a night training
exercise in a formation with two other helicopters, was struck
broadside by a second copter on a separate mission, Army spokesmen
said.
   All four soldiers on the second craft also died, in what the
Army said was its worst aviation accident since 248 Fort Campbell
servicemen were killed in a jet crash in Canada in 1985. The two
other helicopters flying in formation were not damaged and landed
safely.
   An investigation by the Army Safety Center at Fort Rucker, Ala.,
was to finish its work at the crash scene six miles from the
airfield by Friday and reconvene at Fort Rucker, officials said.
   The safety center's report on the accident is expected within
three months.
   One crash investigator has said initial findings indicated that
``human and environmental factors'' _ and not mechanical failure _
were suspected as responsible for the collision.
</TEXT>
