<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BodyDig     03-16 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Body Dig,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains of Former Husband Found Buried in Front Yard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARLOW, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body buried in the police chief's front
yard turned out to be that of his wife's former husband, and now
authorities are trying to find out how the man died and how the
body ended up where it did.
   State pathologist Dr. Roger Fossum was to continue an autopsy
today, according to Gregory Swope, senior assistant attorney
general.
   Dental records identified the remains as those of Russell Bean,
Swope said Tuesday. Bean disappeared 10 years ago; his wife,
Sylvia, married the police chief, Robert Chambers, a year after
Bean's disappearance.
   Sources close to the investigation told The Associated Press
that police began digging in Chambers' front yard following
revelations by his father, Clifton Chambers, who died last
Wednesday.
   Police discovered the bones on Monday after three days of
digging.
   The Keene Sentinel reported that police investigators learned
the elder Chambers confessed to his daughter that Bean died
accidentally in a fist fight after hitting his head on a rock.
Clifton Chambers also told his daughter that he helped bury Bean's
body, the newspaper said.
   The attorney general's office, which has handled all news
releases in the case, has declined to comment on the source of its
information.
   Swope said only that the dig ``was undertaken when allegations
arose that a corpse was buried at that location approximately 10
years ago.''
   No charges have been filed in the case.
   Chambers, 36, and his wife, Sylvia, about 35, have been secluded
at a friend's home and have not spoken with reporters.
   Chambers, who has lived in the town of 600 most of his life,
three years ago took over as part-time chief. He also is part-time
chief of nearby Gilsum. He took an indefinite leave of absence from
the Marlow job on Saturday.
   Sylvia Chambers is the town welfare director and has worked with
the Girl Scouts and the cancer society.
   The couple lives in a five-room, 1{-story cabin with their four
teen-age children by previous marriages.
   This is the second time in five years that Marlow has been
shocked by a criminal investigation.
   In 1983, Audrey Hilley, who became known as the ``black widow,''
was arrested in Marlow. She had been convicted in Alabama of
poisoning her husband in 1975 and later trying to poison her
daughter.
   While a fugitive, she married a man in Florida, moved with him
to Marlow, left on a trip to Texas, faked her death and returned to
him posing as her twin sister. She died last year of exposure after
failing to return from a furlough from a women's prison in Alabama.
</TEXT>
