<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrexelSainthood     03-16 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel Sainthood,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Theologians Agree Deafness Cure Was Miracle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of theologians has ruled the
unexplained healing of a youth's hearing impairment was a miracle
attributed to Mother Katharine Drexel, advancing efforts to have
the heiress-turned-nun declared a Roman Catholic saint.
   The panel's decision will be reviewed by the 19 cardinals of the
Congregation for the Causes of Saints, which will take up the case
after Easter and recommend any further action to Pope John Paul II.
   A group of doctors said in December they could find no medical
explanation for the healing in 1974 of Robert J. Gutherman, now 28,
of Bensalem, after an infection had destroyed the hearing in his
right ear.
   He regained hearing after his family and members of the order
Miss Drexel founded, the Sisters of the Blessed Sacrament for
Indians and Colored People, prayed for her intervention.
   Miss Drexel, who died in 1955 at the age of 96, was declared
``venerable'' on Jan. 26, 1987. If the theologians' decision is
upheld by the cardinals and the pope concurs, she would be declared
``blessed,'' the final step before sainthood.
   Before she could be declared a saint, a second miracle would
have to be credited to her.
   Miss Drexel founded the Sisters of the Blessed Sacrament in 1891
and gave $20 million toward helping blacks and American Indians.
   ``I am elated,'' said Sister Faith Okerson, executive secretary
of the Cornwell Heights-based order. ``It's a real gift to us and
our nation.''
   But Sister Patricia Lynch, a spokeswoman for the order, said
Miss Drexel would have been happier to learn about the appointment
Tuesday of Eugene A. Marino as archbishop of Atlanta.
   Marino, who will be the first black American archbishop,
attended an elementary school founded by the Sisters of the Blessed
Sacrament in Biloxi, Miss.
   ``She was not one for a lot of fuss about herself,'' Sister
Lynch said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
