<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens 1stLd-Writethru a0420 03-16 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0420,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Wins Week of Heavy Pre-Emptions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd pvs to explain how pre-emptions
affect network ratings. Picks up 3rd graf, `With only ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC's ``Aaron's Way'' made it into the top 10 in
the A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings as the television season winds down
and the networks begin giving spring tryouts to potential series.
   Last week's ratings were skewed by pre-emptions for college
basketball and the Rev. Billy Graham's televised fund-raising, but
NBC still won, taking the top five places.
   Network analysts estimate that about a quarter of the country's
network affiliates pre-empted network shows for the Graham crusade
on Friday night, lowering the networks' ratings. Graham's show is
syndicated, so its ratings aren't included in the weekly Nielsens.
   With only five weeks left, ABC is holding onto second place in
the season-long ratings race, thanks to high ratings for its Winter
Olympics coverage.
   NBC won the week that ended Sunday with an average, prime-time
rating of 15.9. CBS had a 12.7 and ABC 11.8. The season-to-date
averages are NBC 16.3, ABC 14.0 and CBS 13.6.
   To make up the 0.4 point it lags behind ABC, CBS would have to
beat ABC by two points each of the remaining five weeks of the
season, an unlikely prospect.
   CBS, however, has rebounded in news ratings. For the week that
ended Friday, the ``CBS Evening News'' had an average rating of
11.1, its second-straight victory. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' had
a 10.2 and ``NBC Nightly News'' had a 9.4.
   The rating is the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions.
   After a lengthy reign at the top of the news ratings last
summer, NBC is now struggling in third, although the close rankings
make the news race virtually a three-way tie.
   NBC analyst Gerald Jaffe said results of the November sweeps
showed NBC with a disadvantage in local news lead-in. NBC
affiliates had an average rating of 11.5, which ``Nightly News''
improved on, to 11.9.
   CBS had the best advantage. Its affiliates had an average rating
of 12.9, and the network newscast improved that to 13.1. ABC
affiliates averaged a 12.0 rating and the network broadcast was a
12.3.
   ``Network news is an island in a sea of local news,'' said
Jaffe. ``If the local news is going down, there's not much you can
do to keep the network news from going down, too.''
   NBC continued to dominate prime time. ``The Cosby Show'' was No.
1 even though the episode was a repeat. Next was NBC's ``Cheers,''
``A Different World,'' ``Night Court'' and ``Golden Girls.'' The
rest of the top 10: ``Murder, She Wrote'' CBS, ``The People's
Choice Awards'' CBS, ``60 Minutes'' CBS, ``Growing Pains'' ABC.
``Aaron's Way,'' a new NBC series starring Merlin Olsen as the
patron of an Amish family trying to cope in California, made its
debut at No. 10, the best showing of the crop of new series getting
spring tryouts.
   The premiere movie of ABC's new series ``Probe'' did well,
landing in 28th place, but its regular time period on Thursday
didn't make a dent in the ratings and was ranked 60th of 68.
   ABC seems to have successfully transplanted ``Growing Pains''
from Tuesday to Wednesday, where it was strong enough to pull
``Head of the Class'' into 11th place.
   Katharine Hepburn proved she is still a ratings draw. Her NBC
movie ``Laura Lansing Slept Here'' was 12th.
   CBS did make headway against NBC's Thursday's lineup with the
debut of ``48 Hours'' in its new time period opposite ``Cosby.''
Last week's documentary on runaways ranked 34th with a rating of
22.9.
   The lowest-rated shows of the week were: ``Buck James,''
``Probe,'' ``Ohara,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Hotel,'' ``Barry Manilow,
Swing Street,'' ABC's Super Tuesday coverage, ``The Thorns,'' CBS'
Super Tuesday coverage and ``The Redeye Express.''
</TEXT>
