<1ST_LINE>u i PM-IRA-Funeral 7thLd-Writethru   03-16 0720</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IRA-Funeral, 7th Ld - Writethru,a0653,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Killed At Burial Of IRA Members</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD detail, eyewitness accounts, related
rioting; edits to tighten. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON-14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers fired pistols and
hurled hand grenades at a graveside service for three slain Irish
Republican Army guerrillas today, killing three people and injuring
34, police reported. One man was arrested.
   Thousands of mourners threw themselves to the ground as the
explosions ripped across the Milltown Roman Catholic cemetery,
while hundreds of others raced across the graves pursuing a
suspected attacker.
   One attacker, weaving and dodging between gravestones, flung a
hand grenade at the pursuing mourners.
   Organizers of the funeral for the guerrillas, who were shot by
British troops in Gibraltar, immediately blamed Protestant
paramilitaries for the attack.
   Police moved in to surround the cemetery and a dozen ambulances
ferried the 34 injured, including several young children hit by
gunfire, to the nearby Royal Victoria Hospital.
   The three dead, all men, were not immediately identified. A
hospital spokeswoman said one of the injured, a woman, was in
serious condition and three men also were gravely wounded.
   ``It's obvious it was an attack by Loyalist (Protestant)
movements,'' Martin McGuinness, vice president of Sinn Fein, the
outlawed IRA's legal political front, told reporters in the
cemetery.
   The violence erupted about 15 yards away as the flag-draped
coffins of Mairead Farrell, 31, Sean Savage, 24, and Daniel McCann,
30, were being lowered into a single grave. The unarmed trio were
shot March 6 by British troops in Gibraltar, and British
authorities alleged the three were on a bombing mission.
   Within hours of the cemetery attack, youths hijacked and set
fire to a bus in the Ardoyne area in nearby Catholic West Belfast,
despite Sinn Fein appeals for calm. It roused fears of renewed
rioting in the West Belfast, already tense because of the funerals.
   At the cemetery, mourners screamed as at least five explosions
rang out. McGuinness said that witnesses had spotted four men
getting out of white van and slip into the cemetery just before the
attack.
   Amid scenes of chaos in the cemetery, several hundred youths
gave chase to one attacker who fled, still firing and throwing a
grenades, witnesses said.
   ``I saw maybe 300 youths chasing this one gunman who turned
every 15-20 yards, threw a hand grenade and loosed off a shot
before running again,'' said cab driver Aidan O'Reilly.
   ``The mourners were gaining, but bunched up and he threw another
grenade into the middle of them, then got out on to the motorway.
... He was egging them on to come and get him when he threw the
grenade.''
   At the cemetery, Sinn Fein organizers completed the funeral
while priests comforted the wounded.
   The Rev. Alec Reid, who was saying prayers next to the graveside
as the last of the coffins draped in the Irish tricolor was being
lowered, said he saw a young man throwing something from the back
of the crowd.
   ``I thought they were stones, but it looks as if they were
grenades. He was also firing shots into the crowd.''
   In London, British officials said Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher was immediately informed.
   The mourners had followed the coffins through somber streets to
the cemetery.
   At a mass earlier in St. Agnes, mourners listened silently as
the priest charged that the three IRA men were murdered.
   Shortly before the funeral began, a bomb exploded on a street
more than a mile from the church, slightly injuring a British
soldier on foot patrol, police reported.
   The almost exclusively Catholic Irish Republican Army is
fighting to push the British out of Protestant-dominated Northern
Ireland, join it with the Republic of Ireland and set up an
all-Ireland socialist state.
   Britain says the slain guerrillas were shot by commandos while
preparing a car bomb attack on the changing of the guard outside
the governor's residence in the colony on the southern tip of Spain.
   The three were unarmed, but Britain said they made movements
that led the soldiers to believe their lives were in danger. The
Irish government has complained that the soldiers should have tried
to arrest the trio.
   In the tense buildup to the funerals, Protestants stoned hearses
that brought the IRA bodies home Tuesday.
</TEXT>
