<DOCNO> AP880316-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Rebels     03-16 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Dead In Heavy Fighting In Northern Luzon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGUED, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers today battled more than 100
communist rebels who burned a town hall and kidnapped three
policemen. At least four rebels and three soldiers were killed, the
military said.
   Before dawn, about 120 rebels entered San Juan, and most took
over the municipal building while others searched homes, Maj.
Wilmur Panabang told repoters. San Juan is 210 miles north of
Manila.
   Panabang, the Philippine Constabulary assistant provincial
commander, said troops arrived at daybreak in trucks and an armored
personnel carrier from the provincial capital of Bangued, about 20
miles away, and attacked the rebel positions.
   The troops were backed by three helicopter gunships, but
Panabang denied they fired rockets at the rebels in the town hall.
   ``We wanted to do that but we were afraid to miss and hit houses
instead because the town hall is in the middlle of town,'' he said.
   Provincial Governor Vicente Valera ordered the evacuation of
residents from San Juan and nearby villages during the fighting and
military pursuit operations to prevent civilians from getting hit
in the crossfire.
   At least four rebels and three soldiers were killed before the
guerrillas broke off the engagement about five hours later, set
fire to the building and retreated to the nearby mountains,
Panabang said.
   Only seven bodies were recovered following the fighting,
including those of two soldiers whose remains were charred in the
fire. But Panabang quoted witnesses as saying the rebels loaded
nine bodies on a commandeered jeep as they departed.
   He said the rebels ``may very well have suffered up to 13 dead''
in the raid.
   One trooper also was wounded in the fighting, Panabang said.
   The retreating guerrillas took three police hostages with them,
including San Juan police chief Alejandro Arcanghel, he said.
   More than 100 troops backed by the three helicopter gunships and
the armored personnel carrier pursued the rebel force into the
hills around San Juan until midday, Panabang said. He said the
military planned to resume pursuit of the rebels shortly.
   The attack was the bloodiest in northern Luzon this year and was
the second in Abra province.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
