<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HanfordContamination     03-16 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hanford Contamination,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Crane Operators Contaminated at Plutonium Facility</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two crane operators at a plutonium
production plant were contaminated with a low level of radiation,
and one of the men carried the radiation into his home, a plant
spokesman said.
   Investigators found radiation in the cab of a crane at the plant
but the source of the contamination has not been determined, said
Bill Whiting of Westinghouse Hanford, which operates the
Plutonium-Uranium Extraction Plant at the Hanford nuclear
reservation under government contract.
   Contamination was found on one of the men when he reported to
work Monday and a check of his home determined he had spread the
contamination there, Whiting said.
   Radiation was found on the other employee's hands and clothes
Monday as he prepared to leave for the day, Whiting said.
   The level of radiation was extremely low and posed no health
threat, he said.
   Both operators were decontaminated and given clearance to return
to work.
   A radiation team checked the homes of the two crane operators
and two other employees Monday night, Whiting said. They removed a
wash cloth, electric razor, towel and undershirt from the home of
the employee who registered contamination when he arrived at work,
he said.
   The maximum contamination level in the crane operator's home was
3,500 counts per minute, or less than half the radiation present in
the glowing part of a lighted gas lantern, Whiting said.
   ``You can buy higher levels of radiation at the store,'' he said.
   It wasn't known how radiation on the operator who contaminated
his home had been missed in daily checks of employees leaving the
plant.
   The contamination was isolated at the plant in the area
surrounding the crane, he said.
   Investigators' preliminary report will be issued within 10
working days, Whiting said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
