<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--School Explosion,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Closed After Chemistry Lab Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion in a chemistry lab injured a
teacher and a student today and forced officials to close Newton
County High School.
   Both the 34-year-old teacher and the 16-year-old student were
reported in stable condition, but a Georgia Baptist Medical Center
spokeswoman said the teacher was expected to undergo plastic
surgery.
   The teacher was taken by helicopter to the Atlanta hospital with
burns, bruises, hand injuries and minor facial injuries, said
spokeswoman Colleen Nowak.
   The student suffered cuts on her arms and was expected to be
kept overnight at Newton County General Hospital, said a
spokeswoman there, Kathy Klauss.
   The explosion occurred during a chemistry experiment about 8:45
a.m., said Herb Burnsed, assistant superintendent of the Newton
County school system.
   Fumes spread into hallways and prompted officials to dismiss
classes for the day, he said.
   The victims were not identified pending notification of
relatives.
</TEXT>
