<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AndersonDay     03-16 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anderson Day,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hostage Terry Anderson Honored In Lorain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Hostages, PM-Hostages-Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.R. KROPKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LORAIN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small group of people dedicated to Terry
Anderson's release from captivity in Lebanon today hoisted an
American flag and tied a yellow ribbon to the flag pole at City
Hall.
   The ceremony marked the third anniversary of the capture of
Anderson, who was born in Lorain and spent the first seven years of
his life in this northern Ohio city.
   Anderson, 40, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was abducted March 16, 1985. He is the longest-held of 22
foreign hostages in Lebanon. There has been no word of him for
three months.
   A dozen people, including some of Anderson's relatives, attended
the ceremony in cold, dry weather.
   Jack LaVriha, chairman of the town's Free Terry Anderson
Committee, spoke briefly and accused the Reagan administration of
dragging its feet and doing little on behalf of Anderson and oher
hostages in Lebanon.
   Gwen Jones, Anderson's aunt, said after the ceremony that the
family is ``finding it very hard and frustrating.''
   Anderson's sister, Peggy Say, will be speaking at the Lorain
Veterans Council's 42nd annual banquet on Saturday. Mrs. Say, of
Batavia, N.Y., was in Washington today for a ceremony for Anderson
and other hostages.
   In Beirut, two Lebanese newspapers today published letters
addressed to Anderson and his pro-Iranian captors, along with
pictures of his 2-year-old daughter.
   Mrs. Jones said she hadn't thought her nephew would be held this
long. She said that if she could talk to him, she would ``tell him
to keep praying. I'm sure the Lord is going to answer those
prayers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
