<DOCNO> AP880316-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Taiwan-Movies     03-16 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Taiwan-Movies,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan to Allow Import of Foreign Films Shot in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Taiwan government will allow foreign
films shot on the China mainland to be shown here, an official said
Wednesday.
   Government spokesman Shaw Yu-ming told reporters the government
decided to lift the ban on the films because Taiwan citizens have
been allowed since last year to visit the Chinese mainland for
family reunions.
   Officials of the Government Information Office's Motion Pictures
Department said applications to import the movies will be accepted
effective Wednesday.
   Shaw said, however, that the new policy won't apply to
Mandarin-language films shot in China by companies in the British
colony of Hong Kong, which, together with domestic films, are
governed by a more restrictive law. This restriction will be
reviewed in May.
   Shaw said Taiwan film companies still will be banned from going
to China to shoot movies.
   The public repeatedly has urged the government to ease the
restrictions on foreign films, especially since ``The Last
Emperor,'' a movie shot in Beijing, won nine Oscar nominations last
month.
</TEXT>
