<DOCNO> AP880316-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   03-16 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0743</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   March 9
   Westerly (R.I.) Sun on nuclear reactor safety:
   The cumulative effect of frequent censure of the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission for lax enforcement of safety standards is to
bolster a where-there's-smoke-there's-fire conclusion.
   This time ... the NRC's apparent (desire) to OK relicensing of
reactors closed for safety flaws in 1985 by the Tennessee Valley
Authority brought testy comments at a House committee hearing.
   The projected restarts are planned although the Justice
Department has not completed its investigation of charges that the
TVA's nuclear power manager, Steven A. White, made ... false
assertions as to the reactors' compliance with safety rules.
   Rep. Sam Gejdenson of Connecticut ... zeroed in on the
conclusion of the commission ... that White ``intentionally lied to
the NRC.''
   He spoke for many ... when he said: ``The thing I am concerned
about is that the Justice Department could decide that Mr. White is
guilty of lying ... and the NRC would have ordered a restart of
that reactor.''
   A fair question: What's the big hurry?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 15
   Baltimore Evening Sun on the execution of Willie Darden:
   As Florida authorities prepared for the ritual of taking Willie
Jasper Darden's life ..., they maintained that his conviction for a
1973 murder was based on ``irrefutable evidence.''
   In fact the evidence is refutable _ refutable by at least two
witnesses who were not called at Darden's trial more than a decade
ago. But what is irrefutable is that Darden, a black man, was tried
before an elected white judge in an inflamed predominantly white
community in rural Florida, prosecuted by a white district
attorney, ... convicted by an all-white jury drawn from friends and
neighbors of the murder victim, and sent to the electric chair by a
white governor. ...
   Is there anyone of any color, creed, ethnic background or
religious or ideological persuasion who truly believes he could get
a fair trial for his life under such circumstances?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 15
   The Kansas City (Mo.) Times on aid to the Contras:
   If Congress has behaved schizophrenically over Contra aid, part
of the reason may be that deception by the administration has made
it hard to tell reality from phantasm in Nicaragua.
   The administration has put lawmakers in the unfortunate position
of having to question the leadership of their democratic government
while simultaneously trying to fend off communist leadership in
another.
   That helps explain why lawmakers have over time voted for and
against Contra aid, and why it is difficult now for military aid to
be approved.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 11
   Riverside (Calif.) Press-Enterprise on budget deficit
projections:
   There is a White House budgeting ritual. Call it Fiscal Chicken.
...
   The White House budget office issues its spending plan. The
spending is all geared to impossibly high economic growth
predictions. In six or eight months, it becomes apparent that there
just isn't that much steam in the economy.
   Shame might compel most people to concede, but this is where
this budget office gets tough. ...
   Only when evidence of this impossible optimism becomes just
mountainous do the president's men back off a bit in their
predictions. And as it retreats, the Office of Management and
Budget is required to observe that there's a new economic boom
coming, just around the corner.
   Recently President Reagan's fiscal 1989 budget was issued. ... A
deficit of $130 billion is foreseen.
   To make all these figures come out so serendipitously, the White
House budget office underlaid them with a forecast of 2.4 percent
economic growth in calendar 1988 and 3.5 percent growth in calendar
1989.
   The Congressional Budget Office has now come out with its own
economic forecast. It envisions growth of 0.6 percent less in '88
and 0.9 percent less in '89. Run the White House budget numbers off
that base and it produces a fiscal 1989 deficit of $165 billion.
   Under the usual rules, the White House wouldn't admit its
optimism before about September. But this being the year of
transitional election, it may never admit it.
   It is Ronald Reagan's last chance to set a new record for rosy
optimism. He'll probably want to have a run at it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
