<DOCNO> AP880316-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   03-16 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: at it.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 8
   The Commercial Appeal, Memphis, Tenn., on state-federal
relationships:
   State and local governments have long had a love-hate
relationship with Washington. They gladly accept federal subsidies,
but resent conditions on how to spend the money.
   Now they are getting the worst of both worlds: burdensome
mandates without the funds to pay for them.
   The National Governrs' Association has voted to make this issue
its highest priority for 1988.
   The governors _ along with mayors, city councils and school
boards _ believe they deserve far more credit for honesty, good
will and competence than the federal rulemakers are willing to give
them. They are right.
   In many areas, such as education and welfare reform, these
officials have shown themselves to be more innovative and effective
than Washington. ...
   The governors have 163 specific proposals to lighten the
regulatory load. Congress should pay close attention.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 15
   Albuquerque (N.M.) Journal on drug testing of transportation
employees:
   The discovery of cocaine in the system of the pilot of a
commuter airplane that crashed near Durango, Colo., in January
highlights a troubling dimension of the debate over who, if
anybody, among American workers should be subjected to mandatory
random drug testing.
   It was in January that the National Transportation Safety Board
disclosed a Conrail engineer had used marijuana prior to a January
1987 collision between an Amtrak passenger train and a Conrail
freight train, in which 16 passengers were killed.
   The personal rights of individuals employed in the
transportation industry may have to give way to the right to safety
of those who depend upon them to give alert, drug-free service in
preparing and crewing commercial airliners and trains.
   If there is a group in our society in which mandatory, random
testing would have potential for saving lives, the public
transportation industry is it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 14
   San Antonio (Texas) Express-News on trading with the Soviet
Union:
   Of all the Cabinet departments, the Department of Commerce is
probably the least conspicuous to the average American, but beware.
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity wants to increase trade
with the Soviet Union. Selling Levis, Fords and Coca-Colas to 250
million Soviets is tempting, but caution should be exercised.
   The Soviets won't allow their market to be bought for a
pittance. They want high-tech products more than blue jeans and
cola.
   The Pentagon opposes any trade in sensitive military gear. It
should.
   Getting a corner on Soviet markets is enticing, but these are
the same people who trample the civil rights of their citizens, who
use slave labor to manufacture some of their goods, and who, in
parts of the world, look down rifle barrels at U.S. troops.
   In summary, it's OK to boost trade in some areas, but don't give
away the store.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 9
   The News Tribune, Woodbridge, N.J., on Masters and Johnson's
AIDS research:
   In their new book ... so-called sex experts Drs. William Masters
and Virginia Johnson have suggested that one in 20 men who have had
at least six sexual partners for five years are infected with the
AIDS virus.
   They say the rate is slightly higher among women.
   Previous studies have shown the undeniable link between
intravenous drug use and AIDS, and homosexual behavior and AIDS.
   What Masters and Johnson have done is suggest the link between
casual heterosexual sex and AIDS may be greater than previously
thought.
   Time will tell who is right. We want to believe Masters and
Johnson's scary scenario is wrong. But who knows?
   AIDS is such a mystery that it is difficult to offer reliable
statistics. The debate really isn't how, but how much.
   We could dismiss Masters and Johnson's methodology as wrong.
What would be worse would be to dismiss the risk, and be dead wrong.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
