<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   03-16 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: dead wrong.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 9
   Medford (Ore.) Mail Tribune on Jesse Jackson:
   Jesse Jackson says he plans to be the Democratic Party's
presidential nominee. ... With all due respect, we beg to differ.
...
   Jackson cannot survive a close examination. His record includes
too many radical stands, too many blanket condemnations of the
United States and too many associations with foreign leaders of
questionable character. ...
   In practical terms, Jackson's best hope is that his delegate
strength will force the party's leaders to make sure that the
presidential platform features issues of concern to the people who
have supported him.
   Expecting much of anything beyond that is wishful thinking.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 10
   Brainerd (Minn.) Daily Dispatch on postal rate increases:
   Dear Postmaster General:
   We're writing to you now, before postage rates rise next month.
   So you want to raise the price of the common, first-class stamp
to 25 cents? That's only a jump of 14 percent, or three cents.
   Trouble is, that's just part of the problem.
   You also want to raise the rates for second-class mail by 18
percent and for third-class mail by 25 percent.
   And guess who is going to help offset the increase. Yep, the
consumer.
   Affected businesses will be forced to charge higher prices.
Magazines and newspapers will be forced to charge higher rates for
advertising and subscriptions.
   We're afraid that higher postage rates will impose hardships on
postal patrons whose only consolation will be a probable decline in
the amount of junk mail.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 11
   The Hutchinson (Kan.) News on college admissions standards:
   Mediocrity may be just so-so in most places, but in the Kansas
House of Representatives, medocrity is excellent.
   With a vote so lopsided that it could never be described as
average, the House spurned the idea of setting some (rather low)
admissions standards for entrance to the state's top universities.
...
   Kansas students would have responded well to the modest
challenge outlined in the educational admissions bill.
   No conscientious student would have been prevented from getting
a college degree, and a series of higher educational standards
would have led to more valuable degrees. ...
   Mediocrity is not nearly the superlative value that politicians
think it to be.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 11
   The Milwaukee (Wis.) Journal on anti-drug legislation:
   Barely two weeks before the current state legislative session is
to end, the omnibus drug bill promoted by Gov. Thompson and several
lawmakers appears ready for action.
   The massive bill, which sets out an $11.6 million drug-fighting
program, is the state's broadest attack on drug abuse in years and
deserves bipartisan support.
   Apparently, the only danger the bill faces is the possibility of
getting hung up over one of its more controversial features _ the
so-called ``Len Bias'' provision.
   Named for a University of Maryland basketball player who died in
1986 after taking cocaine, this provision would allow prosecution
of drug suppliers on charges of second-degree murder if a client
died of drug use.
   While that provision likely would have a deterrent effect on
drug dealers and should be retained in the bill's final version, it
is by no means the heart of the legislation.
   Debate over its inclusion should not be permitted to hold up
legislative approval of the omnibus bill.
   More important are the bill's (1) stiffer criminal penalties for
the sale and use of a broad class of drugs and (2) needed funds for
drug and alcohol treatment programs. ...
   The bill strongly deserves approval before the Legislature
adjourns.
</TEXT>
