<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoyinBox     03-16 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boy in Box,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Pleads Guilty To Locking Boy In Box, Faces Maximum 90-Day
Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman charged with keeping an 8-year-old
boy in a coffin-like box for two years said she confined the boy to
protect her possessions and pleaded guilty to unlawful imprisonment.
   ``I restrained (the boy) during my sleeping hours in order to
keep him from destroying property. My judgment may not have been
proper, but my judgment as to the amount of restraint seemed proper
to me under the circumstances,'' said Retha Skyles in a handwritten
statement.
   Ms. Skyles, 54, entered her plea Tuesday in Pierce County
Superior Court before Judge Thomas Swayze Jr., who set sentencing
for April 26.
   In exchange for the plea, the prosecution agreed that Ms. Skyles
be sentenced under provisions for first-time offenders, said deputy
prosecutor Barbara Corey-Boulet.
   That means a judge could sentence the woman to up to 90 days in
jail plus two years' probation and counseling.
   Ms. Skyles was charged with keeping the son of her
step-granddaughter in a playhouse-sized box from May 1, 1985, to
May 1, 1987. The box often was locked and contained a jar in which
the boy was expected to urinate, the charges said. The boy was not
allowed to attend school.
   An anonymous referral tipped off state Child Potective Services
workers on April 29, 1987, and they took the boy and his
11-year-old sister into custody. The siblings have lived with
foster parents and are doing well, Ms. Corey-Boulet said.
   One of Ms. Skyles' adult sons said the confinement was a
temporary way to handle the tantrum-prone boy.
   He said the family believed he was brain-damaged because of his
mother, who the son said abused drugs and wouldn't take proper care
of the boy. The natural mother denied she was a drug abuser.
</TEXT>
