<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Spain-Strike     03-16 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Spain-Strike,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spanish Teachers Continue Strikes For More Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of Spain's 270,000 public school
teachers on Wednesday began a second two-day strike for higher pay,
forcing cancellation of classes for more than 5 million students,
union and Education Ministry officials said.
   The ministry said it won't negotiate while the threat of strikes
continues.
   The nation's two largest unions, the Socialist-led General
Workers Union and the communist-oriented Workers Commissions,
called the strike.
   The unions said 92 percent of teachers backed their March 9-10
strike. The Education Ministry estimated teacher participation at
60 percent.
   Negotiations broke off last month over public elementary and
secondary school teachers' demands that they receive pay equal to
that of similarly qualified civil servants.
   A union spokesman said primary school teachers earn an average
of about $929 a month and want it raised to about $1,170, while
secondary and technical school teachers want about $1,380 a month.
   Education Ministry Undersecretary Joaquin Arango said teachers
last year received the biggest raises _ 13 percent _ among civil
servants. The rest of the civil servants received raises of 5
percent. Spain's 1987 inflation rate was 4.6 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
