<DOCNO> AP880316-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Denmark-Opium     03-16 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Denmark-Opium,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danish Seed Company Developing Opium-Free Poppy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A seed company has developed a poppy
with a reduced content of opium, a spokesman said Wednesday.
   The white poppy is popular in Denmark for its seed,
traditionally used in bread. The plant's juice contains opium,
which can be refined into morphine and heroin.
   ``We are doing this so that drug addicts will not feel tempted
to pick or cut the poppies to get the drug, and so that farmers
will continue to be allowed to grow poppies,'' said Christian
Petersen of Daehnfeldt, the biggest seed producer in Europe.
   Drug addicts have been known to plunder poppy fields in Denmark.
In other countries, including the United States, Great Britain and
West Germany, poppy cultivation has been banned.
   ``We ... have been able to reduce the opium content by half. In
a couple of years, we expect to have more or less eliminated it
completely,'' Petersen said.
</TEXT>
