<DOCNO> AP880316-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1250EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MisleadingTests     03-16 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Misleading Tests,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Test Critic Files Fraud Complaints in 50 States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West Virginia physician has filed consumer
fraud complaints in all 50 states charging four major publishers
with selling achievement tests that give a misleadingly rosy
picture of student progress.
   The complaints were filed by John Jacob Cannell, who gained
prominence last November as a test gadfly with a 26-page report
accusing publishers of the Iowa Test, the Metropolitan Achievement
Test and similar tests of giving ``children, parents, school
systems, legislatures, and the press misleading reports on
achievement levels.''
   The November report led officials of the U.S. Department of
Education to summon 40 test experts and publishers to a closed-door
meeting last month to discuss possible actions.
   Cannell, who is from Daniels, W.Va., filed his complaints
Wednesday with the 50 state attorneys general, and distributed them
to reporters. But he said he had not provided copies to the
publishers named in the complaints.
   Three of the four publishers said they had no comment because
they hadn't seen the complaint. But a spokesman for CTB@McGraw
Hill, publisher of the California Achievement Test and
Comprehensive Test of Basic Skills, said Cannell's work was ``full
of fallacious statements.''
   Cannell's complaint claimed ``that 90 percent of school
districts and 70 percent of children in America's public elementary
schools are presently testing above average in elementary grades on
one of the six commercial tests used in the U.S.A.''
   Thirty-eight of the complaints named CTB@McGraw Hill; 36 named
The Psychological Corporation, which publishes the Stanford
Achievement Test and the Metropolitan Achievement Test; 31 cited
Riverside Publishing Co., which publishes the Iowa Test of Basic
Skills, and 26 listed Science Research Associates, publisher of the
SRA exam.
   The complaints ask that publishers be required to identify
school districts using their tests, provide free annual updates of
the norms that determine how students score, and provide new test
questions for free each year to ensure that schools cannot ``teach
to the test.''
   Cannell, founder and head of the 700-member West Virginia
education watchdog group Friends for Education Inc., also called
upon each state to analyze standardized tests to determine if they
have gotten easier over time.
   He also demanded that test publishers supply new, more accurate
tests at no charge to ``compensate consumers for any
misrepresentations received from previously deceptive tests.''
   In September, Cannell filed similar consumer complaints in his
home state and in Kentucky. He withdrew them last month after
McGraw Hill announced it would provide annually updated norms.
   Paul Williams, director of research and management of CTB@McGraw
Hill, said Cannell condemned standardized tests generally for
giving too rosy a picture of student progress, but ``he only looks
at half the pie'' because Cannell omits the fact that test scores
for high school students have declined.
   Responding to some of Cannell's specific complaints, Williams
said publishers would probably resist demands to identify school
districts using their tests. ``We have a responsibility to protect
the confidentiality of our customers,'' he said.
   Williams said his company already updates test norms annually,
but he rejected Cannell's demand that that service be provided free.
   He said it would be possible for testmakers to provide states
with new questions each year, ``but it's also expensive. If our
customers want it, we would respond.''
   He added that the technical manuals that publishers routinely
provide school districts using their tests already provide much of
the information Cannell demanded, such as how difficult the tests
are.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
