<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1311EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DaliLawsuits     03-16 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dali Lawsuits,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paris Art Gallery Sues Beverly Hills Art Dealer For Alleged Dali
Fakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Paris art gallery filed federal lawsuits
accusing a dealer of operating a $32.5 million nationwide forgery
network specializing in the works of surrealist painter Salvador
Dali.
   T.R. Rogers, whose Beverly Hills gallery was raided in August
when forgery allegations surfaced, was named with four others in
the $145 million package of suits filed last week in Los Angeles
and New York on behalf of Galerie Furstenberg of Paris.
   Also named were wholesalers Philip Coffaro, Thomas Wallace and
Carol Convertine and art authenticator Julien Aime, all of New York.
   The New York suit accuses all five of running an ongoing
criminal enterprise in violation of federal racketeering laws.
   Rogers' attorney, David Steiner, called the lawsuits
``preposterous,'' and Arnold Ross, a New York lawyer representing
Coffaro, said, ``There doesn't appear to be any basis to it at
all.''
   ``I'm sure there will be substantial cross-complaints filed
against them for the outrageous claims they're making,'' Steiner
said.
   Beverly Hills detectives began an investigation into Rogers'
gallery last summer after Jean Argillet, owner of Galerie
Furstenberg, told police the originals of some of the works in
Rogers' gallery represented as Dalis were actually in his own
gallery in France.
   The case has since been turned over to the major frauds section
of the Los Angeles County district attorney's office.
   The international Dali market has long been the subject of an
authenticity controversy because the artist made numerous copies
during his youth and now refuses to come out of seclusion in Spain
to authenticate disputed canvasses.
   Ms. Convertine pleaded guilty to felony fraud and grand larceny
charges in New York last year.
   A grand jury is now contemplating criminal charges against a
Honolulu gallery. Another criminal case was begun in New Mexico,
and the Federal Trade Commission is taking civil action against a
gallery in Arizona.
   According to the Galerie Furstenberg lawsuits, the defendants
reproduced photos of Dali originals, and through photomechanical
means engraved the images on copper plates and ran off multiple
copies.
</TEXT>
