<HEAD>County Draws The Line At Sheriff's Pencil Request</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLEGAN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Allegan County Sheriff's
Department submitted a $930 bill for 5,000 pencils bearing the
sheriff's name, county officials drew the line.
   Sheriff's department officials said the pencils were to be
distributed to students to promote the department's new Youth
Services Bureau, and that's why the bill was submitted to the
county finance committee as a school safety expense.
   ``It's a good thing it doesn't say re-elect (Sheriff) Robert
Schra ... but it came through to us as saying political pencils,''
County Commissioner Flora Moore, co-chair of the finance committee,
said Tuesday. ``Nine hundred dollars worth of advertising pencils
is quite a lot for us to put our John Henry on.''
   Schra said his name appears on most items distributed by the
department, and he is confident the bill will be approved once an
explanation is provided to the committee.
   Moore said she might reconsider the funding if the message is
changed.
   ```Observe the safety rules always' would be fine,'' she said.
</TEXT>
