<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PassportPolicy     03-16 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Passport Policy,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs Seizing Passports Along With Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs agents seized the passport of a man
they accused of smuggling 10 to 12 pounds of cocaine just hours
after a new get-tough policy went into effect, agency spokesmen
said.
   ``A lot of people come in with contraband and go right back out
of the country without going to court. It's become a joke,'' Vann
Capps, director of operations for the Customs Service at Miami
International Airport, said of the passport seizure policy.
   ``This is another tool we can use that is vital to our defense
against drugs,'' he said.
   The new rule will apply to anyone attempting to bring illegal
drugs into the country, regardless of how small the amount, Capps
said. Customs officers routinely make six to 10 drug seizures daily
at the Miami airport; the new program could result in the
confiscation of hundreds of passports weekly, he said.
   Some legal experts have criticized the new policy. They question
the constitutionality of restricting a person's freedom to travel
before the person has been convicted of a crime.
   On Tuesday morning, Dwight Aristotle Borelli, 21, of Miami,
brought home two suitcases with false sides on a flight that
originated in La Paz, Bolivia, and stopped in Panama City, Panama,
said Customs spokesman Michael Sheehan.
   ``Within the false sides of the suitcases, inspectors found
approximately 10 to 12 pounds of cocaine,'' Sheehan said.
   Borelli's U.S. passport was seized and he was arrested about 5
a.m., five hours after the policy took effect, Sheehan said.
Borelli, charged with unlawful importation of cocaine and
possession of a controlled substance, was turned over to the vice
president's drug task force, which prosecutes federal cases.
   Customs inspectors turned Borelli's passport over to federal
prosecutors, who can use it as evidence, Sheehan said. Once the
case is resolved, Borelli will have to apply to the State
Department to get the passport back.
</TEXT>
