<HEAD>Dallas Musuem Acting Director Is San Francisco-Bound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The acting director and chief curator of the
Dallas Museum of Art has resigned to take a position in San
Francisco, museum officials said.
   Steven Nash, 43, will become associate director-chief curator
and curator of European art at the Fine Arts Museums of San
Francisco.
   He will join his former boss, Harry Parker III, who resigned as
DMA director last April to become director of the San Francisco
institution, which includes the M.H. de Young Memorial Museum and
the California Palace of the Legion of Honor.
   Since coming to Dallas in 1980 as the DMA's deputy director and
chief curator, Nash has been responsible for major exhibitions and
acquisitions to the museum's permanent collection. Most recently,
Nash was responsible for the museum's acquisition of its first
paintings by Picasso.
   His resignation is effective Aug. 1.
