<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Homeless     03-16 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Homeless,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papers Publish Reports of Homelessness in Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two newspapers have published accounts of
homelessness in the capital, saying vagrants are living in
underground passages, garbage dumps and staircases.
   The reports, in the national Democratic Party daily Kurier
Polski and in the Warsaw evening daily Express Wieczorny, offered
an unusually vivid discussion of the topic of homelessness, which
officially does not exist in Poland's communist system.
   The articles, published Monday, also reflect the current
liveliness of the official press in Poland, in which censorship of
news on domestic topics has been markedly relaxed.
   ``Statistics don't say how many homeless people there are in
Poland. But from unofficial sources we know there are about 15,000
of them in Warsaw alone,'' said Express Wieczorny. Warsaw's
population is 1.5 million.
   The Kurier Polski article talked about a colony of 20-50
homeless people recently discovered living in underground passages
for the city's central water heating system.
   ``Until not long ago nobody knew that the dark, unending
corridors ... were pulsating with life. Along with all kinds of
worms, the capital's tramps are living there,'' the paper said.
   Asked about the reports at his weekly news conference Tuesday,
government spokesman Jerzy Urban said he had not seen the articles,
but, ``I stand by my statement that there is no such social problem
as homelessness in Poland.''
   Although there is a severe housing shortage in Poland, there is
no evident homelessness in the streets. Beggars are rarely seen and
vagrancy is a crime.
   According to the articles, the homeless include alcoholics,
ex-convicts, mentally ill people and people who are estranged from
their relatives.
   ``Most of them resigned from normal family life by their own
will. One day they simply left their homes and went away,'' said
the Kurier Polski article.
   ``They live in railway stations, in staircases, in garbage dumps
and even in (underground) canals,'' said the Express Wieczorny
article. ``They are dirty, often have head louses and are exhausted
because of malnutrition.'' It said their number is growing.
   The paper said a church social organization, the Adam
Chmielowski Aid Society, is active in Warsaw and five other cities
helping to arrange shelter and jobs for the homeless. The society
gets support from the Roman Catholic Church and the Ministry of
Health and Social Care, it said.
   Kurier Polski, the official paper of the Polish Democratic
Party, which is allied with the ruling Polish United Workers
(Communist) Party, said the homeless people redeem bottles or
rummage through trash and sell salvageable clothing at the city's
markets.
   ``Every earned zloty goes for the purchase of vodka,'' it said.
   It said the colony living in the underground corridors near the
Zeran heat and power plant was discovered two weeks ago when one of
the inhabitants died from alcohol poisoning.
   After a few days, some of the vagrants reported the death to
nuns, who summoned police, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
