<DOCNO> AP880316-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1348EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GuaranteedTuition     03-16 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guaranteed Tuition,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislatures May Be Able To Reverse Tuition Guarantee Tax Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   States may be able to avoid paying federal
taxes on college tuition prepayment plans simply by rewriting laws
governing such programs, a tax law expert said Wednesday.
   ``If you can drag it kicking and screaming into the normal
function of a state governent,'' then a legal case could be made
that earnings on a guaranteed college tuition trust's investments
should be free of federal taxes, said Lawrence A. Jegen, an Indiana
University law professor who also heads Indiana's tuition-guarantee
program, BEST.
   The Internal Revenue Service has ruled that the Michigan
Education Trust would be required to pay federal taxes on its
earnings, although individual investors in the trust would have no
additional tax liability, Michigan Gov. James Blanchard said
Tuesday.
   Five states, including Indiana, have adopted tuition-guarantee
programs modeled after Michigan's.
   Under the programs, parents who make advance payments into the
trust fund are guaranteed that when their child is ready to enter a
state college or university they can do so without additional cost.
The payments typically can be made either all at once or
periodically.
   The states invest the money, so the amount parents must pay
depends upon not only the child's age when the payment is made and
the estimated cost of tuition when the child reaches 18 but also on
estimates of the trust's return on its investment.
   Michigan Treasurer Robert Bowman estimated the IRS ruling could
add 20 percent to the cost of investing in the Michigan trust, if
the trust was fully invested in taxable bonds.
   Jegen said that because the IRS said parents would not have to
pay taxes on their investments, state legislatures would have an
opening for rewriting their laws.
   ``If they (IRS) have concluded that the investors are not
subject to taxation, they have to have done that on some basis,
that once you put your money away, the funds are no longer yours,
that you are not an annual beneficiary of that fund,'' Jegen said.
``Once you separate the investors from the tax consequences and
maybe conclude that the fund is subject to taxation, ... it would
be a fairly small step to have that fund be a part of the state
operations, so much so that it would not be subject to taxation.''
   Constitutionally, the federal government cannot tax the state in
the performance of the functions a state is expected to perform,
Jegen said.
   ``The further away you get from a governmental function, the
more likely it is to be taxable,'' he said.
   For example, a license plate for a car is not subject to federal
taxes because providing license plates is a normal state function,
he said. Proceeds from the sales of textbooks at a campus bookstore
are taxable, because a state is not expected to be in the business
of selling books.
   Jegen said he had not seen the ruling, and his final analysis
would depend in part on the IRS' precise argument.
   The IRS, citing privacy considerations, would not explain the
ruling, nor would it confirm a ruling had been made.
   Besides Indiana, Wyoming, Maine, Florida and Tennessee have
adopted guaranteed tuition programs similar to Michigan's.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0153 </DOCNO>
