<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Rostenkowski-HealthBills     03-16 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rostenkowski-Health Bills,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Sees Bill Threatened by Push for Home Care Subsidies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill to protect families from the financial
threat of catastrophic illness is being threatened by a competing
push for new subsidies for home health care, the chairman of the
House Ways and Means Committee said Wednesday.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., told reporters he believes the
House and Senate, which passed different version of the
catastrophic health care bill, can agree on a version President
Reagan could sign.
   A Senate plan to phase in prescription drug benefits, as opposed
to a House provision putting them in place immediately, could keep
down costs, Rostenkowski said. That would make the bill more
acceptable to the president, who first proposed the catastrophic
coverage in his State of the Union address last year, he said.
   The catastrophic bill was being threatened, however, by Rep.
Claude Pepper's push for legislation to expand Medicare to include
home health care subsidies for the disabled and chronically ill, he
said.
   Pepper, D-Fla., chairman of the House Rules Committee and at 87
the oldest member of Congress, got the chamber's leadership to
schedule a vote on his five-year, $25 billion plan although it had
not gone through the normal committee channels. Rostenkowski's
tax-writing committee did not examine the proposal, which would be
financed by raising Medicare taxes.
   Rostenkowski said some health advocates were telling lawmakers
to support the home care bill instead of the less-costly
catastrophic insurance measure on the ground it is a more pressing
need.
   He said there is a lot of political allure to having the
government help people with those home health costs, especially in
an election year.
   ``I don't know whether any candidate, looking toward November,
can say no to that,'' Rostenkowski said.
   He said supporters were trying to push the bill through without
the study needed to make it work.
   ``I doubt very much that I will support ... the Pepper bill,''
Rostenkowski said. ``You're raising big bucks, and you're changing
the whole direction of the health care system.''
   There was no reason Congress could not eventually move forward
on both measures, but trying to do both this year would likely
result in neither getting done, Rostenkowski said.
   ``I'm trying to get one bill passed, and that's catastrophic
health,'' he said.
</TEXT>
