<1ST_LINE>r w AM-QuailSex     03-16 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quail Sex,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Golden Fleece Award To Study That Shows Quail Sex Improves With
Practice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. William Proxmire gave his ``Golden
Fleece'' award Wednesday to two government agencies for a $107,000
study that found the sexual performance of Japanese quail improved
with practice.
   ``This project gives new meaning to bird watching,'' Proxmire
said of the study, ``Learning and Reproductive Behavior.'' The
research concluded that a peeping tom quail was much more
interested in watching a female quail _ dead or alive _ than in
looking at another male or even a female duck.
   Proxmire, a Wisconsin Democrat, presents the ``Fleece'' each
month to recognize what he considers a waste of taxpayer money.
   Proxmire said that since songwriter Cole Porter made clear years
ago that ``birds do it ...'' what need is there for research into
``stimuli and responses ... involved in various components of their
sexual behavior?''
   There's plenty of need, said Jack Renirie, a spokesman for the
National Science Foundation, which is sharing funds for the study
with the National Institute of Mental Health.
   ``This was a study of learning _ not of the quail,'' Renirie
said in a telephone interview. ``The quail was chosen because it is
an easily available laboratory animal that readily engages in the
behavior that he (the researcher) wants to study.
   ``One reason he's studying learning in connection with
reproduction is that reproduction happens to be one of the real
strong motivating factors in animals,'' he said.
   Renirie recalled similar criticism several years ago when
another government agency was researching the sex life of the
screwworm fly. That research, he said, enabled scientists to halt
destruction of herds of cattle by the fly.
   According to a summary by the foundation, the quail research
could even provide answers to the spread of AIDS.
   The ``research will ... tell us about an aspect of sexual
behavior that has received little systematic attention to date,''
the foundation said. ``Given the life-threatening nature of certain
forms of sexual behavior with the spread of AIDS, knowledge of how
sexual habits are acquired is very important.''
   The foundation selected Japanese quail for the study because of
its uninhibited mating habits. ``When a sexually mature male is
placed with a female, copulation occurs rapidly, often in less than
five minutes,'' the foundation said.
   Researchers were interested in three ``sexual learning
phenomena: sexual looking, classical conditioning of sexual arousal
and improvement in copulatory performance with practice.''
   Proxmire said the study ``found that practice improved sexual
performance. Even the most inhibited males `eventually acquired as
vigorous performance as all other subjects.'''
   It also found that the male quail spent a considerable amount of
time staring at the female through a small window in a cage.
   ``The `sexual looking' phenomenon was so strong that these
amorous males didn't seem to care whether or not the female
recipient of their longing glances was alive or dead,'' Proxmire
told colleagues. ``However, these male quail showed a distinct
viewing preference for female quail over male quail or female
ducks.''
   Although the research ``may be well designed and carefully
executed, the question remains whether, with massive federal
deficits and limited funds for scientific research, spending for
this project is the best use of taxpayers' monies,'' Proxmire said.
   The National Science Foundation funded the early parts of the
quail research, through March 1987; the National Institute of
Mental Health has been backing the study since. Proxmire said
another $100,000-plus is expected to be spent by NIMH _ for a total
of more than $200,000 _ over the next two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
