<1ST_LINE>u a PM-GreylordIndictments     03-16 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greylord Indictments,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Judges Indicted In Greylord Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced federal grand jury
indictments today against seven people, including current and
former Cook County judges, bringing to 87 the number of people
charged in the Operation Greylord corruption probe.
   The newest charges in the probe of the nation's largest local
court system target Judge John J. McDonnell, 52, and retired Judge
Francis J. Maher Sr., 73.
   They are accused of accepting cash bribes from lawyers to fix
misdemeanor cases, according to U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas.
   Others indicted include a Cook County deputy sheriff, a court
clerk, a police officer and two attorneys, Valukas said at a
morning news conference.
   They were charged with a variety of crimes ranging from
extortion, lying to a grand jury and income tax fraud.
   The new accusations bring to 15 the number of judges charged
since the Greylord investigation began producing indictments in
December 1983, Valukas said. Twelve judges have been convicted and
one was acquitted, he said.
   Valukas said the investigation would continue.
   McDonnell was charged with racketeering, extortion, obstruction
of justice and tax evasion. He faces a maximum sentence of 74 years
in prison and a $255,000 fine if convicted, Valukas said.
   Maher was charged with racketeering and racketeering conspiracy
and faces a maximum penalty of 40 years in prison and a $50,000
fine if convicted, Valukas said.
</TEXT>
