<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1434EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush'sStrength     03-16 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush's Strength,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls: Will Bush's Strength Translate to General Election?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush may have a virtual
lock on the Republican presidential nomination, but his prospects
for winning the general election are far less assured, poll
analysts said Wednesday.
   Indeed, some polls indicate that Sen. Bob Dole, Bush's
all-but-vanquished Republican opponent, could be as strong or
stronger as the GOP nominee in the fall. Dole has argued that he
would be more likely than Bush to win the presidency if nominated.
   Bush ``has certain weaknesses vis-a-vis Dole,'' said Doug
Muzzio, an ABC News poll analyst. While the flaws are not decisive,
``it certainly indicates he's not a prohibitive favorite to beat a
Democrat,'' Muzzio said.
   One potential problem is Bush's failure thus far to win strong
backing of independents. While Bush swept the Republicans in
Illinois on Tuesday, Dole won 46 percent of the independents voting
in the GOP primary, to 42 percent for Bush, ABC's exit poll said.
   Because Republicans are a minority of the nation's electorate,
``if Bush is going to win the general election he's got to start
attracting independent voters,'' said Warren Mitofsky, chief of
polling at CBS News.
   Dole also has shown more potential appeal to Democrats. An NBC
News-Wall Street Journal poll late last month said 24 percent of
Democrats might consider supporting Dole for president, to just 9
percent for Bush.
   Both Bush and Dole have been roughly in dead heats with
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis in hypothetical contests, in
surveys by Louis Harris and Associates on Feb. 18-23, Time magazine
March 10, and Newsweek March 10-11. A USA Today poll March 9 also
put Bush in a tie with Dukakis; a Dole-Dukakis race was not
proposed.
   Bush did better in hypothetical contests against other potential
Democratic nominees, and analysts said he is likely to be perceived
as stronger as his primary victories mount.
   At the same time, Bush at the moment has the advantage of being
better known than the Democrats, and that, too, is likely to
change. And he may lose the bulk of undecided voters, who typically
turn against an incumbent, said David Clemm of the Gordon S. Black
Corp. polling firm.
   Exit polls on Bush's support in Illinois revealed ``little
chinks in his armor,'' said Sheldon Gawiser, a poll analyst for NBC
News. While 55 percent of Republican voters said Bush was tough
enough to be a good president, 24 percent said he was not and 21
percent were not sure, Gawiser noted.
   Also, while 30 percent said Bush would be a very strong leader,
42 percent said somewhat strong, 16 percent said not very strong, 6
percent said not at all strong and 6 percent didn't know. Neither
result showed the confidence that may be expected in such a strong
front-runner's own party, Gawiser said.
   Similarly, among the 23 percent of Republicans who said
leadership was a key issue, ABC News found that Dole and Bush split
the vote. Said Muzzio: ``A prohibitive front-runner should be
showing some leadership, particularly given the fact that he holds
the second-highest office in the land.''
   In another measure, 41 percent of Republican voters said Bush
had not fully disclosed his knowledge of the Iran-Contra affair; 32
percent said he had and 21 percent were not sure, NBC found. The
issue, while not key to most Republicans, could gain significance
in the general election, Gawiser said.
   Humphrey Taylor, president of Louis Harris and Associates,
suggested that one source of Bush's popularity among Republicans,
his closeness to President Reagan, could prove a liability with
many Democratic voters in November.
   ``Right now to guess whether it will be a close election or not
is premature,'' Taylor said. ``It is perfectly possible that Bush
could really firm up his support and be a very strong candidate.
It's equally possible the ground will move under his feet, and
he'll look very vulnerable.''
</TEXT>
