<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CapitolFlags     03-16 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Capitol Flags,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confederate Flag, Other Standards Removed from Oklahoma Capitol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Confederate flag that sparked protests by
a black legislator has been pulled down from the entrance to the
state Capitol.
   The Confederacy's standard had flown over 14 Flags Plaza along
with the flags of Great Britain, France, Mexico, the Choctaw Indian
Nation and other states which once controlled what is now Oklahoma.
But now only one pole bearing the U.S. and Oklahoma flags stands
there.
   Helen Arnold, head of the Office of Public Affairs, said Tuesday
she ordered the flags removed as part of reconstruction work on the
plaza which began last fall. It wasn't clear when the flags came
down as many workers at the Capitol only noticed their absence
Tuesday.
   Arnold said there were no plans to put the flags back until the
Legislature and various commissions decided what to do with the
area to celebrate next year's centennial of the Land Run of 1889.
But she said, ``I think it's probable the flags will not go up
again.''
   The Confederate flag prompted a vigorous protest last year by
Rep. Don Ross, who asked Gov. Henry Bellmon to order it removed and
sought to have the state attorney general rule it illegal but was
denied both times.
   Ms. Arnold would not say whether Ross' protest led to the
removal of the flags.
   Ross said he had not been informed that the flags were not to go
back up, but he said he was ``delighted'' by their removal and did
not plan any further action.
</TEXT>
