<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-16 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Being dead for 2,500 years deserves a lot of
respect. Just ask Ed Rodley.
   Rodley, staff assistant at the Boston Museum of Science,
organized the move Tuesday of an Egyptian mummy from its permanent
residence at the Massachusetts General Hospital to the museum for
its Ramses the Great exhibit next month.
   ``It's probably the most worrisome thing I've moved,'' said
Rodley. ``It's a mummy. It was a person. If you drop a vase, that's
one thing. If you drop a dead Egyptian and his head falls off,
that's another.''
   That head was blackened from embalming fluids. But the man's
white teeth shone in a resolute grimace.
   The 2,500-year-old body of Padihershef had been refurbished only
three years ago. Centuries of dust came off, the teeth were cleaned
and steamed, the bandages rewrapped, his body-length lacework of
blue porcelain beads cleaned and restrung and his head, which had
become dislodged, was glued on straight.
   Rodley said the most precarious part of the hour-long move was
the six-minute, 1,500-yard journey over city streets by moving van.
But it was accomplished without mishap, the stonecutter's body
resting silently in yellow plastic bubble stretcher designed for
moving victims of nuclear accidents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just try to get around Evansville using
the state Department of Highways map, published as inset to the
official 1988 state road map.
   It includes a marker for Evansville College. That became the
University of Evansville 21 years ago.
   The school fared better than the University of Southern Indiana
and Lockyear College, though. Both those were left off the map, as
was the Lloyd Expressway.
   Altogether, local officials found about a dozen errors.
   And the Department of Highways has apologized for including the
outdated map.
   ``It will be revised this year, I guarantee you that,'' said
Karen Cecil, public information director for the department.
</TEXT>
