<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1446EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietDoctrine     03-16 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Doctrine,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Soviet Doctrine a Signal of Economic Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An emerging new Soviet military
doctrine appears to signal Kremlin realization that it cannot
compete in a full-blown arms race and still carry out much needed
economic reforms.
   As the Soviets debate possible force reductions, their diplomats
are trying to persuade the West to scale back through arms control
agreements.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, meeting in Bern with his
Soviet counterpart Dmitri Yazov, says he wants Yazov to explain
whether the new ``reasonable sufficiency'' doctrine will mean fewer
tanks, artillery and missiles facing the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   Yazov and other Soviet generals are billing the new doctrine as
defensive, but Carlucci says their formulation appears to require
continued high levels of offensive capabilities.
   U.S. analysts say Soviet force reductions may not occur until
the United States and Soviet Union reach an agreement on cuts in
conventional forces.
   Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, in a speech in Budapest in
1986, proposed major conventional cuts, and the two sides are
negotiating, but no agreement has been reached.
   NATO leaders last month urged the Kremlin-led Warsaw Pact to cut
its tank and infantry forces to the same level as NATO. Western
analysts say the Soviet bloc has a 2-1 edge.
   Many U.S. analysts, however, doubt the Kremlin intends to reduce
its forces, and Carlucci told reporters Tuesday, ``If anything,
their military continues to grow. They continue to modernize.''
   Harriet Fast Scott, the author of books and articles on the
Soviet armed forces, said of the new doctrine, ``Reasonable
sufficiency is whatever you want it to mean. It satisfies both the
hawks and the doves, at home and abroad.''
   Another U.S. scholar, James M. McConnell of the Center for Naval
Analysis near Washingon, says ``the important part of reasonable
sufficiency is the arms control part.''
   McConnell, in a paper on the doctrine, said Kremlin leaders are
``saying, in effect: To secure growth and greater national security
in the long haul, the U.S.S.R. must renounce some of its current
military ambitions.''
   The Kremlin must be thinking that ``unilateral steps along this
road, however, will only put the Soviet Union at the mercy of the
West. `We must bargain now while the U.S.S.R. is still ahead, and
see to it that NATO disarmament proceeds pari passu (in pace) with
out own,' '' wrote McConnell.
   Part of the Western confusion over the doctrine stems from
differing views offered by Soviet academics.
   Gen.-Col. M.A. Gareyev, deputy chief of the Soviet General
Staff, said last year that ``the Soviet Union is in favor of
restricting military potentials within the bounds of reasonable
sufficiency, so that the armed forces will be able structurally to
conduct only defensive operations.''
   Another Red Army officer, Col. Lev Semeiko, who comments
frequently in the press, called the Soviet formulation ``truly
revolutionary, since for the first time it proposed the mutual
rejection by the two sides of such a type of military action as the
offense, traditionally considered basic.''
   As recently as 1986, McConnell wrote, the Desk Military
Encyclopedia of the Soviet Union dismissed such a defensive posture
as only ``expedient when confronted with a superior military
opponent, or when it was necessary to economize forces ... to
accumulate a preponderance of forces for an offensive.''
   Another Soviet military officer who writes frequently on
doctrine, Col. V. Larionov, said last year that ``defense is the
more economical method of action,'' signaling that economic, rather
than purely propagandistic, motives are driving the doctrine of
``reasonable sufficiency.''
   U.S. officials argue that cutting nuclear weapons saves little
money, and that sharp reductions in conventional armies are needed
to free up money for the civilian economy.
   Carlucci reinforced that point at a dinner with Yazov on Tuesday
night, telling him that nuclear arms control ``doesn't save money.
It costs money. We are spending $198 million'' for on-site
inspections to verify elimination of medium-range nuclear missiles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
