<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PuertoRicoPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0741 03-16 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Statehood Big Issue in Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB last graf to add Jackson's first name bgng ``The
island's...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ballots give little indication
who is running and what is at stake in Sunday's Democratic and
Republican presidential primaries in this U.S. commonwealth.
   Democratic ballots show the familiar, smiling faces of ex-Gov.
Carlos Romero Barcelo and Senate President Miguel Hernandez Agosto.
Candidates themselves are represented by symbols _ a hockey puck
for Paul Simon, an egg for Richard Gephardt.
   Bob Dole is pictured on Republican ballots along with George
Bush and a blank space for voters who want to write in the name of
Pat Robertson. Only Bush's picture matters. Robertson never was a
factor and Dole's delegates quit two weeks ago and tried to call
off the primary.
   ``No one else but George Bush has a chance,'' party chairman
Luis Ferre says.
   Puerto Ricans care who sits in the White House, and understand
that their 14 GOP and 51 Democratic National Convention votes, if
cast for the winner, may result in more high-level appointments and
favorable treatment on food stamps, low-income housing and other
issues important to the island.
   But what really is at stake Sunday is control of the local
Democratic party, currently split between the Popular Democratic
Party and the out-of-power New Progressive Party.
   The primary also is a sort of referendum on the island's
political status, and a test of strength between Gov. Rafael
Hernandez Colon and Romero Barcelo, a two-time ex governor who
would like to return to the Fortaleza, Puerto Rico's White House.
   The NPP wants Puerto Rico to become the 51st U.S. state. The PDP
favors a continuation of the status quo, whereby Puerto Ricans are
U.S. citizens with most every right and obligation except they
cannot vote for president and pay no federal taxes.
   Thus, votes for Romero Barcelo indicate a preference for
statehood, and strengthen his hand against rivals within the NPP,
including San Juan Mayor Baltasar Corrada del Rio, also a
gubernatorial candidate. Votes for Hernandez Agosto endorse some
form of political autonomy, and PDP Gov. Hernandez Colon.
   ``Everyone here knows _ and anyone in the United States that
knows Puerto Rico politics knows _ that what's cooking ... is a
confrontation between the PDP and the NPP, and not a primary of the
Democratic parties,'' Jose Dapena Thompson, the NPP mayor of Ponce,
said.
   The contests have been heavily publicized, with both sides
organizing rallies and long car calvacades, horns tooting and
loudspeakers blaring, in urban housing projects and mountain
villages across this lush island.
   Romero Barcelo and Hernandez Agosto are regular guests on TV and
radio talk shows, and San Juan's four newspapers prominently
feature stories like NPP allegations of faulty voter lists and PDP
fears about double-voting.
   One million Puerto Ricans are expected to vote Sunday. The
Democratic National Committee is sending a commission to monitor
its primary, citing past ``instances of Puerto Rican voters casting
votes in both party's primaries.''
   Bush won the 1980 primary. The Republican Party has stated in
its platform for more than a decade that it supports statehood for
this U.S. territory of 3.5 million located 1,000 miles southeast of
Florida.
   The island's 51 Democratic pledged delegates will be uncommitted
to any presidential candidate. There is a separate ``beauty
contest'' balloting that has drawn several of the Democrats to the
territory in search of, literally, a symbolic win _ the candidates
were assigned symbols by lot to distinguish them on the ballot.
Jesse Jackson, a square, and Sen. Albert Gore Jr., a triangle, are
scheduled to visit Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
