<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghan     03-16 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Name New Ambassador to Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union on Wednesday named a former
Moscow Communist Party chief and ambassador to Denmark to replace
the envoy in Afghanistan, who a Western diplomat said had suffered
a heart attack.
   The government newspaper Izvestia said Nikolai G. Yegorychev had
been chosen ambassador to Kabul to replace Pavel P. Mozhayev, who
had held the job since August 1986.
   The news agency Tass said Yegorychev, who was born in 1920, has
been a party worker since 1950, and from 1962-67 was head of the
Moscow party organization. Since then he served in several
agricultural ministries, as ambassador to Denmark for 14 years and
an official of the Soviet Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
   Yegorychev was replaced as Moscow party chief by Viktor Grishin,
who served until he was ousted by Gorbachev in December 1985.
   Grishin, who some thought wasthe main alternative to Gorbachev
when the Soviet leader was chosen in March 1985, has been accused
of permitting widespread corruption in the Moscow party
organization.
   Izvestia said Mozhayev, 57, had been transferred to other,
unspecified work.
   The Western diplomat said Mozhayev had suffered a heart attack
about a month ago, and that his replacement was not unexpected nor
necessarily politically significant.
</TEXT>
