<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ImportedSand     03-16 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Imported Sand,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Sand Imported for Galveston Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Galveston's beaches will soon change
color _ from brown to white _ with the help of sand imported from
Florida.
   For years, people have complained about Galveston's murky water
and brown, narrow beaches, said Ralph McPheeters, administrator of
a development called Palm Beach at Moody Gardens.
   ``What do most people think of when they think of beaches?'' he
asked Tuesday. ``White sands.''
   ``We can't do anything about the water but we sure can do
something about the sand,'' he said.
   Within two weeks, he said, two ocean barges full of white sand
are expected from Orlando, Fla., he said. The sand, purchased from
Orlando sand mines, was selected because it has the right
consistency and color for building sand castles, he added.
   Mayor Jan Coggeshell said the white beach would be a welcome
addition.
   The development is the latest part of a multimillion-dollar
project on the shores of Offatts Bayou. It will accommodate 3,000
people and include a 1,000-foot waterfront boardwalk and two huge
freshwater lagoons complete with a 12-foot waterfall and white sand
bottom.
</TEXT>
