<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Primaries-RoshHashana     03-16 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primaries-Rosh Hashana,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Authorizes State Primary Date Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo signed legislation
Wednesday to switch the date of the New York state primary to keep
it from falling on the Jewish holiday of Rosh Hashana.
   The primary, not to be confused with New York's April 19
presidential primary, will be held Thursday, Sept. 15. It was
originally scheduled two days earlier.
   Three other states had switched their primaries already to
prevent the conflict. Connecticut and Rhode Island will hold their
primaries Sept. 14, while Massachusetts will join New York with a
primary Sept. 15.
   Six states _ Arizona, Minnesota, New Hampshire, Utah, Vermont
and Wisconsin _ will hold primaries on Rosh Hashana, Sept. 13.
   In New York, Jews usually represent 20 percent or more of the
vote in Democratic primary contests.
   The state primaries determine nominations for governor, state
legislative seats, Congress and local offices.
</TEXT>
