<DOCNO> AP880316-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1526EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     03-16 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Superpower Meeting Next Week Hoped To Help Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Conflicts, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan's chief negotiator said Wednesday that
next week's visit to Washington by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze may help clear the roadblocks in the Afghanistan
peace talks.
   Zain Noorani said the superpowers may ``at least find it easier
to settle among themselves'' the issue of a simultaneous cutoff of
military aid to both warring sides.
   Shevardnadze is scheduled to be in Washington March 20-23 to
continue preparations for a superpower summit.
   The United States and Pakistan, which represents the Afghan
guerrillas in the peace talks, both are demanding that Moscow's aid
to its Kabul allies cease at the same time as the assistance _
mainly from Washington _ to the insurgents fighting the
Soviet-backed government.
   Moscow and Afghanistan have rejected this as interference in
their domestic affairs and said the Soviet aid to Afghanistan
cannot be compared to foreign aid to insurgents.
   Noorani told reporters the aid cutoff was one of Pakistan's two
main concerns that should be resolved before the signing of a peace
settlement.
   Pakistan's other main concern is the establishment of a new
Afghan government to oversee implementation of a settlement and
ensure the safe return of more than 5 million Afghan refugees.
   For the first time, Noorani spelled out in detail Pakistan's
idea for resolving the issue, saying Pakistan agreed with the
Soviet Union and ``everyone else'' that the future government was a
matter to be settled by the Afghans.
   But he said the Afghans should be given a ``helping hand'' in
forming it.
   Noorani said Pakistan envisaged a conference of all Afghan
parties, ``including representatives of the present regime ... in
Geneva or Vienna or anywhere else,'' at an unspecified date.
   He said the conference could best be coordinated by U.N.
Undersecretary General Diego Cordovez, the intermediary between
Afghanistan and Pakistan in the nearly 6-year-old peace talks.
   Noorani said Pakistan was prepared to stay in Geneva ``as long
as it takes to conclude the accords making up the peace
settlement.''
   Earlier, the head of the Afghan delegation, Foreign Minister
Abdul Wakil, gave a similar pledge. He said Afghanistan ``sees no
reason for a suspension of the talks.''
   New sessions were scheduled Thursday, the second day after a
Soviet-set target date for the conclusion of talks.
   The Soviets have offered fresh assurances, however, that they
will still remove an estimated 115,000 troops two months after a
settlement is signed. Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in
1979.
   The two chief delegates resumed trading charges through the
media that the other side was stalling the negotiations. Wakil said
Islamabad is creating ``artificial obstacles'' and warned that
failure to reach a settlement might cause the war to spread to
Pakistan.
   Noorani said Wakil was paying ``mere lip service to peace and
harmony in Afghanistan.''
   In Moscow, U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock met Wednesday with
Shevardnadze and was warned that the Kremlin wants the United
States and Pakistan to stop ``artificially procrastinating'' on an
end to the war, the Tass news agency said.
   The news agency said the discussion between Shevardnadze and
Matlock dealt mostly with the Afghanistan issue.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Richard Gilbert confirmed that Matlock
had a meeting with Shevardnadze that included a discussion on
Afghanistan, but said it is embassy policy not to disclose details
of diplomatic exchanges.
</TEXT>
