<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomelessEvictions     03-16 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Evictions,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Squatters Evicted From Berkeley House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 35 activists for the homeless were
evicted Wednesday from an abandoned house, while supporters ran up
side streets knocking over garbage cans and setting trash fires,
police said.
   One woman was arrested and several protesters scuffled with
police during the vandalism spree, which began at 6 a.m. as police
removed squatters occupying a house owned by the University of
California, officers said.
   The activists took over the house five blocks south of campus
about a week ago, breaking in through boarded windows, said
university spokesman Tom Debley. The university ordered the
eviction after the city fire marshal inspected the three-story
house Tuesday and declared it a fire hazard, he said.
   ``There were a few minor scuffles with police but the eviction
itself was peaceful,'' said Debley.
   The eviction was carried out by university police, with Berkeley
officers standing by. Within hours, bulldozers moved in to demolish
the building, which was to be torn down to make way for student
housing, Debley said.
   The university runs an 80-bed shelter for the homeless on campus
property, Debley said.
   Homeless activist Al Winslow, who lives in another building as a
squatter, said the group would take over another house. He
estimated 2,000 people live on the streets of Berkeley.
   The squatters, a mixture of homeless people and activists,
include some members of the 10th Street Housing Collective, which
staged a two-year occupation of an abandoned house owned by a bank,
said Nikki Rexroat, of Mayor Loni Hancock's office. The group was
evicted from that house two days before taking over the university
building, Rexroat said.
   The woman arrested was being held in the city jail for malicious
mischief, disturbing the police and interfering with a police
officer, police said.
</TEXT>
