<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Nicaragua-Deposit     03-16 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Nicaragua-Deposit,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charge Nicaragua Failed To Make Bank Deposit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is looking into a published
report that the Nicaraguan government failed to deposit $11 million
it owed to the InterAmerican Development Bank after saying it had
done so.
   The bank accepted Nicaragua's word, reinstated the Central
American nation as a borrower in good standing and disbursed $11
million to Nicaragua from old loans that had been withheld,
according to the report in The Washington Times.
   ``The very next day the IDB received the bulk of the 11 million
which Nicaragua had supposedly deposited in IDB accounts six days
before,'' Rep. Jim Bunning told a congressional hearing Wednesday.
   David C. Mulford, assistant secretary of the Treasury for
international affairs, said his department had asked the bank for a
copy of its report on the incident, which allegedly occurred last
Nov. 11. The Times article appeared Jan. 5.
   ``I wasn't aware of that situation, which we refer to as
`round-tripping,' and it is something that is being looked into,''
Mulford told the House Banking subcommittee on international
development institutions.
   ``I would point out, however, that since that incident occurred,
Nicaragua again immediately fell into arrears and therefore is not
eligible to receive further disbursements,'' Mulford said.
   Later he added: ``The incident you mentioned ... does not appear
to be isolated just to Nicaragua. ... We understand that this type
of `round-tripping' is something that's been done by the bank from
time to time, and you can lay it down in a way to inadequate, not
tight enough management.''
   Mulford said the U.S. government is still refusing to make a new
contribution to the bank, which is owned by 44 governments, until
they agree to a new voting system that would enable the United
States and Canada to block loans they consider undesirable.
   Under the present system, borrowing countries control the votes.
The U.S. government also wants changes in management.
   The bank now plans to lend about $2.5 billion a year.
</TEXT>
