<HEAD>Bradley Says He'll Endorse Presidential Candidate Before June 7</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., told state
Democratic Party leaders Wednesday they should not pursue an
uncommitted slate of New Jersey delegates for the June 7
presidential primary.
   Bradley said he will endorse a presidential candidate before the
primary. While party officials said Bradley gave them the
impression he would endorse Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the
senator told reporters he has not yet made a decision.
   Emerging from a closed-door meeting with about 30 party leaders,
Bradley said he hopes the announcement of his choice for the
nomination would end speculation that he wants to be the party's
1988 nominee.
   ``It's like I've said from the beginning,'' Bradley said. ``This
is not the time for me. This should close the door on a Bradley
presidential bid.''
   Bradley previously had urged state party officials not to
endorse any candidate until after the Super Tuesday March 8
balloting around the country. Some Democrats tried to put together
an uncommitted slate in hopes they could throw their support to
Bradley at a brokered convention.
   State Committee Chairman Raymond Durkin said he thought Bradley
was leaning toward Dukakis.
   ``He (Dukakis) has a leg up here and the money that will last
until he gets to New Jersey,'' Durkin said. ``Dukakis has a pretty
good presence in New Jersey.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Cisneros Turns Down Offer To Speak At Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Henry Cisneros has turned down
an offer to speak at the Democratic National Convention but
Hispanic leaders want him to change his mind, an aide to Cisneros
said Wednesday.
   Cisneros rejected the offer by the Congresional Hispanic Caucus.
But Rep. Albert G. Bustamante, D-Texas, the caucus chairman, said
``we're still trying to get him to change his mind. Cisneros would
just be a natural'' to address the convention in Atlanta in July.
   Shirl Thomas, Cisneros' administrative assistant, said the
caucus was not taking ``no'' for an answer. ``He thought about it
for a long time and we talked about it frequently,'' Ms. Thomas
said. ``It is a very flattering thing to be asked to do and he did
not take it lightly at all.''
   She said Cisneros cited a busy schedule and family
considerations in his decision to reject the offer to speak at the
convention.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Orr Predicts Indiana Could Put Bush Over the Top</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indiana's May 3 primary could give Vice
President George Bush the delegates he needs to clinch the
Republican presidential nomination, Gov. Robert D. Orr said
Wednesday.
   Orr commented at a news conference where he was joined by
Indianapolis Mayor William H. Hudnut and other prominent
Republicans who support Bush.
