<HEAD>Doctor Who Faked Suicide Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADFORD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former surgeon who faked a suicide last
year after being charged with trying to strangle his estranged wife
is being held without bond after surrendering to authorities,
officials said Wednesday.
   David Johe, of Charleston, W.Va., surrendered to District
Justice Barbara Boser on Tuesday, authorities said. ``It came as
quite a surprise,'' she said.
   A preliminary hearing is scheduled April 19 for Johe, who
practiced at Bradford Hospital.
   Johe, 35, was arrested in June 1987 on attempted murder,
aggravated assault and trespassing charges after he allegedly
entered the home of his estranged wife, Blair Plott Johe, in
Bradford and tried to strangle her.
   Johe was released on $25,000 bond, then disappeared after
leaving two suicide notes _ one at his home in Ellicottville, N.Y.,
and the other in his van near Niagara Falls.
   The one found in the van last July said: ``Goodbye. I hope the
water is not too cold. I guess I'll never know. David.''
   His body was never found, however, and some authorities said
they never believed he died.
   A Bradford judge in December dismissed a motion that would have
declared Johe dead after Mrs. Johe reported receiving unsigned
Christmas cards and presents for her three children that she
believed were from her husband.
   Last week, Johe's father, Charleston architect Howard Johe,
confirmed that his son was alive and had called him recently.
   ``I believe he just got tired of running and decided to turn
himself in,'' said Bradford police Officer Bradley Mason.
</TEXT>
