<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--AMRAAMTest     03-16 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--AMRAAM Test,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Says New Missile Scores One for Two in Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force said Tuesday one of two AMRAAM
air-to-air missiles fired during a test last month missed its
target.
   The service, in a brief statement, said the test was conducted
Feb. 22 when an F-15 Eagle jet fighter fired two of the missiles
against two target drones flying over the White Sands Missile Range
in New Mexico.
   ``One scored a direct hit against its assigned target drone,''
the Air Force said. ``The other missile did not intercept its
target and analysis is continuing to determine the cause of the
miss.''
   The test brought to 45 the number of successful trials out of 54
missile firings conducted to date.
   The AMRAAM _ Advanced Medium Range Air-to-Air Missile _ is a
so-called ``smart'' missile that has been under development since
1981. It is designed to use its own small radar to home in on enemy
planes without having to be guided by a pilot.
</TEXT>
