<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Panama     03-16 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Upbeat On Spanish Offer Of Asylum For Noriega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House offered encouragement Tuesday
for Spain's offer of asylum for Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio
Noriega and left open the possibility of not seeking his
extradition on drug-trafficking charges.
   President Reagan said ``we do want Noriega out of there and a
return to a civilian democratic government.'' Noriega has been
indicted on drug charges in the United States, and the
administration has imposed economic sanctions against Panama to
force his ouster.
   Spain has said it would be willing to receive Noriega provided
he asks for asylum and the United States does not seek his
extradition.
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said, ``we have looked with favor upon efforts by Spain and other
countries to help solve this problem, but that's as far as we're
willing to go.''
   He acknowledged that U.S. officials have held talks with their
counterparts in Spain, but he refused to talk about the question of
extradition. ``We simply aren't prepared to comment on those
specific points at this time,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``We'll pursue the legal course. There are always a lot of
options that can be taken under those circumstances,'' Fitzwater
said. A White House official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said one option was a political decision not to seek extradition.
   Some officials see the waiving of extradition as a key to
encouraging a quick departure by Noriega.
   Reagan was asked about Noriega during a picture-taking session
in the Oval Office with congressional leaders.
   He said ``I'm not in a position to answer'' whether the United
States would allow Noriega to go to a third country without facing
extradition to the United States.
   However, Reagan said emphatically, ``We do want Noriega out of
there and a return to a civilian democratic government.''
</TEXT>
