<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Patriots, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0725,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress OKs Prime Site for Black Patriots Monument</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 4-5 bgng, ``Rep. James ...'' with Florio
quote and cost estimates and sites for both memorials.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House gave final congressional approval
Tuesday to legislation authorizing prime federal parkland in
Washington for a national monument to the 5,000 black patriots who
served in the American Revolution.
   The voice vote by the House followed Senate approval of the bill
on Feb. 26.
   The House is expected to approve similar, Senate-backed
legislation Wednesday that would authorize a choice Washington site
for a national memorial to Americans who fought in the Korean War.
   Rep. James J. Florio, D-N.J., said the Korean War memorial, to
be built on the mall that extends from the Lincoln Memorial to the
Capitol, will be ``a fitting and long-overdue monument to the
55,000 Amricans who lost their lives in a forgotten war.''
   Private sponsors say they have raised $2.5 million toward a goal
of $10 million for the Korean War memorial. The black patriots
monument, also expected to be built on the mall, will cost an
estimated $4 million.
   Both the black patriots and the Korean War monuments previously
were authorized by Congress, and will be built with private
donations.
   A 1986 law requires House and Senate approval of Interior
Secretary Donald Hodel's finding that the memorials deserve a
preferred Washington location because of their ``pre-eminent
historical and lasting significance to the nation.''
   The capital's prime monument area includes the National Mall,
the grassy parkland between the Capitol and the Lincoln Memorial;
the Ellipse, the circular park behind the White House; Lafayette
Park, West Potomac Park and the Capitol grounds.
</TEXT>
