<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Paul     03-16 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Paul,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colonel Denies Drug Charges; Accuses Media of Defamation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Col. Jean-Claude Paul, who commands
the most feared army unit in Haiti, said Tuesday he is not involved
in drug smuggling and journalists are defaming him.
   A federal grand jury in Miami indicted Paul, 49, last Thursday.
It accused him of allowing his private airstrip near Port-au-Prince
to be used to smuggle drugs from Latin America to the United States.
   ``I deny everything in this affair,'' Paul said by telephone
from his office in the barracks of his 700-man Dessalines
Battalion, located just behind the presidential palace. ``I am a
Haitian in Haiti. This concerns the Americans, not me.''
   When asked about the indictment he denied owning or operating a
landing field.
   ``That's a lie,'' he said, and laughed. ``I have no landing
field. I'm not even an aviator.''
   Paul said he had not been officially informed of an indictment
and declared: ``It is the newspapers that are saying that.''
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Jeffrey Lite said Monday that Ambassador
Brunson McKinley personally told President Leslie Manigat of the
indictment last week.
   Manigat, elected Jan. 17 in voting supervised by the army, has
made no public comment on the matter. A spokeswoman for the
Information Ministry said Monday the government had not received
official notification of the indictment.
   In the telephone interview, Paul said: ``There is a campaign of
denigration against me. Haitians, when they want to denigrate
somebody and can't do it in Haiti, go abroad to do it.''
   Haiti Progres and Haiti en Marche have printed banner headlines
and front-page stories in the last few weeks about Paul's alleged
involvement with drug trafficking. The opposition weekly papers are
based in the United States and printed there.
   Le Matin and Le Nouvelliste, the two Port-au-Prince dailies, and
all 14 radio stations except the Roman Catholic church's Radio
Soleil have refrained from reporting the indictment.
   One station manager said Paul threatened him with violence if he
broadcast the story.
   Western diplomats and a former army officer said it is general
knowledge that Paul operates a landing strip near Thomazeau, a
village northeast of Port-au-Prince near the Dominican border.
   Asked what he would do to defend himself against charges in the
Miami indictment, Paul said, ``Military regulations are very strict
concerning that. It is up to the corps, not me, to assume my
defense.''
   Soldiers from Paul's battalion, who reinforce Port-au-Prince
police, were blamed for most of the attacks on civilians during
anti-government protests last summer. At least 30 people were
killed and 200 injured.
   Dessalines soldiers also were accused of protecting and even
aiding thugs who roamed the streets of the capital on Nov. 29, the
day of an election managed by an independent commission, killing at
least 34 people and causing the election to be canceled.
</TEXT>
