<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--People-Blitzer     03-16 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--People-Blitzer,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blitzer Selected To Head Scholars Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Blitzer, president of the National
Humanities Center in Research Triangle, N.C., has been selected to
direct the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars in
Washington, the center's trustees announced Tuesday.
   He will succeed James H. Billington, who became librarian of
Congress last September.
   The Wilson Center was established by Congress in 1968 as the
nation's official memorial to the 28th president. It provides about
50 research fellowships each year to academics, journalists and
officials from the United States and other governments.
   Blitzer, as an official of the Smithsonian Institution, helped
shape the legislation which founded the center. He headed the
center's fellowship selection committee for almost a decade.
   He is a specialist in the history of political theory and taught
at Yale from 1950 to 1961. While there, he was elected twice to the
position of alderman in New Haven, Conn.
</TEXT>
