<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FreezerMurder     03-16 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freezer Murder,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Wiz Gets 36 Years Again for Murdering Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer expert has been sentenced for
a third time to 36 years in prison for poisoning his wife and
hiding her body in a freezer.
   Circuit Judge Nicholas Geeker refused Tuesday to back down from
his original sentence for Ed Everage although it has twice has been
rejected by the 1st District Court of Appeal in Tallahassee.
   The appeals court initially sent the case back to Geeker because
he had cited some improper justifications for exceeding sentencing
guidelines calling for a 12- to 17-year term. The second time he
made a procedural error.
   Defense lawyer Leo Thomas said Everage will appeal his sentence
again.
   Everage, 44, who has a doctorate in chemical engineering and did
computer-aided research for the Monsanto Co. in Pensacola, was
convicted of second-degree murder for killing his wife, Aileen, 40,
in 1984.
   Everage claimed his wife accidentally swallowed a cold capsule
he had filled with cyanide for his own intended suicide. He said he
hid the body in the unplugged freezer because he didn't think
anyone would believe him.
   Everage had reported his wife was missing, saying she had been
dispondent over their recent move back to Pensacola from Charlotte,
N.C.
   Geeker has cited the cover-up as justification for exceeding the
sentencing guidelines. Other reasons he initially listed, including
a belief that Everage was a danger to his two sons and himself,
were rejected by the higher court.
   Everage has remained in the Escambia County Jail since his 1985
conviction at the request of local authorities. They say he has
saved Escambia taxpayers $250,000 by developing computer programs
for the jail and Sheriff's Department.
</TEXT>
