<DOCNO> AP880316-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0624EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FluorescentSavings     03-16 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fluorescent Savings,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Push For National Standards On Fluorescent Lighting
Ballasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imposing federal efficiency standards on the
electrical devices that start fluorescent lights would save a
massive amount of electricity, the equivalent of the power created
by seven atomic plants, a congressman said Tuesday.
   Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., said a bill that he was introducing
would save 7,000 megawatts by the year 2000, nearly $11 billion in
energy costs. He also said the measure would save more than $21
billion in power plant construction that could be avoided with the
energy savings.
   ``The energy saved by these standards is equivalent to the
energy produced by 15 large coal power plants or seven nuclear
power plants,'' he said. Gejdenson said his estimates came from the
American Council for an Energy Efficient Economy, a non-profit
research group based in Washington.
   Gejdenson and Rep. Phil Sharp, D-Ind., chairman of the Energy
and Commerce subcommittee on energy and power, said the bill would
mandate energy efficiency standards for ballasts by amending the
National Appliance Energy Conservation Act passed last year. That
law sets standards for stoves, refrigerators and other major
appliances.
   Massachusetts, Connecticut, California, Florida and New York
have adopted similar measures on the state level. In Connecticut
alone, state officials estimate that consumers will save between
$223 million and $496 million by the end of the century, according
to Gejdenson.
   Most fluorescent lights use ballasts with an aluminum wire coil
and small iron cores. Under the proposed standards, producers would
have to use either copper wire and steel cores or solid state
circuitry. Both types are already available.
   The alternative ballasts are about twice the price of the
standard aluminum ballast, but they last twice as long.
   Sharp said the alternative ballasts would save 10 percent to 15
percent in electricity over the traditional aluminum ballasts.
There are more than 50 million ballasts sold annually, he said.
   Industry groups supported the legislation, saying it would
simplify their business by having one nationwide standard.
   Michael Stein, president of the Certified Ballast Manufacturers
Association, noted that the five states with their own standards
have differing laws, and that other states are considering their
own requirements.
</TEXT>
