<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FishWars     03-16 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fish Wars,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Head Says 15 Vessels Detected Fishing Illegally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Alaska senator called for a temporary ban
on fishing in part of the Bering Sea as the Coast Guard said
Wednesday that 15 foreign vessels have been detected fishing
illegally in Alaskan waters over the past 18 months.
   Coast Guard Commandant Adm. Paul Yost said the vessels did not
include the seven Japanese trawlers videotaped by American
fishermen in Janaury nor six Polish vessels spotted by a National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration plane in February.
   Yost said it was impossible to catch any of the ships spotted by
Coast Guard planes because they were long gone before a cutter
could arrive on the scene, but information on the sightings was
sent to the North Pacific Fishery Management Council.
   ``You can't cite them from an aircraft. You need ships to do the
actual enforcement,'' Yost told reporters, adding the Coast Guard
has two ships to patrol the 800,000-square mile U.S. fishing zone
off Alaska.
   Yost was among the dozen witnesses that testified before the
Senate Commerce Committee about illegal fishing in American waters
and possible overfishing in an area of the Bering Sea known as the
``doughnut hole.''
   Alaska Republican Sen. Ted Stevens, a committee member, said he
would introduce a resolution calling on the State Deparment to open
talks with the Soviet Union about closing the ``doughnut hole'' to
all fishing until scientists complete studies of the area.
   Other witnesses told the committee:
   _Evdience in a 1982-1983 court case showed the existence of a
``master plan by the Japanese fishing fleet in Alaskan waters to
evade enforcement vessels and manipulate catch records.''
   _The Soviet Union revoked the licenses of the captains of
several of its fishing boats in April 1987 after the U.S. Coast
Guard spotted the vessels fishing in American waters.
   _Overfishing by foreign fleets in the international waters off
the Bering Sea may ultimately affect the fish harvest by domestic
fishermen in the U.S. zone.
   In addition, committee staff released a letter from Kazuo Shima,
councillor of the Japanese Fisheries Agency in Tokyo, that said
reports of illegal fishing in the American zone were ``vastly
exaggerated.''
   The letter to Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., committee chairman,
also called for ``multilateral talks'' about the Bering Sea fishery.
   Ed Wolfe, the State Department's ambassador for oceans and
fisheries, said the Reagan administration was reviewing the legal
implications of such a closure.
   The catch by fishing vessels from Japan, Korea, Poland and China
in the 4,500-square-mile ``doughnut hole'' has risen from about
200,000 metric tons in 1984 over 1 million metric tons in 1987.
</TEXT>
