<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 2155EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Military-Taxes     03-16 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military-Taxes,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Duns Overseas Civilian Employees of U.S. Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service said Wednesday it
is sending tax bills averaging $4,000 to thousands of civilian
employees of the U.S. military who work abroad.
   As many as 40,000 of these civilians work in military
commissaries and recreation facilities. They are known as NAF
employees because they are paid out of non-appropriated funds _
typically from the revenues of those facilities.
   The IRS said the employees may owe as much as $30 million in
back taxes because they wrongly claimed the foreign-income
exclusion, which allows Americans working abroad to exempt up to
$70,000 a year from U.S. taxes. This benefit is not available to
government employees, but many NAF workers insist they are not
government employees because of the source of their paychecks.
   The IRS has rejected that distinction since 1954, but said
taxpayers who disagree may appeal.
   The agency said it already has mailed audit reports and tax
bills to 600 employees in West Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
