<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildArrest     03-16 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Arrest,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family of Arrested 5-Year-Old Gets $166,000 From Warren County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINCHESTER, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warren County officials have agreed to
pay $166,000 to the family of a 5-year-old boy who was arrested at
his home one night, taken to jail, informed of his rights and
interrogated about vandalism at a construction site.
   The settlement came Monday, when a trial was to have begun in
U.S. District Court on the family's lawsuit against several
officials. The county also will pay attorneys' fees. The settlement
will be paid by the county's insurance company over 21 years.
   Jeremy Lance, now 9, began having nightmares, visions of the
devil and fears of dying soon after the incident, said his mother,
Billie Jean Lance Myers. The boy has been seeing a psychiatrist,
she said.
   ``He knows he was done wrong, and this is to set things
straight,'' she said. ``Maybe knowing this is all over, there will
be a sense of relief.''
   The family sued former Warren County Deputy Sheriff Billy
Prater, now a highway patrolman; former Youth Services Officer Dale
Potter, now city judge in McMinnville; the county sheriff; and the
county executive.
   Ms. Myers said Prater came to her house about 10:30 p.m. on June
5, 1984, and took Jeremy in a patrol car to jail, where Prater and
Potter questioned the boy. Ms. Myers said she was kept waiting for
about 30 minutes before she was allowed to see her son.
   ``We think the sum paid to Jeremy ... compensates Jeremy for the
damage done to him and the horrible nightmare he has lived
through,'' said the family's attorney, Michael Galligan.
   The suit was dismissed once by U.S. District Judge Thomas Hull,
but reinstated by the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Cincinnati.
</TEXT>
