<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Talks     03-16 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Talks,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Issue Statement Calling Sandinistas Totalitarian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nicaraguan rebels on Tuesday
accused the Sandinistas of being totalitarian for refusing to allow
opposition political parties to be represented at cease-fire talks
planned for next week.
   Presidential press spokesman Manuel Espinoza said Monday night
that the leftist government vetoed the rebel request last week.
   ``One of the reasons is space,'' Espinoza said. ``There's just
not room for a mountain of people.''
   The first face-to-face talks in Nicaraguan territory between the
government and rebels, known as Contras, are set to begin Monday at
Sapoa, a border post near the Costa Rican border. The meeting had
been set for last week, but the government canceled it after the
Contras at the last minute insisted on a preliminary meeting to
work out the topics for discussion.
   The rebels backed off that demand and both sides agreed to an
open agenda. One issue the Contras want to include in the
discussions is a proposal by Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando
y Bravo that calls for political amnesty and a revision of the
military draft law, among other things. The rebel delegation will
be headed by its top political leader, Adolfo Calero.
   The Sandinistas are insisting that the talks center only on the
mechanics of working out a cease-fire in line with a regional peace
plan the five Central American presidents signed last August.
   The government group will be led by Defense Minister Humberto
Ortega, the brother of President Daniel Ortega.
   A Contra statement Tuesday said Nicaraguan Resistance, as the
rebels are formally called, ``puts special importance and utility
on the participation by the respresentatives of the internal
opposition in the talks, considering its protaganist role in the
Nicaraguan conflict and its participation in a national solution to
the national conflict.''
   The rebel communique, read over the telephone to The Associated
Press, said the rejection of the presence of opposition party
members as well as the dismissal of the cardinal as mediator of the
negotiations confirmed the Sandinistas' ``totalitarian tendencies.''
   President Ortega on March 2 said Obando y Bravo's mediation no
longer would be needed because the talks would be direct. The move
was seen here as retaliation for the cardinal's proposal, which
included political themes that the government said it would not
discuss.
   President Ortega on Tuesday said he did not ``discount that at
the last minute the mercenary forces will come up with pretexts so
the meeting would not take place.''
   An esimtabed 50,000 people have been killed and wounded in the
war that has continued for more than six years.
   President Ortega also proposed Monday the renewal of talks with
the internal political opposition, also a condition of the peace
plan. Those talks broke off last December when the political
parties insisted on discussing a change in the constitution.
   The peace outline was signed in August by the presidents of
Nicaragua, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras and Costa Rica. It
seeks to end wars here, in El Salvador and Guatemala.
   It calls for cease-fires, political amnesties, democratic
reforms and an end to logistic or strategic support for
insurgencies.
</TEXT>
