<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChemicalFire 1stLd-Writethru a0831 03-16 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0831,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Reporting Illnesses After Chemical Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 11 grafs at end with background on fire, chemical
company, other comments.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 10 firefighters have become ill
after battling a weekend fire that destroyed a warehouse containing
thousands of chemicals, authorities said Wednesday.
   Several residents of a nearby mobile home park also reported
rashes and other adverse health effects after Saturday night's fire
in the town of Seabrook, which was the worst accident involving
hazardous materials in state history.
   ``Until we take a look at specifically what compounds were
involved, it's difficult to evaluate the seriousness of the health
implications,'' said Brian Strohm, deputy director of the state
Division of Public Health. He was unaware of anyone being
hospitalized.
   State Fire Marshal Bill Toland said some of the 75 to 80
firefighters called in to extinguish the fire have reported nausea,
tightness in their chests and other symptoms.
   Toland said Exeter's fire chief ordered his firefighters to go
to a hospital for blood tests _ and the chief himself wasn't
feeling well.
   Strohm estimated that 10 to 14 firefighters have fallen ill. He
said the state became aware of the illnesses Tuesday. He said he
was not aware of any new illnesses since then.
   The firedestroyed an 8,000-square-foot warehouse of the Aesar
Division of Johnson Matthey, an international precious metals
company with U.S. headquarters in Malvern, Pa.
   Johnson Matthey officials did not immediately return a telephone
message Wednesday afternoon.
   The warehouse contained about 3,000 chemicals, including heavy
metals and inorganic chemicals, the company said in a statement.
   Officials said the fire caused millions of dollars in damages
and will cost millions more to clean up. Johnson Matthey has hired
Clean Harbors Inc. of Kingston, Mass., to conduct the cleanup.
   Federal and state investigators on Wednesday continued trying to
determine the cause of the fire. Toland said investigators from the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms believe it was
accidental.
   Another fire broke out in Seabrook at the same time Saturday
night, at an abandoned lumber yard. That fire caused an estimated
$500,000 damages. Toland said its cause also remains unknown.
   About 80 residents of a trailer park were evacuated when wind
shifted and blew a plume from the chemical fire in their direction.
   Fearing that radioactive materials could have been stored in the
warehouse, some firefighters were tested for radiation exposure but
the tests were negative. Officials from the stalled Seabrook
nuclear power plant provided testing assistance.
   Strohm said determining possible health risks from the warehouse
fire is difficult because some of the chemicals' properties may
have changed when mixed with each other and with water and when
they burned.
   Barbara Curtis, Johnson Matthey's manager for environmental
affairs, said Clean Harbors workers have finished cleaning the
warehouse parking lot and are building a temporary cover over the
fire site to prevent any precipitation from seeping through.
   State hazardous-waste officials have said they are conducting
laboratory tests of the runoff but have not received results.

</TEXT>
