<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0858,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Clear GOP Leader, But Democratic Race More Scrambled Than
Ever</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new 7th graf with Fahrenkopf remarks bgng ``Republican
National...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic presidential race was as scrambled as the
Republican contest was clear Wednesday after Sen. Paul Simon's
Illinois victory enhanced the chances the Democrats would met this
summer without an obvious nominee.
   On the Republican side, the biggest question appeared to be
merely whether _ or when _ George Bush's rivals, trounced in
primary after primary, would drop out.
   Bush, donning his leader-at-work mantle, lunched with President
Reagan and played dinner host to Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir while savoring his 55 percent majority over Bob Dole's 36
percent and Pat Robertson's 7 percent in Tuesday's Illinois
primary, the one that Dole once said would start his turnaround.
   Dole tended business in the Senate and pondered his future. In
the face of defeat, he met with supporters in Washington.
   ``They're all very friendly, very positive, very upbeat, saying
`Hang in there,''' Dole said.
   Robertson, a big loser Tuesday, went home saying he would have
to scale back his effort. He has spent within $2 million of the $27
million allowed by law for the primaries.
   Republican National Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf signaled it was
time for the GOP race to end. He said Dole and Robertson should
``start thinking past the convention and start thinking about
November'' and the need to win the White House.
   But among the Democrats, the talk was of a brokered convention,
which Simon says is inevitable, and of the steps that some party
leaders said must be taken to prevent so publicly divisive an event
this summer.
   Simon, aglow in the winner's circle at last, said the nomination
in a deadlocked convention could easily come to him because ``I'm
probably the second choice of as many people as anyone else.''
   At the same time, he all but conceded the next big bloc of
delegates _ Michigan's 138, to be awarded in a primary March 26 _
and concentrated on another state he thought he could win,
Wisconsin, on April 5.
   Home-state voters pumped up Simon's political adrenaline with
his 43 percent showing in Tuesday's Illinois primary, against
Jackson's 31 percent, Dukakis' 17 percent and a weak 5 percent for
Albert Gore Jr. and 2 percent for Richard Gephardt. But Simon
conceded he still must prove himself.
   ``I have to win outside the Great Lakes region,'' Simon said,
``and I will.'' He flew directly to Milwaukee and told reporters,
``You are going to be seeing a lot of Paul Simon.''
   But the debate among Democrats was whether they should search
for a formula to avoid a deadlocked convention. Paul Kirk, the
Democratic national chairman, has proposed a meeting after the
primaries at which party leaders and the candidates would close
ranks around the front-runner. He said a brawl at the convention
would damage the Democrats' chances in the election.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, often pictured as the beneficiary of
a brokered convention, seconded Kirk's motion.
   ``I think it would be a mistake to go to Atlanta, have a
divisive convention, have a contention over a canddidate, have
deals cut practically in public,'' Cuomo said.
   Jackson said he would attend a post-primary season summit, but
only to talk about fair play and fair rules at the July convention.
   ``My base of support is broader than any other candidate,''
Jackson said, contending the nomination could go to him outright.
   Simon, acknowledging he won't be the front-runner, said there
was nothing wrong in the image of a convention deal selecting the
nominee.
   ``Brokered conventions produced Franklin Roosevelt, Harry
Truman, John F. Kennedy,'' he said. ``We didn't do too badly for
this country in those brokered conventions.''
   Gephardt struck an underdog posture, saying ``the odds are
against me here in Michigan.''
   ``They say I'm the underdog. I like being the underdog because
the underdog usually does well,'' he said. The Missouri congressman
said he would duplicate a campaign gimmick that drew publicity just
before Iowa's long-ago caucuses: several dozen of his House
colleagues will stump Michigan for him on Friday.
</TEXT>
