<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Chambers Bjt   03-16 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chambers, Bjt,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summations Delivered in Chambers Murder Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor in the ``preppie murder'' trial
suggested in closing statements Wednesday that the defendant
strangled a teen-age woman after a bitter Central Park argument
about his alcohol-induced impotence.
   ``Perhaps he couldn't perform because he had too many tequilas
and beers,'' Assistant District Attorney Linda Fairstein said of
21-year-old Robert Chambers.
   ``Whatever the exact words were, only two human beings know what
triggered the fight. It was an argument that escalated and became
physical,'' she said.
   Earlier, Chambers' attorney ridiculed the prosecution version of
the death of Jennifer Levin and said his client accidentally killed
her during rough sex in the park.
   ``What he was doing was reacting to the pain. He was trying to
stop her,'' lawyer Jack Litman said during his four-hour summation.
``He used force to repel the pain that was being caused to him.''
   Chambers is charged with second-degree murder. A former drug
abuser who is under indictment on burglary charges in another case,
Chambers admits he killed the victim but says it was an accident
after she attacked him sexually and hurt him.
   Fairstein repeated her charge that Chambers brutally beat and
murdered Miss Levin, 18, while in a rage in the early morning of
Aug. 26, 1986.
   ``He squeezed her neck until her young life expired in his
deadly hands. ... She struggled against death. She was in intense
pain,'' Fairstein said. ``She writhed and squirmed to free
herself.''
   Holding a photo of Miss Levin taken in a bar hours before her
death, Fairstein told the jury: ``One can't help but look at that
photograph and pray for time to stand still, for time to grab her
and say, `Don't go with Robert Chambers.'''
   Litman, in his summation, repeatedly told the jury in state
Supreme Court in Manhattan that the evidence supported Chambers'
version of the woman's death.
   Litman reminded jurors that Miss Levin had pursued Chambers in a
bar on the Upper East Side of Manhattan the night of her death
because she wanted to have sex with him. A friend of Miss Levin
testified the slain teen had said her previous encounters with
Chambers had been ``the best sex'' she ever had.
   ``That's why she pursued him, and that's why _ unfortunately _
this wound up the way it has,'' Litman said.
   To convict Chambers in the highly publicized case, ``You must
exclude to a moral certainty every inference except one of guilt _
and you can't do that,'' he said.
   ``There are 20 different explanations that are as consistent
with reality as the one they're (the prosecution) going to try to
give you,'' said Litman.
   Following the summations, the jury is to receive its
instructions in the case Thursday before beginning deliberations.
</TEXT>
