<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra-Prosecutor     03-16 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra-Prosecutor,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Challenge Pending to Walsh's Authority To Bring Iran-Contra
Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Contra Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The very authority by which independent
counsel Lawrence E. Walsh brought indictments Wednesday against
four major participants in the Iran-Contra affair is being
challenged in a constitutional battle before the Supreme Court.
   But a Supreme Court decision striking down the so-called special
prosecutor law would not necessarily invalidate the indictments
returned against former national security adviser John M.
Poindexter, fired White House aide Lt. Col. Oliver L. North,
retired Air Force Maj. Richard V. Secord and his business partner,
Albert Hakim.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III had given Walsh a back-up
appointment in the Justice Department in an attempt to shield the
Iran-Contra inquiry from legal attacks that the special prosecutor
law improperly takes power from the president and confers it upon
the federal judges.
   However, the status of Walsh's investigation is further blurred
because he began his work before the back-up authority was
conferred. The targets of the investigation are expected to argue
that the initial absence of the supporting authorization taints the
entire inquiry.
   The Supreme Court will hear arguments April 26 in the
constitutional challenge to the special prosecutor law. Eight
justices will decide the outcome. Justice Anthony M. Kennedy has
removed himself from consideration of the case without explanation.
A decision is expected by July.
   A panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington
ruled, 2-1, in January that the independent counsel provision of
the Ethics in Government Act of 1978 is unconstitutional.
   The law authorizes a federal court to appoint a special
prosecutor when the attorney general recommends an independent
investigation of a high-ranking administration official accused of
a crime.
   The appeals court ruling came in the investigation of former
Justice Department official Theodore B. Olson on charges he lied to
Congress.
   Alexia Morrison, the independent counsel investigating the Olson
case, appealed to the Supreme Court. Ms. Morrison did not receive
back-up authority from Meese and her investigation would be ended
if the high court declares the special prosecutor law
unconstitutional.
   Two other inquiries by independent counsels also could be
affected by the court's ruling.
   The perjury conviction of former White House aide Michael K.
Deaver could stand or fall on the outcome. The investigation that
led to the illegal lobbying conviction of former White House aide
Lyn Nofziger had back-up authority similar to that conferred in the
Iran-Contra case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
