<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Economy-Glance     03-16 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy-Glance,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments in the economic picture
Wednesday:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Production at U.S. factories, mines and utilities rose 0.2
percent in February, following a 0.3 percent January gain. It was
the fifth consecutive increase and left American industry producing
at a level 5.8 percent higher than a year ago, although the gains
are below advances registered in late 1987.
   The February increase included a 0.2 percent rise in
manufacturing, identical to January's gain. In both months, auto
assembly lines were shut down as automakers worked to reduce a high
backlog of unsold new cars.
   Auto production fell 0.9 percent in February and now stands 8.5
percent below where it was in October.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOUSING STARTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction increased sharply in February, by 8.9
percent, the biggest monthly gain since a 12.7 percent rise in
December 1986.
   It follows declines of 1.9 percent in January and 15.8 percent
in December. All regions posted increases except the West, where
starts fell 9 percent.
   Many economists had predicted a housing rebound, since mortgage
rates have fallen since the first of the year and are again in the
single-digit range.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>EMPLOYMENT PROSPECTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Job prospects for production and service workers are the
brightest they have been in three years but are declining slightly
for technical, professional and office workers, according to a
survey by the Bureau of National Affairs, a private publisher of
business research.
   Twenty-one percent of the 398 corporations and organizations
surveyed said they anticipate expanding production and service work
forces from April through June. A year ago 15 percent expected an
increase in hiring.
   But only 19 percent of the companies surveyed said they plan to
increase technical and professional staffs, down from 21 percent
for 1987's first quarter.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S. STOCK MARKET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices climbed in late trading, putting on a show of
strength in advance of Thursday's monthly report on the nation's
balance of trade.
   The Dow Jones average rose 16.91 to 2,064.32.
   The market had been in a holding pattern since the start of the
week as traders await the figures on the trade balance for January.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JAPAN-MARKETS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Tokyo, the Nikkei Stock Average closed at 25,704.43 points,
up 228.76 points. The dollar closed at 127.49 yen, up 0.24 yen, on
the foreign exchange market.
</TEXT>
