<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Delegates     03-16 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delegates,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegate Numbers Point To Murky Picture For Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The results of the Illinois primary were just
what the delegate counters for Democratic candidates Paul Simon and
Jesse Jackson expected, including Michael Dukakis's third-place
finish without a single delegate.
   Simon spokesman Terry Michael predicted early Tuesday that the
favorite son senator would claim 135 delegates in the
direct-election primary. Simon captured 136 of the 173 delegates at
stake.
   Steve Cobble, delegate counter for Jackson's campaign, expected
his candidate to finish with close to 40 delegates based on his
forecasts for various counties in Illinois. Jackson gained 37
delegates.
   The last-minute advertising blitz launched by Dukakis failed to
translate into delegates for the Massachusetts governor.
   ``Dukakis never made any headway,'' said Cobble. ``He had four
days of banging his head.''
   Michael, who contends that after all the primaries and caucuses
the Democrats will be ``gridlocked,'' said the Illinois results
solidify his theory of no clear winner heading into the convention.
   ``Not only does it further assure the likelihood that no one
claims a first-ballot victory on the morning of June 8, it pokes
big holes in Dukakis attempt to claim inevitability,'' Michael said.
   The last big primaries _ New Jersey and California _ are held
June 7.
   Dukakis still maintains a slight edge in total national
convention delegates, according to The Associated Press survey. The
Massachusetts governor has 464.5 delegates with Jackson second at
460.55 and Gore third with 354.8. Simon stands in fourth place with
171.5 delegates and Gephardt is fourth with 145.
   There are 272.65 uncommitted delegates.
   On the Republican side, Vice President George Bush _ to no one's
surprise _ picked up 69 delegates out of the 82 at stake in
Illinois. Kansas Sen. Bob Dole finished a distant second and gained
13 delegates.
   Bush has a commanding lead in the AP delegate count with 774 of
the 1,139 needed to nominate. Dole is second with 178 delegates and
former television evangelist Pat Robertson is third with 17. There
are 72 uncommitted delegates in the Republican race.
   David Sparks, delegate counter for the Bush campaign, said the
total was slightly higher than the delegates the vice president
expected, and the campaign immediately started looking to the
future.
   ``In Puerto Rico, we have a terrific organization. In
Connecticut, that's yet another home state of George Bush and
Wisconsin has a good organization,'' Sparks said.
</TEXT>
