<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 2313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NuclearLiability     03-16 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Liability,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Defeats Move To Make Nuclear Contractors Share Accident
Liability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Wednesday rejected an attempt to
make private contractors at least partially liable for any future
accidents caused by negligent work at the nation's nuclear weapons
plants.
   The chamber voted 53-41 against a proposal by Sen. Howard
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, after Senate Energy Committee Chairman Bennett
Johnston said that subjecting private contractors to potentially
huge damage claims while they are performing ``the most important
and sensitive function of this government'' would merely drive them
away from the nuclear weapons business.
   ``Rather than attracting the big companies with the reliability
and the expertise, we'd wind up with fly-by-night operators running
these plants,'' said Johnston, D-La. The Senate's vote came on
Johnston's motion to table the Metzenbaum proposal.
   Metzenbaum, citing a long list of problems in the Department of
Energy's nuclear complex, argued that ``Unless we hold the
contractors responsible, there is absolutely no incentive for them
to operate these facilities as safely as possible.''
   Most of the DOE's nuclear facilities, which produce the
components for nuclear warheads, are operated by private companies,
whose contracts total an estimated $100 billion.
   The debate over contractor liability occurred as the Senate
neared passage of a bill to renew the Price-Anderson Act, the
government's 30-year-old system of no-fault insurance covering
nuclear accidents.
   The key feature of the measure is a tenfold increase, from $700
million to $7 billion, in the maximum amount of money that would be
available for quick disbursement to victims of any single accident
involving nuclear reactors.
   In the case of nuclear utilities, each commercial reactor would
be required to continue to carry the maximum amount of private
insurance available _ about $160 million. If any given accident
cost more than that to compensate victims, the additional money _
up to $7 billion _ would be assessed equally among all 110 nuclear
plants now operating.
   Once that pool was exhausted, it would be up to Congress to
provide additional money to victims from taxpayer funds.
   The government, meanwhile, would continue to self-insure its own
nuclear plants, offering the same $7 billion maximum that could be
disbursed quickly in the wake of an accident. The system, for both
commercial and government operations, shortcuts the usual legal
requirements for damage claims by eliminating the necessity for
victims to bring individual suits in court.
   Since the legislation was first passed in 1957, DOE contractors
have been virtually absolved of any responsibility to share the
financial burden in the event of an accident at a government plant.
   The Senate did approve, 94-0, an amendment offered jointly by
Johnston and Metzenbaum which provides for stiff fines, ranging to
$100,000 per day, for violations of safety rules by DOE
contractors. Additional fines, and prison sentences ranging up to
five years, could be imposed on corporate officials who commit
``knowing and willful'' safety violations.
   But Metzenbaum fell short on his bid to have contractors share
the financial burden caused by accidents, even though, in a
last-minute bid for additional support, he watered down the
amendment to stipulate that a company could be held financially
liable for no more money than its profit on its contract at the
plant where an accident occurs.
   Johnston noted that several companies have threatened to
withdraw from bidding on future contracts unless they continued to
be exempt from liability.
   The Energy Department already has shut down one weapons
production reactor, the Hanford facility in Washington state. The
others, at the Savannah River plant in Aiken, S.C., are being run
at partial levels because of safety and environmental problems.
Dupont announced last year it will not seek to renew its contract
to run Savannah River. Westinghouse is considered a front-runner to
take over that plant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
