<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-American 1stLd-Writethru a0759 03-16 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-American, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0759,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Hints Arab-American May Be Expelled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Awad charged, released on
bail, details. Picks up 10th pvs: `He must ...; DELETES 15th graf
pvs, ``Israeli officials ... as redundant.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab-American who advocates non-violent
resistance to Israeli occupation of the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip was arrested Wednesday and may be expelled, officials said.
   Mubarak Awad, 44, was charged with participating in an
anti-Israeli demonstration. Awad said he was questioned for four
hours about taking part in a women's sit-in in Isawiya, an Arab
village incorporated into Jerusalem after Israel captured the area
in 1967.
   He said he was released by city police on $2,000 bail and
ordered to appear before a judge, but no date was set for the
hearing.
   Awad, a Palestinian born in Jerusalem, is an American citizen
with homes in Jerusalem and Wapakoneta, Ohio. He was in Israel on a
three-month tourist visa that expired in November.
   Awad said he told police investigators the protest began
peacefully.
   ``The women were demonstrating with olive branches to protest
the ransacking of five houses by police. I went there, I saw the
broken furniture and smashed windows,'' Awad told The Associated
Press after his release.
   He said he left the village when police ordered him out, then
watched from a hillside as police fired tear gas to break up the
sit-in. He said Arab youths responded by throwing rocks.
   Awad said he was stopped a short time later by traffic police
for failing to signal a right turn.
   He said they ordered him detained when he was unable to present
either his Israeli identity card or his U.S. passport, which were
seized last November when Awad defied an expulsion order.
   During the questioning, ``the police mentioned expulsion. They
said it could be this time for you,'' Awad added.
   A senior government official who spoke on condition of anonymity
said the charges could lead to Awad's deportation.
   ``He must be investigated. The charges against him will be
checked, according to that we will decide,'' said the official.
   ``I'm not saying he is definitely going to be expelled, but this
(investigation) may affect it. Everything depends on what the
investigation shows.''
   On Monday, Israel's Supreme Court ordered the Interior Ministry
to show within 60 days why Awad had not been expelled.
   U.S. officials have repeatedly urged Israeli officials to allow
Awad to remain.
   ``We've been in touch with him and a consular officer visited
him at the police station,'' said David Good, a spokesman for the
U.S. Consulate. ``We are following the case closely.''
   Awad came under fire after the publication in Hebrew of his book
titled ``Non-Violent Resistance: A Strategy For the Occupied
Territories.''
   The book urged the 1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip to refuse to pay taxes, lay down in front of bulldozers
to prevent land confiscation and boycott Israeli products.
   Although Awad has played only a minor role in the current
uprising, some of his passive resistance ideas have been adopted,
such as boycotting jobs in Israel and refusing to pay taxes.
</TEXT>
