<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DriverSlain     03-16 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Driver Slain,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auto Speed King Mickey Thompson and Wife Shot to Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN PETERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRADBURY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen on bicycles ambushed and killed
auto speed king Mickey Thompson and his wife in their driveway
Wednesday, days after he told a friend he had received several
death threats and feared for his life.
   The 59-year-old racing promoter and his wife, Trudy, 41, were
found dead at dawn, said sheriff's Deputy Doug Gatlin. Two male
assailants fled on bicycles, investigators said.
   ``It was a double homicide, an assassination,'' said Deputy
Richard Dinsmoor.
   Thompson became famous as the ``Speed King'' in the 1950s when
he set the first of his nearly 500 auto speed and endurance
records. Longtime friend Carroll Shelby described him as ``one of
the greatest hot-rodders we've ever had'' and ``the dominant figure
in off-road racing.''
   As recently as Sunday, Thompson expressed fears for his life
after receiving numerous death threats, friends and associates said.
   ``He was a little concerned,'' family friend Ernie Alvarado
said. He said he talked to Thompson early Sunday and Thompson
mentioned the death threats.
   ``I don't know why Trudy had to be involved,'' Alvarado said.
``Everybody loved her.''
   Neighbors heard six or eight shots and deputies found the bodies
about 6 a.m. in the driveway of the couple's gated, Spanish-style
estate in an area of $1 million-plus homes 20 miles from downtown
Los Angeles, investigators said.
   ``We don't know a motive,'' said Deputy Dan Cox, who wouldn't
divulge the type of weapon used. Several bullets struck each of the
Thompsons in the upper torso, he said.
   Mike Difilippo, a building contractor who lives across the
street, said he was awakened by shots.
   ``I heard yelling, `Don't shoot.' That was Trudy,'' said
Difilippo. He said Thompson had voiced concern for his life after
winning a series of multimillion-dollar lawsuits against another
racing promoter.
   Promoter and one-time partner Mike Goodwin lost a series of
lawsuits to Thompson, and Goodwin's Stadium Motorsports Corp.
assets were ordered liquidated last year by a judge to settle the
matter.
   At one point, Thompson hired a guard, Difilippo said. ``He told
me around Christmas they had threatened to kill him,'' Difilippo
said.
   The Thompsons apparently were ambushed as they were getting into
their van, Cox said. The van, its passenger window shattered,
rolled down the sloping driveway into a block wall.
   Doug Stokes, spokesman for Thompson Entertainment Group in
Anaheim, said the Thompsons were apparently leaving the house for
work when the shooting occurred. He didn't know of any threats
against Thompson.
   Thompson in 1960 became the first to travel over 400 mph on land
when he drove a four-engine streamlined car 406.6 mph at the
Bonneville Salt Flats in Utah.
   He later turned to drag racing and Indianapolis car racing, and
was a top competitor in road racing and off-road championships in
the United States and Mexico.
   Thompson's other sports activities included stunt flying and
management of prizefighters.
   Racing put him in the hospital 27 times, including a seven-month
stay when he was paralyzed from the waist down after a boat racing
accident. It was two years before he walked again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
