<DOCNO> AP880316-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0007EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma-Students     03-16 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Students,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Killed In Fighting with Villagers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Tuesday occupied the campus of a
technology institute and detained a number of students suspected of
being involved in battles with villagers that left one student dead.
   Authorities barred reporters from the Rangoon Institute of
Technology in West Gyogone, seven miles north of downtown Rangoon,
following the weekend fighting.
   Burma Broadcasting Service, the government radio station, said
Tuesday the violence began at a tea shop Saturday night when
students and villagers quarreled over the playing of a cassette
tape. Five villagers were arrested, it said.
   On Sunday, larger groups of both students and villagers resumed
the fighting and some 200 students set fire to seven buildings,
according to the broadcast.
   It said police quelled the rioting with volleys of tear gas but
13 students were injured and one, Maung Phone Maw, was fatally
wounded. The report did not say how he was killed and added the
government was investigating and would take ``necessary action''
against those involved.
   A resident of West Gyogone told The Associated Press that police
and army units were seen leaving the campus Tuesday night escorting
three police vans carrying an unknown number of students.
   The witness, who spoke with the condition he not be identified,
said there was no violence as police occupied the campus and picked
up the suspects.
</TEXT>
