<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Republicans 1stLd-Writethru a0871 03-16 1011</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Republicans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0871,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Pressured to Quit, Says ``I Decide''</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS graf 2, new 3rd graf to UPDATE; INSERTS 5 grafs after
15th graf pvs, Sen. Alfonse, with more comment from senators</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole came under increasing pressure
on Wednesday to give up his faltering presidential campaign as
Republican Party chairman Frank Fahrenkopf said it was time to
``start thinking about November.''
   A dozen of Dole's Senate supporters openly debated the merits of
his continuing a candidacy that seemed doomed to failure _ although
none of them advised Dole to get out of the race. In any event,
Dole said, ``They're not going to decide. I decide what I'm going
to do here.''
   Dole's campaign manager, William Brock, said: ``We're in
business.'' Asked for how long, he said, ``Until Bob wants to
change it.''
   With Vice President George Bush marching with seeming
inevitability toward the nomination, Dole's aides said the senator
had decided to stay in the race until the Wisconsin primary on
April 5. They said no decision has been made for beyond that date.
   Bush's aides gave the Kansas senator wide berth. ``We're
prepared to accept whatever decision Bob Dole makes,'' said Rich
Bond, the vice president's deputy campaign manager. He said Bush
was ready to match Dole dollar for dollar in any primary state
where he chooses to compete, and another spokesman said the vice
president has a $4.5 million campaign treasury at his disposal.
   The other aide, Pete Teeley, said he believes Bush will have
enough delegates to claim the nomination by the end of April or
early May in any event.
   Fahrenkopf's comments seemed a broad hint to Dole that the time
is approaching to abandon the race. He stressed his campaign
neutrality, but added that he has a responsibility as chairman ``to
ask them (the candidates chasing Bush) for some self-reflection.''
   Fahrenkopf said Dole and former television evangelist Pat
Robertson should ``start thinking past the convention and start
thinking about November'' and the general election.
   He said either of the two would have to win roughly 75 percent
of the remaining delegates at stake to have a chance at the
nomination, and he called on them to assess ``realistically'' why
they are still in the race.
   Bush has won 774 delegates in The Associated Press count,
compared with 178 for Dole and 17 for Robertson. It takes 1,139 to
win the Republican nomination at the party convention this summer.
   None of the three active candidates was campaigning during the
day. Dole was in the Senate, Bush attended to vice presidential
duties and Robertson was at home in Virginia.
   But there was an extraordinary public airing of Dole's prospects
by his supporters in the wake of Bush's Illinois primary landslide
on Tuesday.
   Sen. Nancy Landon Kassebaum, Dole's Senate colleague from
Kansas, said, ``I guess the general feeling among some of us is he
should go on through Wisconsin.''
   She added, ``If there's a way to stay in all the way and speak
to the issues ... it benefits the party and benefits him, and it
keeps the campaign on a positive level,'' she said. ``But I'm not
sure it can be done that way. Maybe it's not worth the strain of
continuing on.''
   Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., ``If he wants to stay in for a few
more weeks he can do it. He's staying in because he's invested
three years of his life.''
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato of New York, who told CBS News on Tuesday
that it looked ``pretty clear and convincing'' that Bush would be
the nominee, said Dole's chances are ``very very difficult, if not
impossible. But that's all right. It's not over till it's over.''
   Sen. Paul Trible, R-Va., said the meeting was of Dole's ``best
friends interested in his best interest and that of the party,''
adding: ``This is a decision for Bob Dole to make, and we will
support that decision.''
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said ``no conclusions were
drawn'' in the meeting, but ``I think there was a general
consensus, more than a general consensus, that now the campaign
ought to go forward.''
   ``I believe that he should stay in,'' Grassley said, adding that
at the meeting, there was ``absolutely not'' anyone urging Dole to
get out.
   Grassley said Wednesday's Iran-Contra indictments were not
discussed in the meeting, but said: ``There's going to be some
Reagan baggage that George Bush has to contend with.''
   That view was echoed by Sen. Dave Durenberger, R-Minn., who was
not at the meeting but advised Dole to stay in the race. ``George
can't duck the (Iran-Contra) issue,'' he said.
   Dole said his colleagues were `'very friendly, very positive,
very upbeat, saying, `hang in there.''' Bush's aides were careful
not to gloat, but said it was as good as over.
   Teeley said Dole's ``got to do what's best for him.'' But he
added that Connecticut, which holds the next GOP primary on March
29, ``is going to be a very strong state for us, there's no
question about it.''
   Bush enjoys the support of several Republican elected officials
in the state. Sen. Lowell Weicker, nominally neutral in the
presidential race, is writing a newspaper article praising the vice
president and is considering a formal endorsement at a Bush
campaign function being planned for a few days before the primary,
sources said.
   Beyond that, Teeley said Bush is in a strong position in
primaries in Wisconsin, New York and Pennsylvania. He said he
believes the vice president will clinch the delegates needed for
the nomination either on April 26 when Pennsylvania votes or a week
later, with primaries in Ohio and Indiana.
   Robertson, who met with Republican Party chairman Fahrenkopf on
Tuesday, says he won't compete in either Connecitcut or Wisconsin,
but will concentrate his efforts in caucus states. Robertson says
he is now concentrating on expanding his political base for the
1992 campaign.
   Fahrenkopf said Robertson indicated in the meeting that he
intends to remain a candidate until the nominating convention.
</TEXT>
