<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Dukakis-HealthCare     03-16 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Health Care,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Health Care Bill Shaped By Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis' highly touted universal
health care plan has been streamlined since it was raised a year
ago, its deadlines extended, its bureaucracy reduced and its
funding expanded by millions of dollars.
   But the proposal's basic premise, making Massachusetts the first
state to guarantee health insurance protection for all its
residents, remains intact.
   The plan, which Dukakis has held up as an example to the nation
in his Democratic presidential campaign, awaits final action by a
legislative conference committee.
   Senate Ways and Means Chairman Patricia McGovern, the chief
architect of the bill, said Wednesday the House and Senate
proposals are so similar that ``there are no major sticking
points'' that would prevent passage.
   Universal health care in Massachusetts first came to the
attention of the Legislature in a position paper issued by McGovern
in February 1987.
   ``In my wildest dreams, I didn't think a year later we'd be
almost on the verge of accomplishing it,'' she said. ``I thought it
would take much, much longer.''
   Dukakis wasn't an initial supporter of universal health care,
considering it too costly. In his original proposal in August, the
governor did not suggest any state spending for the plan,
maintaining that employers should shoulder the cost.
   McGovern is credited with getting the governor to support the
present plan, which would phase in health care until all residents
are insured by 1992.
   The present plan retains Dukakis' proposed unemployment
surcharge tax on employers who don't provide coverage by 1992. But
it also contains a state commitment of $500 million or more over
the next four years to make sure everyone is covered.
   The governor has taken the issue on the campaign trail, talking
as much about the 600,000 uninsured in Massachusetts as the 40
million uninsured nationally.
   Only Hawaii has anything comparable to what's been proposed in
Massachusetts. The state has required employers to provide workers
with insurance coverage since the early 1970s.
   The federal Employee Retirement Income Security Act was passed
after Hawaii's law took effect to prevent other states from
imposing similar mandates on employers, and questions remain about
how Massachusetts' proposal will fare under federal review.
   Massachusetts' small businesses lobbied hard and successfully
against Dukakis' bill last year.
   This year, although some small business groups still oppose it,
the measure has been reshaped to reflect their concerns.
   State-brokered pooled insurance for small employers was added.
So were tax breaks and a ``hardship trust fund'' in which the state
agrees to help employers pay insurance costs that exceed 5 percent
of their revenues.
   The House also passed an amendment exempting employers of nine
or fewer workers from the 1992 deadline for providing employee
coverage. The Senate version has no such exemption, and the issue
is expected to be a focal point of the conferee negotiations.
   Other major changes since Dukakis first proposed the bill
include allowing more time to put the system into effect and
scrapping a plan to create a ``super agency'' to oversee the
universal health care system.
</TEXT>
