<1ST_LINE>u w AM-North     03-16 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tearful North Vows To Fight Allegations: `I Will Never Give Up'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Contra Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Col. Oliver North, his face drawn and
gray, his voice breaking, said Wednesday he was caught in the
cross-fire of a bitter dispute between Congress and the president
and that ``it is a shame the new battleground for such a fight will
be in a courtroom.''
   The Marine officer talked to reporters a few hours after a
federal grand jury indicted him and three others on conspiracy
charges.
   ``I did not commit any crime. I intend to fight allegations of
wrongdoing for as long as necessary,'' said North. He said the
fight will entail enormous costs, personal and financial, but
``nevertheless, I can assure you, I will never give up, we will
win.''
   North's eyes clouded and his voice quavered as he thanked the
American people ``who have shown so much love and concern these
past 16 months by their millions of telegrams and letters and
prayers and support.''
   Beside him was his lawyer, Brendan Sullivan, who also
represented North at last summer's hearings before joint committees
of the Senate and House. Sullivan, whose spirited defense of his
client was one of the highlights of the hearings, said that seeking
Wednesday's indictment ``was one of the worst prosecutorial
decisions in the history of our country.
   ``It is a decision of an unaccountable prosecutor who came to
Washington determined to allege that some crime, any crime had been
committed,'' Sullivan said.
   Sullivan added that Lawrence E. Walsh, the independent counsel
``presents an indictment after 15 months (of investigation) based
on mistaken facts, novel and sometimes ridiculous legal theories.
   ``The return of an indictment under these circumstances
presented here is an abuse of the criminal process,'' Sullivan
said. ``Everyone must seriously wonder about a decision to indict a
man like Oliver North, a highly decorated Marine Corps officer,
based on his tireless effort in the interests of his country.''
   For his part, North said it was a sad irony that the decision to
indict should occur on the fourth anniversary of the abduction in
Lebanon of William Buckley and the third anniversary of the
kidnapping of Terry Anderson, The Associated Press' Middle East
correspondent.
   ``The indictment is also sad for our country,'' North said. He
said that as a Marine officer he had always done his best.
   ``Unfortunately, I have now been caught in a bitter dispute
between the Congress and the president over the control of foreign
policy, the power of the president to deter communism in Central
America and the president's duty to protect our citizens against
terrorist acts abroad,'' North said.
   ``It is a shame that the new battleground for such a fight will
be a courtroom,'' North said.
   After he read his statement, North turned to leave. A reporter
asked ``who authorized you to conduct U.S. foreign policy?''
   ``I'm not going to take any questions,'' said North.
</TEXT>
