<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Twin-BrainDamage     03-16 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Twin-Brain Damage,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Separated Siamese Twin Chokes On Formula, May Have Suffered Brain
Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separated Siamese twin Patrick Binder may have
suffered new brain damage after choking during a routine feeding,
Johns Hopkins Hospital said Tuesday.
   Patrick had been left unattended briefly late Sunday afternoon
when he choked on formula fed to him through a nasal tube,
according to Lisa Hillman, spokeswoman for the Hopkins Children's
Center. Since then, he has had some seizures, she said.
   A nurse making a routine check on the room Patrick shares with
his brother Benjamin, found he had stopped breathing, called for
emergency help and began mouth-to-mouth resuscitation.
   Patrick was rushed to the pediatric intensive care unit, where a
ventilator was attached to mechanically aid his breathing.
   The child awakened an hour later, an indication that his
breathing had not stopped for very long, Ms. Hillman said.
   Doctors believe ``there may be some damage,'' Ms. Hillman said,
because ``he has had, since the incident, some mild seizures.'' She
described them as ``jerking movements of the face'' and said they
had been stopped by medication.
   The twins had been doing well since surgery last month to
implant titanium mesh plates in the opening at the back of their
heads, created by a complex, marathon operation last September to
separate their joined skulls.
   Doctors said both boys sustained slight brain damage during the
separation procedure, and the long-term effects remain uncertain.
   Benjamin remained in good condition Tuesday, while Patrick was
listed in stable condition and showing slight improvement in the
intensive care unit.
   Doctors had hoped the 13-month-old twins would be going home to
Ulm, West Germany, by the end of March, but Ms. Hillman said
Patrick's setback could cause a delay.
</TEXT>
