<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 2310EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DestroyerSlaying     03-16 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Destroyer Slaying,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Disbursement Officer Was Shot, Autopsy Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators Wednesday were
trying to determine when and where the USS John Hancock's
disbursement officer was strangled, shot and robbed of the ship's
payroll, a Navy spokesman said.
   The body of Lt. Ratish Prasad, 24, was found Tuesday inside a
locker on the destroyer. About $94,000 was missing from his office
safe, the Navy said, revising the amount downward from Tuesday's
estimate of $120,000.
   ``He was shot at close range, and also strangled,'' said Chief
Petty Officer Art Riccio.
   There was no indication Prasad also was bludgeoned, as first
reports indicated, Riccio said. ``With all the blood and
everything, that's the way it looked,'' Riccio said. ``The bullet
apparently passed right through the head.''
   Final autopsy reports have not been released, Riccio said.
   The time of death and where Prasad was shot had not been
determined, Navy officials said. No bullets or casings were found,
and the caliber of the weapon was not known, Riccio said.
   Riccio said the twice-monthly payroll, due for disbursement
Tuesday, was $70,000, and about $20,000 in cash usually is kept in
the safe.
   No information was available on suspects from Navy Investigative
Service officers working with Duval-Jacksonville sheriff's
deputies, Riccio said.
   People trying to board the destroyer or other Navy ships must
pass checkpoints at the base entrance, the pier area and the ship
itself, Riccio said.
   Only family members and friends of the crew who have been
previously cleared are allowed aboard the ship in port, he said.
Even Naval personnel who do not have business on the ships cannot
board, he said.
   Prasad, who was single and came from Park Forest, Ill., had
enlisted three years ago.
   Lt. Cmdr. Tim Taylor said Prasad normally would have been met at
his office about 8 a.m. by an armed master at arms, a member of the
ship's security force. Prasad himself normally would not have been
armed, Taylor said.
   Prasad and the master at arms then would have gone to the
officer's quarters, chiefs' quarters, then crew messes to pay crew
members, Taylor said.
   When the disbursing office door was discovered open, a search
was mounted for Prasad, who had gotten off duty at midnight then
spent the night on board, Taylor said.
   Prasad's body was found in an isolated storage area one deck
below his office, Taylor said.
</TEXT>
