<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-PaylessDays     03-16 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Payless Days,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Noriega Protester Shut Down Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protests that began months ago with
allegations of criminal conduct by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega have
turned into public rage over unpaid salaries in an economy without
money.
   The largest demonstrations in nine months of turmoil,
accompanied by strikes, took place Wednesday. They started at about
10 a.m. and riot squads managed to disperse the crowds by
mid-afternoon. By early evening the streets were deserted except
for police patrols.
   People were reported injured, but there were no confirmed
figures. There were reports of widespread looting and several
stores were set ablaze.
   Noriega, who rules Panama as chief of the 15,000-member Defense
Forces _ the military and police _ has been indicted in Florida on
narcotics charges and President Reagan said Tuesday he wants the
general ``out of there.''
   Economic pressure applied by the United States includes a freeze
on Panamanian government accounts in U.S. banks and withholding
Panama Canal revenues. This has dried up the supply of U.S.
dollars, Panama's national currncy.
   Wednesday's protests began soon after young officers led by
Police Chief Leonidas Macias mounted an unsuccessful coup.
   Shops and other businesses closed early. Reporters saw
protesters at a barricade stop and open a refrigerated truck and
empty it of frozen chickens.
   Electric power went off throughout the country at about midday,
soon after workers of the National Power Company walked out to
protest not being paid.
   Government workers were sent home after waiting all morning for
biweekly paychecks that did not arrive.
   Public transportation stopped because employees were not paid.
   In lower-income neighborhoods, burning barricades appeared at
street corners. Many protesters identified themselves as
``civilistas'' _ members of the National Civic Crusade, a coaliton
of about 200 business, professional, labor, student and opposition
groups.
   The Crusade was formed last June, after the first reports that
Noriega was involved in drug dealing, corruption and allegedly even
political murder. Its stated purpose was to force him out.
   Protesters at many street corners Wednesday stoned the few buses
that were running and any cars suspected of being from the
government. Those carrying journalists were allowed to pass.
   ``It is time for the gringos to come in,'' a demonstrator
shouted at a carload of reporters, using the slang for North
Americans.
   Carlos Gonzalez de la Lastra, a Crusade leader, said: ``The
fight will intensify tomorrow.''
   One large group of protesters was made up of health workers from
Social Security hospitals. They yelled that they have not been paid
and many fought riot police with rocks and sticks.
   Soldiers went to Social Security institutions Wednesday morning
and disarmed hospital security guards, also members of the Defense
Forces.
   ``They probably do not want the people to take the guards' guns
away,'' a hospital employee said.
   A nurse said of Noriega: ``He must go. Look what he is doing to
this country.''
</TEXT>
