<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-16 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Storm Dumps Heavy Snow in Rockies, Record Lows in Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The second late-winter storm in a week dumped up to a foot of
snow in mountain areas of Utah, Wyoming and Colorado on Wednesday
and moved into the Plains states, while record cold gripped the
Southeast.
   A winter storm warning was posted in northwestern Kansas, and
storm watches went up in parts of Texas, Missouri and Oklahoma. Up
to 8 inches of snow were forecast for parts of Kansas and Missouri.
   The wintry weather comes on the heels of a storm that brought
heavy snow to the area last weekend.
   Parts of Utah and western Colorado got heavy snow Wednesday
morning, with more than a foot at Fillmore and Clear Creek Canyon,
in central Utah, 10 inches at Lander, Wyo., about 4 inches at Red
Mountain Pass, Colo., and Colorado Springs, Colo., and 2 inches at
Goodland, Kans.
   Blowing snow cut visibility at Laramie, Wyo., to an eighth of a
mile.
   Heavier snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 5 inches at Roosevelt, Utah, 4 inches at Goodland, Kans.,
and Milford, Utah, and 2 inches at Russell, Kans.
   Record lows were set in 18 cities in the Southeast on Wednesday
morning, including Apalachicola, Fla., 31; Calico Rock, Ark., 16;
Charleston, S.C., 28; El Dorado, Ark., 26; Greer, S.C., 25;
Hollywood, Fla., 44; Hot Springs, Ark., 25; Key West, Fla., 55;
Meridian, Miss., 23; Miami, 44; Miami Beach, 45; Mobile, Ala., 30;
New Orleans, 38; Tallahassee, Fla., 24, and West Palm Beach, Fla.,
43.
   A frost and freeze warning was in effect overnight for South
Carolina.
   Rain dampened south-central and southeast Texas, and scattered
light rain was reported in the Texas Panhandle and southwest
Oklahoma.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 0.38 inch at Corpus Christi, Texas; 0.31 inch at Alice,
Texas; 0.30 inch at Palacios, Texas, and 0.26 inch at Corpus
Christi, Texas.
   Snowshowers occurred from Vermont across much of New York,
western Pennsylvania and eastern Ohio to the mountains of West
Virginia.
   Temperatures at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 16 degrees at Limon,
Colo., to 72 degrees at Wink, Texas, and Palm Springs, Calif. The
nation's morning low was 12 degrees below zero at West Yellowstone,
Mont.
   Temperatures dropped to near freezing Wednesday morning in the
Pacific Northwest, where Yakima, Wash., tied a record low of 23
degrees.
   Thursday's forecast called for snow from southern Michigan
across the middle Mississippi Valley, Kansas and much of Oklahoma
to parts of northwest Texas; rain mixed with snow from the lower
Ohio Valley across southeast Missouri and northwest Arkansas to
eastern Oklahoma; rain across portions of the lower Mississippi
Valley and much of Texas, and thunderstorms scattered over southern
and eastern Texas.
   High temperatures should reach the upper 20s or 30s from
northern New England to New York and from Michigan across the upper
half of the Mississippi Valley and all of the Great Plains to the
central Rockies, the 60s or 70s from the south Atlantic Coast
across the Gulf Coast to southern Texas and from the desert
Southwest to the pacific Northwest, and the 40s or 50s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
