<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra 7thLd-Writethru 1stadd 03-16 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 7th Ld-Writethru, 1st add,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: NSC staff.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Poindexter was named in two counts of obstructing a
congressional inquiry and two other counts of false statements.
   Poindexter was accused of lying to the House and Senate
intelligence committees on Nov. 21, 1986, by saying he did not
learn about the November 1985 shipment of Hawk missiles to Iran
until three months later.
   The indictment also charges that Poindexter, a computer buff,
deleted from the NSC computer system all stored messages that he
had sent or received.
   Poindexter and North are also charged with lying to House
committees in the summer of 1986 by falsely stating that North was
not helping raise money for the Contras or providing military
advice to the rebels.
   The obstruction and false statement charges against North and
Poindexter each carry five-year sentences and a $250,000 fine.
   After a full day of deliberations, Walsh was called to the grand
jury room at 3:54 p.m. and told the panel was ready to return an
indictment. The 21 members of the grand jury then filed upstairs to
a courtroom where the 101-page indictment was formally returned to
U.S. Magistrate Jean Dwyer.
   The case was assigned to U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell, 77,
who was appointed by President Johnson and presided over one of the
Watergate trials.
   Last week, Poindexter's predecessor as national security
adviser, Robert C. McFarlane, pleaded guilty to four misdemeanor
charges that he withheld information from Congress in 1985 and in
1986 by denying that members of his staff, particularly North, were
helping raise private money to arm the Contras during the Contra
aid ban.
   The indictment also charged North with obstructing the
independent counsel's investigation of the security system at his
Great Falls, Va., home by creating false documents to conceal the
fact that Secord had paid $16,000 for it installation. He was
charged with illegally accepting the security system as a gratuity.
   The indictment also charged that North pocketed $4,500 of
$90,000 in travelers checks that he received from Contra leader
Adolfo Calero to cover expenses related to the rebel cause and the
efforts to obtain release U.S. hostages in Lebanon.
   In a statement, Hakim's lawyer, N. Richard Janis, said: ``We
believe strongly that Mr. Hakim has committed no crimes and that
ths indictment is unfair and unwarranted.''
   Sen. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, who chaired the Senate
Iran-Contra committee, said, he believed ``justice will ultimately
be done.''
   ``While I personally remain convinced that they exhibited
insufficient sensitivity to the rule of law, and to the fact that
under our system of government the Congress makes the laws, we must
await the verdict of a jury of their peers as to whether this
insensitivity was criminal in nature,'' Inouye said.
   But Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, another member of the Senate panel
who was one of the administration's strongest supporters during the
congressional hearings, said the investigation was ``a colossal
embarrassment to our whole government.''
   ``It's going to be a very tricky trial to try to prove these
charges in an open forum,'' Hatch told reporters.
   ``I'm not white-washing this. There were serious mistakes made
here,'' Hatch said.
   Last spring, two conservative fund-raisers, Carl R. ``Spitz''
Channell and Richard Miller, pleaded guilty to felony charges that
they conspired with North to illegally use a tax-exempt foundation
to raise $3.2 million for the Contras.
   The indictment also charged North with participating in that
conspiracy.
</TEXT>
