<1ST_LINE>u i UN-SharpevilleSix 3rdLead   03-16 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>UN-Sharpeville Six, 3rd Lead,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Ask South Africa to Spare `Sharpeville Six</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council unanimously urged
South Africa on Wednesday to commute the sentences of the
``Sharpeville Six,'' sentenced to be executed for a 1984 death by
mob violence.
   Its resolution asked for a stay of the executions, scheduled for
Friday, and said South Africa's ``practice'' of executing opponents
of apartheid has harmed the search for peace.
   On Tuesday, President Reagan issued a personal appeal for the
lives of the six.
   They were convicted in the 1984 mob killing of a black township
councilman stoned and burned to death in the Sharpeville township
south of Johannesburg. An appeals court judge ruled that they did
not kill him personally but had common purpose with the mob.
   Dragoslav Pejic of Yugoslavia, Security Council president for
March, said death sentences for the ``African patriots'' had caused
``undivided international condemnation and uproar.'' He also said
thousands of innocent black South Africans have been detained and
tortured.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar sent a telegram to
President P.W. Botha of South Africa asking mercy be shown the five
men and one woman on humanitarian grounds.
   He said clemency would help reduce tensions in South Africa,
where 5 million whites control the government and the 26 million
blacks have no voice in national affairs.
   The council resolution spoke of the ``Pretoria racist regime's
decision to execute the Sharpeville Six ... in defiance of
worldwide appeals.''
   Ambassador A. Leslie Manley of South Africa issued a statement
criticizing the council, which frequently condemns his country.
   He said the government ``strongly objects'' to council action
that interferes ``not only in an internal South African matter but
also a matter which is the result of the due process of law.''
   South Africa ``is not insensitive to the feelings aroused by
capital punishment but must respect the independence of the
country's judicial system,'' his statement said. ``Murder is a
common law crime. It has nothing to do with the color of a person's
skin.''
   It said South African courts ``are highly respected'' and that
there are few countries ``if any, where the courts enjoy a higher
degree of independence from the executive authority.''
   This was the council's second action in a week of a resolution
condemning apartheid, the official South African policy of race
discrimination. Last Tuesday, the United States and Britain vetoed
a resolution that would have imposed economic sanctions.
   Wednesday's resolution said the executions would ``further
inflame an already grave situation in South Africa.''
   It urged South Africa to commute the sentences and asked all
countries and organizations to ``use influence and take urgent
measures to save the lives of the `Sharpeville Six'.''
   The United States, Soviet Union, Britain, France and China are
permanent members of the council, with veto power. Other nations
currently serving are Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Italy, Japan,
Nepal, Senegal, West Germany, Yugoslavia and Zambia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
