<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AquinoTrial     03-16 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aquino Trial,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sound Expert Testifies To Events at Benigno Aquino Airport Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese sound expert testified
Wednesday that tape-recordings show President Corazon Aquino's
husband was killed on an airport stairway in 1983 by a gun other
than previously claimed, and that soldiers shouted ``Let me do it!''
   Matsumi Suzuki, president of Japan Acoustics Institute of Tokyo,
testified at the trial of 34 soldiers and three civilians accused
of murdering former Sen. Benigno Aquino and Rolando Galman, a
purported communist agent originally accused as Aquino's assassin.
   Aquino's murder led to a groundswell of opposition to
then-President Ferdinand E. Marcos that culminated in a February
1986 popular revolt which deposed Marcos after 20 years in office
and swept Mrs. Aquino to power.
   Suzuki identified four soldiers as the ones who shouted ``This
is it!,'' ``Let me do it!'' and ``Shoot, shoot!'' seconds before
Aquino was murdered at Manila airport on Aug. 21, 1983. He said the
soldiers shouted in Tagalog, the main Filipino language.
   Aquino was shot as he left a China Airlines flight under
military escort on his return from three years self-exile in
America to lead the opposition to Marcos. The soldiers shot Galman
on the tarmac seconds after Aquino fell.
   Suzuki, speaking in Japanese through an interpreter, said he
analyzed sounds picked up by journalists' tape-recorders during the
assassination and from test-firing various types of guns in
Japanese and U.S. studios.
   Chief prosecutor Raul Gonzales later told reporters Suzuki's
testimony supports the prosecution's claim that Aquino was killed
on the stairway, where only soldiers were in a position to shoot
him in the back of the head.
   The Marcos government claimed Galman shot Aquino on the tarmac
with a .357-caliber Magnum.
   Suzuki said his analysis of tape-recordings show the first shot,
which has been established as the one that killed Aquino, could
have come only from a .45-caliber pistol.
   He said the sound of the footsteps of Aquino and his four
soldier escorts were clearly picked up by two boom microphones
extended over the top of the 21-step stairway as the party began
descending.
   ``We can clearly analyze the sound of the first step to the 11th
step,'' he said. ``After the 11th step ... the sound of gunfire was
heard.''
   The tapes picked up the words ``Eto na'' (This is it), followed
by ``Ako na. Ako na'' (Let me do it. Let me do it) and ``Pusila.
Pusila.'' (Shoot. Shoot.)
   Suzuki said that from a study of voice prints, he concluded the
words ``Eto na'' were shouted by Lt. Jesus de Castro, chief of the
security detail who remained at the stop of the stairs while Aquino
was led down.
   The words ``let me do it'' were spoken by Sgts. Claro Lat and
Arnulfo de Mesa one after the other, he said.
   Suzuki said the fatal shot came after both Castro and Constable
1st Class Mario Lazaga shouted ``shoot'' one after the other.
   Defense Lawyer Rodoldo Jimenez objected that ``voice analysis is
not an exact science.''
   But Suzuki and Gonzalez claimed that like fingerprints, a voice
print is unique and cannot be duplicated.
   Judge Regino Hermosisima, one of the three judges trying the
case, said the court was accepting Suzuki's testimony as ``part of
the evidence although this is not an exact science.''
   An earlier trial acquitted 25 soldiers and one civilian
implicated in the Aquino-Galman murders. But soon after Mrs. Aquino
became president, the Supreme Court ruled Marcos had influenced the
decision and ordered a retrial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
