<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BoyinBox     03-16 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boy in Box,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Pleads Guilty To Locking Boy In Box</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who pleaded guilty to keeping an
8-year-old in a playhouse-sized box for two years says she was
trying to prevent the boy from destroying her property while she
slept.
   Retha Skyles, 54, pleaded guilty to unlawful imprisonment
Tuesday. Sentencing was set for April 26.
   The child, who was kept in the box from 1985 to 1987, is the son
of Ms. Skyles' stepdaughter. When the boy was removed from the
Skyles home, he said he was surprised to learn that all little boys
weren't kept in boxes, court papers said.
   In a handwritten statement, Ms. Skyles said, ``I restrained (the
boy) during my sleeping hours in order to keep him from destroying
property.
   ``My judgment may not have been proper, but my judgment as to
the amount of restraint seemed proper to me under the
circumstances,'' she said.
   The box often was locked and contained a jar in which the boy
was expected to urinate, police said. He was not allowed to attend
school, but did attend church. When he was removed from the home,
he had a severe case of head lice.
   The law provides for a maximum sentence of 90 days in jail, two
years' probation and a requirement that the woman pay indefinitely
for counseling for the boy, deputy prosecutor Barbara Corey-Boulet
said Wednesday.
   However, a judge can declare the case exceptional and impose a
stronger sentence.
   The prosecutor declined to comment on whether she thought the
sentence contained in the law would be appropriate, adding only
that the boy is ``going to be needing a lot of counseling as he
adjusts to a more normal life and she's (Ms. Skyles) going to be
paying for that. That's the kind of punishment that will benefit
the child.''
   Larry Fehr, executive director of the non-profit Washington
Council on Crime and Delinquency, said: ``One can't help but be
struck by the discrepancy ... in regard to a child being confined
for a much longer period of time than the person who pleaded guilty
to the crime.''
   Ms. Skyles' attorney, Wallace Cavanagh, did not return messages
left with his office Wednesday.
   An anonymous tip led Child Protective Services workers to the
Skyles home, where they took the boy and his 11-year-old sister
into custody. They are living with foster parents and are
``thriving,'' said Frank Mendizabal, DSHS spokesman.
</TEXT>
