<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Ferries     03-16 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ferries,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferry Workers Vote To Continue Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,000 ferry workers voted
overwhelmingly Wednesday to continue a six-week strike against a
ferry line, despite a company ultimatum to sign new contracts or
lose their jobs.
   In an outdoor meeting in this southeast England port, all but
two of the ferry workers from the National Union of Seamen raised
their hands in favor of maintaining the strike.
   Roger Wilkins, deputy general secretary, and other union leaders
urged members to step up picketing and fight what they said were
moves by P and O European Ferries to hire non-union foreign workers.
   The strike has halted sailings of P and O's 11 vessels between
Dover and the French ports of Boulogne and Calais across the
English Channel and Zeebrugge, Belgium, across the North Sea.
   Peter Ford, chairman of the ferry company, denied the company
planned to use foreign workers and said he was disappointed with
the vote.
   ``I hope they will opt for the new contracts,'' he said.
   The ferry workers struck after the company announced plans to
reduce the number of crews for each vessel.
   Pay for a deckhand ranges from $23,125 to $33,300 a year.
   The union agreed to fewer jobs to maintain profitable operations
against the challenge of the Channel Tunnel project, but wanted the
cuts spread over three years.
   The underwater rail tunnel now being built between England and
France is scheduled to open in May 1993 at a cost of $9 billion and
is expected to cut into ferry profits.
   The company's ultimatum followed the collapse of five days of
talks with the union, which were convened by the government's
arbitration service. Each side accused the other of intransigence.
   Six hundred ferry masters and officers will decide whether to
settle a dispute with the company at a meeting Saturday.
   The company wants to cut 200 of their jobs because of
redundancies and new work patterns. The officers have not been on
strike.
</TEXT>
