<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CopterMemorial     03-16 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copter Memorial,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter Crash Victims Remembered at Memorial Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A soldier in one of the units involved
in a helicopter collision that killed 17 servicemen said at a
memorial service Wednesday that the loss was magnified by ``the
bond between us soldiers.''
   Military and civilian dignitaries, including Gov. Wallace G.
Wilkinson, joined family members and other mourners in the 450-seat
Post Central Chapel for two services.
   The first half-hour memorial honored the seven Army aviators
flying the helicopters when they collided March 8; the second paid
homage to the 10 foot soldiers on board.
   An open Bible rested on a simple altar, flanked by banners
representing the the 101st Airborne Division and flags pinned with
colorful streamers representing battles in which units of the 101st
fought.
   The seven helicopter crewmen were represented in front of the
altar by seven flight helmets placed atop sabers for the officers
and M-16 rifles for the enlisted men. Infantry helmets were used to
represent the foot soldiers.
   The 17 were killed when a UH-60 Black Hawk helicopter, returning
from a night mission, was struck by another copter on a separate
mission at Fort Campbell.
   Army investigators said they have not determined the cause of
the crash.
   ``During the toughest of times we find ourselves wondering why
we choose to be infantrymen,'' said Spec. 4 Colin Cannon, whose
unit included 10 of the victims. ``It is a job that is at best
difficult and at its worst fatal.''
   The loss was magnified by ``the bond between us as soldiers,
which brought us closer to each other in a way that so many others
can never know; something that only people who serve in a
profession such as ours can ever understand,'' Cannon said.
   ``I have flown personally with each of these (helicopter crew
members). I can tell you without reservation that they truly loved
what they were doing,'' said Lt. Col. Joseph A. Fucci, commander of
the 101st Aviation Regiment's 5th Brigade.
   ``We all share in the loss of these men. And though all the
grief that we feel does not begin to compare with the sorrow being
felt by their wives and their families, our hearts and our prayers
go out to you,'' he said.
</TEXT>
