<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Anderson-Batavia     03-16 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anderson-Batavia,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Solemn Day In Hostage Terry Anderson's Hometown</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Anderson-Anniversary, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATAVIA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of yellow ribbons adorned trees,
traffic signs and lapels on Terry Anderson Day in the journalist's
hometown Wednesday, the third anniversary of his kidnapping by
Moslem extremists in Lebanon.
   ``The most sacred experience is to be remembered by frends,
loved ones and by God,'' said the Rev. Jack Wolter of St. James
Episcopal Church, where prayer services were held for Anderson.
   ``We pray that Terry will be remembered today and soon delivered
from his tormenters,'' Wolter said.
   Anderson, the chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press, was kidnapped in Beirut and has been held longer than any of
the 22 foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   The activities in Batavia coincided with a national observance
in Washington, D.C. The anniversary also was marked in Anderson's
birthplace, Lorain, Ohio, where a group including relatives hoisted
an American flag and tied a yellow ribbon to the flagpole at City
Hall.
   ``May this be a day of miracles,'' the Rev. Thomas Vickers, who
has acted as personal chaplain to Anderson's family in recent
months, said in Batavia. ``Please Lord, set him free.''
   Journalists outnumbered the handful of churchgoers at an early
morning service at St. James. Vickers asked reporters to put down
their notebooks to join hands and pray for a colleague.
   At the church's midday service about 30 people heard a service
by Vickers and Wolter, who said Christians had a duty to speak up
for those who suffer injustice.
   Anderson's younger brother, Jack, who grew up in Batavia and
works as a prison guard in Ocala, Fla., urged those attending to
write their congressmen to press the government to do more to win
the release of the hostages.
   ``I'm sure Terry is thinking of Batavia today,'' he said. ``I
know he wants more than anything to be able come back here and be
with his family and friends.''
   Several florists in the small city of 17,000 donated more than
two miles of yellow ribbon, which was tied in bows and handed out
to residents. Nearly every tree, sign post and railing along Main
Street sported yellow ribbon.
   ``We always knew people were concerned about Terry,'' Jack
Anderson said. ``But in the past they didn't turn out and make an
effort to show it.''
   Anderson's sister, Peggy Say of Batavia, has fought to free her
brother since his kidnapping, but her activities did not win
widespread support in her hometown until recently.
   ``People didn't know how to react,'' said Terry Fritts, a talk
show host on radio station WBTA. ``I don't think many people
opposed what Peggy was doing. They just didn't know if it was the
best thing to do.''
   Mrs. Say, who was in Washington on Wednesday, and other family
members have said they hope the attention will force the
administration to develop a new policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
