<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0869 03-16 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0869,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Plays Down Racial Division Of Illinois Vote</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS grafs 2-4 with Jackson comment on Iran-Contra
indictments; ADDS 2 grafs with later event</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Wednesday he's counting
``the number of votes, not the color of votes'' in the wake of his
second-place showing in his home state of Illinois where he
garnered less than 10 percent of the white vote.
   Jackson also said the four men indicted Wednesday on conspiracy
charges in the Iran-Contra affair _ Lt. Col. Oliver L. North, fired
national security adviser John M. Poindexter, retired Air Force
Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord and Secord's business partner, Albert
Hakim _ were ``fall guys.''
   ``They were in fact implementing this administration's policy,''
Jackson said, calling the Iran-Contra affair `` a source of
embarrassment to this administration and a disgrace to our
country.''
   Back on the subject of the Illinois contest, Jackson was upbeat.
   ``We came in a strong second in Illinois,'' he told reporters.
``I am gratified with the response to my campaign in Illinois
yesterday.''
   ``We did well. Illinois did well by both of its favorite-son
candiates,'' he said, when asked about pre-election polls that had
showed him virtually dead even with home state Sen. Paul Simon.
Jackson ended up with 31 percent of the vote, to Simon's 43 percent.
   Exit polls showed Jackson overwhelming won the state's black
vote, but pulled only 7 to 8 percent of white voters into his camp.
That was less than the 10 percent he garnered across the Super
Tuesday states on March 8, and a represented an apparent setback
from his strong showings in Northern states that have black
populations of 1 percent or less, including Minnesota, Maine,
Vermont and Alaska.
   When asked if that spelled trouble in the states yet to come as
he tries to attract crucial white support to his campaign, Jackson
replied, ``Let's count the number of votes, not the color of
votes.'' He noted he is first in the cumulative popular vote count
of states that have held primaries so far, and is a close second in
the delegate count to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   ``Of 30 contests now I have come in number one or number two ...
We have reason to celebrate in my campaign. We are where every
campaign wants to be.''
   Jackson made the comments following an observance at Holy
Trinity Church of the third year of captivity for American hostage
Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press who is being held in Lebanon.
   Earlier he had a chance meeting at National Airport with rival
Sen. Albert Gore Jr., of Tennessee, who was leaving as Jackson was
arriving. The two spoke briefly, and according to Jackson talked
about party unity.
   Organizers of the hostage memorial said all the presidential
candidates were invited to the service, which included remarks by
former hostages and family members of Anderson and others still
being held. Jackson, who helped gain release of downed Navy pilot
Lt. Robert Goodman from Syria in 1983, was the only one who
attended.
   At a news conference afterward, Jackson said he has ``done
everything I can'' to make contacts that might secure the hostage
release, but that the situation is complicated because he does not
know who is holding the hostages.
   He criticized the administration, however, saying that the U.S.
intelligence operations should be put to work finding the location
of the hostages and the identity of the captors so that
negotiations for their release can begin.
   ``They can be found, through our intelligence network,'' he
said, adding that negotiations should begin ``either directly or
through our allies.''
   Outside the church in the posh Georgetown neighborhood of
Washington, Jackson caused a stir among Holy Trinity elementary
school students, Georgetown University students and passersby who
rushed out to shake his hand.
   The school children squealed in delight as he raced across a
cobblestone street to greet them, then went to the other side to
shake hands with college students who rushed out on the balconies
of their brownstone homes to cheer him.
   ``I don't think I'd want him to win, but I think I might vote
for him. He's the only one bringing out the important issues,''
said Erich Vaden, 19, a Georgetown student.
   Later, Jackson went to one of Washington's most well-known
drug-trafficking neighborhoods, where he and District of Columbia
Mayor Marion Barry addressed a rally. Jackson made a strong
anti-drug statement, telling 300 people, ``We must stop drugs or
drugs will stop the people.''
   ``You must be sober and free of drugs whether you have a job or
not,'' he said. Jackson also said drugs are a foreign policy issue
that has been dealt with inadequately by the Reagan administration.
</TEXT>
