<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-CivilRights 4thLd-Writethru a0962 03-16 1055</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Civil Rights, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0962,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Vetoes Civil Rights Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 13th graf bgng: ``Prohibit discrimination ... to CORRECT
private aid to public aid.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan vetoed a major civil rights
bill Wednesday, saying it would ``vastly and unjustifiably extend
the power of the federal government over the decisions and affairs
of private organizations.''
   Reagan also proposed an alternative that he said would ``protect
civil rights and at the same time preserve the independence of
state and local governments, the freedom of religion and the right
of America's citizens to order their lives and businesses without
extensive federal intrusion.''
   The veto was immediately criticized by civil rights and other
groups, and congressional Democrats predicted a quick override.
   The legislation, which had bipartisan support, passed the Senate
75-14 on Jan. 28 and the House 315-98 on March 2. Both votes are
more than the two-thirds majority necessary to override a
presidential veto.
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Labor and
Human Resources Committee, called the veto ``a kick in the teeth of
civil rights. It is the most regrettable and least justifiable of
all the Reagan vetoes.''
   The bill the president vetoed was designed to undo the effects
of a 1984 Supreme Court ruling that, in cutting off federal funds
because of illegal discrimination, the government could treat each
specific ``program or activity'' separately.
   That meant that other parts of the institution involved could
still receive federal funds.
   Under the bill, federal aid to the entire institution would have
to be cut off in such cases.
   In his veto message, the president said he supported legislation
to ``strengthen the civil rights coverage of educational
institutions'' that were affected by the high court's decision.
   He said he had already endorsed legislation to do this but his
new bill ``goes further than the legislation previously endorsed.''
   Reagan's bill is similar to one rejected by the House by a vote
of 266-146.
   The president said his bill would:
   _``Prohibit discrimination against women, minorities, persons
with disabilities, and the elderly across the board in public
school districts, public systems of higher education, systems of
vocational education, and private educational institutions which
receive any public aid.
   _``Extend the application of the civil rights statutes to entire
businesses which receive federal aid as a whole and to the entire
plant or facility receiving federal aid in every other instance.
   _``Prohibit discrimination in all of the federally funded
programs of departments and agencies of state and local
governments.''
   Reagan said his bill ``complements well our body of existing
federal civil rights laws.''
   ``Congress, on the other hand, has sent me a bill that would
vastly and unjustifiably expand the power of the federal government
over the decisions and affairs of private organizations, such as
churches and synagogues, farms, businesses, and state and local
governments,'' he said. ``In the process, it would place at risk
such cherished values as religious liberty.''
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., chairman of the House Education
and Labor Committee, said he was confident the House will override
the veto. ``I don't think many members will be so weak-kneed that
they will change on the basis of lobbying that is now going on,''
Hawkins said.
   House Speaker Jim Wright said in a statement that ``President
Reagan may want to turn the clock back on civil rights, but the
American people do not... I am confident that the Senate and House
will move swiftly to override this unfortunate and shortsighted
veto.''
   A Senate leadership aide said the chamber would vote Thursday on
overriding the veto. The House was not expected to act before
Tuesday.
   Ralph G. Neas, director of the Leadership Conference on Civil
Rights, and Benjamin L. Hooks, chairman of the organization, issued
a statement denouncing the president's action and predicting that
it would be overturned.
   ``While we are confident that huge bipartisan majorities in both
houses of Congress will vote to override a presidential veto, we
believe strongly that this veto is not in the best interests of the
country because it sends a terrible signal to the nation,
especially in this bicentennial year of the Constitution,'' the
statement said.
   ``The president sometimes expresses wonder that anyone can
criticize him on his civil rights record,'' the two leaders said.
``In fact this administration is compiling the worst civil rights
record of any administration in half a century.''
   The AFL-CIO issued a statement Wednesday calling the veto ``a
strong message of retreat from enforcement of laws intended to
prevent discrimination based on race, sex, age and handicap.''
   The United States Catholic Conference, an association
representing the nation's Roman Catholic bishops, issued a
statement saying the conference was
   ``deeply disappointed that the president saw fit to veto one of
the most important pieces of civil rights legislation to come along
in many years.''
   It said the bill would have done much to ``strengthen federal
civil rights protection while safeguarding vital concerns about
human life and religious liberty.'' The conference vowed to work
``actively'' for an override.
   The White House, in a statement accompanying Reagan's veto
message, said the administration alternative would protect
religious liberty by limiting coverage to the part of a church or
synagogue that participates in a federal program. The statement
said the Reagan bill would provide that when a religious secondary
or elementary school receives federal assistance, only that school,
and not the entire religious school system, would become subject to
federal regulation.
   The statement said the measure would ``ensure that the reach of
the federal regulation into private businesses extends only to the
facility that participates in federally funded programs, unless the
business as a whole receives federal aid, in which case it is
covered in its entirety.''
   It said the administration bill also states explicitly that
farmers will not become subject to federal regulation by accepting
federal price support payments and that grocers and supermarkets
would not be afgfected because they accept food stamps from
customers.
   It said the independence of state and local governments would be
preserved because federal regulation would be limited to the part
of a state or local entity that receives or distributes federal
assistance.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday he believed
the bill would attract the support of ``a large number'' of
senators and representatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
