<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Visas     03-16 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Visas,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official: More Soviets Receiving Visas to Visit, Live Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More Soviets are applying to visit or live abroad
and fewer of them are being refused permission, a Soviet official
said Wednesday.
   Sergei Apatov, head of the Moscow police department's visa
office, told Soviet journalists that 82 percent of Soviets who
apply to go to Israel are granted permission.
   About 200 people have been turned down, he said. He did not
break the number down into travel and emigration requests or
provide an overall figure.
   The government newspaper Izvestia and the official Tass news
agency carried reports on Apatov's briefing.
   Apatov said citizens were refused permission either because of
their access to state secrets or because they could not satisfy
their relatives' financial demands.
   He said those not allowed to leave because of their alleged
access to state secrets can reapply, usually after six months.
   Many Soviet Jews say officials abuse the law that says people
can not leave if they know state secrets or are needed by their
families for financial reasons.
   Western sources say more than 8,000 Soviet Jews were allowed to
emigrate in 1987, after several years when emigration was held to
about 1,000 a year. Emigration reached its peak in 1979, when more
than 51,000 people left.
   Apatov said a reduction in the paperwork needed to travel abroad
also prompted more Soviets to apply for permission for trips.
   The number of people applying to travel to capitalist countries
increased 93 percent in the first two months of 1988, Apatov said.
The number of people refused such permission fell 44 percent in
1987 from the previous year, he said, without providing specific
figures.
   A fee imposed on those leaving for capitalist and developing
countries has been halved to 200 rubles (about $320), Apatov said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
