<DOCNO> AP880316-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 2124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0932 03-16 0851</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0932,0875</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham, In First Trial Appearance, Denies Appointments Based on
Money</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with later testimony, comments on public
image, trusting aides, allegation of protecting aide accused of
death threat, rescinding Martin Luther King holiday. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham took the stand at his
impeachment trial Wednesday and said that he did not protect an
aide accused of making a death threat and did not sell appointments
for campaign contributions.
   The governor, portraying himself as a naive victim of political
enemies who skewered him with bad publicity, said the public never
saw him as ``the nice guy I really am.''
   ``I've learned a lot,'' he said in his first appearance at the
Senate trial, which opened Feb. 29. The first-term Republican was
scheduled to return to the stand on Thursday.
   Mecham, 63, is the first U.S. governor to face an impeachment
trial in six decades. Wednesday's session was his first return to
the seat of state government in more than a month.
   He is accused of trying to obstruct an investigation of an
alleged death threat against a former aide who was about to testify
in an investigation of Mecham's finances. He is also charged with
concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 in state
money by loaning it to his auto dealership.
   Mecham has denied wrongdoing.
   The 192-seat Senate gallery was jammed as Mecham took the stand.
Senators remained standing as he took an oath to tell the truth.
   Defense attorney Fred Craft asked whether Mecham intended to
protect the aide accused of making the death threat, Lee Watkins.
   ``Protect him from what?'' Mecham asked. ``I've heard those
allegations. I wish somebody would tell me what I protected him
from.''
   Craft mentioned a conversation in which Mecham was alleged to
have ordered the state's top law enforcement officer to resist the
attorney general's investigation of the alleged threat.
   ``Were you intending to do anything to protect Lee Watkins (in
that conversation)?'' asked Craft.
   ``Not in the least,'' said Mecham.
   Mecham has claimed he was inadequately informed about the death
threat allegation.
   He has acknowledged he may have told the state's top police
official, Department of Public Safety Director Ralph Milstead, to
resist the attorney general's efforts to investigate. Milstead has
said he cooperated with the attorney general.
   Mecham on Wednesdsay also denied allegations that he rewarded
fund-raisers with jobs. ``Money was never an object and it was
never used as a criteria to get a job,'' he said.
   The governor also denied that Watkins was his biggest
fund-raiser, saying Watkins ``brought in some loans'' but not a
huge amount in contributions.
   Last week, Donna Carlson, a former Mecham aide, had testified
that Watkins was protected by the Mecham administration because of
his fund-raising.
   She said that when she once complained about Watkins' position
in the governor's inner circle she was told by the governor's
then-chief of staff: ``We have to take care of Lee. He raised a lot
of money for the campaign.''
   Earlier Wednesday, Sam Udall, Mecham's former appointments
secretary, had testified that campaign contributions were a
criterion, although not a major one, in making appointments to
state boards and commissions.
   Udall also testified that he did not immediately realize that
two proposed appointees to the Housing Finance Review Board had
been recommended by Barry Wolfson, who provided a $350,000 campaign
loan to Mecham.
   Mecham, a millionaire auto dealer, said Wednesday that he
himself was his biggest campaign contributor.
   ``Unfortunately I always have been,'' he said of his political
career, which included four previous runs for governor before his
successful 1986 campaign.
   Mecham also seized the opportunity to complain of being
misunderstood on one of his first official acts, elimination of the
state's Martin Luther King holiday. He said that his action was
mandated by the attorney general and that he replaced a paid state
holiday with an unpaid ``recognition day.''
   ``What we did was tell peoiple we in Arizona believe in civil
rights for all people,'' he said.
   Shortly before Mecham appeared, the Senate resoundingly voted
down a motion to dismiss the charges. The senators also defeated
defense motions to declare a mistrial or to hold a hearing on
defense claims of witness tampering.
   Robert Usdane, House Republican majority leader, noted that
claims by Mecham's lawyers that the state police were intimidating
witnesses were under investigation by law enforcement agencies.
   Mecham, a perennial political outsider who won election in a
three-way race, has been staying at suburban Glendale offices he
calls his ``government in exile.'' He retains his salary and is
referred to as governor during the impeachment proceedings, but
Mofford has gubernatorial power pending the outcome of the trial.
   It would take a two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate to
convict Mecham and remove him from office. The senators could then
take another vote and bar him for life from holding state office.
   Mecham also faces a criminal trial April 21 on charges he
concealed the $350,000 loan, and a recall election is scheduled for
May 17.
</TEXT>
