<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LehderTrial     03-16 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lehder's Accusations Cause Brief Turmoil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reputed druglord Carlos Lehder Rivas
interrupted his smuggling trial Wednesday to say he had evidence
the chief prosecutor was blackmailing the judge, an allegation the
prosecutor called ``high comedy.''
   U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle said the man who sent the letter to
Lehder had ``mental problems'' and had made similar allegations
about authorities in Tampa, where he had been convicted on
extortion and racketeering charges.
   U.S. District Judge Howell Melton read the letter and said he
had also received previous letters from the man.
   Lehder, 38, charged with smuggling tons of cocaine into the
United States, rose as the court was breaking for a mid-morning
recess.
   ``Your honor, I would like to disclose that I have received
evidence that Mr. Merkle is blackmailing Judge Melton and I'd like
to present it,'' he said.
   ``This is high comedy,'' Merkle said as Melton said he'd like to
hear any such evidence.
   The statement apparently was unexpected even by Lehder's
attorneys. It resulted in quick recesses so they could confer with
their client. The letter-writer's name was not revealed in court.
   ``This individual is familiar to me. He has mental problems,''
said the prosecutor.
   ``I do not intend for the integrity of this court, nor the
prosecutor to be impugned,'' the judge said of the allegations. ``I
would categorically say that at this time, they are absolutely
untrue.''
   The judge gave the defense until Thursday morning to file any
motions they might want to make concerning the material.
   Lehder said the information had been filed by the letter writer
with a federal appeals court and the Senate Judiciary Committee.
``I wanted to just call it to the judge's attention so that
something can be done about it,'' said Lehder.
   Defense attorney Edward R. Shohat said his client had no
personal knowledge about the source of the information.
   Lehder, reputed to be one of the leaders of Colombia's Medellin
cocaine cartel, is on trial on charges he and others conspired to
import some 3.3 tons of the drug into the United States from
Colombia via the Bahamas.
   Co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged with being a part of the smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
