<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MortonThiokol-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0913 03-16 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Morton Thiokol-Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0913,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Fines Morton Thiokol Over Fatal December Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, `The contractor ...' with four grafs to
UPDATE with Thiokol response; DELETES 16th graf pvs, `Three
violations ...' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state agency cited Morton Thiokol Inc.
for six safety violations and fined the aerospace company $31,700
Wednesday in a fire in an MX missile motor assembly building Dec.
29 that killed five workers.
   The victims' presence in the building and failure to use
remote-control equipment instead at the time of the fire were among
the most serious violations alleged by the Utah Division of
Occupational Safety and Health.
   The penalties represent the maximum that could be imposed, said
Doug McVey, UOSH administrator.
   The contractor has 30 days to appeal the citations and penalties
to the independent Utah UOSH Review Commission. Three violations
were deemed willful and serious, two were deemed serious and one
was ``other than serious.''
   In a statement late Wednesday, Chicago-based Morton Thiokol said
that it is ``confident that the facts will not substantiate any
conscious or knowing violation of the act'' and that it will
challenge the citations.
   Morton Thiokol described many of the alleged violations as
``random instances unknown to company management, which reflect a
failure of some employees to follow all rules established by the
company.''
   The company said increased supervision and stricter enforcement
of the company's discipline program have been instituted as a
remedy.
   The workers were withdrawing the core from a casting of the
first stage of an MX missile when 100,000 pounds of solid fuel
ignited in a fireball. The blaze caused $6.2 million in damage to
the plant 25 miles west of Brigham City.
   Morton Thiokol makes the missile's four stages, and also makes
the space shuttle's solid-fuel rocket boosters, which failed when
the Challenger blew up in January 1986.
   The fire at Thiokol's Wasatch Division has held up production of
the MX missile until the cause of the fire can be determined and
corrected.
   Air Force investigators, in a briefing Wednesday, blamed either
static electricity or friction, perhaps from grit, as the probable
cause of the fire, said Art Kingdom, a spokesman for Rep. Wayne
Owens, D-Utah.
   Another theory is that as the propellant was compressed, its
chemistry changed, making it more volatile, Kingdom said.
   McVey said state investigators agreed with the Air Force's
findings, although his division's investigation focused on safety
regulations, not the cause.
   Results of the Air Force's investigation were scheduled to be
made public Thursday, but members of Utah's congressional
delegation were briefed a day in advance.
   UOSH alleged that workmen were removing the core from an engine
manually rather than by remote control. The cores, or metal forms,
are removed after the propellant has been poured into the casing
and allowed to harden.
   The agency also said protective walls and barricades were not
provided, and proper precautions against static electricty weren't
taken.
   In addition, it said, dual controls for a hydraulic system were
not interlocked to prevent unintentional operations, and employees
entering the explosive material area did not turn over all
prohibited articles, such as coins and keys.
   Also, an unauthorized crowbar was in a restricted area, UOSH
said.
   Kingdom said the Air Force recommended better electrical
grounding, increased humidity and more care in withdrawing cores
from engines.
   The Air Force said the fire destroyed one of three missile
engine cores. Investigators said two completed castings are
awaiting withdrawal of the cores before the engines can be shipped
to the Air Force in California, Kingdom said.
   Kingdom said the Air Force had indicated it needed the engines
within the two months to continue its MX test program.
</TEXT>
