<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ByrneOut 1stLd-Writethru a0808 03-16 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Byrne Out, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0808,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Mayor Jane Byrne May Quit Politics after Third Straight
Loss</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5 pvs bgng, `Mrs. Byrne ...' to UPDATE with
comment from Byrne.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Jane Byrne kicked in the door of
Chicago's fabled backroom politics nearly a decade ago, unsmiling
and unafraid of mixing it up with the Democratic machine's big boys.
   But after her third straight electoral setback, this one for
clerk of the Cook County Circuit Court and viewed by many political
observers as the first step in a comeback bid, Mrs. Byrne
apparently is calling it quits.
   ``When we say the people spoke,'' Mrs. Byrne said of Tuesday's
primary defeat, ``they apparently shouted.
   ``And therefore,'' she added, ``I'm very good at taking hints.''
   ``I truly believe that politically it's all over for me,'' Mrs.
Byrne said Wednesday before leaving for Phoenix, Ariz.
   She headed west for ``some rest and relaxation,'' said Joe
Pecor, her campaign manager. Asked whether she would run again, he
said, ``Where she is concerned, one should never say never.''
   ``She has demonstrated time and again that she has a very solid
core of support running somewhere between 35 (percent) and 40
percent of the Democrats in Chicago and the county.''
   But that wasn't enough to stave off the late Harold Washington's
upset bid in the three-way 1983 Democratic mayoral primary, and it
wasn't enough when she tried to avenge that loss against Washington
last year.
   It turned out be too little again Tuesday when she lost to
Aurelia Pucinski, endorsed by the party organization that Mrs.
Byrne once held, vise-like, in her grip.
   And this latest loss came in a race rich with resonance and
names _ Pucinski, Byrne and Edward ``Fast Eddie'' Vrdolyak _ that
speak to the past, present and perhaps even the future of Cook
County's quirky Democratic politics.
   Mrs. Byrne, a former debutante with a flair for the dramatic,
became the city's first woman mayor in 1979, scoring a
rags-to-riches victory after campaigning against the political
machine of the late Mayor Richard J. Daley.
   She defeated the machine's candidate, then-Mayor Michael
Bilandic, with the help of much of the city's machine-weary blacks,
but later made peace with the regular Democrats.
   Included in that group were several aldermen Mrs. Byrne had
railed against as members of ``an evil cabal,'' most notably
Vrdolyak and Roman Pucinski, Aurelia Pucinski's father and one of
the machine's most loyal servants.
   But she paid dearly for cozying up to the old guard, as well as
for several other moves _ replacing blacks with whites on the
school board, then handing out hams at public-housing projects as
the 1983 election neared.
   Washington, galvanizing the black vote, turned her out of office
and became the city's first black mayor.
   He spent the next four years retooling the party machinery to
fit his needs, then became the first two-term mayor since Daley by
handily beating back successive challenges from Mrs. Byrne last
February in the primary and then Vrdolyak, running as a third-party
candidate, in April.
   After Washington's death in November, Alderman Eugene Sawyer
became mayor.
   Vrdolyak, saying the party under Washington had become
untenable, completed his move away from the Democratic organization
last year. Running as a Republican, he was unopposed in Tuesday's
primary for court clerk.
   In the meantime, Ms. Pucinski, an attorney and Metropolitan
Sanitary District commissioner, stepped out of her father's shadow
and was welcomed into the Washington camp.
   So much so that she may have beaten Byrne in Tuesday's race on
the strength of her showing among Chicago's blacks, who helped
propel her to a 52 percent to 38 percent victory over Mrs. Byrne
with nearly all the votes counted. Two other candidates, Thomas
Fuller, and Janice Hart, a follower of political extremist Lyndon
LaRouche, split the rest of the vote.
   Ms. Hart defeated Ms. Pucinski in the 1986 Democratic primary
for the Illinois secretary of state's office, won that November by
Republican Jim Edgar.
   Byrne's defeat spoiled an anticipated Byrne-Vrdolyak struggle in
the fall, a match of two former titans for an obscure office both
hoped would lead to bigger things.
</TEXT>
