<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthKorea     03-16 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kim Dae-jung Resigns As Opposition Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kim Dae-jung resigned Thursday as
leader of his party in an attempt to unite the opposition before
National Assembly elections expected in April.
   He said he was stepping down because his presence as head of the
Party for Peace and Democracy was blocking unification and because
he failed to win the Dec. 16 presidential elections.
   ``I have keenly felt guilty,'' Kim Dae-jung said in a statement
read by a party vice president, Park Young-sook, who said she would
be acting party president.
   The statement made no mention of Kim Dae-jung's future plans. He
did not make the statement himself because he was ill, party
officials said.
   Efforts to unite Peace and Democracy with the rival
Reunification Democratic Party collapsed last week when Kim
Dae-jung refused the other party's demand that he resign.
   It was not clear if his resignation Thursday would clear the way
for the opposition to unite. The Reunification Democratic
leadership met after Kim Dae-jung's announcement to consider its
response.
   Kim Dae-jung acted after the Reunification Democrats moved to
unite with three smaller opposition parties.
   Many opposition supporters are angry that the two main
opposition parties have failed to join together, and party leaders
fear a major loss of support.
   Kim Dae-jung and his supporters split from the Reunification
Democratic Party to form the Peace and Democracy Party late last
year after he and Kim Young-sam, the Reunification Democrats'
leader, failed to agree on who should run for president.
   Both Kims ran and were defeated by the government party's
nominee, Roh Tae-woo, who became president Feb. 25. Opposition
supporters blamed the two Kims for the defeat because they split
the opposition vote.
   Kim Young-sam resigned as Reunification Democratic Party
president in February to clear the way for the two parties to
unite. Unity talks ran into problems over leadership and political
goals and collapsed.
   The opposition is concerned it will suffer a major defeat in the
National Assembly elections expected April 26.
</TEXT>
