<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Weapons-Philippines     03-16 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weapons-Philippines,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Probe Arms-To-Philippines Plot Pointing To Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities in at least two states
are investigating whether Ferdinand Marcos tried to arrange an arms
shipment to Philippine forces loyal to him, according to federal
officials and other sources.
   Marcos' chief American attorney denied the former Philippine
president was involved in any arms shipments. ``That's a dry well
for you, my friend,'' Richard A. Hibey said Friday in Washington.
``There's no truth to that allegation.''
   Word that authorities were pressing such an investigation
surfaced here last week when U.S. District Judge Alfred J. Lechner
Jr., in sentencing a defendant in an arms smuggling case here,
referred to a continuing probe.
   Chris Franzblau, an attorney for the defendant, Abelardo Morua,
said Tuesday that federal agents had asked his client about Marcos.
   ``They asked a lot of times about if whether we had anything to
tie up Marcos to this transaction,'' he said, adding that Morua was
unable to provide such a link.
   Morua was charged with three others in a Customs Service sting
operation stemming from the alleged arms deal.
   No arms were alleged to have changed hands. However, officials
said the shipment would have supplied automatic rifles and
submachine guns for an 80-member force.
   Leon Dicker, a disbarred Hewlett, N.Y., attorney, was convicted
of conspiring to export weapons. The two others were acquitted.
Dicker was sentenced to four years in prison. Morua received a
two-year term.
   During the trial, the government said the arms were destined for
Thailand, but two federal officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said last week that the weapons were believed headed for
pro-Marcos forces in the Philippines.
   Pro-Marcos elements failed in at least two coup attempts in 1987.
   During Dicker's trial, the prosecutor said New York businessman
Robert L. Steele had worked with Dicker on the proposed arms
shipment.
   Steele, who was not charged, and Dicker have been linked to
Orlando C. Dulay, a Marcos supporter and former provincial governor
later connected by Philippine military sources to an August 1987
coup attempt against the government of Marcos' successor, Corazon
Aquino.
   Dulay was questioned by police on the grounds of a Marcos-owned
estate in Lawrence Township in August 1986. He said Steele and
Dicker, whom he identified as his lawyers, told him to clean up the
estate. He was not arrested.
   A newspaper in Manila said last week that Dulay was contacted by
U.S. authorities who traveled there seeking his cooperation in an
investigation of alleged arms shipments to pro-Marcos groups.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Peyton in Honolulu on Monday
confirmed that he met with Dulay last week, but said he could not
comment further because of an ``ongoing criminal investigation.''
   Raul Rabe, deputy chief of mission at the Philippines Embassy in
Washington, said Dulay joined Marcos in Honolulu before being
deported to the Philippines, where he faced charges in the 1986
slayings of three presidential campaign workers for Mrs. Aquino.
   Marcos has been living in exile in Honolulu since his 1986
ouster. He has said he wishes to return to his homeland.
   Last year, two U.S. businessmen testified before a House
subcommittee that Marcos had sought to buy weapons for shipment to
the Philippines in June, four months after Dicker's arrest. They
played for the panel secretly taped conversations with Marcos.
   It could not be determined if the alleged coup attempt, the
Dicker case and the Honolulu investigation were directly related.
   Neither U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. nor Richard Mercier,
head of Customs' Newark office, would comment on the case. Leonard
S. Walton, Customs director of illegal export investigations in
Washington, also would not comment.
   On Monday, Marcos issued a statement denying he wanted to resume
power ``through violent means.''
   Steele did not return repeated phone messages left this week and
last at his Commonwealth Group Ltd., a company in New York City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
