<1ST_LINE>a a PM-US-Polish adv17   03-16 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Polish, adv 17,0809</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs March 17 and thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Polish Ambassador Trying to Mend Ties Shattered by Martial Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jan Kinast left his post at the Polish Embassy
in Washington 20 years ago little dreaming he would return this
winter trying to mend relations shattered by martial law and a
foreign debt that is still rising.
   ``I keep pretty busy,'' says Kinast, a junior diplomat at the
Polish Embassy in Washington 1964-68 and Poland's first ambassador
to the United States since the military crackdown against the
independent Solidarity trade union in December 1981. Kinast's
predecessor, Romuald Spasowski, defected to protest martial law.
   So far, Kinast is having better luck winning friends for Poland
among America's officials than its businessmen and bankers.
   ``We are delighted with Ambassador Kinast,'' said Deputy
Secretary of State John Whitehead, who has traveled twice to Poland
since martial law was lifted in 1983. Whitehead, in a telephone
interview, described Kinast's immediate previous post, deputy
foreign minister, as analagous to his own job as No. 2 in the State
Department.
   Kinast, like many Poles, is a chain smoker, and nicotine stains
the thick glasses through which he pores over reams of finanicial
statistics.
   Poland's foreign debt, which was $25.5 billion in 1981, rose to
$39. billion by Dec. 31, 1987, driven higher by the collapsing
dollar and a lack of quality exports.
   The Reagan administration has lifted the freeze it imposed on
new credits to Poland during martial law, but Poland is still such
a bad risk that Western bankers balk at offering any new loans.
   John Davis Jr., who just became the first U.S. ambassador to
Poland since 1982, said in a televised interview last week that
Polish authorities appeared genuinely interested in economic
reforms.
   ``If economic reform is in place, and we see that it is in
place, it may be that there are some opportunities for joint
ventures, or other means of being helpful,'' said Davis.
   Poland took one step toward better relations with the United
States by closing down a business enterprise affiliated with the
Abu Nidal terrorist organization last fall and ordering the two men
in charge to leave Poland in January. U.S. anti-terrorism experts
say they are watching the situation carefully.
   And U.S. officials say more American help might be forthcoming
if Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski reached political
accommodation with Solidarity and Poland's Roman Catholic Church.
   ``I think that U.S. help would follow liberalization,'' Davis
said in an interview broadcast from Warsaw by ABC-TV.
   The billions of dollars Poland received in credit in the 1970's,
Davis said, ``went down the drain through a combination of bad luck
and bad management,'' creating the economic crisis that spawned
Solidarity in August 1980.
   But Kinast said in a recent interview in his Washington office
that Poland is looking not for new long-term credits but for
short-term commercial credits to facilitate transactions.
   ``Ninety-five percent of our (foreign) purchases are cash,'' he
said. ``No other country in the world is buying machines and
durable goods for cash.''
   A Polish trade delegation which visited Washington Feb. 14 for
the 10th session of the Joint American-Polish Trade Commission _
the first such meeting since 1981 _ went home with friendly words
instead of dollars.
   One deal under discussion is the purchase or rental by Poland's
state-owned Lot airlines of two or three jets from Boeing Corp. The
planes would fly between U.S. cities and Warsaw, and money from
tickets sold in the United States would pay for the planes, say
Polish officials.
   There are geopolitical overtones in Poland's latest turn toward
the West. Lot grounded its fleet of eight Soviet-made Ilyushin 62
jets, the best Moscow has to offer, after one crashed last May near
Warsaw, killing all 183 people aboard.
   A government commission blamed a faulty roller bearing for the
crash, Poland's worst, and the weekly Przeglad Tygodniowy recently
complained that the IL-62 is more costly to operate, and requires
more maintenance, than other jetliners.
   Kinast said that Poland, like other Soviet bloc countries, is
seeking joint ventures with the West, and may be willing to waive
previous requirements, allowing private Polish firms to take part,
allowing the Western firm to own more than half the joint venture,
and relaxing rules and taking hard currency out of Poland.
   Poland is seeking Western help in the agricultural sector, as
well. On Feb. 20, the The Foundation for the Development of Polish
Agriculture, created with the help of the Rockefeller Brothers'
Fund, was opening up a $2.4 million-line of credit for private
farmers in Poland to stimulate the export of hams.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs Thurs March 17 and thereafter</NOTE>
