<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday March 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Full Employment' and Inflation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans are accustomed to hearing Federal
Reserve chiefs discourse on the threat of inflation, but some might
have been mystified by Alan Greenspan's reference to it this week.
   Greenspan told Congress that a further decline in the jobless
rate, now 5.7 percent, might produce upward pressure on wages _
and, since wages are a large constituent of prices, the probability
of inflation.
   How can that be, many Americans are asking?
   How can there be a worker shortage when 7 million members of the
labor force are without jobs? How can there be a labor shortage
when the jobless rate is so much above the old 4 percent ``full
employment'' standard?
   And how can inflation, which is usually associated with a
boiling economy, be a threat at a time when expansion is so
sluggish at times it takes the most sophisticated statistical
measures to catch any movement at all?
   Greenspan's reference to the subject is bound to be passed off
by some as a mere requirement of the office, a ritual expression
that is now expected of a Fed chairman, since his predecessor had
made it the No. 1 enemy.
   But there is more to it than that.
   The most significant ``more'' involves a better understanding of
market forces than existed back in the 1960s, when it was generally
believed that unemployment could drop to 4 percent before inflation
flared.
   Experience taught otherwise, as witness the decade of inflation
that followed in the 1970s.
   The second ``more'' involves the makeup of the labor force.
   In the 1960s, the economy had lots of younger workers to fill
the beginning jobs. In the 1980s there are fewer labor-force
entrants. And Congress is considering sharp increases in the
minimum wage.
   Stated differently, most of those who are available to take jobs
today are older and more experienced and thus come at higher
prices. You don't need a decline to 4 percent before worrying about
inflation. You worry at 5 percent.
   In truth, there is no certainty among economists on the point at
which a falling jobless rate becomes inflationary. Clearly, they
were wrong in putting it at 4 percent in the 1960s, because
double-digit inflation ensued.
   It can be argued, therefore, that it is merely wisdom and
responsibility that causes a Fed chief always to be vigilant, and
for him to act on the theory it is wiser to ward off inflation than
to treat the infection later.
   Greenspan told Congress that in his opinion the country is
getting close to the point at which inflation could be ignited.
   ``Certainly it's less than a percentage point,'' he said, adding
that it was his impression that the flare point was ``closer to a
half, and maybe somewhat less than that.''
   Is he premature in his concern?
   Hardly, if you consider that the last big bout of inflation was
one of the worst and longest the country has ever experienced, and
that it took a harsh recession to defeat it.
   Consider also that a case of inflation in the range of 6 percent
_ mild, when compared with the double-digit disasters of the 1970s
_ can cut in half the value of everyone's money in a dozen years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday March 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
