<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-BlacksandPoverty Adv20-2Takes   03-16 0958</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blacks and Poverty, Adv 20-2 Takes,0982</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>King's Old Neighborhood: `He'd Know We've Stepped Backward'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Name `Loic Wacquant' in 11th graf cq.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years after a sniper's bullet felled Martin Luther King
Jr., his dream of equality and prosperity for American blacks still
shines like a beacon. Despite some remarkable progress, however,
for too many it remains only a dream. The first story of three in a
series that assesses black progress in economics, politics and
social influence looks at a poor West Side Chicago neighborhood
where King lived in 1966 to wage war on slums and poverty.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``This is truly an island of poverty in the midst of an ocean of
plenty.''
   _ Martin Luther King Jr. in his 1967 book, ``Where Do We Go From
Here: Chaos Or Community?''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bonnet Hampton knows what it's like to huddle in
bed with a baseball bat at hand, wondering how to protect her
babies from rats scurrying across the rotting wooden floor of her
tenement flat.
   She knows how to sidestep young men strung out on drugs huddled
in dingy hallways, and she's no longer shocked by dead bodies _
even at her doorstep.
   ``You don't get used to it,'' she said, ``but it's not a
nightmare. If you see someone get shot or stabbed today _ usually
you'd be nervous for days. It's not like that. ... It's just
another one. You don't lose any rest over that.''
   Hampton lives in North Lawndale. A generation ago, Martin Luther
King Jr. lived here in a four-room flat. King had come north to
wage war on poverty and inequality, but 20 years after his death,
the slums and disparity remain. So do dreams of a better life.
   This poor black community he adopted has become even poorer _
and that, say those who knew him, would grieve King if he were
alive today.
   ``If King were to look at Lawndale ... he'd think that his worst
nightmare had come true,'' said Gary Orfield, a University of
Chicago political science professor who did volunteer work with
King.
   Some residents reluctantly agree.
   ``I think he was great enough to know and powerful enough to
know his dream is not being fulfilled,'' said Cleodia Dawkins
O'Quinn, who welcomed King to her home. ``He would know we have
stepped backward.''
   Black poverty is a bleak fact of life. Nearly one in three
blacks _ 31.1 percent _ lived below the poverty line in 1986,
compared with 11 percent of whites, according to federal statistics.
   And 20 years after the Kerner Commission examined inner-city
problems following the mid '60s riots and warned the United States
was moving toward two societies, ``one black, one white _ separate
and unequal,'' the gap remains.
   Life for inner-city blacks has worsened, scholars said in a
follow-up study this year, partly because of industrial decline.
Over 35 years, Rust Belt cities have lost almost half their
manufacturing force, according to a report by the University of
Chicago's William Julius Wilson and Loic Wacquant.
   Chicago, the report said, lost half its manufacturing
blue-collar workers from 1967-82. And that's taken its toll on
North Lawndale. The neighborhood's misery index is high. According
to federal, city and state records:
   _ Four of ten people lived in poverty in 1980, an increase of a
third over a decade earlier.
   _ More than a third of the housing is uninhabitable or so
deteriorated it's beyond rehabilitation.
   _ Eight of 10 children are born out of wedlock. The 1986 infant
mortality rate, 27.2 per 1,000 live births, was more than 2{ times
the U.S. average.
   _ Women headed 61 percent of the households in 1980.
   _ One in five people was out of work in 1980. Unemployment, some
activists say, may now be as high as 30 percent.
   Much of North Lawndale has simply vanished. Since 1960, more
than half the residents, thousands of jobs and most industries have
fled. Gangs are more vicious, drugs more common.
   Still, optimists remain, proud, hard-working folks fighting to
turn things around. ``We have been at the lowest of low,'' said
Jesse Miller, head of the Lawndale Peoples Planning and Action
Conference, an activist group. ``The citizens of this community are
facing up to the problems.''
   But reversing those fortunes is a formidable task. North
Lawndale has block after block of weed-filled lots, gutted
buildings and men in their prime who while away their days
loitering on street corners or huddled around fires in garbage cans.
   ``You can't envision how it looked before,'' Mrs. O'Quinn said,
shaking her head sadly. ``It's a wilderness now.''
   Once a largely Jewish community with gray stone houses, stores,
factories and banks, North Lawndale turned from white to mostly
black in the 1950s. Absentee landlords and political neglect had
contributed to its decline by 1966 when King moved into a
$90-a-month, third-floor flat, with inadequate heat and halls
reeking of urine.
   ``You can't really get close to the poor without living and
being here with them,'' he said. King lived in the building, since
torn down, on and off for several months that year.
   King tried to fight slumlords, build tenant unions, end
discrimination. He led open-housing marches in all-white
neighborhoods and tried to be peacemaker when riots flared in the
summer of 1966.
   King, folks say, brought hope to North Lawndale. His
assassination brought destruction. Riots that tore apart U.S.
cities after King's death in 1968 unleashed a storm of rage here as
well _ the skies were ablaze, the streets filled with looters,
blocks of businesses turned to rubble, houses to ashes and dreams
to despair.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1444EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-BlacksandPoverty Adv20-1stAdd   03-16 0901</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blacks and Poverty, Adv 20-1st Add,0926</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>CHICAGO: to despair.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``The riots killed or ... almost mortally wounded the hope of
the community,'' said Primus Mootry, executive vice president of
the local Better Boys Foundation.
   ``There was no Marshall plan for this war-torn community. It was
as if someone decided to let them sit there in the mess that they
made and let them stew,'' he said. ``The consequences have been
devastating. The community has been damned from the outside.''
   Today, North Lawndale has 61,000 residents, less than half the
population of almost 125,000 in 1965. Much of the middle-class has
fled.
   ``If I had somewhere to go, I would have run, too,'' said
33-year resident Mildred Hunter.
   Tens of thousands of jobs also disappeared. Seventy-five percent
of businesses were lost from 1960 to 1970. International Harvester
Co. (now Navistar) closed a plant. Sears Roebuck & Co. later moved
its world headquarters out of North Lawndale, keeping only a
distribution and planning center.
   The main shopping strip, Roosevelt Road, remains a burned-out
shell. A proposal by a national organization of planners, builders,
bankers and others to build a $9.5 million shopping mall has been
postponed.
   After 25 years of ``uninterrupted decline, North Lawndale
resembles a war zone,'' Wilson and Wacquant said in their study.
   Today, the neighborhood has some food and liquor stores. To buy
anything else, ``you have to go an area you're not wanted to spend
your money,'' said Isabelle Burrell. ``It's insulting.''
   Shopping, however, seems like a minor problem against the drug
dealing, gangs and violence.
   Hampton, for example, a 30-year-old with three teen-agers and a
baby, has survived four apartments and 14 years of horror stories:
she's fended off giant rats slurping out of her toilet, been forced
out by an arsonist, witnessed a robbery, faced drug users shooting
up in the hallway and seen murder victims, including a decapitated
man.
   ``I've seen a lot of disaster,'' she said, adding that she
carries a knife by day, a gun at night. ``We have a lot of lunatics
out here.''
   Hampton talks about returning to her native Mississippi. In the
meantime, she attends church with her children, visits their
schools and preaches against drugs.
   ``They understand it,'' she said. ``They have seen it.''
   Others have, too. Residents can rattle off the corners where
drugs are sold like newspapers, customers pulling up in cars day
and night.
   ``The only game left is the drug game,'' said Leon Farley, an
unemployed counselor. ``To survive, to eat, to pay the rent. We
don't have a lot of jobs.''
   Drug trafficking wasn't always a problem, and the gangs of
decades past directed their violence at each other.
   ``They didn't bother those of us doing good things,'' said Mrs.
O'Quinn, who with her husband runs a drum and bugle corps for
youths. `The gangs don't respect anything now.''
   Mootry confirmed gangs are more lethal: zip guns, knives and
chains have been replaced by Uzi submachine guns and other
sophisticated weapons.
   Yet the biggest problem, he said, may be a perception among
youths that North Lawndale is ``an island ... a walled city (where)
nothing comes in and nothing comes out. That is the way in which
they are socialized. That's a great tragedy.''
   Mootry's organization tries to broaden horizons, offering
recreational and education programs, including scholarships that
have sent teens to Harvard and the University of Chicago. Block
clubs, slum-busting projects and infant health programs also have
been started.
   ``Because people live in the ghetto, you don't got to be dealing
in dope, be a prostitute or on public aid,'' said Hunter, the
long-time North Lawndale resident. ``You can live anywhere and be
what you want to be.''
   Some businesses have stayed afloat, too. The Community Bank of
Lawndale, which opened in 1977 with $2 million in assets, now has
$25 million.
   But Jim Hadley, senior vice president, said investors still
question the neighborhood's viability, despite its prime location
and good transportation.
   A main reason is housing shortages. Only 727 units have been
built since 1969, city officials say. Some federally subsidized
housing has been built and almost $7 million has been spent to
improve 5,000 units since 1983, they add.
   ``As long as you don't have any housing, you're not going to
have desirable residents,'' said resident Edward Manning. ``This
community is not going to be the way you'd like it to be anytime
soon.''
   Manning and others say a comeback depends on folks flexing
political muscle. For years, ``we didn't demand nothing and we
didn't get anything,'' he said.
   That, many say, changed with the 1983 election of Harold
Washington, the city's first black mayor who died last year and is
regarded in the same revered tones as King.
   Miller, who last Tuesday defeated the incumbent for the
Democratic ward committeeman post, says North Lawndale's problems
may be the same as they were a generation ago, except for one
difference: ``The political maturity is there now.''
   ``Lawndale was and is a very poor community,'' he said. If King
were alive, ``I think he'd be proud of the attitude of the
residents. There's still hope. There are still efforts ... to bring
Lawndale into the 20th century. I think we're very close.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sharon Cohen is the AP Midwest regional
reporter, based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
