<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Blacks-SCLC Adv20   03-16 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Blacks-SCLC, Adv 20,0861</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>SCLC Still Works to Meet the Needs, Complaints of the Poor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Blacks and Poverty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ritual of the poor is conducted almost every
day at the Southern Christian Leadership Conference's headquarters
here.
   They walk in and sit quietly on battered chairs, their eyes
scanning walls lined with photographs of Martin Luther King Jr.
marching along Alabama roads.
   They wait, sometimes for hours, hoping for help to find a job, a
home or a lost welfare check.
   ``They helped my sister last year when her lights was off, so I
was thinking they would help me find another place to stay _ you
know, a cheaper one,'' said Betty Mitchell, who works at a
fast-food restaurant and was waiting at the SCLC offices last week.
   But trying to meet such demands strains the financially strapped
organization and its skeleton crew, which struggles both to treat
the symptoms of poverty and find a cure for the disease.
   ``Oh, Lord, we get more requests than we can handle,'' said the
Rev. Joseph Lowery, SCLC president. ``We do what we can, but we
just don't have the staff to respond to all the cases.''
   The poor bring complaints about everything from police brutality
to housing and hiring practices, Lowery said.
   ``The major incidents, for example, are the violence of
minimum-wage jobs, or no jobs at all,'' Lowery said. ``The violence
of homelessness. The violence of being the last hired and first
fired.
   ``Most poor people are working; they simply don't earn enough to
get out of poverty.''
   The SCLC has tied itself to the needs of the needy since 1957,
when it was founded by King, Lowery and the Revs. Ralph Abernathy
and Fred Shuttlesworth to expand the non-violent movement against
legal segregation. Its eventual victory over discriminatory laws
earned the SCLC a reputation of militancy that holds to this day.
   ``We are the activist arm of the movement. When you do that, you
step on toes and you don't become the most popular kid on the
block,'' Lowery said. ``We know it's not as popular to give us
support as it is some other groups that are not as controversial.''
   The nation heard from the SCLC frequently last year as it spoke
out on issues it felt could jeopardize human rights. It organized
marches in virtually all-white Forsyth County, Ga.; helped
establish a biracial committee on race relations there; opposed
Judge Robert Bork's nomination to the U.S. Supreme Court; condemned
statements about blacks in sports made by Al Campanis and Jimmy
``The Greek'' Snyder, and negotiated with major league groups to
move blacks into upper management.
   ``We still believe in the efficacy of conscience-working and
consciousness-raising and, if necessary, civil disobedience,''
Lowery said. ``We're going to have to continue to have advocacy
groups to keep pressure on _ creative, non-violent pressure. We
have to keep that alive.''
   The group, which lacks solid corporate support, operates from a
dingy brownstone in Atlanta's historic Auburn Avenue district. The
building has changed little since it was first occupied in 1962.
   ``This is Martin's desk,'' Lowery said, running his hand over
the cluttered, chipped wooden desk in his office. ``We have not put
thick carpets on the floor or lined the walls and ceilings with
chandeliers because that's not where our priorities are.''
   On April 4, the 20th anniversary of King's assassination, the
group will kick off its 1988 Poor People's Crusade with hearings on
homelessness and unemployment. It will also hold rallies, starting
in Memphis, Tenn., then sweeping through Alabama, Georgia and
Mississippi.
   The SCLC was ready to start a similar campaign when King was
gunned down at a Memphis hotel in 1968. Days later, SCLC members
dried their tears and marched on Washington, D.C., carrying
thousands of the nation's poor with them to dramatize poverty.
   This time around, the SCLC wants more than a display of what's
gone wrong with efforts to wipe out poverty, Lowery said.
   ``The crusade is trying to get poverty on the national agenda,''
Lowery said. ``Whoever comes into office (as president), we want
them to have a commitment to eliminating poverty and look at it as
the urgent, critical problem that it is.''
   Lowery said he hopes the campaign will change the recent
tendency to celebrate the national King holiday in January with
glitzy, ceremonial events that ignore the issues that dominated
King's life.
   ``We're beginning to honor Martin as a orator, as a dreamer, but
we're not honoring the message,'' Lowery said, glancing at a large
photograph of him talking with King in a church pulpit.
   ``You've got people now who are paying honor to him on that
holiday who are not doing anything about helping the poor or
working for economic justice.
   ``They say, `Dr. King this, Dr. King that,' then they don't
register to vote, they don't join a boycott, they don't work for
peace and human dignity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
