<DATELINE>ROCHESTER HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. will try to meet
its foreign competition by trimming executive-suite jobs and
stepping up teamwork on the plant floor, according to a Chrysler
vice president.
   By year's end, the nation's No. 3 automaker will begin cutting
its eight-level organizational chart to a six-tier plan similar to
Japanese auto company structures, Anthony St. John, vice president
of human resources and Chrysler's chief labor negotiator, said
Tuesday.
   The company also plans a new dispute-resolution system for
management employees in addition to opening early negotiations with
the United Auto Workers union on a contract for some 60,000 union
employees.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp., AT&T and NCR Corp. have unveiled
computers and IBM said it was making a version of the popular Unix
operating system available on its largest mainframes.
   The announcement Tuesday by International Business Machines
Corp. was another acknowledgment of the growing popularity of Unix,
a kind of internal traffic cop for computers that was invented by
American Telephone & Telegraph Co.
   Unisys announced additions to its 1100 family of mainframe
computers. NCR introduced the System 10000, which it called a
family of mid-range, multi-user computers.
</TEXT>
