   Eli Lilly & Co. has rejected a demand by
British lawmakers that the pharmaceutical giant set up a trust fund
for victims of a discontinued anti-arthritis medication.
   The demand rejected Tuesday was made Monday by 100 British
lawmakers who signed a letter to Richard D. Wood, Lilly chairman
and chief executive officer.
   Hundreds of former users of the anti-arthritis drug Oraflex,
sold in Britain under the name Opren, sued Lilly in the mid-1980s,
claiming that the drug caused severe side effects, including liver
and kidney disorders. The drug also was linked to several deaths.
