<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     03-16 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rebound Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices have rebounded slightly, although
analysts say trading remains cautious and light.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for April
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, rose
9 cents to settle at $15.68 per barrel Tuesday.
   The contract fell 70 cents Monday in response to reports that
Saudi Arabia, the largest producer in the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, had rejected calls for new restrictions on
crude production.
   WTI rose above $16 late last week after OPEC members called for
a meeting of the cartel's pricing committee to stabilize market
prices. Officials of non-OPEC producers also met to discuss similar
concerns.
   Analysts said they didn't know what to make of Tuesday's
rebound. Prices began lower but moved higher later in the session.
   ``I think that what you're seeing here is a reassessment of the
market,'' said Peter Beutel, assistant director of Elders Futures
Inc. ``I'm not saying that means it's a positive reassessment.
There's a lot of uncertainty right now in the market.''
   Wholesale gasoline for April delivery, down 1.23 cents on
Monday, rose 0.02 cent to 44.38 cents per gallon on Tuesday.
Wholesale heating oil gained 0.13 cent to 43.47 cents per gallon,
after falling 1.35 cents in the previous session.
</TEXT>
