<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0147EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Federated Bjt   03-16 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated, Bjt,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shareholders Take Their Time in Deciding Between Campeau and Macy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc. shareholders
apparently are not rushing to decide between the competing tender
offers of R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. and Campeau Corp.
   Campeau announced Tuesday that 2.4 million Federated shares had
been tendered to the Toronto-based developer but not withdrawn by
the close of business on Monday.
   Campeau's offer of $75 cash per share for 70.5 million Federated
shares was to expire at midnight EST Friday, although a federal
judge has extended that deadline into next week.
   Macy, whose $77.35 a share offer for 70.43 million Federated
shares expires April 4, declined to announce how many shares it had
received. Maureen Milano, a spokeswoman for the retailer, said
figures usually are not announced until after an offer's expiration.
   Federated stock fell 50 cents to $65.50 a share in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading on Tuesday.
   The number of shares tendered to Campeau, which represents less
than 4 percent of the company's goal, indicates shareholders might
be waiting to see what will happen next in the battle for Federated.
   The focus of attention was federal court in Manhattan, where
U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand was considering the validity of
Federated's ``poison pill'' shareholders rights plan and the
expiration date of the Campeau bid.
   During a hearing late Monday, Macy asked Sand to delay
expiration of Campeau's offer by 20 days to lessen the pressure on
Federated shareholders to accept the hostile bid.
   Macy contended the Campeau offer, which was amended from an
earlier proposal, actually was a new offer and under federal law
would have to remain open past its planned Friday expiration.
   Sand was seeking an opinion from the Securities and Exchange
Commission on the Macy argument and said he would not rule before
today.
   Sand also was considering Campeau's challenge to the poison
pill, which Federated's board approved in January before Campeau
made its hostile bid and after developer Donald Trump indicated
interest in the nation's fifth-largest retailer.
   The plan allows current Federated shareholders to buy more of
the company's stock at a steep discount during a hostile takeover,
making a takeover prohibitively expensive.
   Campeau says its bid cannot proceed while the poison pill is in
effect.
   Sand said both buyout offers would have to remain open at least
three business days after he ruled on the poison pill, meaning
Campeau's offer must now remain open into next week.
   On Monday, Macy sweetened its merger agreement with Federated by
$200 million in cash to a total of $6.3 billion. Macy is offering
$77.35 a share in cash for 70.43 million Federated shares, up from
its original $74.50 per share. Macy will exchange shares in the
merged company and issue convertible debt securities for the
remainder of Federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares.
   Campeau is offering $75 in cash per share for 70.5 million
Federated shares. The remaining of Federated stock would be
acquired later for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger,
giving the deal an aggregate value of $68 per share or a total of
$6.18 billion.
   On Tuesday, Federated announced its fourth-quarter earnings.
   The company said its net income rose nearly 10 percent to
$176.97 million, or $2 per share, up from $1.71.3 million, or $1.82
per share, in the same period a year earlier.
   Sales for the quarter, which ended Jan. 31, totaled $3.55
billion, up from $3.44 billion.
   For all of fiscal 1987, Federated said it earned $313 million,
or $3.40 per share, up 14 percent from $287.6 million, or $2.97 per
share, in 1986.
   Sales for the year rose to $11.12 billion frtom $10.51 billion.
</TEXT>
