<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MortgageDelinquencies     03-16 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mortgage Delinquencies,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lenders Report Number Of Mortgage Delinquencies Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Late mortgage payments and mortgage
foreclosures increased in the last quarter of 1987, with delinquent
payments rising for the first time in two years, according to the
Mortgage Bankers Association.
   The lenders trade group reported Tuesday that the number of
homeowners who were at least 30 days late in making a mortgage
payment edged up to 4.99 percent of the 10 million mortgages
surveyed in the fourth quarter.
   This compared to 4.63 percent in the July-September quarter,
which had been the lowest level in more than eight years.
   Warren Lasko, executive vice president of the association,
called the increase ``disappointing but not disheartening,'' noting
that the increase reflected continued weakness in depressed areas
of the country such as the oil-producing states of the Southwest.
   Foreclosures also rose to 0.27 percent of mortgages, up from
0.25 percent in the third quarter, with much of the increase coming
in the Midwest and the South.
   The increase in late mortgage payments was the first rise since
the fourth quarter of 1985, when the delinquency rate climbed to
5.75 percent.
   Even with the increase late last year, all regions of the
country reported lower deliquency rates when compared to a year
earlier.
   The West had the fewest delinquent mortgages in the final three
months of last year at 4.6 percent, followed by the Northeast at
4.76 percent and the North Central states at 5.96 percent. The
South had the highest delinquency rate in the fourth quarter with
6.07 percent of mortgage-holders at least 30 days late with a
payment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
