<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0150EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FirstCity Bjt   03-16 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-First City, Bjt,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First City Grants Second Extension To Debt Holders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First City Bancorporation of Texas Inc. again has
extended its deadline to dissident debt holders who have been asked
to redeem their securities at a discount under a federal bailout
plan for the institution.
   Only about 51 percent of the holders of First City notes
totaling $225.9 million had tendered their securities as of lare
Tuesday afternoon.
   Texas' fourth-largest bank holding company had sought 90 percent
of those securities, which were to be redeemed at less than face
value as part of a buyout plan contained in a $1.5 billion bailout
led by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   If completed, it would be the second-biggest U.S. bank rescue
ever.
   The low response prompted First City to extend Tuesday's 5 p.m.
EST deadline to March 29. It was the second extension given by the
Houston-based company _ the first being last week after only 41.4
percent, or $93.6 million, of the notes had been redeemed for cash.
   Chicago investor A. Robert Abboud, who would become chairman of
First City under the bailout plan, said actions were being taken to
complete the transaction by alternate means but did not elaborate.
   Under a buyout plan that was made a condition of the federal
bailout, holders of First City's debt securities wre offered from
35 cents to 45 cents on the dollar for their notes.
   Abboud, who said debt holders would fare worse if the bank were
liquidated, told federal regulators in Washington last weekend that
not enough of the note holders had agreed to sell at those prices.
He also has contended there was no intention to raise the amount of
the offer.
   However, some industry analysts have indicated that some debt
holders who don't tender their notes might end up getting a better
deal once First City is recapitalized. Depending on the strength of
the recapitalized institution, the bonds could trade at
significantly higher prices than Abboud is offering.
   Still other analysts have said the FDIC could refuse to raise
the offer for fear of setting a precedent for future bank bailouts.
   Some of the alternatives being discussed for First City included
dropping the participation threshold below 90 percent or
terminating the tender offer.
   Other options available to the FDIC, analysts said, include
canceling the Abboud deal and reopening bidding for the bank, or
having the FDIC itself take over First City. The FDIC did just that
in 1984, pumping $4.5 billion into Continental Illinois Bank and
Trust of Chicago during the largest U.S. bank bailout ever.
   Another plan calls for First City's 59 banks in Texas and one in
South Dakota to fail and merge into a ``bridge bank'' until a new
buyer is found. Still another option is for the holding company,
with $11 billion in assets, to enter voluntary bankruptcy
proceedings.
   First City grew quickly during the Texas oil boom, but was
hammered by energy and real estate losses when oil prices
plummeted. For 1987, the company posted a $1.1 billion loss.
   The bailout plan calls for $970 million in federal assistance, a
$500 million infusion of capital raised privately by an investor
group headed by Abboud and a spinoff of $1.79 billion in book value
of poorly performing assets.
   On March 4, more than 71 percent of the bank holding company's
37 million shareholders approved the controversial bailout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0151EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Germany-Airbus     03-16 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Airbus,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airbus Subsidy Battle Heating Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, angry over European
subsidies for the Airbus aircraft-manufacturing consortium, is
increasing pressure on Airbus nations to abolish or at least reduce
the payments, say diplomatic sources.
   ``The Americans at a minimum want the Europeans to give a signal
that they are willing to accept some effective discipline in regard
to subsidies,'' an informed diplomatic source, who asked not to be
identified further, said Tuesday.
   The United States estimates that the four countries involved in
Airbus Industrie _ France, Britain, West Germany and Spain _ have
pumped $10 billion into the consortium since it was created 17
years ago.
   Ministers of the four Airbus countries are to meet with U.S.
trade officials in the southern West German resort city of
Constance on Friday to continue discussions on the dispute.
   Willy de Clercq, the European Economic Community's external
relations commissioner, said last week that there was a ``realistic
chance'' of settling the dispute, but said EEC governments could
not entirely renounce state aid payments to Airbus.
   He predicted an agreement would require ``further rounds of very
difficult negotiations.''
   The United States maintains that subsidies to Airbus are unfair
to U.S. aircraft makers in the wide-body, long-haul passenger jet
market.
   The Airbus nations contend the subsidies do not distort trade
and are allowed under the civil aircraft provisions of the General
Agreements on Tariffs and Trade.
   The EEC also contends U.S. aircraft manufacturers long have
enjoyed huge, indirect subsidies through military contracts from
the Pentagon and millions in government research grants.
   The United States has threatened to retaliate against Airbus if
the negotiations fail, despite a recent decision by the four Airbus
ministers to have Airbus managers enter into direct negotiations
with McDonnell Douglas Corp. on a possible joint project.
   The aim of the talks is to see whether the two sides could
collaborate on one or more new airplanes. Under the prosposal, the
new aircraft would not compete with existing models.
   But diplomatic sources told The Associated Press that the move
was unlikely to reduce tensions over the subsidy issue.
   ``It may well be helpful for Airbus and McDonnell Douglas to
agree on a joint project, but that will not solve the core problem
of the current subsidies,'' said another diplomatic source, who
also declined to be identified further.
   A spokesman for U.S. trade representative Clayton Yeutter in
Washington declined comment on the upcoming meeting. Yeutter is
expected to attend the talks.
</TEXT>
