<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FirstRepublicBank Bjt   03-16 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-First RepublicBank, Bjt,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giant Texas Bank Holding Company Seeking Federal Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First RepublicBank Corp.'s attempt to seek federal
assistance comes as the nation's 13th-largest banking company tries
to bolster the waning confidence of its depositors and the
financial markets.
   First RepublicBank indicated Tuesday it was seeking federal aid
to keep from failing, and had held preliminary discussions with the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   ``We seek some assistance, yet to be defined. We will be putting
together, over the next few weeks, a plan that we can submit to the
FDIC for assistance,'' said Gerald W. Fronterhouse, chairman and
chief executive officer.
   ``It was important that we initiate those discussions in order
to provide a more stable environment for our company,'' he said.
   Shaken by the slumping real estate and energy sectors and a loss
of confidence in the institution by Wall Street, First RepublicBank
suffered a loss of about $600 million in deposits over a five-day
period last month, prompting the decision to seek federal help.
   ``Certainly two or three weeks ago we didn't believe this would
be necessary,'' said Joseph C. Bowles, a spokesman for the company.
   First RepublicBank officials tried last month to combat rumors
that the bank was considering merging with another financial
institution, taking the unusual step of buying full-page newspaper
ads to assure customers their deposits were safe.
   Bowles said he didn't believe the latest development would lead
more depositors to withdraw their money because ``we expect our
customers will understand that their money is protected.''
   First RepublicBank is discussing whether to pursue open-bank
assistance from the FDIC, generally used only if the agency finds
keeping a bank open would be less costly to the government than
letting it fail.
   An FDIC bailout of that kind would require regulators to
determine that the bank would fail without help.
   Disclosure of the talks with the government _ and the company's
suspension of payment of preferred stock dividends _ were greeted
with pessimism by Wall Street.
   First RepublicBank's stock fell 25 cents to $1.50 a share
Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange _ a 14.3 percent drop.
   Furthermore, Standard & Poor's Corp. downgraded First
RepublicBank's senior debt rating to its lowest level short of
default. The Wall Street credit rating form also downgraded the
bank holding company's certificate of deposit and commercial paper
ratings.
   Fronterhouse contended the company would continue to thrive and
remain an important institution in the state for years.
   But financial analysts said the request for federal aid could
foretell a buyout or merger for First RepublicBank, which was
created by the merger of Dallas rivals InterFirst Corp. and
RepublicBank Corp. in 1987.
   ``The real estate market turned down, I think, much more rapidly
than the bank had thought and it just turned into a snowball
effect,'' said Frank Anderson, a Dallas independent bank
consultant. ``And they got into a situation where news was being
leaked from meetings of some of their top-level officials to
various news media.
   ``And whereas that did not cause the problem, it surely
exacerbated the problem,'' said Anderson.
   First RepublicBank lost $656 million in 1987, mainly because a
staggering 17 percent of its $15 billion loan portfolio was either
past due or renegotiated.
   Reports indicate the holding company stands to lose another $450
million this year. The company has 73 affiliate banks in Texas and
assets of $33.2 billion, and employs 15,188 people.
   Separately, Houston-based First City Bancorporation of Texas
Inc. extended a Tuesday deadline for debt holders to redeem their
securities at a discount under a rescue plan representing the
second-largest bank bailout in U.S. history.
   First City granted a second extension, to 5 p.m. EST March 29,
after the required 90 percent of debt holders failed to tender
their the securities.
   Some industry analysts contended that First RepublicBank's
decision to seek federal aid could help Texas banking.
   ``It should lend further stability to the banking system in the
state,'' said Sandy Flannigan, an analyst and vice president of
PaineWebber Inc. ``There has been a great deal of negative press,
and the fact that they are seeking some kind of FDIC assistance
should create some additional confidence in the system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
