<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ManufacturersHanover     03-16 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Manufacturers Hanover,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manufacturers Hanover President In Suprise Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John R. Torrell III's surprise resignation as
president of Manufacturers Hanover Corp. comes as the bank holding
company is on the verge of an expected rebound from recent
financial setbacks.
   Torell resigned ``at his initiative'' to pursue other business
opportunities, according to spokesman John Stefans. The resignation
is effective at the end of this month.
   ``The board accepted it with deepest regret,'' Stefans said.
   Recent speculation on Wall Street about a possible management
shakeup at the bank had focused not on Torell but on John F.
McGillicuddy, Manufacturers Hanover's chairman and chief executive,
according to analysts.
   In his most recent position, Torell was the company's No. 2
executive behind McGillicuddy and widely was considered his heir
apparent.
   Analysts have said Torell played a key role in helping the
banking company emerge from its recent earnings problems and was
largely responsible for developing its successful consumer finance
business.
   In its annual report released earlier this month, Manufacturers
Hanover said it expected a profit of at least $807 million this
year. Like other big money-center banks, Manufacturers Hanover
established a huge loan-loss reserve to cover shaky foreign debts
in 1987, which was largely responsible for a $1.14 billion loss
that year.
   Torell, 48, said in a news release from the bank that after a
27-year career at Manufacturers Hanover, including 10 years as a
director, ``it is time for a change.''
   Torell joined the bank fresh from graduation from Princeton
University. He became vice chairman in 1978, president of the bank
in 1982 and president of the holding company in 1985, Stefans said.
   Manufacturers Hanover is the nation's sixth largest bank holding
company with assets totaling $73.3 billion.
   A search committee of the board will be convened to choose a
successor for Torell. Candidates from inside and outside the
institution will be considered, according to McGillicuddy.
</TEXT>
