<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Citibank-Students Bjt   03-16 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Citibank-Students, Bjt,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citibank Accused of Denying Credit to Humanities Majors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citibank says it is retreating from a
policy that denied credit cards to some university students because
they majored in humanities, after receiving complaints from around
the country.
   In the latest fallout from the policy, students at the
University of California who said they were denied cards because of
their humanities majors called for the bank to change the policy or
get its representatives off campus.
   ``It doesn't take people from college to see that their
reasoning that a humanities major is more of a financial risk than
an engineering major is pretty weak,'' said student Kennedy Yip, 22.
   Yip _ a rhetoric major _ received a Visa last year while
attending a different college as a mathematics major. Yip's
rejection letter for a Citibank MasterCard dated Feb. 13 listed
``field of study'' as the cause.
   Other liberal arts majors who say Citibank rejected their credit
applications include some studying Italian and history.
   Bill McGuire, a Citibank spokesman in New York, said the bank
was ``moving away'' from the policy, which would be discontinued by
the end of June. He admitted the company had received complaints
from students at other universities around the country but he would
not identify the schools.
   McGuire, in an interview Tuesday with the Oakland Tribune, would
not describe how the policy was applied.
   Some students with humanities majors at Berkeley reported they
had received Citibank credit cards.
   Furthermore, a spokesman for the U.S. Comptroller of the
Currency in Kansas City, Mo. said Tuesday that the Equal Credit
Opportunity Act does not prohibit using a student's academic major
in a credit application system.
   Nevertheless, some of the students turned down for credit at
Berkeley are seeking to have Citibank denied access to the campus,
where its representatives set up tables around the student union to
accept credit applications.
   The humanities policy surfaced last week when Irene Chang, a
reporter for the independent campus newspaper, The Daily
Californian, asked a campus bank-card canvasser how to apply.
   ``I told her I had heard a rumor that English majors were being
turned down, and she said I should give her a student photo
identification instead of my registration card, which lists my
major,'' Chang said Tuesday in an interview.
   ``She then told me to fill in the application by putting in
business administration or electrical engineering as my major,
instead of English, which she said was what students (at another
university) were doing,'' Chang said.
   Matt Denn, Berkeley student body president, said he doesn't want
to threaten Citibank but believes student government's right to
regulate groups at the student union building gives him ``leverage
to suggest a policy change.''
   Molly Sorkin, 22, an art history major rejected last fall for a
Visa from Citibank because of her major, says she supports punitive
action against Citibank.
   ``It's obvious discrimination, and I don't think they should be
allowed to get away with thinking that some majors are the ones
that are going to be making all the money,'' she said.
   ``What I study says nothing about my responsibility or whether
or not I can pay my bills,'' said Sorkin, who graduated in December
and now works in retail sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
