<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tokyo's leading stock index surged today to its
highest level since last October's crash, while the U.S. dollar
rose slightly as traders awaited the release of U.S. trade deficit
figures for January.
   The dollar closed at 127.49 yen, up 0.24 yen from Tuesday's
close. It opened at 127.38, and ranged between 127.32 yen and
127.55 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which climbed 42.16 points Tuesday, closed today
at 25,704.43 points, up 228.76 points, or 0.90 percent.
   Today's closing was the highest since stock prices plunged in
October. The previous post-crash high was 25,682.82 points, on
March 2.
   Volume in the first section was estimated at 1.6 billion shares,
roughly the same as Tuesday, but 1.1 billion shares changed hands
during the morning session alone in what traders were calling
exceptionally heavy trading.
   Heavy industrials, steel and electronics were leading the surge,
said one broker.
   Investors were spurred by U.S. payments data for the final
quarter of 1987 showing the invisible trade balance in the black,
one analyst said.
   In the foreign exchange market, traders continued their attitude
of wait and see.
   ``The yen is easing against the dollar ... but everyone is
waiting for the latest U.S. trade data,'' said an exchange dealer
at a major commercial bank in Tokyo.
   The U.S. Commerce Department is scheduled to release the
nation's foreign trade figures for January on Thursday.
