<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Reagan-CivilRights Bjt   03-16 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Civil Rights, Bjt,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Set to Veto Civil Rights Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: time of action uncertain, but top likely before noon EST;
also moved on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan was poised today to veto a
major piece of civil rights legislation and call for an alternative
giving corporations and religious schools more exemptions from
anti-discrimination laws.
   A top civil rights leader said the veto would leave ``a terrible
and lasting stain on the Reagan presidency'' and Democratic leaders
predicted that Congress would quickly override the president's
action.
   Today was the deadline for action on the sweeping measure,
designed to overcome the effects of a 1984 Supreme Court decision
that has allowed institutions to receive federal aid even when some
of their departments discriminate illegally.
   The bill would require all parts of any institution receiving
federal aid to obey anti-discrimination laws.
   ``We have said all along we would veto,'' White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday.
   Fitzwater said the president believes the Supreme Court's
decision, which involved Grove City College in Pennsylvania, was a
mistake but that the corrective legislation goes too far in seeking
to correct the problem.
   The bill became an issue in Tuesday's Illinois presidential
primary when Vice President George Bush refused to say whether he
would veto or sign the legislation if he were president.
   Fitzwater said the administration has ``a very positive
alternative bill'' but he declined to give details.
   An administration official, however, speaking on condition he
not be identified, said the alternative was expected to be ``very
much like'' a GOP substitute that the House rejected by a 266-146
vote on March 2.
   That measure would have scaled back the bill's impact on
corporations and allowed more schools to avoid compliance with
civil rights laws on religious grounds.
   Reagan wrote to House Republicans that he objected to the bill
that eventually passed because it ``dramatically expands the scope
of federal jurisdiction over state and local governments and the
private sector'' and ``poses a particular threat to religious
liberty.''
   The Senate passed the bill 75-14 and the House passed it 315-98,
margins substantially greater than the two-thirds majority of both
houses needed to override a presidential veto.
   House Majority Leader Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said Tuesday
that he expected the Senate to override Reagan's veto later this
week and the House to follow suit next week.
   Ralph Neas, executive director of the 200-group Leadership
Conference on Civil Rights, said that by vetoing the bill Reagan
would be ``favoring federal subsidies to discrimination.''
   ``A presidential veto of a bill to end federal funding of
discrimination would be unconscionable,'' he said. ``It will leave
a terrible and lasting stain on the Reagan presidency.''
   The administration official who spoke anonymously said the White
House strategy would be to try to get House members who voted for
the GOP substitute to vote to sustain the veto. Since 146 _ the
number of legislators who supported the House GOP substitute _ is
slightly more than one-third of the full House membership of 435,
that could be enough to sustain.
   The civil rights bill would require entire colleges, school
systems, government agencies and private entities to comply with
anti-discrimination laws if any program or activity within them
receives federal money. Institutions that did not comply would lose
their federal funding.
   The Supreme Court's Grove City decision limited the penalty to
the specific program or activity that violated the law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0302 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0840EST</FILEID>
