<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 0911EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoIncentives     03-16 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Incentives,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Ups Rebates on 6 Models, Plans Cut After Weekend on 3
Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. has boosted buyer incentives on
six models, offering as much as $1,500 in rebates, and one analyst
said a ``fire sale'' seemed to be under way at the No. 3 U.S.
automaker.
   Chrysler said Tuesday it was raising rebates on five 1987 and
1988 Dodge cars and trucks and one Jeep model. The incentive
program has no expiration date.
   The automaker also said it planned to reduce rebates on three
other models after the weekend.
   Analysts credit the aggressive use of incentives with spurring
sales. In early March, Chrysler's domestic car sales were up 18.3
percent and its light truck sales were up 24.1 percent from a year
ago.
   ``Chrysler has the most generous incentives of any automaker.
It's really running a fire sale on its left-over '87s,'' said
Ronald Glantz, analyst with Montgomery Securities Inc. in San
Francisco.
   Rebates rose to $1,500 from $750 on the Daytona Pacifica; to
$1,000 from $750 on Daytona Shelby Z and standard Ram pickups; to
$1,000 from $500 on standard Ram B150, B250 and B350 passenger
vans; and to $750 from $500 on Dakota mid-size pickups and Jeep
Comanche pickup.
   Chrysler said it also added its 1987 and 1988 Chrysler LeBaron
convertible to the program with a $750 rebate.
   On Monday, rebates on three other models will be reduced. The
rebate on the 1987 and 1988 LeBaron coupe will drop to $750 from
$1,500; to $1,000 from $1,500 on the Dodge Ramcharger sport-utility
vehicle; and to $500 from $750 on the Dodge Daytona Highline.
   Instead of rebates, buyers can opt for low-rate financing with
interest rates of 3.8 percent on loans up to 48 months and 8.8
percent on loans up to 60 months, Chrysler said.
   Meanwhile, General Motors Corp.'s GMC Truck division said it was
extending its $500 rebate campaign through the end of the month on
1987 and 1988 S-15 compact pickups and sport-utility vehicles.
   GM also added its new 1988 Sierra full-size pickup and 1987 and
1988 Rally passenger vans and Vandura cargo vans to the program,
also with $500 rebates.
   The rebates may be used in addition to continuous option
discounts.
   Analysts said GM sales fell in early March because buyers took
advantage of widespread incentives in February.
</TEXT>
