<1ST_LINE>r f BC-NorthwestFares     03-16 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Northwest Fares,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Eases Advance Purchase Requirement on Some Discount
Fares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines has lowered the advance
purchase requirement, to three days, on a discount fare used by
business travelers.
   The change took effect Tuesday as major airlines, including
Northwest, raised full coach fares and ended some discount fares,
sharply increasing the cost of travel for people who cannot make
plans in advance.
   Northwest's change, which its competitors are expected to match,
will make it easier for travelers to take advantage of some
discount fares. The fare, available on a limited number of seats on
most routes, carries no cancellation penalty and has no other
restrictions.
   Under the changes that took effect Tuesday, most discount fares
generally require a seven-day advance purchase and carry a
cancellation penalty of 25 percent.
   If other airlines match the Northwest fare, it would be the
first modification of a series of fare increases proposed this
month by Continental Airlines and matched by all leading carriers.
   William Wren, vice president for public relations at Northwest,
said the airline was joining its competitors in extending to seven
days from two the advance purchase requirement on Maxsaver fares,
the lowest fares available.
   In addition, Wren said some carriers were proposing a 14-day
advance purchase requirement, but that Northwest did not support
the idea.
</TEXT>
