<1ST_LINE>u b PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru f0039 03-16 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0039,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Up Sharply, Industrial Production Inches
Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with figures on industrial
production, tighten. Picks up 5th graf pvs, On Tuesday ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction posted the biggest increase in more than a
year as new projects climbed by 8.9 percent in February, while
industrial production edged up 0.2 percent, the government reported
today.
   The Commerce Department said last month's gain in housing
construction raised activity to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 1.49 million units. The increase followed declines of 1.9
percent in January and 15.8 percent in December.
   The unexpectedly strong February report was likely to ease
worries about a possible recession. The 8.9 percent rise in housing
starts in February was the sharpest monthly gain since a 12.7
percent rise in December 1986.
   The increase in February industrial production represented the
fifth consecutive monthly gain, according to the Federal Reserve.
The Fed said the advance followed a 0.3 percent increase in January
and left American industry operating at a rate 5.8 percent above a
year ago.
   Analysts said the report was consistent with their view that the
economy will continue to move forward this year, but at a slower
pace than in 1987.
   On Tuesday, a jump in early March auto sales and news of a
record 1987 trade deficit failed to wield much influence in the
financial markets.
   Major automakers said Tuesday that sales of domestic cars and
light trucks rose 6.3 percent in the first 10 days of March
compared with a year earlier, led by surging sales of vehicles made
by Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. Industry leader General Motors
Corp. reported weaker results.
   In Washington, the Commerce Department said the deficit in the
broadest measure of foreign trade surged to a record $160.7 billion
in 1987, a reflection of America's deepening debt to the rest of
the world.
   The deficit in the U.S. current account was 13.7 percent higher
than the 1986 deficit of $141.4 billion and marked the fifth
consecutive year that this trade deficit has hit a new record.
   The Reagan administration has sought to downplay the
significance of the trade deficits, but private economists contend
the rapid buildup of foreign debt could cause a further weakening
in the dollar's value and a recession.
   The current account measures not only the flow of merchandise
across U.S. borders but also the flow of services, primarily
investment earnings.
   Net debtor status means Americans own less investments abroad
than foreigners do in this country.
   Despite the latest trade statistics, Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Alan Greenspan said Tuesday that Americans shouldn't be
overly concerned and that foreign investors make ``good corporate
citizens.''
   ``We will find that foreign investment in the United States will
be a plus,'' even at present record levels, Greenspan told the
House-Senate Joint Economic Committee.
   Neither the auto sales or foreign trade figures had much impact
on Wall Street, where stocks were mixed in light trading. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials fell 2.66 points to 2,047.41.
   Prices in the bond market, a sensitive barometer of interest
rates and the economy, also ended little changed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
