<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Sears-WesternAuto     03-16 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sears-Western Auto,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears Buying Western Auto Supply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. announced today it has
agreed to buy a majority interest in Western Auto Supply Co. and
will make a tender offer for the remainder of Western Auto's
outstanding shares in a $402 million deal.
   Sears said in a statement it will pay $19 a share for 52.3
percent of Western Auto's stock held by certain stockholders,
including officers and directors.
   Sears said it will offer the same cash price for all remaining
stock if it can win the approval of Western Auto's board of
directors this week.
   Western Auto's stock, which is traded on the over-the-counter
market, was up $6 to $18.50 a share in early trading today.
   The stock buyout would cost Sears $250 million and the retailer
also would assume the auto supply company's $152 million debt.
   Western Auto is a Kansas City-based marketer of auto supplies,
tires, appliances and lawn and garden equipment. It has 6,600
employees and operates 278 company-owned retail stores. It also
sells at wholesale to 1,570 independently owned Western Auto stores
nationwide.
   The acquisition would represent Sears' further expansion into
specialty marketing. The nation's largest retailer previously
bought apparel store and optical center chains.
   Last year, Western Auto had a profit of $10.5 million on sales
of $930.8 million. Sears earned $1.65 billion and had revenues of
$48.44 billion.
   Sears said it reserved the right to cancel the deal if the
Western Auto board fails to give its approval by Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
