<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Robins     03-16 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Robins,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proposed Merger Hits Snag In Federal Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge sent attorneys working on
A.H. Robins Co.'s merger agreement with American Home Products
Corp. back to the drawing board today, but the hitch did not appear
to be major.
   ``My view right now is I will not approve it as it stands,''
U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. said at a brief hearing
on the proposed merger.
   Merhige, who is overseeing Robins' Chapter 11 bankruptcy case
with U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Blackwell N. Shelley, said he was
concerned about the status of Dalkon Shield claims during the
expected appeals of the case.
   Under the $700 million merger agreement, American Home Products
would not be obligated for claims from users of the intrauterine
device until the final order is entered after appeals.
   Merhige said he found that provision unacceptable.
   ``I'm not going to delay this any more. These women have waited
and waited and waited,'' the judge said.
   Merhige suggested that the case go forward by having American
Home Products put up $100 million of the proposed $2.475 billion
fund to resolve claims against the intrauterine birth control
device.
   If the merger is voided on appeal, Merhige said, then American
Home Products could recover the money from Robins.
   Merhige sent the attorneys to work on the problem.
   Robins' reorganization must include a settlement of about
195,000 claims from women who contend they were injured by the IUD,
which was sold by Robins in the early 1970s.
   Robins and American Home Products of New York reached a merger
agreement Jan. 21 after the Richmond-based pharmacuetical company
had negotiated similar agreements with two other potential buyers,
France's Sanofi SA and the Rorer Group Inc. of Pennsylvania.
   Robins has been under Chapter 11 protection from creditors since
August 1985 because of the Dalkon Shield claims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
