<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1140EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-Economy     03-16 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Economy,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Economy Expected to Grow 8 Percent This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brisk exports will help South Korea's
economy grow by at least 8 percent this year, the Economic Planning
Board said.
   In its revised economic management program issued Wednesday, the
agency forecast that South Korea's gross national product would
swell to the equivalent of $145 billion, up 8 percent from last
year.
   That would boost the country's per capita GNP for this year to
$3,450, up $637 from last year, the planning board said.
   Under the original projections, 1988 GNP was expected to reach
$124 billion for a per capita GNP of $2,922.
   The GNP is the total output of goods and services a country
produces in a year.
   Government officials said stronger-than-expected exports so far
this year have prompted them to revise the projections upward.
   South Korea's merchandise exports during January and February
reached $8.01 billion, up 39.9 percent from the same period last
year.
   At that pace, total 1988 exports would rise to $55 billion and
imports to $50 billion, creating a trade surplus of $5 billion,
according to the revised figures.
   The projected trade surplus, combined with an expected surplus
of $2 billion in invisible trade items such as tourism income,
would help South Korea register a current-account surplus of $7
billion this year.
   Helped by strong exports, South Korea's current-account surplus
more than doubled to $9.78 billion last year from the 1986 level.
   The current account measures trade in goods and services plus
certain unilateral transfers.
   The projected current-account surplus would help South Korea
trim its external debts to $31 billion from $35.6 billion at the
end of last year, the agency said.
   An additional 354,000 new jobs would be created this year but
the unemployment rate would rise to 3.7 percent from 3.1 percent
last year, it said.
</TEXT>
