<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koppers Rejects BNS Bid; Mulls Recapitalization</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf to CORRECT construction to chemicals business.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co.'s board today rejected a $1.27
billion takeover bid from a group led by Beazer PLC and Shearson
Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. and said it is mulling a
recapitalization plan to fend off unwanted suitors.
   British investor Brian Beazer, who heads the London-based
construction concern, and Shearson Lehman launched a $45-per-share
tender offer for Koppers' common shares on March 3. Koppers
management today called the offer inadequate and recommended
stockholders not tender their shares.
   Beazer, Shearson and NatWest Investment Bank Ltd., a British
investment bank, reportedly own about 7.45 percent of Koppers'
outstanding common shares.
   The Pittsburgh-based road builder and manufacturer of
construction materials said in a statement its board is
``considering alternative plans intended to enhance shareholder
values both immediately and over the long term.''
   Koppers shares fell 75 cents to $53.75 in early trading on the
New York Stock Exchange after jumping $2.25 on Tuesday.
   Charles Pullin, Koppers' chairman, said the board is considering
a recapitalization plan that would involve a ``substantial cash
distribution or dividend'' to common shareholders.
   He said the company will explore the sale of some or all of its
construction materials and services business, the proceeds of which
would be used to fund the dividend payout.
   Beazer has said it probably would sell Koppers' chemical
business if it gained control.
   Pullin said a recapitalization also could include the sale of
stock to an employee stock ownership plan that the company would
establish.
   ``Koppers' board believes that the company remaining independent
would, over the long term, be a superior alternative to accepting''
the buyout offer, the company said.
   Koppers said the Beazer-Shearson offer to pay $107.75 for each
of the 150,000 outstanding shares of preferred stock was adequate
but declined to advise preferred shareholders whether to tender
their stock.
   Beazer and Shearson made their bid through BNS Inc.
</TEXT>
