<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1228EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PetroleumUse     03-16 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Petroleum Use,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Production Fell, Imports Rose in February</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic crude oil production dropped again last
month, while increased imports continued to feed the nation's
ever-growing thirst for petroleum-based products, a trade group
reported Wednesday.
   The nation's output of crude dropped 1.8 percent from January to
8.16 million barrels a day _ a fall of 11 percent from the level of
two years ago, the American Petroleum Institute said in its monthly
report.
   At the same time, daily imports averaged 6.66 million barrels of
crude and products, which was up 14.8 percent from 5.8 million
barrels a day in February 1987, the Washington-based group said.
   That marked a 38 percent increase in imports from February 1986,
when the nation bought 4.84 million barrels of foreign crude and
products each day, said Joe Lastelic, an API spokesman. A barrel is
the equivalent of 42 gallons.
   February's deliveries of refined products increased by 2.5
percent, or 417,000 barrels daily, reflecting expected trends in
actual consumption after an unusual 7 percent year-to-year leap in
January, the report said.
   Gasoline led the increase in deliveries of refined products,
rising 2.6 percent from last February. On a year-to-date basis,
however, this worked out to an expected 2 percent gain when
adjusted for unusual factors, the trade group said.
   The report said annual domestic consumption of motor fuels has
grown by 2.2 percent to 3.2 percent a year in the 1982-1987 period,
as Americans traveled nearly 3.8 percent more each year.
   Among other highlights, the API reported that:
   _February deliveries of home heating oil and diesel fuel were
essentially flat, compared with February 1987, partly because
weather in New England and the Mid-Atlantic states was warmer than
usual.
   _Heavy fuel oil, known as residual fuel oil, rose 2 percent from
the previous February, apparently reflecting ``the competitive
nature of the fuel in the electric utility and industrial markets.''
   _Kerosine jet fuel deliveries fell a sharp 3.5 percent from a
year ago, in part because of heavy inventory buildup in January.
   _The utilization rate of the nation's refineries slackened to
81.9 percent from an average 83 percent use over the winter months,
as the winter heating season wound down.
   _Inventories of crude and products dropped 1.6 percent from
January and 2 pecent from February 1987.
</TEXT>
