<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Getty-Oil     03-16 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Getty-Oil,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tyler Company Agrees to Let Getty Become Majority Stockholder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A son of late oil billionaire J. Paul
Getty will become a majority stockholder in DeltaUS Corp. under an
agreement reached with the financially troubled Tyler drilling
company.
   The 57-year-old Delta USCorp. last turned a profit in the oil
boom year of 1981.
   An unnamed corporation owned wholly by Gordon P. Getty is to pay
$7 million for newly issued shares of common stock in Delta, giving
Getty 75 percent ownership of the Tyler company, Delta chairman
Keating Zeppa said Tuesday.
   The agreement also calls for the Getty-owned corporation to
provide Delta with a $2.5 million cash infusion to help finance its
weakened drilling operations.
   Zeppa said Delta suffered a net loss in excess of $10 million
last year on revenues of $51 million.
   The company has 1,100 employees, less than half its peak
employment of about 2,400 workers in 1982. Only 13 of its 50
U.S.-based rigs are active, Zeppa said. Six of seven Delta rigs in
Italy are in operation.
   The agreement with Getty should ``give us the ability to
withstand worse-case conditions for three to four years and still
be around when things turn up (in the drilling industry),'' Zeppa
said.
   Zeppa said Getty does not anticipate any changes in management
or current operations.
   Getty, 54, is a resident of San Francisco and reportedly has no
plans to assume an executive role with Delta.
   Getty played a major role in 1984 merger talks involving Getty
Oil Co. and Houston-based Pennzoil Co.
   Texaco Inc. wound up making a higher bid and buying the
California-based company.
   A Houston jury in 1985 awarded the largest court judgment in
history _ $10.53 billion _ to Pennzoil, which had argued that
Texaco had improperly interfered with the proposed Pennzoil-Getty
merger.
   Texaco has since agreed to pay Pennzoil $3 billion to settle the
case.
</TEXT>
