<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Kenosha-Chrysler     03-16 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kenosha-Chrysler,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union at Kenosha Chrysler plant plans to approach shareholders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers Local 72 plans to
approach Chrysler Corp. stockholders in its fight to keep as many
of the automaker's jobs in Kenosha as possible this fall when car
assembly is scheduled to end here.
   Ed Steagall, president of the local, said Tuesday the union
plans to solicit proxies from stockholders in time for Chrysler's
May 19 shareholder meeting in New York.
   Steagall said the union is ``contacting somebody to see how to
obtain the maximum amount of proxies'' and would announce its
strategy at a news conference.
   Asked what the proxies would say, Steagall said the union has
not set a complete agenda.
   A proxy is a ballot that empowers somebody to vote for another.
   Joseph Philippi, an auto analyst at Shearson Lehman and Hutton
in New York, said he doubts the union could get enough votes to
make Chrysler's board of directors change its mind about halting
assembly operations at Kenosha.
   But he said the proxies could serve as a show of support for the
union cause.
   ``It's a means of registering protest,'' he said. ``In terms of
the effectiveness, I seriously doubt they're going to get enough
votes for it.''
   Baron Bates, Chrysler vice president of public affairs, the
company is on the verge of sending out its proxies, said the UAW
itself is a big Chrysler shareholder. Several Local 72 members also
own shares which they got in a stock swap after Chrysler bought
American Motors Corp. last August.
   Chrysler said Jan. 27 that it would stop car assembly at Kenosha
by September, wiping out 5,500 jobs. It, however, intends to
preserve about 1,000 jobs in continuing engine operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
