<1ST_LINE>r f AM-India-Carbide     03-16 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Carbide,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Postpones Hearing on Carbide Compensation suit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: version also running for AMs on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has postponed until April 12
hearings in the $3 billion compensation suit filed by the
government against Union Carbide Corp. for the 1984 Bhopal gas
disaster, it was reported.
   Bhopal District Judge M.W. Deo on Wednesday delayed the hearings
because of an appeal in the Madhya Pradesh High Court against an
order directing Carbide to pay $350 million in interim relief to
the gas disaster victims. The high court has scheduled its hearing
on the appeal for April 4.
   Deo had ordered Carbide to pay interim relief in December. The
compensation suit was filed in his court by the government in
September 1986.
   The government says the Danbury, Conn.-based multinational
corporation is responsible for the poisonous gas leak from the
Carbide plant in Bhopal. Union Carbide says the leak was caused by
sabotage.
   At least 2,800 people were killed and more than 20,000 injured
in the Dec. 3, 1984 disaster, considered the world's biggest
industrial accident.
</TEXT>
