<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Sweden-Tolls     03-16 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sweden-Tolls,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No More Waiting With New Toll System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish researchers have developed an
electronic identity card for cars so that drivers can pay tolls
without stopping, according to a spokesman for the company which is
marketing the invention.
   The 5-by-6 centimeter (2-by-2.4 inch) plate on the rear window
identifies the car by a microwave transmitter to a computer when
the car passes a toll booth at normal speed, said Stig Rune
Johansson, of Kista Industrier AB.
   He said the small town of Aalesund on Norway's western coast
became the first to try the system last October. It was developed
at Stockholm's Institute for Microelectronics.
   About half the 3,000 cars passing through Aalesund's tunnel
every day never stop and pay the fee. The information is
transmitted to the car owners' bank, and charges are automatically
deducted once a month.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
