<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1340EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Soviet-ForeignVenture     03-16 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Foreign Venture,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Announce Biggest Joint Venture Worth About $6 Billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Oil Ministry and U.S., Italian and
Japanese companies signed an agreement Wednesday that would create
the Soviet Union's largest joint business venture with foreigners.
   Under the $6 billion deal, the venture would build and operate a
petrochemical complex off the Caspian Sea in the Central Asian
republic of Kazakhstan. It is expected to produce 400,000 tons of
polypropylene, 600,000 tons of polyethylene and more than 1 million
tons of granulated sulfur annually.
   Polypropylene and polyehylene are used to make plastics.
   The foreign partners are Occidental Petroleum Corp. of Los
Angeles, the Italian companies of Montedison and Enichem and
Marubeni of Japan.
   Officials of the four companies signed a preliminary agreement
with Soviet representatives on Wednesday, committing them to study
plans for the petrochemical complex for nine months before
completing a long-range contract.
   Montedison Chairman Raul Gardini said the Soviets had invited
the four companies to establish the joint venture.
   ``It reflects the necessity for the Soviet Union to get involved
in the world market and the necessity for Western firms to get
closer to sources of raw materials in order to process them more
efficiently at the sites,'' he said.
   The Soviet Union has vast natural resources, and is the world's
largest oil producer.
   Vassily A. Dinkov, Soviet oil minister, told a news conference
that housing for the petrochemical workers, roads, a railroad link,
electricity and communications facilities are under construction
for the complex, which will be built near the western Kazakh town
of Kulsary.
   Under the agreement, Dinkov said, gas and oil extraction
facilities are to be operating next year, with refining plants
following within the next few years. Oil reserves in the deposit,
known as the Tengiz Oil Field, are estimated at between 14 billion
and 17.5 billion barrels, Dinkov said.
   Foreign participants will hold a total of no more than 49
percent of the joint venture's capital, with the rest held by the
Soviet government.
   Occidental Chairman Armand Hammer told the news conference each
of the foreign partners will invest $750 million in the project,
and the Soviets will put in $3 billion. The Western partners will
utilize bank financing, he said.
   Previous joint ventures, which have sprung up under Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's overhaul of the Soviet economy, have been worth in the
millions of dollars.
   The foreign partners will sell half the complex's products
abroad. The Soviets will sell the other half, either domestically
or on the world market.
   Hammer, whose business ties with the Soviets date to the 1920s,
expressed confidence that the Western partners will find the deal
financially satisfying.
   ``We're not here for charitable purposes,'' he said. ``We, each
of the four companies, expect to make profits.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0330 </DOCNO>
