<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Sears-WesternAuto     03-16 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sears-Western Auto,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retailing Giant Buying Western Auto Supply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. is expanding its role in
specialty retailing with a plan announced Wednesday to buy Western
Auto Supply Co. in a $402 million deal.
   Sears said it was buying 52.3 percent of Western Auto stock from
officers, directors and others for $19 a share and will make a
tender offer for the remainder of the stock at the same price.
   The acquisition will cost the nation's biggest retailer $250
million. It also will assume the auto supply company's $152 million
debt.
   Western Auto's stock, traded on the over-the-counter market,
rose $5.87{ a share to $18.37{ by Wednesday afternoon.
   John Landschultz, a financial analyst in Chicago with Mesirow
Financial Corp., said this was probably the first of several steps
Sears would take to increase its presence in the specialty field.
   ``This move does several things that were needed,'' said
Landschultz.
   First, he said, it gets Sears out of the major malls where it
has had a dominent influence and into the smaller markets. It also
capitalizes on Sears' strength in automotive parts and equipment.
   Western Auto sells auto supplies, tires, appliances and lawn and
garden equipment through nearly 2,000 stores nationwide.
   The Kansas City-based company operates 278 retail stores it
owns, and sells wholesale to 1,570 independently owned Western Auto
outlets.
   Sears said John T. Lundegard, Western Auto's chairman and chief
executive officer, will remain as head of the auto supply unit and
will report to Alfred G. Goldstein, president of Sears' specialty
merchandising.
   These personnel decisions are significant, said Landschultz.
   ``It's very important that (Lundegard) stays in place,'' he
said, adding that Goldstein has been extremely successful in the
specialty field.
   The acquisition would represent Sears' further expansion into
specialty marketing. It previously bought apparel and optical
chains.
   But the Western Auto deal is the first significant move in this
direction, said Landschultz.
   Last year, Western Auto earned $10.5 million on sales of $930.8
million. Sears earned $1.65 billion and had revenues of $48.44
billion.
</TEXT>
