<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ContinentalTrial     03-16 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Continental Trial,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lytle Exceeded Lending Authority, Court Told</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former vice president of Continental Illinois
National Bank & Trust Co. exceeded his authority and improperly
approved risky loans in the years before the bank's near-collapse,
a former lending officer testified.
   John Lytle, accused of misusing bank funds, exceeded a limit of
$5 million on the amount of loans he could approve by granting
extensions on a loan, the former lending officer, Anne Liddell,
testified Tuesday.
   And she said Lytle's initials appeared on a credit reporting
form that was submitted in her name but that she did not fill out.
The form listed the history of a prospective borrower.
   ``My name was misspelled,'' she said.
   Ms. Liddell's statements came during the second day of testimony
in the five-day-old U.S. District Court trial of Lytle and two
other men.
   Lytle headed energy lending in Oklahoma for Contintental. The
government has accused him of buying high-risk loans from the
now-defunct Penn Square Bank in Oklahoma City in exchange for
nearly $600,000 in kickbacks between 1980 and 1982.
   Defendant William Patterson, former head of energy lending at
Penn Square, gave the kickbacks to Lytle in the form of unsecured
personal loans, the government contends.
   A third defendant, Tulsa oil driller Jere Sturgis, is accused of
purchasing oil-well investments from Lytle at inflated prices in
hopes of getting future loans from Continental.
   All three are charged with multiple counts of wire fraud. Lytle
and Patterson are also charged with misapplication of bank funds.
   The 1982 failure of Penn Square Bank jolted Continental, which
was rescued in a massive bailout by the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. two years later.
</TEXT>
