<2ND_LINE>BC-Wickes,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wickes in Talks to Sell Kayser-Roth Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wickes Cos. Inc. said Wednesday it
is negotiating to sell the Kayser-Roth Hosiery Group to members of
the unit's management and Narragansett Capital Inc. of New York.
   The hosiery unit, based in Greensboro, N.C., is one of the
world's leading manufacturers of men's and women's hosiery,
including such brands as No Nonsense, Liz Clairborne, Calvin Klein,
Burlington and Supp-Hose.
   It has 9,600 workers at 16 manufacturing plants and four
distribution centers in the United States and Europe.
   The Kayser-Roth units were part of Gulf & Western Industries'
consumer and industrial products segment that was acquired by
Wickes for $1 billion in 1985.
   The hosiery group was one of three units put on the auction
block by Wickes last October. The others are its Kayser-Roth
Apparel Group and Wickes Lumber.
   None of the three has been sold. Wickes had tentatively agreed
to sell the lumber segment to members of management, but that deal
was called off in January because of financing problems. The lumber
unit's management group is seeking other financing and Wickes is
looking at other possible buyers.
   The three units last year had sales of $1.8 billion and
operating income of $80 million. Of that, the hosiery group
accounted for $500 million in sales, but no operating income
figures were disclosed.
   Wickes has said that proceeds from the asset sales will be used
to buy back stock, pay debt and possibly fund acquisitions to
expand continuing operations.
   The management group leading the buyout talks includes James I.
Spiegel, who was president of the consumer and industrial products
units and corporate senior executive vice president at Gulf &
Western and later at Wickes, and Michael C. Proies, president of No
Nonsense Fashions Inc. Spiegel retired from Wickes in early 1986.
   Narragansett is a private investment firm that manages over $500
million in risk capital. Industrial companies that make up its
investment portfolio have sales of about $1 billion a year.
Narragansett also owns several radio and television stations and
cable TV systems serving more than 350,000 subscribers.
</TEXT>
