<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Brothers'Suit     03-16 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brothers' Suit,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Pitted Brother Against Brother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business took precedence over brotherhood in a
suit that ended in U.S. District Court when Michael B. Shane was
awarded $1.3 million after suing his brother and partners six years
ago.
   Michael Shane is the founder of Leading Edge Products Inc. of
Canton, a leading supplier of Asian-made clones of IBM personal
computers, in 1980.
   The case decided by a jury Tuesday involved Appendagez, a
company founded in 1973 that sold a popular brand of blue jeans
called Faded Glory.
   Michael Shane was 25 and had made $1 million selling wigs when
James Ip, a Hong Kong businessman, approached him about selling
blue jeans. They were joined by Shane's brother, James Shane, and
Charles Lee, a Hong Kong businessman.
   Ip owned 14.5 percent of the Hong Kong company that made the
jeans.
   Appendagez at its peak sold $50 million to $60 million in jeans
a year, said Michael B. Keating, lawyer for Michael Shane.
   Michael Shane was president and majority stockholder of
Appendagez until 1979 when he sold his stock in the company in two
transactions.
   In January 1979, he sold 30 shares for $1.3 million. In
November, he agreed with his three partners to sell his remaining
26 shares for $50,000 and ended all business relations.
   Three years later he sued his brother and his other two former
partners, charging them with securities fraud.
   He claimed that between the times of the two transactions, the
three conspired to deceive him about the condition of Appendagez so
they could buy him out for less than his remaining shares were
worth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880316-0336 </DOCNO>
