<HEAD>Tiger Pays Off $132 Million Debt from Failed Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiger International Inc. said Wednesday it
has paid off, at a substantial discount, $132 million in debt from
its failed North American Car rail-car leasing unit.
   The debt was paid off using proceeds from a new $100 million
debt offering and an unspecified amount of internally generated
cash, the company said.
   Tiger, parent of the world's oldest and largest air-cargo
concern, Flying Tiger Line Inc., wrote off its entire $132 million
investment in North American Car in 1984.
   In January, Tiger said it had reached an agreement with holders
of the North American Car debt to repay them at a discount.
   Tiger wouldn't say Wednesday how much the discount was, other
than that it was substantial.
   The $100 million in new debt is in notes that are due no later
than 1993 and are secured by a pledge of 51 percent of Flying
Tiger's stock.
