<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market showed some spotty losses in
quiet trading today, continuing the sluggish pattern of the past
two sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 6.30 to 2,041.11
by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 4 to 3 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 604 up, 840 down and
489 unchanged.
   The market has been in a holding pattern since the start of the
week as traders await Thursday's report on the nation's trade
balance for January.
   Most economists look for a modest increase in the trade deficit
after two months of pronounced declines. If the figures match those
expectations, analysts believe the market wouldn't feel any great
shock effects.
   But traders apparently are sticking with a cautious approach
until then so as not to be caught off guard by any surprise either
way.
   After the trade report, the market is also faced with a
quarterly ``triple witching hour'' involving a series of stock
index options and futures that will be settled Friday.
   That too may pass quietly, brokers say, but until it is over it
adds an additional element of uncertainty for investors.
   Losers among the blue chips included Merck, down 2 at 156\;
American Express, down | at 25|; USX, down { at 31[, and American
Telephone & Telegraph, down \ at 28].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.20 to 149.79. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .82 at 295.93.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 114.54 million shares with an
hour to go.
