<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 2145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-VentureMoney     03-16 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venture Money,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Of Venture Capitalist Has More Funds For '88 Deals, Study
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of venture capitalists recently polled
will have an average of $44.8 million to invest in growing
companies this year, up 11 percent from the average earmarked for
investments last year, according to a study released Wednesday.
   Grant Thornton, the accounting and management consulting firm
that conducted the survey, notedthat 93 percent of the 183 venture
capital firms that responded said they anticipate receiving more
requests from young companies seeking funds for expansion this year
compared with the previous year.
   Forty-seven percent of the venture capitalists polled said they
would invest in more companies this year, the study said.
   Only 13 percent of the respondents said they have shifted
investment strategies since the October stock market crash, with
several noting they prefer ``later-stage'' companies that may
present less risk.
   A full 96 percent said they expect going public will be a more
difficult and lengthy process in the post-crash environment.
   Grant Thornton mailed questionnaires to 501 venture capital
firms across the country in January. The 183 completed surveys
represent at 36 percent response rate.
</TEXT>
