<HEAD>Warner-Lambert Sets Up Joint Partnership With China For Gum, Cough
Drops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS PLAINS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner-Lambert Co. said it is
planning a $5 million joint venture with the People's Republic of
China to make and market chewing gum, cough drops and candies.
   The pharmaceutical company said an agreement with the Chinese
government calls for a plant to be built in the city of Harbin,
capital of the northeastern province Heilongjang.
   Warner-Lambert said it would provide the machinery and
technology while the government would provide the land, building
and some equipment.
   The joint venture, to be called the Harbin Warner-Lambert
Confectionary Co. Ltd., would employ about 120 people, the company
said in an announcement Tuesday. The plant would produce Dentyne
gum, Halls cough drops and Fruitfuls candies for use in China and
for export.
   Warner-Lambert has another joint partnership with China, called
Suzhou Capsugel Ltd., which makes empty hard gelatin capsules. It
was established in 1985.
</TEXT>
