<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Europe-Takeover     03-16 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Europe-Takeover,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Societe Generale Calls First Shareholders Meeting Since Takeover
Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Societe Generale de Belgique SA
announced Tuesday that it will call a shareholders meeting on April
14, the first since Italian financier Carlo De Benedetti tried to
take control of Belgium's largest holding company two months ago.
   Cerus SA, the French investment company controlled by De
Benedetti, has called for such a meeting. Societe Generale said
Cerus and other allied companies had furnished proof that they hold
at least 20 percent of shareholder capital, the minimum percentage
required to force the calling of such a meeting.
   Societe Generale said the agenda of the meeting will include a
speech by the president of the company, Rene Lamy, and the
nomination of directors.
   In addition, the company said, there will be items on the agenda
which had been requested by Cerus.
   Cerus has said that the number of company directors must be
decided and that the nominations of De Benedetti as well as his
allies, Andre Leysen of Gevaert N.V. and Pierre Scohier of
Compagnie Belge de Participations Paribas SA, must be put forward.
   Cerus also has said that a request would be made that Societe
Generale not make use of its recent capital increase of 12 million
shares. The shares were issued by the company immediately after it
became aware of De Benedetti's takeover bid, but De Benedetti
contested the capital increase in court and the case is still under
review.
   Societe Generale claims that, together with its allies led by
France's Compagnie Financiere de Suez, it controls more than 52
percent of the company's shares. De Benedetti and his allies, on
the other hand, say they have more than 47 percent.
</TEXT>
