<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market jumped ahead in late trading
Wednesday, putting on a show of strength in advance of Thursday's
monthly report on the nation's balance of trade.
   Trading remained relatively quiet, however.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which sat for most of
the day with a modest loss, closed up 16.91 at 2,064.32.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 5 to 3 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 952 up, 558 down and 475 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 153.59 million shares, against 133.17
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index gained
1.29 to 151.28.
   The market had been in a holding pattern since the start of the
week as traders awaited the figures on the trade balance for
January.
   Most economists look for a modest increase in the trade deficit
after two months of pronounced declines. If the figures match those
expectations, analysts believe the market wouldn't feel any great
shock effects.
   After the trade report, the market is also faced with a
quarterly ``triple witching hour'' involving a series of stock
index options and futures that will be settled Friday.
   That too may pass without much disruption of stock prices,
brokers say, but until it is over it adds an additional element of
uncertainty for investors.
   Meanwhile, the debate continues on Wall Street over whether the
market is making a sustainable comeback from the crash last fall.
   The pessimists argue that stocks are merely enjoying a ``bear
market rally'' that may not last much longer. But to date the
optimists seem to have the upper hand.
   Takeover rumors continued to abound. Pillsbury, said variously
to be a potential target for any of several financiers, gained 3~
to 42 and led the active list on volume of more than 2.3 million
shares.
   Similarly, U.S. Shoe climbed 2{ to 22{ and Carolina Freight
picked up 3] to 27}.
   Airline stocks were strong, continued to benefit from relatively
low oil prices and signs of movement in the industry toward higher
fares.
   AMR rose 1\ to 43[; Delta Air Lines 1[ to 48{; Trans World
Airlines | to 25{; NWA ] to 43~, and Allegis 2[ to 81|. Allegis
said its self-tender offer for 35.50 million of its shares at $80
apiece was oversubscribed by 11 million shares.
   Point-plus gainers among the 30 stocks in the Dow Jones
industrial average included International Business Machines, up 1\
at 115\; General Motors, up 2 at 73}; International Paper, up 1[ at
44, and DuPont, up 1| at 88.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $20.24 billion, or
0.77 percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 177.08 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials rose 2.84 to 311.39,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 2.52 at 268.65.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
gained 1.97 to 378.54. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 297.51, up .76.
