<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Murdoch-AAP     03-16 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murdoch-AAP,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murdoch's Company to Acquire Australian Press Agency, Get Big
Reuters Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News Corp., an international media
company controlled by publisher Rupert Murdoch, said Wednesday it
had arranged to buy nearly all the shares of Australian Associated
Press Pty.
   That company, which is no relation to the Associated Press in
the United States, distributes news and photographs throughout
Australia. It owns a 7.75 percent voting stake in Reuters Holdings
PLC, the large British news and information service.
   If Murdoch's acquisition succeeds, his company would become the
biggest single shareholder in Reuters because News Corp. already
owns a 6.8 percent voting stake in Reuters.
   News Corp., which had owned 44.65 percent of the Australian
Associated Press, said it had acquired another 8.3 percent from
Bell Group Ltd., a concern controlled by Australian investor Robert
Holmes a Court.
   News Corp. said it also had agreed to acquire a 44.65 percent
stake from John Fairfax Ltd., one of Australia's major media
companies.
   Prices weren't disclosed.
   Murdoch, a native Australian who became a U.S. citizen in 1985,
already controls about 60 percent of Australia's press and has
encountered government resistance to an expansion from government
antitrust officials.
   It was not immediately clear whether Murdoch's arrangement to
effectively acquire the Australian Associated Press would be
blocked by the government. But an official of the Trade Practices
Commission, which regulates such transactions, said it would
investigate.
   The official, who declined to be identified by name, said
elements of the sale appeared to conflict with an order issued last
year that prevented Murdoch from acquiring the parent company of
the Australian Associated Press, the Australian Associated Press
Information Services Ltd.
</TEXT>
