<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Robins 2ndLd-Writethru f0178 03-16 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robins, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0178,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Merger Deal Hitch in Dalkon Shield Case Resolved</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with two grafs to CORRECT spelling of spokesman in
second graf; uppicks 3rd graf pvs: The $100...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge approved the A.H. Robins
Co.'s merger pact with American Home Products Corp. on Wednesday
after Robins agreed to put $100 million toward Dalkon Shield claims
before its Chapter 11 bankruptcy case is completed.
   U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr., who earlier in the
day had raised questions about the merger deal, signed an order to
execute the agreement in the wake of the pharmaceutical company's
offer, said Roscoe E. Puckett Jr., a Robins spokesman.
   The $100 million would cover administrative costs to set up a
Dalkon Shield trust fund that eventually will grow to $2.475
billion, the amount Merhige said is needed to pay claims against
the intrauterine birth-control device.
   The claims covered by the initial funding would be smaller
amounts to women who show minimal proof of Dalkon Shield use and
injury, said Puckett, the Robins spokesman.
   Earlier Wednesday, Merhige, citing years of delay in paying
Dalkon Shield claims, refused to ratify the merger unless it
allowed some compensation before the company's reorganization
became final.
   The surprise ruling sent attorneys in the 2{-year-old bankruptcy
case back to the drawing board to hammer out a compromise that
would allow payments of some claims pending expected appeals of the
reorganization.
   ``You know it's coming. I know it's coming,'' Merhige told the
attorneys of expected court challenges. ``But we can't wait any
longer.''
   Merhige's objection involved a section of the merger agreement
that would allow the New York-based American Home Products, which
plans to acquire Robins through a $700 million exchange of stock,
to back out after one year, if appeals of the court's confirmation
order for Robins' reorganization plan are still pending.
   Putting off payments of injury claims against the intrauterine
device until all appeals are resolved and a final order approving
the reorganization is entered would be unacceptable, the judge said.
   Instead, the judge suggested that American Home Products put up
$100 million to begin paying claims pendig appeal. If the
reorganization is later voided, he said, then AHP could recover the
money from Robins.
   ``I'm not going to delay this any more,'' he said. ``These women
have waited and waited and waited.''
   Under the agreement reached later Wednesday, Robins will put up
the $100 million instead of AHP, Puckett said.
   Until the hearing before Merhige and U.S. Bankruptcy Judge
Blackwell N. Shelley, there were no known hitches with the merger,
except for a $25 million breakup claim against Robins filed by the
Rorer Group Inc.
   Robins and Rorer, a suburban Philadelphia drug manufacturer, had
reached a tentative merger pact late last year. But in subsequent
talks involving Rorer, AHP and a third potential Robins' buyer,
France's Sanofi SA, officials of Robins accepted the American Home
offer.
   Merhige said he would conduct a hearing on the Rorer claim at a
later time.
   The American Home deal, reached Jan. 19, had been endorsed by
attorneys for 195,000 women with Dalkon Shield claims and by Robins
stockholders. In addition to the $2.475 billion Dalkon Shield trust
fund, Robins' trade creditors would receive full payment of claims.
   When the merger proposal came up in court, Robins' attorney
Dennis Drebsky said the plan ``happily is largely consensual.''
   But Merhige surprised attorneys by announcing, ``I have a
problem.''
   The judge said AHP's withdrawal option put an unnecessary delay
on paying claims unless the appeals court ordered a freeze on
payments pending a resolution of the case.
   Robins filed for Chapter 11 protection from creditors in August
1985 as millions of dollars in claims mounted against the Dalkon
Shield. The company distributed about 4.5 million of the IUDs in
the United States and abroad in the early 1970s.
   At the time it entered bankruptcy court, Robins had settled
9,500 of 15,000 Dalkon Shield lawsuits with payments of about $530
million. Injury claims have ranged from pelvic infections to
sterility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
