<FILEID>AP-NR-03-16-88 1758EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-16 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0847</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Move Higher on Panama Trouble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices spurted upward Wednesday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, reponding to a drop in oil inventories and to
turmoil in Central America.
   On other markets, copper futures moved sharply higher; cattle
prices were a little higher while other livestock and meat
declined; grain and soybean prices retreated.
   Oil traders said an unsuccessful coup attempt in Panama against
the regime of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega set the oil market on
edge.
   ``And there were rumors that workers on the Panama oil pipeline
went on strike,'' said Richard Kane, an analyst in New York with
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   The pipeline is the primary means of moving crude oil shipped
from Alaska across Panama to other tankers that take it to Gulf
Coast.
   There also were rumors that the Panama military cut off roads to
the U.S. military base in the Panama Canal Zone and fears that the
canal could be closed, Kane said.
   ``All this helped people to make up their minds to cover'' their
``short'' positions, Kane said.
   There has been an unusually large number of open contracts on
crude oil, with many traders having sold contracts with the idea of
buying them back later in hopes prices would fall in the interval _
a practice known as ``selling short.''
   Fearing the events in Panama could drive prices up instead, many
people who were short felt it was wise to buy now to offset their
earlier sales, Kane said.
   The reports out of Panama topped a market that opened bullish on
industry data released Tuesday.
   The American Petroleum Industry said crude oil, gasoline and
heating oil stocks were all down in the latest week. Gasoline was
down 3.59 million barrels from the previous week and heating oil
was reduced by 5.6 million barrels.
   ``These are very good product drawdowns,'' said Kane.
   Prices for West Texas Intermediate crude oil rose 19 cents to 32
cents a barrel, with the contract for delivery in April settling at
$16. Heating oil was .43 cent to .66 cent higher, with April at
44.08 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .40 cent to .89
cent higher, with April at 45.24 cents a gallon.
   Copper futures rallied strongly after suffering sharp declines
the previous day on the Commodity Exchange in New York.
   The recovery was triggered by a reversal in outlook for the size
of stockpiles in the exchange warehouses.
   ``The inventory expectations went from the plus side to the
minus side,'' said Bette Raptopoulos, an analyst in New York with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The expectations Wednesday, she said, was that there would be
further drawdowns in stocks.
   Trading of precious metals, meanwhile, was quiet as the market
awaited the government's report Thursday on the nation's foreign
trade balance during January.
   Copper settled .30 cent lower to 3.05 cents higher, with the May
contract at 97.55 cents a pound.
   Gold was $1 lower, with March at $445.30 a troy ounce; and
silver was 3.8 cents to 4 cents lower, with March at $6.327 a troy
ounce.
   Grain and soybean futures prices turned weaker on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Selling from South America put pressure on the soybean market
from the start, said Jerry Gidel, an analyst with G.H. Miller & Co.
   This was compounded by industry data putting the amount of
soybeans processed in mills during February at 3.7 million tons,
substantially lower than a month earlier and the year-ago figure.
   The implication is that soybean processors still have large
supplies of beans.
   Gidel said the corn and wheat prices were depressed by a lack of
export interest.
   Wheat was 1{ cents to 2} cents lower, with March at $2.92{ a
bushel; corn was \ cent to 1\ cents lower, with March at $1.97{ a
bushel; oats were } cent lower to 1 cent higher, with March at
$1.89{ a bushel; and soybeans were 2\ cents to 4 cents lower, with
March at $6.11{ a bushel.
   Live cattle futures rallied to close a little higher, while
other livestock and meat were weaker at the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Traders said a snowstorm in the Plains encouraged buying of
cattle futures.
   Live cattle settled .05 cent lower to .15 cent higher, with the
April contract at 73.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged
to .32 cent lower, with March at 82.40 cents a pound; live hogs
were unchanged to .30 cent lower, with April at 44.77 cents a
pound; and frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to .25 cent lower,
with March at 52.50 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures moved higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settled 2.80 points higher at 268.80 points. The
underlying spot index gained 2.52 points, closing at 268.65.
</TEXT>
