<2ND_LINE>AM-De Laurentiis,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Laurentiis Sells Some Rights to Film Library</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially troubled De Laurentiis
Entertainment Group Inc. said Tuesday it will sell the foreign
television, video and non-theatrical rights to virtually its entire
320-movie library for $69 million.
   The foreign rights are being acquired by a newly formed British
company controlled by financier Michael W. Stevens.
   Stevens also controls Parafrance Communications S.A. of Paris
which, through its Tele-Cip subsidiary, is the largest privately
owned television production concern in Europe.
   De Laurentiis still is seeking a buyer for the remaining rights
to its library and the sprawling Wilmington, N.C., studio where
most of its films are made.
   The company has been dogged by a string of box-office flops
since it went public three years ago.
   In first nine months of the company's past fiscal year, it took
$42.5 million in writeoffs on unsuccessful films. The company
posted a net loss for the three quarters of $36.2 million. Results
of the fiscal year ended Feb. 29 haven't been released.
   In mid-February, the company's founder, Italian filmmaker Dino
De Laurentiis, 68, stepped down as chairman and chief executive,
but he continues to own 60 percent of the company.
