<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Henley 1stLd-Writethru f0208 03-16 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Henley, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0208,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Henley to Restructure, Buy Back 22 Pct of Stock</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to CHANGE cost of buy-back to $512 million
based on Wednesday's closing price; picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng,
Henley is ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LA JOLLA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henley Group Inc., a two-year-old
holding company, on Wednesday announced plans to split into two
public companies and buy back 22 percent of its stock.
   The stock buy-back would cost about $512 million at current
prices. Henley jumped $1.75 a share to close at $25.625 a share in
over-the-counter trading.
   Henley is an amalgam of 35 construction, environmental, energy,
chemcial, manufacturing and finance businesses spun off in April
1986 by Allied-Signal Inc., which itself was formed by a $5 billion
merger in 1985.
   Henley has gained a reputation for tightening operations to
boost profits in individual units and then taking those units
public. The current market value of Henley's investments in its
subsidiaries that have publicly traded shares and its other
long-term investment securities is $2 billion.
   In recent months Henley has been involved in a so-far
unsuccessful bid for Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp., the
Chicago-based railroad, land and natural resources giant.
   Under the restructuring, which was approved in principle by the
company's board on Wednesday, Henley's assets would be divided
between two public companies:
   _Wheelabrator Group Inc., which already is publicly traded,
would take over Henley's stake in its successful Wheelabrator
Technologies Inc. subsidiary and other assets related to the
refuse-to-energy business.
   Wheelabrator Group would have the flexibility and resources to
speed up the expansion of its businesses through mergers,
acquisitions and joint ventures.
   _A newly created entity, to be called Henley Group Inc., would
own Signal Capital Corp., Signal Landmark Holdings Inc., Henley
Manufacturing Corp. and Henley's stake in Fisher Scientific Group
Inc., plus other assets.
   ``This program will enable our shareholders to participate
directly in Henley's $650 million investment in Wheelabrator
Technologies, the nation's leading refuse-to-energy business,''
said Michael Dingman, Henley's chairman and chief executive.
   Shares of the new entity that will be created for Henley's other
holdings will be distributed to stockholders as a partially taxable
special dividend, the company said.
   Henley's board also authorized the repurchase of 20 million of
the company's 90 million outstanding shares. The number of
outstanding shares peaked at 129 million in November 1986 before
the company initiated a series of stock buy-backs.
   After the buy-back is completed, Henley will have repurchased
nearly 43 percent of its stock.
   Separately, Henley said it decided to waive protection under a
recently enacted Delaware statute providing that a holder of 15
percent of a company's stock is prohibited from merging with the
company or undertaking certain other actions for three years.
   ``We do not believe it is in the best interests of shareholders
to impose these restrictions,'' Dingman said. ``We prefer to give
investors a free hand to make those decisions.''
   Henley's top management owns about 6.5 million of the company's
shares. That stake would rise to 9.3 percent with the completion of
the stock repurchase.
   Henley spokesman Norman Ritter said management wasn't
considering a bid to take the company private.
   Henley also said it intends to raise $1 billion by issuing
notes, then using the proceeds to pay off its current $980 million
in bank debt. That will allow the company to arrange $2.5 billion
in new bank credit, Henley said.
</TEXT>
