<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Avis-Cornrows     03-16 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Avis-Cornrows,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Avis Ends Five-Year Ban on Cornrows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAN GEHORSAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The car rental company Avis suddenly
reversed a five-year policy forbidding employees to wear cornrows
after two black workers filed a racial discrimination complaint
Tuesday.
   In a memorandum filed with the Philadelphia Commission on Human
Relations, longterm employees Linda Holman, 43, and Wanda Williams,
35, contended a ban against the small, tight braids injected
``racial considerations into the employment process.''
   They argued the ban targeted blacks because the hair style was
worn predominantly by blacks, often as an affirmation of their
African heritage.
   Just hours after the memorandum was filed by the American Civil
Liberties Union, the Avis headquarters in Garden City, N.Y.,
notified the Philadelphia branch the ban had been lifted.
   ``I am delighted that Avis is in fact trying harder,'' ACLU
attorney Stephan Presser said. ``The ... office tells me I am to
inform my clients that they are free to wear their cornrows proudly
to work tomorrow. This is the fastest victory I ever had in my
life. I'm just delighted. My clients won.''
   John Britton, a spokesman for Avis Rent A Car Systems Inc., said
the company was in the process of ``formalizing'' new standards
allowing cornrows before the employees' filed their complaint. The
new grooming guidelines will appear in a brochure that will be
issued to Avis' 1,400 national branches in May, he said.
   Cornrows were banned in a written circular in 1983 along with
``extreme'' bouffant hairdos and unkempt layered cuts.
   ``But things are modified, hairstyles are modified and attitudes
are modified,'' Britton said. ``In the '60s, we used to require
women behind the counter to wear girdles, and we had rules
governing hair length and facial hair. All those things have
changed over time.''
   When the ban was implemented, cornrows were not predominantly
considered a sign of black pride, he said.
   ``My first awareness of cornrows was with a (white) movie
actress, Bo Derek,'' he said.
   Avis reversed its position as part of an effort to respect
cultural differences, he said.
   According to Presser, Ms. Holman and Ms. Williams were warned
that they would be fired when they began wearing cornrows in July.
The rental agents wore wigs over the cornrows ``until they
literally became a headache'' and then gave up the hairstyle, he
said.
   Their memorandum charged that the ban on cornrows violated city,
state and federal job discrimination laws. Had the Philadelphia
Commission on Human Relations concurred, the agency could have
taken Avis to court, Presser said.
   Presser said he will wait a few weeks to see how the women fare
before withdrawing the charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
