<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NortheastPipelines     03-16 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northeast Pipelines,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FERC Says Construction Applications Involve 31 Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission
decided Wednesday that 71 applications to construct new natural gas
pipelines serving the Northeast really amount to 31 projects, and
the staff has warned two that they are in danger of rejection
already.
   The analysis was necessary because a single project may require
more than one request to the commission to proceed. If a new
pipeline would use a segment of an existing line in the middle, it
might mean three applications _ one for the middle and one for each
end.
   The commission attracted the applications during an ``open
season'' ending in January for new pipeline applications to serve
New England, New York, Pennsylvania and New Jersey, where demand
for gas is rising.
   As is its custom, the commission declined to release immediately
the text of what it had voted on, but staff lawyer Susan Court told
reporters afterward the commission wanted public comment on its
analysis and how to proceed, and would request market data from the
applicants and schedule technical conferences in the next step.
   Chairman Martha Hesse told her four fellow commissioners she
would propose a schedule in the next few days.
   Without the text of what the commission voted, it was impossible
to tell which companies fell in what class. But the commission was
told in a staff briefing that of the 31 projects, 20 appear to be
competitive, requiring hearings comparing one proposal against
another.
   Court said later it was not clear yet whether all 20 would be in
one hearing, or whether separate competitions were involved and the
hearings could be held in groups, perhaps according to the market
that would be served.
   Seven projects have no competition and can proceed on their own,
and backers of four were sent ``deficiency letters,'' warning that
their applications were inadequate.
   Two of those letters went to ANR Corp., whose Erie subsidiary
has one project, and to Panhandle Eastern Pipeline Co., whose
Indiana-Ohio subsidiary has another.
   The two companies were among three applying for permission under
an optional procedure whereby the applicant assumes the economic
risk of building the line and is forbidden from spreading those
costs among other other lines and customers if its expectations
don't pan out.
   The commission, however, has limited such applications to
pipelines promising to transport gas for anybody _ and has denied
such applications from ``open access'' companies it judged mere
extensions of a ``closed'' company.
   That is the case with ANR and Panhandle, Court said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
