<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Chrysler     03-16 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Personnel Vice President Says Chrysler Plans Management
Streamlining</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. will try to meet
its foreign competition by trimming executive-suite jobs and
stepping up teamwork on the plant floor, a Chrysler vice president
said Tuesday.
   By year's end, the No. 3 automaker will begin cutting its
eight-level organizational chart to a six-tier plan similar to
Japanese auto company structures, said Anthony St. John, vice
president of human resources and Chrysler's chief labor negotiator.
   The company also plans a new dispute-resolution system for
management employees in addition to opening early negotiations with
the United Auto Workers union on a contract for some 60,000 union
employees.
   Contract talks could begin as early as the third week in April,
St. John said. The UAW agreed last week to Chrysler's request for
early negotiations on a contract to replace a three-year contract
expiring Sept. 14.
   St. John said Chrysler needs to find ways to inspire employee
commitment and loyalty while keeping the company's employment costs
at competitive levels.
   ``The outcome may well be determined by our ability to provide
meaningful assurances of employee security,'' St. John said at a
labor-management seminar at Oakland University's Ken Morris Labor
Studies Center.
   Chrysler's request for an early start of talks was part of an
effort to return to a teamwork labor-management approach, he said.
Talks normally begin in mid-July.
   Tension already is running high in response to Chrysler's
decision to close down operations in Kenosha, Wis., and its plan,
since reversed in the face of bitter UAW opposition, to sell its
Acustar Inc. parts subsidiary.
   ``Our goal is to reach a strike-free settlement,'' St. John
said. ``It is going to then put the adversarial action behind us.''
   Chrysler already has begun talks with the UAW on a contract
covering 800 employees who will continue engine assembly work at
Kenosha and a closing agreement to cover 5,500 employees losing
their jobs in assembly and stamping operations at the former
American Motors Corp. factory.
   In addition to the contract talks, St. John said, the company
will be attempting to negotiate additional modern operating
agreements such as those set up in six of its plants since 1985.
   The agreements involve a teamwork concept, also found in
Japanese auto plants, involving workers in decisions, cutting the
number of supervisors by about 30 percent, and eliminating
artificial barriers such as separate management dining rooms and
parking.
   ``It puts into practice the simple but long neglected truth that
people exist from their shoulders up as well as from their
shoulders down,'' St. John said.
   The 1985 contract established a six-member joint activities
board with three members each from the company and union. The board
has organized training to bring employees up to date in areas such
as computers, new technology, robotics.
   Training programs will be stepped up, along with such modern
operating agreement features such as higher pay for workers
mastering additional skills.
   ``Roughly 25 percent of our hourly work force is illiterate,''
St. John said.
   St. John did not say how many jobs would be involved in the
upper-level cuts, but said most are expected to be accomplished
through retirements and other normal departures.
</TEXT>
