<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EconomyRdp     03-16 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Rdp,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing and Production Up, Markets Quiet Ahead of Trade Figures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stronger industrial production and a rebound in housing
construction were reported by the government Wednesday, but the
financial markets had mixed reactions in advance of a more potent
statistic, the trade deficit.
   The Federal Reserve said industrial production edged up 0.2
percent in February despite output reductions at auto factories and
coal mines. Economists said the gain, although slower than the
January level, represented good news for the economy and further
dampened concerns about a severe slowdown.
   The Commerce Department said the housing industry, after
staggering for two months following the October stock crash,
enjoyed a sharp 8.9 percent increase in construction activity in
February, the biggest gain in more than a year.
   The department said the increase pushed construction of
single-family homes and apartments up to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.49 million units last month following declines of
15.8 percent in December and 1.9 percent in January.
   Those setbacks, coupled with three consecutive monthly declines
in new home sales, had raised concerns because housing is often the
first industry to weaken at the onset of a recession. Economists
feared that home buyers had grown wary following the record
collapse of the stock market in October.
   But the February upturn in construction starts was seen as an
encouraging sign that while housing activity will be slower this
year, it will not weaken so much that it threatens overall economic
growth.
   ``Housing is on the rebound,'' said Warren Lasko, executive vice
president of the Mortgage Bankers Association. ``With interest
rates at low levels and the economy growing and no recession in
sight, we think we have all the ingredients in place to generate a
strong spring building season.''
   Nevertheless, the news hurt the bond market, a barometer of
interest rates and the economy. Since stronger growth implies
future inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income
investments, bond prices tumbled.
   The Treasury's key 30-year issue fell $10 per $1,000 in face
amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to price, jumped from 8.51
percent to 8.60 percent, its highest level since late January.
   On the other hand, the stock market closed largely higher. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which sat for most of
the day with a modest loss, ended with a 16.91 point gain at
2,064.32, though trading was slow.
   Analysts said the markets remained preoccupied with what the
Commerce Department would report Thursday on the January trade
deficit. That monthly statistic has become one of the most
important influences because of its implications for American
monetary and trade policy.
   The deficit declined in November and December, suggesting that
the dollar's depreciation over the past two years has made American
products more competitive. Three straight monthly declines would
provide further confirmation of that trend and lessen pressure for
more devaluation of the U.S. currency.
   Conversely, if the deficit significantly widened in January, the
dollar likely would fall, raising fears of inflation and foreign
flight from U.S. investments.
</TEXT>
