<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BusDrivers 1stLd-Writethru f0208 03-16 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Drivers, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0208,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Department Agrees To Compromise On 17-year-old Drivers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 13th graf, `Williams said...' to CORRECT to 808 among
6,000, sted in addition to; also moving on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DUBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Labor Department agreed Tuesday
to let some North and South Carolina school districts continue to
use 17-year-old bus drivers through the end of the school year.
   The agreement supersedes a Labor Department order that had
required both states to end the use of 17-year-old school bus
drivers by April 1.
   The department had told the two states it was ending an
exemption allowing the 17-year-old drivers because the states had
violated the terms of the exemption, primarily by using drivers who
had moving violations.
   Officials in both states had protested that some districts had
been unable to find qualified replacements, and that abruptly
replacing experienced 17-year-olds with new drivers could create
safety problems.
   Under the agreement announced by Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin,
school districts that have had the most problems finding new
drivers can use 17-year-old drivers through June 15, and all
districts may use drivers who will turn 18 before that time.
   All 17-year-old drivers must have been hired and trained before
the school year began and must have clean driving records, the
agreement said.
   South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell called the compromise a
``fair agreement.''
   ``This agreement was essential to provide the safest possible
situation for our children for the remainder of the school year, as
well as prevent major disruptions in the 12 districts unable to
find qualified adults,'' Campbell said.
   ``The state of South Carolina will not seek another extension,''
Campbell said. ``We will have an all-adult force in place by the
beginning of the next school year.''
   Campbell and state Education Superintendent Charlie Williams
said they support state budget proposals that would raise minimum
bus driver pay from $3.47 to $4.75 an hour and fund some fringe
benefits.
   North Carolina Gov. Jim Martin said he would seek a $24 million
budget amendment during the June session of the General Assembly to
increase drivers' pay to enable the state to attract and hire
additional adult drivers. The state has 2,085 drivers under age 18,
officials said.
   ``During our discussions with Secretary McLaughlin, I think it
became apparent that our school children would be a lot safer
riding with 17-year-olds with seven or eight months of bus driving
experience than it would be to have them riding with drivers who
have little or no experience driving a school bus,'' Martin said.
   Williams said the agreement leaves South Carolina with about 350
adult positions to fill by next year. After beginning the year with
2,250 17-year-old drivers, the state now has 808 17-year-olds among
its 6,000 drivers, Deputy Superintendent of Education Carl Garris
said.
   The 17-year-olds have been permitted to drive in the two states
under an exemption to the Fair Labor Standards Act. But that was
repealed after Labor Department investigations during January and
February found North Carolina had violated the act 80 times, and
South Carolina had recorded 200 violations during the two-month
period.
   The investigation was triggered when a 4-year-old boy in West
Columbia was struck and killed by a 17-year-old bus driver with a
bad driving record.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
